<header>
<title>Development Co-operation Review of France</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/fr.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review of France<br>Summary and Conclusions<P>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>April 1994<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris Cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
<h4>This Report</h4>
The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.
<p>
The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report of the team is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.
<p>
This publication contains the conclusions as agreed by DAC following the review meeting on 30 March 1994, as well as the report prepared by the Secretariat team.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
The report reviews the volume and distribution of French aid, noting that France ranks third in absolute volume of overseas development assistance, with aid accounting for 0.63 per cent of gross national product.
<p>
This report is mainly concerned with French bilateral assistance. It is centred on the consequences of the CFA Franc for the countries affected; aid effectiveness; implmentation of the DAC principles for effective aid; and the French administration's capacity for follow-up evaluation; aid objectives and management systems; French assistance to "women in development" and "population"; and finally, cooperation of the aid administration with French NGO's.
<p>
An important change in French aid management policy that is highlighted is the move away from technical assistance based on substitution to cooperation based on partnership. In this, recipients assume greater responsibility for management.
<p>
The current aid system is very complex with many ministries involved in shaping and managing bilateral aid. This tends to produce complexity in the targets and management of French cooperation and it risks reducing effectiveness. However, reforms to streamline management and improve internal coordination are in progress; and systematic ex post evaluation is being introduced in an effort to increase effectiveness.
<p>
The report notes that discussions are ongoing to see how NGO's can be more involved in the framing and implementation of French development cooperation.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on July 11,
1995</i><p>
