<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lomé 2000 (3) - Rethinking the Lom&eacute; &quot;Partnership&quot;</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H2><CENTER><img src="../images/2000.jpg"></a><p>
Rethinking the Lom&eacute; &quot;Partnership&quot;</H2>
<H4>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>Lom&#233; 2000</i>, No. 3, October 1996: page 2</H4>
</CENTER>
<hr>
<P>
&quot;Partnership&quot; has been the cornerstone of successive
Lom&eacute; Conventions. It refers to a willingness on both sides
to engage in long-term commitments to achieve common goals. It
gives ACP countries the responsibility for their own development
by entrusting them with a lead role in managing Lom&eacute; resources,
with the EU playing a supportive role only. This concept of partnership,
together with the principles of dialogue, contractuality and predictability,
add up to the so-called &quot;Lom&eacute; culture.&quot;
<P>
According to Commissioner Pinheiro, the principle of partnership
will remain &quot;unchallengeable&quot; in any post-Lom&eacute;
arrangement. Yet there is little doubt that major changes will
be introduced in the practice of future partnerships. Current
approaches are unsatisfactory to both sides. Lom&eacute; I (1975)
put the ACP partners clearly in the driving seat, with Europe
adopting a &quot;laisser-faire&quot; attitude (&quot;it's your
money, you decide on its use&quot;). Successive Conventions sought
to integrate donor concerns into the partnership. Currently, the
pendulum seems to have shifted further to the opposite extreme,
with the EU adopting an increasingly &quot;hands-on&quot; approach
(&quot;it's our money and we decide on its use&quot;). At EU level,
it is argued that genuine partnerships are difficult to establish
with ACP countries that have poor governance or administrative
capacities. This leaves little room for transparent and efficient
use of resources. It often forces the Commission to adopt a more
interventionist (substitution) approach.
<P>
Both parties seem to agree on the need for a more down-to-earth
and pragmatic partnership. Ways need to be found to give it again
a sound political foundation (based on common interests), a flexible
<I>modus operandi</I> (allowing for country-specific approaches)
and a long-term perspective (beyond immediate aid management concerns).
<P>
What does this mean in practice? From a European perspective,
the political message is rather straightforward: EU aid is there
to &quot;help those that help themselves.&quot; Partnership remains
the ideal form of cooperation, yet it cannot be assumed to exist,
simply because a contractual agreement is signed and aid is provided.
Partnership needs to be achieved, rather than declared. This means
that the political aspects of cooperation will be the centrepiece
of future partnerships (i.e. human rights, democracy, governance,
sound macro-economic policies). It is likely to imply the end
of &quot;aid entitlements.&quot; Instead, the EU will use greater
selectivity and differentiation in treating ACP countries. There
is growing support for aid allocation based on &quot;needs and
merits&quot; (see box). Another direction of change is the desire
to have a pluralistic partnership, including forms of (direct)
support to non-traditional actors (e.g. the private sector, civil
society organisations).
<P>
It is less clear what changes the ACP side would like to propose
with regard to new forms of partnership. Traditionally, ACP countries
have asked for much more flexible and less bureaucratic partnership
approaches based on trust (rather than imposed conditionalities).
They insist on the need for greater awareness of local, political
realities; home-grown alternatives to policy reform and improved
policy coherence. It is also argued that future partnership agreements
should find new ways to address the debt problem. In the current
political climate, it seems appropriate that the ACP come with
new ideas and approaches to partnership that reflect their needs
while accommodating donor (accountability) concerns.
<P>
