<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 7 February 1997</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
This has not been a very good week for the Caribbean. Bananas, rum, rice,
aid programmes and even the competitive position of air carriers have all
become subject to future uncertainty as a result of changing policies and
US-led industry challenges to the status quo.
<p>
On bananas, the World Trade Organisation (WTO) report on the US complaint
about the EUs banana regime has been delayed, largely, officials in Geneva
say, in order to deal with the growing opposition to the US position. In
Europe banana producers from the region have already made clear that huge
job losses and economic ruin would face the region if, as expected, the
existing import regime is deemed illegal. This view was also reinforced in
the US by the Congressional Black Caucus who told the United States Trade
Representative (USTR), Charlene Barschevsky: "Short sighted policies that
would undermine the Caribbean economics will create instability, lead to
increases in emigration and narcotics trafficking in the region".
<p>
As far as rum is concerned, future prospects in the EU and US market
worsened markedly as one of the worlds largest producers placed increasing
pressure on US trade negotiators to remove all tariffs on white spirits -
and especially rum over a certain value - after the year 2000. Although
there had been some initial signs that the US might be prepared to remove
rum from the proposed measure, it became apparent as the week went on, that
USTR was being pushed to seek a special arrangement for high value rum
producers. The effect of this was to make it imperative that European 
governments, politicians and officials all understood the damaging effect
this would have on the Caribbean rum industry and thus resist US pressure.
As this column went to press, the battle was just beginning in Geneva to
have the international community recognise that the Caribbean rum industry
requires a stable transition to open competition early in the next
millennium.
<p>
The picture on rice is just as unhappy. A delegation of ACP rice millers
came to Europe in the week past to hold talks on the complex inter-related
problems facing their industry in developing exports to Europe. They found
themselves caught between low quotas under safeguard measures restricting
rice imports into the EU; delays in the agreed reduction of a tariff on
direct rice shipments from the ACP to the EU under quotas included in the
Lomi Convention; and continuing Dutch intransigence on achieving an
agreement on quotas under the OCT/EU relationship. The millers found
sympathy and the desire to help. They also began to develop ideas with
those that they met that might end the present impasse. But they also heard
growing concern about the implications of the axis that now exists between
commercial operators in the Netherlands Antilles and in Holland that
appears to be controlling Dutch Government policy towards the supply of ACP
rice to Europe. 
<p>
The message that is beginning to emerge from all of this is that while
globalisation may lead to global opportunity it also fosters global
monopolies. In other words while competition is welcome and creates
efficiency, the desire for global dominance by any company or industry, if
allied with national interest and most especially that of the US, can be
particularly dangerous to small economies such as those in the Caribbean.
<p>
What the Caribbean is now finding is that it is once again the focus in an
international trade war. But the problem is that this time very few in
politics realise the battle can only be won in Washington, Brussels and at
the WTO in Geneva. 
<p>
Politicians in the region should beware that what appears to be obscure and
technical today, will fast become a domestic political question. The
collapse of any one of the industries mentioned above could be sudden and
those presently employed will then seek to know who to blame. This is why
the appointment of Sir Bernard (Brie) St. John as international trade
negotiator for the region is so vital. 
<p>
Time is not on the Caribbean's side. Sir Bernard must be given a clear
mandate by Caribbean heads that allows him the right to executive action.
The principal thrust is likely to be that the industries that still
underwrite the Caribbean's viability need to achieve a stable transition
out of preference. Otherwise newer industries such as tourism, information
technology, financial services et al will never achieve the levels of
investment which are required for them to have a deep-rooted place in the
regional economy. Beyond this Heads of Government at the next Caricom
intersessional meeting need to speak frankly in private to one another if
they are to develop the same level of co-ordination and cohesion that is
now apparent in the associations that represent the economic sectors under
attack.
<P>
All of which is not to remove responsibility from the US Congress, the
United States Trade Representatives office or those US business interests
that seek global dominance, apparently at any expense. 
<P>
Belatedly, there are stirrings in influential circles in Washington that
relate to matters of national security and narcotics interdiction. In at
least three important agencies, important voices are now being raised to
enquire whether the policies being pursued by USTR and the State Department
are in the United States long-term interest, especially in the Eastern
Caribbean. They are pressing for a more integrated approach along the lines
that are recognised within the EU, that is that a sudden end to any one of
the key industries in the Caribbean, will undermine stability and create a
vacuum that will almost certainly be filled by narcotics traffickers and
organised crime.
<P>
When President Clinton visits Barbados later this year and the EC's
Development Commissioner, Professor Pinheiro, meets with Caribbean Heads of
Government in July, the message must be clear and simple. That is, the
region is not opposed to change but needs extra-regional support if it is
to achieve a successful transition towards open markets. What is needed is
an integrated package that provides economic security and stability.
<p>
<HR>
