 Danmarks internationale indsats</I>. Copenhagen: Statens Informationstjeneste.<P>

Holm, Hans Henrik. 1982 # <I>
 Hvad Danmark g&oslash;r. En analyse af dansk u-landspolitik</I>. Aarhus: Politica.<P>

J&oslash;rgensen, Klaus. 1977. # <I>
 Hj&aelig;lp fra Danmark. En studie af dansk u-landspolitik 1960-71.</I> Odense: Odense Universitetsforlag.<P>

J&oslash;rgensen, Hans Genefke, Jacob Norvig Larsen, &amp; Lars Udsholt. 1993 # <I>
 The role of Danish NGOs in development policy</I>. Copenhagen: Mellemfolkeligt Samvirke.<P>

Kristiansen, Kristof K. &amp; Ole Olsen, eds. 1989 # <I>
 P&aring; lempelige vilk&aring;r? Verdensbanken, IMF og u-landene</I>. Copenhagen: FN-Forbundet.<P>

Martinussen, John. 1989 # Danidas handlingsplan. Et essay om administrationens rolle i formuleringen af dansk bistandspolitik. In <I>
 Danmark og det internationale system</I>, eds. Bertil Heurlin &amp; Christian Thune. pp. 244-258. Copenhagen: Politiske Studier.<P>

Mosley, Paul, Jane Harrigan, &amp; John Toye. 1991 # <I>
 Aid and power. The World Bank and policy-based lending</I>. London: Routledge.<P>

Nielson, Poul. 1995 # Udviklingsministerens kommentarer til Center for Udviklingsforsknings redeg&oslash;relse. <I>
 Den ny verden</I> vol. 28, no. 3: 104-108.<P>

Pratt, Cranford, ed. 1990 # <I>
 Middle power internationalism. The North South dimension</I>. London: McGill-Queen's University Press.<P>

Sano, Hans Otto, ed. 1993 # <I>
 Fattigdomsorienteret bistand - en dagsorden for 1990ernes bistandspolitik.</I> CUF Notat. Copenhagen: Centre for Development Research.<P>

Svendsen, Knud Erik. 1981 # Dansk bistandspolitik: Problemer og synspunkter. <I>
 Den ny verden</I> vol. 15, no. 3: 5-29.<P>

Svendsen, Knud Erik. 1987 # The Nordic countries and the IMF/World Bank. In <I>
 The IMF and the World Bank in Africa. Conditionality, impact and alternatives</I>, ed. Kjell J. Havnevik. Seminar proceedings no. 18. Uppsala: Scandinavian Institute of African Studies.<P>

Svendsen, Knud Erik. 1989 # Danish aid: Old bottles. In <I>
 Western middle powers and global poverty</I>, ed. O. Stokke. Uppsala: Scandinavian Institute of Africa Studies.<P>

Svendsen, Knud Erik. 1995 # Social development and international development cooperation. In <I>
 Welfare, development and security. Three Danish essays</I>. pp. 35-58. Copenhagen: The Danish National Institute of Social Research.<P>

Therkildsen, Ole. 1994a # Indledning. <I>
 Den ny verden</I> vol. 27, no. 3: 5-12. <P>

Therkildsen, Ole, ed. 1994b # <I>
 Dansk bistand - en blandet landhandel</I>. Theme issue of <I>
 Den ny verden</I> vol. 27, no. 3. Copenhagen: Centre for Udviklingsforskning.<P>

Udenrigskommissionen af 1. april 1989. 1990 # <I>
 Udenrigstjenesten mod &aring;r 2000.</I> 2 vols. Bet&aelig;nkning no. 1209. Copenhagen: Statens Informationstjeneste.<P>

Udenrigsministeriet. 1993 # <I>
 Principper og perspektiver i dansk udenrigspolitik: F&aelig;lles sikkerhed; demokrati og menneskerettigheder; &oslash;konomisk og social udvikling; milj&oslash;.</I> Copenhagen: Ministry of Foreign Affairs.<P>

Udvalget vedr&oslash;rende dansk bistandspolitik. 1982 # <I>
 Bet&aelig;nkning om principperne for den danske bistand til udviklingslandene</I>. Bet&aelig;nkning no. 958. Copenhagen: Direktoratet for Statens Indk&oslash;b.<P>

W&aelig;ver, Ole. 1995 # Danish dilemmas - Foreign policy choices for the 21st century. In <I>
 Adaption and activism. The foreign policy of Denmark 1967-1993</I>, eds. Carsten Due-Nielsen &amp; Nikolaj Petersen. Copenhagen: DJ&Oslash;F Publishing.</FONT>
<P>

<h3><hr>Endnotes</h3>
<FONT size=-1>
<OL>
<LI><A NAME="e1"></A>Contrary to several other European donors Danish governments have traditionally maintained a unified aid administration within the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, including both bilateral and multilateral development assistance, and including various 'tied aid' programmes. Recently, one has witnessed a growing number of other government bodies being involved in programmes to assist e.g. Eastern Europe or to address global environmental problems. However, this paper maintains a focus on the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The paper has generally been structured in conformity with the design of a comparative research project on European aid administrations, initiated by Overseas Development Institute (UK) and European Centre for Development Policy and Management (Netherlands). <A HREF="#b1">[Back to Text]</A>
<LI><A NAME="e2"></A>Comparing Danish development policies to those of other OECD-countries Martinussen points at more emphasis on both poverty alleviation and multilateral development cooperation. He further notes i.a. an unusually high degree of collaborative efforts with a large emphasis on universally international cooperation and with relatively small emphasis on defence and security concerns. (Martinussen 1989:249).<A HREF="#b2">[Back to Text]</A>
<LI><A NAME="e3"></A>Activities supported by this budget line fall within the juridistiction of both the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Ministry of the Interior, and the Ministry of Environment & Energy. The specific division of responsibilities for environmental assistance has been the source of considerable inter-ministerial rivalry and tensions. Experiences with this new type of Danish aid is not debated in this paper.
Thus, in reality Danish aid figures to an increasing extent surpass the 1% of GDP target that remains the basic aid volume objective, since environmental assistance and expenditures for asylum seekers from developing countries are not included in the aid figures. It is, however, government policy not to consider these expenditure categories as ODA, contrary to current DAC rules.<A HREF="#b3">[Back to Text]</A>
<LI><A NAME="e4"></A>The first Act on development cooperation (1962) included no statement of objectives. Rather it was agreed that during build up of the aid programme, one should allow the relevant authorities to accumulate experiences and professional insights prior to a decision on overall guidelines and objectives.<A HREF="#b4">[Back to Text]</A>
<LI><A NAME="e5"></A>The liberal minority government managed to secure majority support for its economic policies while accepting several defeats with regard to parliamentarymotions on security policy (e.g. on NATO and European nuclear rearmament).<A HREF="#b5">[Back to Text]</A> 
<LI><A NAME="e6"></A>Interestingly, Parliament has not yet had a specific thematic debate on 'private sector development' similar to the ones on 'women', 'environment' etc., and one looks in vain for a specific Danida policy paper on this issue. Hence, the long-standing agreement to ensure a 50% rate of return to Danish companies from the bilateral aid appropriations is mainly reflected in strategies to involve Danish business in development cooperation, and not founded on a specific strategic vision of the role of the private sector in development.
<A HREF="#b6">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e7"></A>These are currently: Strategy for Danish Support to Indigenous People (Danida 1994f); Environmental Assessment for Sustainable Development (Danida 1994g); Human Rights and Democracy. Perspectives for development Cooperation (Danida 1993j); Women in Development. Danida`s WID Policy Towards the Year 2000 (Danida 1993K); Denmark`s Efforts in the Population Field. Strategy. (in Danish - Danida 1994g).
<A HREF="#b7">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e8"></A>Since 1991 the Danish aid administration has been an integrated part of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, contrary to the situation prevailing in 1986-91 when 'Danida' was one of three separate departments within the Ministry. Today, Danish development assistance is managed by the 'South Group' in the Ministry. Hence, in strictly formal terms the 'Danida' label is not currently applied to any specific administrative entity but rather to the activities taking place within the framework of Danish development cooperation policies. However, it seems to be common practice to equate Danida with the South Group. This approach is also pursued in this paper.
<A HREF="#b8">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e9"></A>The plan has recently been made available in an abridged English language version (Danida 1994j).
<A HREF="#b9">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e10"></A>The study notes that prior to 1986 strategic planning had not been employed as a management instrument in Danida. The study furthermore observes that policy formulation is in itself a partly unclear process which is a result of a relatively stable, long-term policy development and a range of more sudden adjustments which may appear as a result of more or less haphazardly arising `issues` (...). (Administrationsdepartementet 1986c:13). 
<A HREF="#10">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e11"></A>This was the case with regard to the proposals for future programme countries and the proposed 'flex-fund' that would be available to stimulate Danish business participation in various projects in developing countries. As a result of the subsequent public and parliamentary debate, the plan for the flex-fund was abandoned and several of the middle-income countries were not short-listed as programme countries. Still, the Plan of Action seemed to indicate that Danish commercial interests had now gained a significantly larger influence on Danish aid policy (cf. Martinussen 1988:252ff).
<A HREF="#10">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e12"></A>A summarised 20-page English version of the paper has been made available (Danida1994i). French and Spanish versions have also been prepared.
<A HREF="#12">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e13"></A>Furthermore, one might add that the document obviously served the purpose of formulating more explicitly the policy foundation for the new Minister for Development Cooperation that had been appointed with the formation of the new government in early 1993.
<A HREF="#13">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e14"></A>A major analysis of agency field effectiveness for 11 multilateral organisations completed in 1991 has been instrumental in enabling Danida to follow more systematically the relative performance of multilateral development agencies (Danida 1991).
<A HREF="#14">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e15"></A>Danida is now moving away from being a retailer with a speciality in `projects towards becoming a wholesaler in support of `sector programmes` (Therkildsen 1994:7).
<A HREF="#15">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e16"></A>Holm compares Swedish, Norwegian, and Danish positions in this respect and finds Danish policies to be the least responsive among the Scandinavians (Holm 1982:177). However, in a general DAC perspective Denmark has beenamong the group of donor countries emphasising dialogue rather than conditionality. Cf. Jørgensen (1977) for a historical account of the early phases of Danish development policy and its emphasis on `neutrality`.
<A HREF="#16">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e17"></A>Two of the key civil servants in the 1988 process from the then Danida policy office recurred in the 1993/94 process as respectively deputy permanent secretary (head of the South Group in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs) and as head of the small strategy unit created specifically to prepare the strategy.
<A HREF="#17">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e18"></A>It is currently agreed that the number of programme countries will normally not exceed 20, except in situations when programmes are beingphased in/out. In this case one may reach the maximum limit of 25.
<A HREF="#18">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e19"></A>Until 1989 Danish bilateral aid was equally divided between project assistance on grant terms and a tied aid programme providing government credits on concessional terms to finance deliveries from Danish companies. During the 1980s concessionality was gradually increased so that by 1988 all tied aid was provided on grant terms. In 1988 it was decided to terminate the tied aid programme as such. Since then, the objective to ensure 50% of bilateral aid to be spent on goods and services procured in Denmark has been measured ex post as the combined result of the total decisions on aid allocations in the bilateral programme. During the period 1989-93 the proportion of bilateral aid that 'returned' to Denmark declined from 68% to 51%. However, the more narrowly defined 'business related' returns on bilateral aid spending dropped from 56% to 27% within the same period. This figure is based on 'production criteria', i.e. only the share of a delivery actually produced in Denmark is included, whereas the other Nordic countries, the Netherlands and Germany all apply a criteria based on the location of the contractor. In 1994 Denmark changed to this approach.
<A HREF="#19">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e20"></A>The programme in Thailand - a country which was selected amidst much debate in 1989 - is currently being phased out since the country's GDP/capita now exceeds the Danish limit of 1,855 USD/capita. In this context it was decided to include Ethiopia among the programme countries in 1994 with a programme that would be gradually built up as Thailand was reduced. No resources were made available, though, for Ethiopia in the 1994 and 1995 budgets. By mid-1995 the Minister for Development Cooperation announced that the country would be taken off the list due to i.a.uncertainty with regard to conducting a regular policy dialogue with the Government. It was furthermore suggested that Malawi would be included in stead. Final approval by the Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee on this issue is still pending at the time of completing this paper (October 1995).
<A HREF="#20">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e21"></A>Danida figures in the Annual Report include technical assistance and support via Danish NGOs, while country figures in the rolling five-year plan are exclusive of these budget categories.
<A HREF="#21">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e22"></A>This figure includes expenditures for bilateral advisors in addition to the budget figures for the 20 programme countries reported in table 3. Most advisors are stationed in the 20 programme countries. The existing official budget presentations separate project aid from technical assistance. On the contrary Danida annual reports include all Danish aid (including NGOs, TA etc.) in the figures for actual country programme allocations.
<A HREF="#22">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e23"></A>It is, however, noteworthy that when in 1988 Danida approached 22 major Danish companies to learn about their views on country concentration, the result was a substantially more differentiated and more widespread obligingness towards the DANIDA-administration request for geographic concentration than the traditional positions of the main interest organisation 'Danish Industry', who favoured a more widely dispersed aid programme (Martinussen 1989:248).
<A HREF="#23">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e24"></A>It is expected that most credits will be allocated to projects in China, India and in some of the middle-income countries in South East Asia. An amount of DKK 173 m. is currently allocated for this purpose, growing to app. DKK 300 m. in 1997 (app. 6% of bilateral aid).
<A HREF="#24">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e25"></A>One may also find NGOs considering it more easy to receive Danida funding for NGO-projects in countries where Danida itself maintains a country programme. This linkage is, however, excluded in the recent strategy for Danida cooperation with Danish NGOs (Danida 1993g).
<A HREF="#25">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e26"></A>Furthermore, Danish commodity import support programmes had been tied to the supply of Danish goods, but improving foreign exchange balances during recent years in several Danish programme countries have meant less need for this type of assistance. This has also been an important contributing factor to the declining rates of return (Ministry of Foreign Affairs 1994b).
<A HREF="#26">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e27"></A>Still, a number of the administrative changes dealt with below stem partly from experiences and recommendations contained in analyses and reports prepared by consultants external to Danida. Compared to the other areas covered in this paper project management stands out as being the least affected by Danida interaction with the aid policy community.
<A HREF="#27">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e28"></A>Currently (autumn 1995) new 'guidelines for programme preparation' are being prepared with the intention to accommodate for the new approach to sector programme assistance and to include more explicit references to the cross-cutting objectives in Danish development assistance, e.g. poverty orientation. The presentation here is based on the 1992-guidelines for project preparation (Danida 1992).
<A HREF="#28">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e29"></A>So far, no `real` country evaluation has been implemented, although Danida 1993b on Zimbabwe and Danida 1995 on Nepal each addresses major aspects related to country programming of Danish assistance. The Zimbabwe study focuses on country programming instruments while the Nepal study analyses the profile of the poverty objective in the country portfolio.
<A HREF="#29">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e30"></A>In 1993 Danida published an interesting study on lessons learned during the ten years since the establishment of the Danida evaluation unit in 1982 (Danida 1993i).
<A HREF="#30">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e31"></A>Policy-based lending is discussed in this paper mainly in relation to World Bank supported adjustment programmes. Like other Western bilateral donors, Danish aid has recently also taken up much more actively issues related to democratisation and human rights. This debate, which is certainly also an expression of the tendency towards more policy-based aid, has primarily been seen in relation to the choice of programme countries for bilateral aid.
<A HREF="#31">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e32"></A>Writing in 1987 Svendsen notes with regard to the IMF and the World Bank that the Nordic countries have kept a low profile, both internationally and in their home constituencies (Svendsen 1987:161).
<A HREF="#32">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e33"></A>In addition, the Nordic countries from the mid-1980s and onwards pursued two other mainly project-related issues in the World Bank: women in development and environmental concerns (Bodelsen 1989).
<A HREF="#33">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e34"></A>A recent Danida evaluation report contrasts the Danish approach with that of Norway who has pursued a `more focused and more instutionalised` use of cofinancing (Danida 1993c:39).
<A HREF="#34">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e35"></A>Five countries, Nicaragua, Uganda, Tanzania, Mozambique and Bangladesh received more than 80% of Danish balance of payment support during this period.
<A HREF="#35">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e36"></A>It has been argued that the perception of an `over-proportional influence' is a general feature among Danish civil servants involved with EU cooperation (Wæver 1995:284).
<A HREF="#36">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e37"></A>Danish government ministries are headed by civil servants recruited from within the bureaucracy. Thus, contrary to several other Western democracies, permanent secretaries and state secretaries are not politically appointed.
<A HREF="#37">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e38"></A>This is in line with a general tendency for aid administrations to move away from focusing on aid modalities and channels for aid delivery towards geographical and professional concerns gaining more prominence as structuring factors in aid administrations (Administrationsdepartementet 1986a:51).
<A HREF="#38">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e39"></A>The first five Danida field missions had been established in the mid-1970s (Administrationsdepartementet 1986d:4), but it was only a decade later than the number of field missions started to grow as is evident from table 7.
<A HREF="#39">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e40"></A>The Ministry of Foreign Affairs had been organised along functional lines since the mid-19th century (Udenrigskommissionen 1990:vol. I, 176).
<A HREF="#40">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e41"></A>In addition the forum principle was applied in the sense that within the South Group the multilateral department is organised according to the fora in which Denmark participates (the UN system, the development banks etc.).
<A HREF="#41">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e42"></A>In addition to the figure for total staff in the South Group 1995, 11 staff members worked with aid related issues in the joint Information Secretariat of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
<A HREF="#42">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e43"></A>It has been argued that prior to the 1991 reorganisation, the Ministry as such (i.e. not only Danida) was characterised by a very centralised mode of operation compared to the situation in several other ministries and other public sector organisations (Christensen 1992:96).
<A HREF="#43">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e44"></A>Exceptions from this trend might be Danida management of support for NGO information and development projects, and the establishment of a Danida business secretariat. Compared to the `big` questions in relation to ministerial reorganisation, these areas are certainly less central.
<A HREF="#44">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e45"></A>In the period 1987-1990 the Foreign Service as such had been reduced with 80 posts while Danida staffing itself had not been cut (cf. Udenrigskommissionen 1990: vol. I, 27). However, staff increases in Danida in the late 1980s could certainly not make up with the rapid growth in aid allocations.
<A HREF="#45">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e46"></A>Senior ministerial management may not have been the sole group in favour of establishing a common career system for both the North and the South group. For the young and ambitious, the new organisation opened for better and faster opportunities for advancing in the very observable hierarchy of the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
<A HREF="#46">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e47"></A>Recently, the Minister for Development Cooperation has reappointed the Board for another 3-year term. For the first time since the formative years of the Danish aid programme the composition of the Board has been changed to the effect that representatives from the Danish Youth Council and the Union of Danish Cooperative Societies no longer serve on the Board. In stead representatives from the consulting companies and two major NGOs are nowincluded among the Board members, while the `observer category` has been abandoned.
<A HREF="#47">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e48"></A>While the Board advices the Minister, these recommendation are passed on indirectly via Danida top management, as the Minister does not participate in Board meetings.
<A HREF="#48">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e49"></A>Interestingly, the Council for International Development Cooperation for some politicians served as a model when the Council for European Cooperation was established in 1993 to allow for more involvement of the public in debates on Danish policies towards the EU. Furthermore, counting i.a. on traditions to provide government funds for NGO development education programmes, the Parliament decided to set aside specific budget lines for adult education and popular campaigns on the issue of European integration during Danish debates on the Maastricht Treaty.
<A HREF="#49">[Back to Text]</A><LI><A NAME="e50"></A>It is evident that field experiences and the changing profile and size of NGO and business` project portfolio both have major impacts on the position of these parties in Danish aid debates. It has not been possible, though, to deal with these aspects within the framework of this paper.<A HREF="#50">[Back to Text]</A> 
</OL>
</font>
