<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/no.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Norway
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Norwegian Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Norwegian Development Cooperation</h3>

Norway's development cooperation stems from an old and powerful humanitarian and religious tradition. As
a strong supporter of the United Nations system, Norway has contributed to the development programmes of
the UN since the early 1950s. Voluntary contributions to the social work of Norwegian missionaries paved
the way for development aid in Parliament and with the public. In 1952 Parliament approved the creation of
The Norwegian Foundation for Assistance to Underdeveloped Countries. In 1968 the Norwegian Agency for
Development Cooperation (NORAD) was created, and in 1969 Norway set itself the target of 1 per cent of
NNI for development cooperation (including 0.75 of GNP for ODA).
<p>
Net official development assistance in 1992 amounted to US $ 1 273 million, which was 1.16 per cent of
GNP, the highest ratio in DAC Member countries. Since 1982 Norwegian ODA amounted to more than 1
per cent of GNP. For 1993 the figure was expected to decline 1.01 per cent amongst others due to the
present economic constraints. For the first time the 1994 figures will include the cost for the reception of
refugees in Norway, resulting in an effective cut of the budget by 3 per cent. These relative budget
decreases will be compensated by improved quality. In principle Norwegian ODA is divided equally
between multilateral and bilateral channels. Since 1970 multilateral contributions have never reached 50 per
cent of the budget. In 1992 the multilateral share was 36 per cent of total ODA. 
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Although certainly in its early years development cooperation was subject to intensive discussions in
Parliament, little of it is laid down in legislation. The Ministry of Development Cooperation (MDC), created
in 1983, was integrated into the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA) in 1989. The Ministry has three
Ministers at the moment, the Minister of Foreign Affairs, the Minister of Trade and Shipping, and the
Minister of Development Cooperation, who is still a member of Cabinet. 
<p>
Norway's aid programme is divided into two roughly equal parts and is managed at two levels, one by the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs under the authority of the Minister of Development Cooperation, and one by
NORAD (Norwegian Agency for Development Cooperation).
<p>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs defines the general priorities and strategies for development cooperation,
the budgeting for Norwegian ODA, it sets general guidelines, formulates priorities and cross-sectoral
policies, and has direct responsibility for emergency, refugee and humanitarian aid, and for the overall
evaluation of the aid programme. The MFA covers around 10 per cent of the total aid budget. Under the
Minister of Development Cooperation three departments work on the formulation of the policies. The
Department for Bilateral Cooperation has divisions for different regions and for humanitarian assistance. The
Department for Multilateral Cooperation deals with UN organisations and development finance institutions,
and the Department for Development Cooperation Programmes is responsible for budget planning, for the
research programme, and for developing guidelines for development cooperation. Aid financed export
credits are administered by an institute under the Minister of Trade, provided NORAD approves of their
development impact.
<p>
Second, Norway's bilateral aid programme is managed by a separate agency, the Norwegian Agency for
Development Cooperation (NORAD). With the merger of the Ministries in 1989, NORAD was separated
again from the Ministry of Development Cooperation and was established as an external Directorate, under
the supervision of the development branch of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. However, it still reported
directly to the Ministry. NORAD is primarily organised along geographical lines. There are two regional
departments, complemented by a Department for Technical Advisory Services, an Industrial Development
Department and a NGOs, Volunteers and Cultural Affairs Department. There is an advisory group on
Women, Environmental Affairs, Democracy and Human Rights Issues (KVIM) to the Director-General.
NORAD has Aid Missions in the main recipient countries, where implementation of the programmes is
done. 
<p>
Recently the MFA has established the Norwegian Resource Bank for Democracy and Human Rights, a fund
for technical assistance for democratic organisation, conflict resolution, constitutional development, human
rights education and related activities.
<p>
Overall policy planning is done by the Department of Development Cooperation Programmes of the MFA.
Advisors and advisory units do exist within the MFA, the MDC and NORAD for cross-cutting issues, such
as WID, environment and human rights. The integration of the Ministry of Development Cooperation into
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs is motivated by the need to improve cooperation within the administration
and to strengthen the coherence in all decision making processes. Internal policy coordination within the
MFA is intensive. Daily or weekly meetings are held by the three Ministers or their representatives
(including NORAD); internal ad hoc committees discuss specific questions and sectors of aid policy. 
<p>
For policy coordination between ministries, a Contact Committee for Environmental Questions was re-
established, comprising representatives of the Ministry of the Environment and of various departments of the
MFA. These two Ministries drafted a Paper on the follow-up to UNCED. The White Paper No. 51 was
jointly written by the departments of the MFA that work under its three Ministers. Task forces, comprising
participants from the ministries concerned and from the Prime Minister's Office are regularly set up for the
preparation of important conferences, such as the Population Conference in Cairo (1994), and the Women's
Conference in Beijing (1995). 
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
Advisory structures form an intrinsic part of the administrational set-up in Norway. NORAD used to have
an Advisory Board (Styrelse) as well an Advisory Council. The members of the Board were appointed by
the Government, and the 20 members of the Council by Parliament. The Council, created to build a
constituency for official development cooperation, included representatives from many sections of
Norwegian society, a.o. research institutes and universities, media, politics, NGOs and industry. Although
the formal mandate of the Council was rather limited, it discussed norms and objectives for Norwegian aid
policies, formulated guidelines, and discussed the annual budget. Its comments were sent to Parliament. The
Council was abolished in 1983, when NORAD was brought under the administrative structure of the newly
created Ministry of Development Cooperation. A new Advisory Council for the Ministry of Development
Cooperation was created, and for NORAD a Program Board was installed. The new Council functioned
mainly as a debating platform. In 1989 the number of advisory boards, -councils, and -committees for all
policy areas in the Norwegian administration was reduced substantially, and the Advisory Council was
abolished again, as well as the Board.
<p>
At the moment two advisory bodies function for the MFA, one on Human Rights questions, led by the
Special Advisor on Human Rights of the Ministry, and one on disarmament questions. The 'North-South
Commission' is a temporary institution. The MFA finances a 'Norwegian Ideas Group', that organises
seminars and issues a newsletter. 
<p>
Until the beginning of the 1990s a Nordic Council of the Ministers of Development Cooperation of
Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden met bi-annually to discuss policy issues. Adjacent to these
meetings advisory meetings were organised of parliamentarians and researchers from the five countries. One
of these advisory meetings was a seminar Human Rights and Democracy held in Helsinki. The proceedings
were published in English. It is not known whether these meetings will be continued.
<p>
Parliament receives the annual budget for development cooperation, strategy and other policy documents,
annual reports as well as sector policy papers and evaluation studies. The annual budget is discussed in a
public session of the Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs. However, unlike the earlier years, when
extensive debates took place in Parliament on development cooperation, Parliamentarians do not seem to
devote much time to the subject nowadays. 
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
NORAD and the MFA both cooperate with NGOs. NGOs work usually for NORAD in those countries
where NORAD has no official presence itself. The Government intends to draw up framework agreements
with NGOs for long-term cooperation. Cooperation on a project-by-project base is declining, since the
Government promotes cooperation with local organisations. There are more then 60 highly motivated
developing NGOs, secular and church related, that were carrying out projects in more then 60 developing
countries in 1991. In 1993 NORAD provided support to 43 organisations. These numbers include
humanitarian, emergency and refugee relief aid. Norwegian NGOs shift from implementation to networking
with international NGOs and cooperation with local NGOs. The NGOs have regular working contacts and
policy discussions with the Ministry. They are active in the public debate and in development education.
Umbrella organisations are: the Norwegian Forum for Environment and Development, the North South
Coalition - both functioning as information banks and pressure groups - and the Missionary Council. NGOs
have well established contacts with politicians and other sectors of Norwegian society. Issues that NGOs
consider important for discussion with the Government are amongst others: post-emergency assistance,
professionalism of NGOs and the consequences for Norway of sustainable development policies. 
<p>
Researchers have always been involved in the formulations of development cooperation policies. Officials
have many contacts with researchers and advisers. The Minister of Development Cooperation used to
finance 3 to 5-year research programs. The Research Council for Development Cooperation was integrated
into the general Research Council of Norway in 1989. The Norwegian Institute of International Affairs
(NUPI) in Oslo used to organise seminars on development cooperation issues and publish the results in a
series. NUPI still issues a bi-annual journal, Forum for Development Studies. A leading role in development
cooperation issues is played by the Christian Michelsen Institute (CMI) in Bergen. The institute is often
requested by the Government to do studies on policy topics, for instance on the consequences for the
Norwegian aid programme of the entry of Norway into the EU. According to the OECD/EADI(1991) 10
institutes and centres in Norway qualify as Development Research and Training Institutes. 
<p>
The Government's intends to foster private sector participation in development cooperation through several
programmes: mixed credits for associated financing, guarantees for investments in and exports to developing
countries, investments in economic and social infrastructure for joint ventures with Norwegian private
enterprises, promotion of imports through the Norwegian Import Promotion Office for Products from
Developing Countries (NORIMPO).
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
