<html>
<head>
<title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC">

<a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a>
<small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small>
<hr>


<h3>After the Earth Summit: Implementing sustainable development<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 2, 1995</h3>



<I>In June 1992 at the Rio de Janeiro Earth Summit, the governments of the world committed themselves to put in place a new global partnership for sustainable development. Central to this partnership was the acceptance that both the quantity and quality of aid to the South would have to be raised. Although aid flows have actually fallen since Rio, donors have taken a number of steps to improve the environmental quality of their assistance programmes</I>. 
<p>
Following <A HREF="bp1_gb.html">Briefing No.1</A> which addressed the theory of sustainable development, this Briefing describes the common post-Rio challenges facing donor agencies, and shows  how European donors are implementing sustainable development in their aid operations.
<p>
The need for more and better aid is a central theme of the Agenda 21 action plan for sustainable development agreed at the Earth Summit. Indeed, Agenda 21 estimated that an annual $125 billion in concessional finance is required to help the South shift its development path towards sustainability. But since Rio, recession and new post-Cold War priorities have meant that aid to the South has actually fallen from $60.8 billion in 1992 to $55.9 billion in 1993. This stark reality places even greater importance on ensuring that all available aid is directed effectively at meeting the needs of partner countries in such a way that the needs of future generations are not compromised. 
<p>
The importance of integrating the environment into aid planning and implementation has long been recognised by donor agencies at the policy level, and most have now introduced basic environmental procedures and managment tools. The Earth Summit builds on these foundations, and shifts the focus of environment and development policy away from simply minimising the negative impacts of aid projects towards designing projects which meet the livelihood needs of the poor within the limits of nature. Implementing this more positive sustainable development agenda creates both opportunities and dilemmas for donor agencies, which are discussed below.

<H3>Reviewing the Implications of Rio</H3>

The Earth Summit&#146;s prescription for sustainable development is both large and complex. The Agenda 21 action plan has 40 chapters, over 100 programme areas and 3000 recommendations, addressing key sectors such as agriculture, industry and urban management, a range of environ-mental priorities such as biodiversity conservation, climate change, desert-ification, hazardous waste, toxic chemicals and water, as well as a a series of cross-cutting issues such as technology transfer, poverty, population and trade. However, no priorities were set and no guidance given on how these broad goals should be translated into operational terms. As a result, donors have to carry out their own review of the implications of UNCED. 
<p>
In the Netherlands, the National Advisory Council for Development has published a comprehensive review of how Dutch aid can be steered towards sustainable development. Its starting point is the the principle of &#145;environmental space&#146;, whereby each person should have equal rights to the Earth&#146;s limited carrying capacity to meet his or her needs. Globally, development policy should be focused at reducing the differences in access to environmental space between North and South, while aid should be targeted at removing the structural factors that increase the likelihood of environmental damage in the South, such as inequalities in property rights, access to resources and involvement in decision-making between men and women. 
<p>
In Sweden, the Ministry for Foreign Affairs established a working group on &#145;sustainable aid&#146;, which has drawn up general principles and sectoral guidelines for improving aid management. According to the group&#146;s report, three key principles for managing aid emerge from the Rio agreements: first, taking a precautionary approach to managing environmental risks; second, ensuring that environmental costs are internalised in project planning so that the &#145;polluter pays&#146;; and third, making environmental impact assessment mandatory for all projects. The importance of policy dialogue with recipient countries was also underlined as being crucial to a proper understanding of their priorities for sustainable development. 

<H3>Reinforcing Environmental Management </H3>

Once donors have developed a clear understanding of the implications of UNCED, attention needs to turn to how their environmental management systems for aid need to be strengthened, so that clear priorities, procedures and responsibilities are established for integrating environmental factors into all development policies and programmes. 
<p>
At the European level,  in June 1993, the Commision adopted a number of  measures to integrate the environment into all of its policies in line with the Treaty on European Union and the Fifth Environmental Action Programme. Each Directorate-General must now assess every policy and project at the design stage for its environmental implications, and carry out an annual evaluation of environmental performance. A high-ranking official in each DG is charged with ensuring that these tasks are carried out, supported by the Environment Directorate. 
<p>
In France, a special protocol of cooperation between the Ministries of Environment and Development was signed in October 1994. This identifies key principles, objectives and tools to take greater account of the environment in French development cooperation. For example, both ministries are now committed to support joint promotion, awareness-raising and research projects. They also agreed to increase the involvement of  non-governmental organisations and local communities in their work. 

<H3>Assessing Environmental Impacts </H3>

UNCED reaffirmed that environmental impact assessment (EIA) is a  precondition for ensuring that aid is directed at long-term sustainable development. The OECD has had guidelines for good practice in environmental impact assessment and in 1993 the Commission introduced its own Environment Manual based on this and Member State experience. The aim of the Manual is to guide decision-makers in the Commission and ACP partner countries on how to integrate environmental factors at each stage of the project cycle from conception to final evaluation. The participation of local people in EIAs is crucial for success, since they are often the best source of environmental information. 
<p>
In 1994, the Danish aid agency, DANIDA, issued a new EIA manual, Environmental Assessment for Sustainable Development to ensure that all activities are designed and implemented in full compliance with relevant national and international environmental laws and standards.  For DANIDA, environmental assessment has a two-fold role: 
<ul>
First, to find ways of preventing, mitigating or compensating for negative environmental impacts; and 
<p>
Second, to identify ways of promoting, enhancing or capitalising on positive environmental impacts. 
<p></ul>
The DANIDA Manual also states that the aim is "to improve development, not prevent it", although it recognises that some still see environment assessment as "anti" development or opposed to growth. Without environmental assessment, there will always be the risk that development in one sector will occur at the expense of development in another sector or at the cost of imposing a burden on future generations, or in other words, development that will not be sustainable. 

<H3>Deciding on Priority Investments </H3>

Integrating the environment into every aspect of the aid portfolio is a necessary, but not a sufficient condition for promoting sustainable development in partner countries. Explicit investments into environment priority areas also have to be made to restore past damage, manage current resources and prevent  future risks.  
<p>
At the international level, five environmental investment priorities can be identified for donor agencies: the conservation of biodiversity; combatting desertification; sustainable management and conservation of forests; preventing climate change; and managing the trade in hazardous waste and toxic chemicals. But it is at the country level in the South that specific priorities should emerge, preferably through a national sustainable development strategy process, as recommended by Agenda 21. In general terms, post-Rio national-level priorities could include issues such as sustainable agriculture, water conservation and management, energy efficiency and renewables, cleaner industrial production, sustainable transport, environ-mental health in cities and coastal zone management.
<p>
The main role for investing in international environmental priorities has been asigned to the  Global Environment Facility (GEF), set up in 1991 and managed by the World Bank, the United Nations Environment Programme and the United Nations Development Programme. The GEF provides a multilateral financing mechanism for implementing the Rio agreements in developing countries, and was recently restructured with $2 billion to fund projects in four priority areas: biodiversity, climate change, international waters and ozone depletion.  
<p>
Bilateral donors have also reviewed their environmental investment priorities in light of Rio. In France, the Ministry of Development Cooperation has drawn up an environmental action plan, which emphasises the importance of improving environmental capacities through training and awareness raising, alongside specific activities for the management of coastal zones, protected areas and tropical forests. French cooperation in Africa is also directed at combatting desertification, tackling urban waste, managing water for rural and urban areas, and conserving biological diversity. The UK ODA has developed strategies for each of its four post-Rio environmental priorities, energy efficiency, forest management, biodiversity and sustainable agriculture. For example, the energy strategy marks a shift from funding new generating capacity to supporting more efficient production and use of energy.

<H3>Measuring Flows to Sustainable Development </H3>

Effective and accurate statistical information on aid flows is needed to track performance against policy priorities. Defining what is &#145;environmental&#146; can be problematic, however since many aid projects integrate social, economic and environmental objectives. The EC categorises environmental projects into four groups, varying according to the proportion of spending going to the environmental objective. In 1993,  about 9% of the EC&#146;s programmable aid was spent on the environment, mainly on integrated rural development, water management, environmental education, biodiversity and forest projects. France, meanwhile, has decided on five main categories of environmental spending: health, water, rural development and natural resources, urban management, industry and communications, and energy, which account for 15 % of aid from the French Ministry of Cooperation in 1993. 
<p>
For German development cooperation, the definition of what is environmental is limited to projects whose objectives are both predominantly and directly targeted at the protection of the human environment and natural resources. Environmental projects would thus include sustainable resource management, anti-desertification, reduction of firewood consumption and sewage disposal, but not promotion of increased agricultural production, provision of drinking water supply or integrated plant protection. Between 1990 and 1993, the proportion of environmental projects in German aid varied between 20 and 25 per cent.

<H3>Developing Environmental Capacities </H3>

Implementing environmental priorities in the South depends on partner countries having the necessary human, technological and institutional capacities in the public, private and civil sectors. The OECD has recently adopted guidelines on capacity development in environment (CDE), which outlines the limited, supporting  role that donors can play in reinforcing environmental capacities: "only those who directly hold a stake in the environment in a given circumstance can make processes sustainable&#148;, it says. 
<p>
Donors can provide financial assistance for a range of activities, including public education and awareness raising, training in corporate environmental management, support to community-based institutions, and advice on environmental policy making and implementation.  NGOs can often be a driving force for capacity development since they can reach groups of the population which are otherwise difficult to involve, improve knowledge and influence attitudes, create political acceptance for longer-term thinking and contribute with examples of practical alternatives. 
<p>
Germany&#146;s capacity development efforts are channelled through the German Foundation for International Development (DSE) and the Carl Duisberg Gesellschaft. The DSE provides environmental training for Southern government officials and NGOs, focusing on environmental law and economic instruments, environmental management techniques (including conflict prevention), environmental planning and environmental monitoring. The Carl Duisberg Gesellschaft, which is supported by German business and industry, has introduced a new water quality training programme and given a special role to  environmental management training for industry. 

<H3>Taking a More Participatory Approach</H3>

Agenda 21 stresses that the participation of local communities is a prerequisite for sustainable development. Participation leads to long-term sustainability because it results in projects that are more likely to meet the needs of beneficiaries and fit with their cultural norms, and because it gives local people a greater sense of project ownership. Empirical evidence increasingly suggests that long-term economic and environmental revitalisation occurs when people&#146;s ideas and knowledge are valued through  their active involvement in project planning and implementation.  
<p>
Since UNCED, donors have been increasingly investing in participatory and community-based initiatives. The transition to a more &#145;bottom-up&#146; approach in EC programmes has already begun with the introduction of the logical framework approach and the promotion of decentralised cooperation. More than half of the programming guidelines for Lom&#233; IV-bis stressed the need for participation, notably environment, sustainable development and social analysis, women, water, forestry, urban development, the private sector, employment, fisheries and tourism. The UK Overseas Development Agency (ODA) has introduced operational guidelines on participation, and as well as using participatory techniques for certain projects, the ODA is trying to change its overall development culture through the adoption of a participatory working method known as &#145;team-up methodology&#146;, where projects are formulated and stakeholders identified through broad in-house participation.
<p>
Only a few donors, such as the World Bank, have yet evaluated their experience with participatory techniques. An informal Learning Group on Participatory Development within the Bank has carried a progress review. This found that a number of projects classified as  &#145;participatory&#146; did not really involve local people, and that while  participation increases up-front costs, namely through increased staff time, these are outweighed by the benefits, such as increased incomes of stakeholders. The Bank has now adopted a participation source book with information on different sectors, and is now examining how to turn it into a standard procedure. 
<p>
<center><table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><b><center>Using Participatory Techniques for Soil and Water Conservation in Kenya</b></center><p>The Kenyan government&#146;s Soil and Water Conservation Branch (SWCB) supported by SIDA has adopted participatory procedures to mobilise local communities for resource conservation.  The intention is for local communities to be involved in the analysis of their own farming and conservation problems, and for decisions and recommendations to be made with their active participation. The SWCB&#146;s Catchment Approach has resulted in widespread, sustainable improvements in soil and water resources. It has been successful not only because it has applied participatory methods, but because these have been supported by institutional changes, including backing from senior Kenyan officials, a tranformation of the role the extension worker from teacher to learner and the transfer of responsibility for conservation activities to local communities.</td></tr></table></center><p>


<H3>Accounting for Environmental Performance </H3>

A key theme running throughout the Earth Summit agreements is the need for greater public involvement in policy making at the local, national and international levels. Within the United Nations system, a new Commission for Sustainable Development (CSD) has been set up to monitor the implementation of the Rio agreements. So far, the CSD has held three sessions, at which governments (including most EU Member States) have delivered reports on their performance; a full-scale review of Agenda 21 will be carried out in 1997. At the country level, a number of EU Member States have introduced consultative mechanisms, roundtables or national commissions to maintain the Rio momentum by bringing together the many diverse groups with a stake in sustainable development (eg government officials, politicians, business and labour groups, academia and NGOs). At the European level, a Consultative Forum on the Environment has been established, but this has yet to turn its attention to development cooperation policies. 
<p>
Increased public reporting of environmental performance is an important feedback mechanism and stimulus to improvement. Here, the World Bank has been the pioneer, producing  its first annual environmental report in 1990. The latest report on fiscal year 1994, Making Development Sustainable, runs to over 250 pages, and provides a comprehensive picture of the Bank&#146;s environmental policies and activitities, its lessons and performance. The report is complemented by a new Bank information policy which allows public access to summary environmental information for its projects, including through the Internet: by June 1994, the Bank was receiving approximately 3000 Internet requests for environmental information each week. Some European donors have published material designed to raise public awareness of the Earth Summit agreements. Belgium&#146;s Administration General de la Cooperation au Developpment has produced, Between Apocalypse and Utopia (Entre L&#146;Apocalypse et L&#146;Utopie), a pamphlet aimed at young people which reviews the main themes of Agenda 21, while La Documentation Fran&#231;aise has published, Planet Earth in Our Hands (La plan&#232;te Terre entre nos mains), a useful handbook which summarises the main outcomes of Rio for civil society, including local authorities, companies and NGOs.  

<H3>Designing Innovative Aid Agreements</H3>

Ensuring that mainstream aid programmes contribute to sustainable development will take time. Alongside this, donors need to explore new models of cooperation that allow for experimentation and innovation. The Netherlands has perhaps gone furthest with its Bilateral Sustainable Development Agreements, signed in March 1994 with the governments of Bhutan, Benin and Costa Rica. The agreements have been designed to break with tradition and are guided by the principles of reciprocity, equity and participation. Thus, the agreements focus on reforms in domestic Dutch policies as well as supporting initiatives in the South. For example, in the agreement with Benin the focus is on the export of "clean" cotton to the Netherlands, and ways in which Benin can be compensated for the higher production costs of more sustainable cotton production.
<p>
Taken together these nine post-Rio priorities for donor agencies represent a substantial shift in "business as usual" attitudes to development cooperation. But they should not be viewed as additional burdens or constraints on aid management. Rather, they offer ways in which aid can become more effective by aiming for the long-term.
<p>
<I>This briefing was prepared by Nick Robins, Coordinator of the European Programme at IIED. He was special adviser to the Environment Directorate of the European Commission in the run-up to the Earth Summit, and has written widely on UNCED and environmental management.</I>






<p>
<hr>

