<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>Urban environment: Out of control?<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 7, 1995</h3>

<I>The enormous scale of urban problems in the South is well known.  According to the World Health Organization, at least 600 million people live in urban areas with such a lack of basic services and with housing of such poor quality that their lives and health are continually under threat. However, the popular image of the uncontrolled growth of large numbers of mega-cities is at odds with reality.  
<p>
This briefing document stresses that environmental problems in urban areas are not so much the result of rapid population growth but more the failure of governments and aid agencies to adapt their policies to rapid economic, social and urban change.  The two urban priorities are first, to increase the capacity, competence and accountability of city and municipal governments and second, to channel more support direct to community or neighbourhood level organizations or initiatives</I>. 
<p>
<H3>The Urban Population in the South </H3>

By 1990, the urban populaiton in the South totalled around 1.4 billion.  This was already more than the total population of East and West Europe, Russia, North America and Japan combined (All population statistics are given for 1990 since the latest census data available is generally from censuses held between 1989 and 1991. Virtually all urban statistics for 1995 are estimates or projections based on older data).  Yet it still represented only 35 percent of the Souths total population.  <I>Most of this population was in urban centres with less than one million inhabitants</I> - see Table 1. A considerable proportion was in small  market towns and local government administrative and service centres.  Mega-cities housed only a few percent of the Souths total population and most countries have no mega-city.    
<p>
Urbanization is also closely linked to economic growth.  The largest urban populations and the largest cities are concentrated in the largest economies.  Of the eight mega-cities in the South with 10 million or more inhabitants in 1990, six were in its four largest economies - China and India (with two each) and Brazil and Mexico.  These four countries also had nearly half of all the cities in the South with a million or more inhabitants.  In general, the higher the per capita income of a country, the higher the level of urbanization - and all the lowest income nations are also among the least urbanized. 

<H3>Urbanization out of control?</H3>

The period since 1950 has brought very rapid growth in urban populations to virtually all regions in the South.  This includes new forms of cities, some of unprecedented size.  The population of many cities has grown more than tenfold since 1950 including Abidjan, Amman, Brasilia, Dar es Salaam, Khartoum, Kinshasa, Lagos, Nairobi, and Seoul.  However, there is also considerable continuity as more than half of the Souths major cities today were already important cities 200 years ago. The rate at which the South is urbanizing has slowed, especially during the 1980s.  Many large cities there had much reduced population growth rates during the 1980s.  Recent censuses also showed that many of the largest cities in the South had populations that were several million people less than estimates made only a few years previously. The main reason has been economic stagnation; virtually all the countries that continued to urbanize rapidly during the 1980s were also those that had high economic growth rates.
<p>
<center><h4>Table 1: The Souths Urban Population in 1990</h4>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><td>Total Population (millions)<td>Number of urban agglomerations<td>Percent of total urban populations</td>
<tr><td>10 million plus inhabitants<td>98.5<td>8<td>6.9</td>
<tr><td>5 - 9.99 million inhabitants<td>113.3<td>15<td>		   7.9
<tr><td>1-4.99 million inhabitants<td>280.2	      <td>  148	<td>	 19.5
<tr><td>Less than one million	<td>943.5	<td>c. 30,000		<td> 65.7
<tr><td>Total urban population<td>1,435.5<td><td>100.0

</td></tr></table>
</center><p>
Where cities grow rapidly, attracting large numbers of migrants, there are always economic, social or political changes underlying such rapid growth.  Economic change is the dominant influence on the level of urbanization and the size of cities.  In most countries, the increase in the proportion of the population living in urban areas reflects the increase in the size of the economy and the increasing importance of urban-based manufacturing and services.  Political change has also been important, especially in sub-Saharan Africa where most countries only gained political independence in the last four decades.  Independence brought an enormous boost to urbanization, as most colonial regimes had deliberately kept down urban populations and as newly independent governments had to build the institutions that are part of a modern nation-state.  The expansion of higher education also boosted urban growth.  So did the possibility of women and children living with their partners in urban areas; most colonial regimes had forbidden or discouraged this to keep down urban populations and the costs of housing the urban labour force.  Thus, a large part of Africas urban explosion over the last forty years has been because it began from such a small base in the 1950s and had been kept so low.
<P>
Urban change in sub-Saharan Africa is often considered out-of-control but the scale and direction of rural to urban migration flows reflect where economic opportunities (or chances of survival) are better.  No-one knows the precise dimensions of urban change in much of Africa, as no recent censuses are available for many countries, and as wars and civil strife have caused large population displacements.  But in countries where recent census data are available, most major cities had much lower population growth rates during the 1980s than in the 1960s and 1970s.  This usually reflects poor economic performance - and also rising levels of urban poverty and cuts in public employees (or their wage levels) that were linked to structural adjustment.  The main exceptions were cities that became major centres for refugees or people displaced by wars, so these grew rapidly, without economic growth.

<H3>Urban Environmental Challenges</H3>

The rapid growth in the urban population has occurred without the needed expansion in the services and facilities essential to a healthy urban environment - piped water, sanitation and storm drainage, all weather roads and pavements, services to collect and dispose of garbage, schools and health centres, and adequate numbers of serviced housing sites.  The capacity of most city and municipal governments has hardly increased, even when the number of people within their boundaries has multiplied many times.  Most such governments have little or no investment capacity; many cannot even maintain existing infrastructure and services, let alone expand and improve them.  
<P>
The result is that in virtually every urban centre - from the large cities and metropolitan areas to regional centres and small market towns - a large proportion of the population lives in houses and neighbourhoods with little or no provision for basic infrastructure and services.  Most also live in poor quality housing - for instance whole households living in one or two rooms in cramped, overcrowded dwellings such as tenements, cheap boarding houses or shelters built on illegally occupied or sub-divided land.  Most urban centres that have grown rapidly have 30-60 percent of their population living in illegal or informal settlements.  Cities in the South face three pressing environmental challenges: greatly improving water supply; sanitation and solid waste collection and disposal; reducing other environmental hazards that are major causes of illness, injury and premature death; and reducing gender-based discrimination in health care and service provision.
<ul>
<li>WATER SUPPLY:  Hundreds of millions of urban dwellers still have no alternative but to use contaminated water or water whose quality is not guaranteed. Their water generally comes from streams or other surface sources that are often little more than open sewers.  Or water is purchased from vendors but its quality is not guaranteed and its price per litre is usually many times that paid by richer households for publicly provided piped supplies. Hundreds of millions of people rely on safer but still inconvenient supplies - for instance public standpipes, yard taps, or wells.   There is often only one tap or water-pump for dozens or even hundreds of households. Long queues at a public tap (especially if water is only available for a few hours a day) and time spent making repeated trips to and from the house with water containers uses up time that could be used in earning an income.  It also makes it impossible to obtain sufficient water for washing and laundry.
<p>
<li>SANITATION:  At least a third of the Souths urban population have no provision for sanitation; many defecate on the street or open sites. A much larger proportion lack adequate sanitation in the sense of toilets that  minimize the possibility of human contact with  excreta and that are easy to keep clean; more than three fifths of the urban population are not connected to public sewer systems.  This is not only the smaller cities; many major cities with a million or more inhabitants have no sewers at all.
<p>
Official statistics on water and sanitation greatly overstate the proportion of urban dwellers with adequate provision. For instance, households who have to share public taps with dozens of other households with the taps some distance from their home - and where the taps are often broken - are usually classified by governments as having adequate supplies.  Millions of households who are classified by governments as having access to sanitation simply have pit latrines - and each such latrine is often shared by dozens of households. Where these are not cleaned regularly and maintained - which is usually the case - the use of such latrines may constitute a greater health hazard for those using them than defecating outside. Many people defecate in the open, thus posing very serious health problems for all those living in the neighbourhood. 
<p>
<li>SOLID WASTES:  Most urban authorities fail to collect between a third and a half of the solid wastes generated by households and commercial enterprises.  In many urban centres in sub-Saharan Africa, only 10-20 percent of the solid wastes are collected.  Most informal or illegal settlements have no publicly provided collection service at all.  Uncollected wastes accumulate on open spaces and along streets or in ditches, bringing serious health problems.  They block drainage ditches and exacerbate flooding.  They provide breeding and feeding grounds for disease vectors. 
<p>
<li>OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARDS: A high proportion of the urban population also suffer from respiratory and other diseases caused or exacerbated by biological or chemical agents in the air. These include indoor air pollutants from the use of coal or biomass fuel in open fires or poorly vented stoves as well as ambient air pollution from emissions from industries, thermal power stations and motor vehicles. A high proportion of the urban population are also exposed to unnecessary chemical and physical hazards in their homes and workplaces.  Few governments give a priority to promoting health and safety at work or to enforcing environmental legislation on air and water pollution and the dumping of solid wastes.  In very few industrial centres is there adequate attention to the treatment and safe storage of hazardous wastes. The lack of attention to pollution control often creates serious ecological impacts in the wider region - for instance water pollution damaging or destroying local fisheries or, for major industrial centres, acid precipitation damaging vegetation and water bodies.
<p>
<li>HEALTH: In most urban areas in the South,  there is a huge and easily preventable burden of injury and disease that is the result of the deficiencies in housing, water supply, sanitation and drainage noted above - combined with inadequate or no provision for health services.  This is especially so in most of sub-Saharan Africa and in the lower income nations in Asia and Latin America.  For instance, recent estimates by the World Bank and the World Health Organization suggest that the disease burden per person in sub-Saharan Africa from diarrhoeal diseases is around 200 times larger than in Europe or North America. 
<p>
<li>GENDER:  Women generally suffer more than men from poor quality and overcrowded housing and from the inadequacies in infrastructure and services because they have sole or primary responsibility for child-rearing and for managing the household.  For instance, it is generally women who are responsible for water collection and who need it to undertake the laundry, cooking and washing of children so their task is much greater if supplies are contaminated or difficult to obtain.  It is generally women (or girls) who tend fires and cook so where smoky fuels are used in open fires or poorly vented stoves, they inhale the largest concentrations of pollutants.  Much of the urban population in the South have no health care service within their locality. This greatly increases the problems faced by those who take responsibility for caring for family members who are sick or injured - again, this is usually womens responsibility.  No health care - or a health care system that does not address the needs of mothers - underlies the very high rates of maternal mortality. In some countries, the proportion of women who die in childbirth is 1000 times that in the North.  As a result, each year, millions of children are left without mothers which obviously greatly reduces their chances of healthy development. 
</ul><p>
<H3>The need for good governance</H3>

The main reason for the urban problems described above is not the scale of population growth but the failure of governments and aid agencies to develop appropriate policies.  What all countries need is city and municipal authorities with a growing capacity, competence and accountability in managing urban development.  This includes the power and institutional framework to control pollution, guide urban growth, maintain the urban fabric and ensure infrastructure and services expand to meet growing population.  The reasons why this has not happened vary from country to country - but they include:
<ul>
<li>the failure of post-colonial governments in much of Africa and Asia to change the colonial legacy that left laws, institutions and structures that were wholly inappropriate for the resolution of such problems;
<p>
<li>the reluctance of national governments to permit city and municipal authorities to develop the capacity, competence and revenue base they need to address urban problems; 
<p>
<li>solutions imported from the North that have proved inappropriate to local priorities and circumstances; 
<p>
<li>an unwillingness to invest in urban areas because of a (generally inaccurate) belief that there is an urban bias in development investments<A NAME="n1"></A>(<A HREF="#1">note 1</A>) or that improving urban housing and living conditions will stimulate more rural to urban migration;<A NAME="n2"></A>(<A HREF="#1">note 2</A>) 
<p>
<li>a failure to encourage and support community or neighbourhood initiatives, which can contribute much to reducing problems at relatively low cost, without making heavy demands on limited government capacity.
</ul><p>
In the lower-income countries, the only long term solution to urban problems will be when governments and aid agencies find ways to support the initiatives of individuals, households, communities and municipalities in developing solutions that match local needs and priorities and make best use of local knowledge and resources. 
<p>
Good governance with its stress on increased accountability and decentralization can also reduce the concentration of urban population in national capitals. One reason why national capitals are often so much larger than all other urban centres is the highly centralized nature of the government and the need for businesses to have close personal contacts with national politicians or officials.  Increasing the competence and capacity of city authorities in secondary cities will also help them ensure their city can compete with capital cities for new investments. 
<p>
<H3>The advantages of cities</H3>

Cities have enormous potential for combining high living standards with low-energy, low resource-use, minimum waste lifestyles. The fact that cities concentrate production and population gives them some obvious advantages over rural settlements or dispersed population.  
<ul>
<li>High densities mean much lower costs per household for the provision of piped, treated water supplies, the collection and disposal of household and human wastes, advanced telecommunications and most forms of health, educational and emergency services. 
<p>
<li>The concentration of production and consumption in cities means a greater range and possibility for efficient use of resources - through material reclamation, recycling and reuse and for the specialist enterprises that ensure this can happen safely.  
<p>
<li>A much higher population concentration in cities means a reduced demand for land relative to population. In most countries, urban areas take up less than one percent of the national territory. 
<p>
<li>Cities represent a much greater potential for limiting the use of motor vehicles and the fossil fuels they need through walking or bicycling or greater use of public transport.
</ul>
<H3>Building Cities from the Bottom Up</H3>

Most new housing and residential areas in urban areas of the South are built from the bottom up by low income groups - even if governments deem most such efforts as illegal.  In recent years, many governments have become more tolerant and some have sought to support this process. This can bring major improvements in living conditions and environmental quality at a relatively low cost.  Among the most important lessons from past experience with supporting this process are: 
<ul>
<li>Outside interventions must be guided by inhabitants needs and priorities and take full account of the limitations on the time and resources that they can contribute;
<p>
<li>There is no replicable model - although there are common principles. The population of each squatter settlement, illegal subdivision or tenement district will have its own needs and priorities;
<p>
<li>Successful community based projects not only achieve tangible goals but also increase the inhabitants confidence and capacity to organize and these are essential in ensuring that progress is sustained. 
</ul><p>
Support for building cities from the bottom up implies not only new priorities for external agencies but also new means of delivering it.  One new model for assistance that is now being widely discussed is a fund that can support a great variety of initiatives, including many that require very modest levels of funding.  Such a fund must also be able to respond rapidly to funding requests.  It may also need to help community groups to develop proposals for funding.
<p>
For donors, therefore, the two urban priorities are first, to increase the capacity, competence and accountability of city and municipal governments and second, to channel more support direct to community or neighbourhood level organizations or initiatives.  Both can combine economic, social and environmental goals and many can address all three simultaneously.  Both have relevance for large cities and small market towns. These priorities fit well with Lomé IVs emphasis on an integrated approach to environment and development and a need to strengthen institutional capacity locally.  They also fit well with Agenda 21s emphasis on capacity building (including the need for each urban centre to develop its own Local Agenda 21) and with the early drafts for the Global Plan of Action for Habitat II, the second UN Conference on Human Settlements to be held in Istanbul in June 1996. 
<p>
<A NAME="1"></A><H3>Notes</H3>
Note 1. In most countries, it is only the major cities (and often only the national capital) that has benefitted from urban bias; most small urban centres have been as starved of public investment and support as most rural areas.  And the main beneficiaries of such a bias were middle and upper income groups. <A HREF="#n1">Return to Text</A>.
<p>
Note 2. For virtually all ACP countries and in most others, it is better economic opportunities in urban areas or better chances of survival that underlie rural-to-urban migration.  Improving basic services in urban areas will not stimulate increased rural-to-urban migration and it will also help lower fertility rates in urban areas.  This is not to say that priority should be given to basic services in urban areas; what is needed is a higher priority to basic services in both rural and urban areas. <A HREF="#n2">Return to Text</A>.
<p>
<I>David Satterthwaite is Director of the Human Settlements Programme at IIED.  He is co-author of Environmental Problems in Third World Cities (with Jorge Hardoy and Diana Mitlin - Earthscan, London, 1992 and of Squatter Citizen: Life in the Urban Third World (with Jorge Hardoy), Earthscan, 1989.  He has worked with UNICEF, WHO and the U.N. Centre for Human Settlements on urban environmental issues and was an advisor on urban issues to the Brundtland Commission (The World Commission on Environment and Development).</I>
<p><hr><small>©Copyright:IIED 1995</small><p><TABLE BORDER=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="index.html"><img src="pix/home.gif" width=100 height=43 alt="Home Page"></a></TD></TR></TABLE></body></html>
