<p>
<a href="http://www.nmis.org/Gate/">The Gate of Heavenly Peace</a>.  An excellent
documentary on the protests of Tiananmen Square in 1989 and the Beijing Massacre of
June 4.  The film explores the history and political culture of China, and combines
it with a penetrating vision into the democratic rebellion of 1989 and its bloody
aftermath.<br>
<a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/balkans/mandy.html">War Crimes Against Women - Caling
the Ghosts</a>. Shown at the International Human Rights Film Festival in New York and
London, this is a film about rape, war and women.  It is the 
story of Jadranka Cigelj and Nusreta Sivac, 'ordinary modern women' in Bosnia until
their neighbours raped and tortured them in the Serb concentration camp Omarska.<br>
<a href="http://www.freespeech.org/index.html">Free Speech TV</a>.  Billing itself as
'a progressive voice in the media revolution', Free Speech TV is a US cable network
delivered to more than 6 million households.  Featuring the best of activist,
community-based and alternative media, Free Speech TV also has a strong commitment to
Internet broadcasting - with VDO and RealAudio available.
