<HTML>
<head>
<title>OneWorld RealAudio</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#b2aab3" link="#ffffff" alink="#C0C0C0" vlink="#C0C0C0">


<center><br>

<h3>realaudio features and interviews</h3>

<p></center>

<center>
<font size=+1> <a href="../news/news_realaudio.html">RealWhat?</a></center><p>


<b><font size=+1><a href="../unicef/progress/sharma.ram">Dr Monica Sharma on women's health</a></font></b><p>

<ul>One in every four women in the developing world dies or is disabled through pregnancy and childbirth, according to the 1996 Progress of Nations Report.  UNICEF UK's Stacey Adams spoke to co-author of the report Dr Monica Sharma about the facts behind this shocking statistic.<br>
See UNICEF's <b><a href="../unicef/progress/summary.html">Progress of Nations Report</a></b> section.<br>
<font size=2>Picture ©Copyright: <b>UNICEF</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>



<b><font size=+1><a href="../news/land_action/may96_land.html">Land Rights in Brazil</a></font></b><p>

<ul>Brazil has recently passed a decree which leaves vast swathes of land - occupied for centuries by indigenous peoples - open to cattle ranchers, miners and loggers.  This will result in genocide and ecological catastrophe, say many observers. Oxfam's Francis McDonagh spoke to the OneWorld News Service about attempts to persuade the Brazilian government to protect indigenous land rights.<br>

<font size=2>Picture ©Copyright: <b>Mark Edwards</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../oxfam/clothes/clothes1.ram">Oxfam's Clothes Code Campaign</a></font></b><p>

<ul>Is your sweatshirt made in a sweatshop?  Chances are it is - if it comes from the Dominican Republic.  Estela is a worker in a Dominican garments factory, where women are paid 20-50% less than men.  She has worked there for several years.  "Conditions in the factories are pretty bad," she says.  I was sacked from one factory because I was ill for a few days."<br>
See Oxfam's <b><a href="../oxfam/clothes/index.html">Clothes Code Campaign</a></b> section.<br>
<font size=2>Picture ©Copyright: <b>Oxfam</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../news/land_action/index.html">Land Rights in the UK: The Land is Ours</a></font></b><p>

<ul>Take a trip to Wandsworth in South London, where land rights activists are building a sustainable village, with gardens, farms and community projects.  The OneWorld News Service was there, and interviews are available with activists George Monbiot, Jim Paton, 'Lion' and journalist John Vidal.<br>
<font size=2>Picture ©Copyright: <b>OneWorld</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>


<b><font size=+1><a href="../owbt/awards/index.html">One World '96 Conference and Media Awards</a></font></b><p>

<ul>The One World Broadcasting Trust's annual conference this year featured contributions from Martyn Gregory, Dr Owens Wiwa, Michael Ignatieff and others, who addressed the topic of impartiality in broadcasting.  The whole day's discussions and speeches are available in RealAudio 2.0 format.  Also on offer is RealAudio of the Awards ceremony, which picked out the best in the British and overseas media.<br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b>BBC</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../scf/scf_movs/scf_vietnam.ram">SCF Case Study: Phuong in Vietnam</a></font></b><p>

<ul>Phuong is 18 months old, and lives with her parents, two sisters and a grandmother in Hungo Dao Commune, Haiphong Province, Vietnam.  Last month she got sick, reports Save the Children Fund, who are campaigning for better health care facilities for children around the world.</ul>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../scf/scf_movs/scf_ghana.ram">SCF Case Study: Mobile healthcare in Ghana</a></font></b><p>
<ul>Few people in Ghana live within reach of health care services, so Save the Children is working witht the government to use the nationwide transport system to bridge this gap.</ul>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../scf/scf_movs/scf_mozambique.ram">SCF Case Study: Antonio in Mozambique</a></font></b><p>
<ul>Antonio is ten and paraplegic, because he didn't get the crucial vaccines as a baby and developed polio.  Save the Children is helping him become mobile, and has set up an immunisation team to travel the area protecting children from preventable diseases.
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b>Save the Children</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../unicef/mitidieri/realaudio.html">Children at war</a></font></b><p>

<ul>Photographer Dario Mitidieri went to Bosnia, supported by UNICEF UK.  His pictures were published by newspapers and magazines around the world.  Here he is interviewed about his impressions of Bosnia's children, by UNICEF's Stacey Adams.<br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b>Dario Mitidieri</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../news/partner_news/newbury.html">The protests against the Newbury bypass</a></font></b><p>

<ul>The protests against the new bypass around the British town of Newbury are challenging the UK's whole model of development.  Is it right to tear down trees and flatten countryside to make a new road, when traffic reduction policies could have the same effect?  Or do cars and lorries take priority for economic reasons?  The <b>OneWorld News Service</b> spoke to Friends of the Earth's Tony Juniper.<br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b>OneWorld Online</b></font><br clear=left><br></ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../unicef/icdb/index.html">UNICEF's International Children's Day of Broadcasting</a></font></b><p>

<ul>On Sunday 10 December <b>UNICEF</b> urged broadcasters across the world to 'tune into kids'.  To lead the way, <b>UNICEF</b> is broadcasting several RealAudio features aimed at children on their OneWorld Web site.  These include a peace message from the Girl Guides of India and what kids want the world to be like when they (like <b>UNICEF</b>) reach fifty.<br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b><a href="../unicef/index.html">UNICEF UK</a></b></font><br clear=left><br>
</ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../unicef/sowc/index.html">UNICEF's State of the World's Children Report</a></font></b><p>

<ul>This year <b>UNICEF UK</b> hosted the launch of the State of the World's Children Report in London.  A parallel launch was conducted on <b>UNICEF UK's OneWorld</b> Web site, containing video clips and a RealAudio recording of <b>UNICEF</b>'s Executive Director Carol Bellamy speaking on the impact of war on children - the main theme of this year's Report.<br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b><a href="../unicef/index.html">UNICEF UK</a></b></font><br clear=left><br>
</ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../unicef/realaudio_machel.html">Gra&ccedil;a Machel: The Impact of Conflict on Children</a></font></b><p>

<ul>In the past decade UNICEF estimates that 2 million children have been killed in wars, and at least 10 million traumatised.  Hundreds of thousands more are forced into joining armies and militias.  A RealAudio recording of Mrs Machel's address to <b>UNICEF UK</b>'s Annual General Meeting on 20 November 1995. <br>
<font size=-1>Picture ©Copyright: <b><a href="../unicef/index.html">UNICEF UK</a></b></font><br><br clear=left>
</ul><br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../realaudio/palmer_bosnia/index.html">Interactive Interviews: John Palmer in Bosnia</a></font><p></b>

<ul>In July of this year, the Bosnian Serbs launched an all-out attack on the UN 'safe havens' of Srebrenica and Zepa in Eastern Bosnia.  Thousands of Muslim men were slaughtered by the victorious Serb army, while thousands more women and children became refugees.  <b>John Palmer</b> was <b>Oxfam's Communications Manager</b> in Tuzla, where the largest refugee camps were set up.<br>
<font size=-1>Photo ©Copyright: Word Pictures Productions Ltd</font><br><br clear=left>

<a name="wei">
</ul>
<p>
<br clear=all>


<b><font size=+1><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/index_oc/index_movs/wei.ram">Endangered Writers: the story of Wei Jingsheng</a></font></b><p>


<ul>As part of <b>Index on Censorship's</b> 'Endangered Writers' series, Frank Ortega tells the story of one Chinese journalist who suffered for his outspokenness. <br><font size=-1>Cartoon by  <a href="../index_oc/cartoon.html">Naji Al-ali</a> </font><br clear=left><br>

</ul>
<p>
<br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/scf/scf_movs/scf_mines.ram">Landmines: the hidden killers</a></font></b><p>


<ul>Cambodia has seven million land-mines, about two for every child. They kill or
   injure some 300 people a month, 50 per cent bleeding to death where they fall.  Audio track taken from <b>Save the Children's</b> video 'A Lethal Harvest'.<br><font size=-1>Photo ©Copyright: Save the Children Fund</font><br><br clear=left>

</ul>
<br clear=all>

<b><font size=+1><a href="../comic/lenny_henry/index.html">Interactive Interviews: Lenny Henry</a></font></b><p>



<ul>The first of our Interactive Interviews features British comedian Lenny Henry answering questions on the role played by <b>Comic Relief</b> in alleviating famine.<br><font size=-1>Photo ©Copyright: OneWorld Online</font><br><br clear=left>


</ul><br clear=all>





<font size=-1>
<b>OneWorld Online</b> wishes to thank the <b><a href="http://kmi.open.ac.uk/">Knowledge Media Institute of the Open University,</a></b> who are hosting our RealAudio features.</font><p>
