<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation and Policy in Europe</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><IMG SRC  = "../images/eu.jpg"><p>
Conseil des ministres de la coop&#233;ration au d&#233;veloppement<br>de l'Union europ&#233;enne
<p>
Rapport (en anglais) de la r&#233;union de juin 1995</h2>

<p>
<hr>

<TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TH><a href="#com"> Compl&#233;mentarit&#233;</a> </TH>
<TH> <a href="#hum"> Droits de l'homme</a> </TH>
<TH> <a href="#reg"> Int&#233;gration r&#233;gionale</a></TH>
<TH> <a href="#str"> Ajustement structurel </a></TH>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<A HREF = "../index.htm#top"><IMG SRC="../images/home.jpg"><br>Retour &#224; la page EUFORIC</a>
<p>
</center>

<p>

<a name="com"><hr><h2><i>Complementarity between the development policies and actions of the Union and of its member states</i></h2></a>
<ol>
<li><b>Development Council Meeting of June 1995</b><br>
The resolution adopted in the follow-up to "Horizon2000" aims at increasing the efficiency
of coordination mechanisms already in place. Ministers stressed the importance of increasing
complementarity for the effectiveness of Member States and Community policies, and
recognised that such complementarity was in no way a threat for national policies.
<ul>
<li>The Resolution of December 1993 will therefore be put into place. Actions required include: 
<li>defining joint sectoral guidelines where necessary; 
<li>holding meetings of experts on sectoral policies; 
<li>testing operational coordination in developing countries; 
<li>coordination at international conferences and meetings. 
</ul><p>
Together with this, regular meetings of Director-Generals for informal discussion of questions
of common interest and follow-up to the coordination and complementarity process will be
implemented.More attention should be given to decentralising the decision-making process at
local level for certain categories of project and programme. The likelihood that co-financing instruments between the Community and the Member States
may assist the complementarity objective should be further studied. 
<p>
Improved coordination should also apply to the aid programming process. Formulating NIPs
for ACP countries and country strategies for the ALA and MED countries should be seen as
an opportunity for a joint examination of the actions of the Community.

</ol>
<p>

<a name="hum"><hr><h2><i>Human Rights</i></h2>
<ol>
<li><b>Development Council Meeting of June 1995</b><br>

The Council adopted a standard clause that will allow the Union to suspend agreements
concluded with third countries as soon as these countries violate human rights. Agreements
in future will include an article requiring the respect of democratic principles and fundamental
human rights as set out in the universal Declaration on Human Rights and the final Helsinki
Act and the Paris Charter. (At roughly the same time, however, the Council proposed to cut
EU budget lines destined for Human Rights work.) 

</ol>

<p>
<a name="reg"><hr><h2><i>Support for regional integration efforts by developing countries</i></h2></a>
<ol>
<li><b>Development Council Meeting of June 1995</b><br>
 

This resolution was taken against the background of the increasing number of initiatives aimed
at regional integration among developing countries.This includes the lowering of barriers to
improve the free movement of goods, services,capital and people.  The Council considers that
regional integration can help to create a favourable general framework provided that:
<ul> 
<li>the institutional framework is both stable and adaptable; 
<li>sufficient openness is maintained towards third countries; 
<li>suitable financial systems are available or are set up; 
<li>the private sector and civil society take an active part in the process of integration; 
<li>the costs and benefits of integration are shared out fairly. 
</ul>
<p>
Support for regional integration must be tailored to the requirements of the countries
concerned,and must not have the effect of discriminating against other countries in the same
region. Development cooperation policy must be based on: 
<ul>
<li>developing capabilities and strengthening institutions; 
<li>support for the private sector. 
</ul>
<p>
The Council notes that the existence of certain trade preferences may be a means of
supporting regional integration. Coordination needs to be stepped up between the Community
and the Member States, with consultation amongst them within international organisations
and at international conferences.
</ol>
<p>
<a name="str"><hr><h2><i>Structural Adjustment</i></h2></a>

<ol>
<li><b>Development Council Meeting of June 1995</b><br>
On the basis of two Commission documents, the first on Community support to structural
adjustment in ACP countries and the second a working document on this policy in the
southern and eastern Mediterranean countries, the Ministers adopted a resolution which puts
forward recommendations to the Commission. 
<p>
According to the resolution, particular attention should continue to be given to more
appropriate conditionality, local capacity for analysis and to taking account of the regional
dimension in the content of certain adjustment programmes. While setting out the improvements made due to the implementation of SAPs, the Council also draws attentions to the inadequacies of the present system. It invited the Commission:
<ul> 
<li>to continue to improve the budget process and maintain adequate levels of investment; 
<li>to ensure that temporary funding is provided for the transitional costs that may accompany
   the costs of placing programmes in a regional trade facilitation or economic integration
   framework;
<li>to assess the impact of the measures concerned on men and women; 
<li>to move from targeting counterpart funds towards more general allocation as soon as
   effective monitoring of the instruments has been achieved; 
<li>to increase the involvement of the States concerned in the monitoring of implementation; 
<li>to ensure greater coherence of Union action in implementing all the Community instruments; 
<li>to take account of external payment obligations when they have a lasting impact on poverty. 
</ul>
<p>
In conclusion, the Council stated that the Community should involve itself more effectively
and harmoniously in support of the structural adjustment process which remains one of the
most important instruments of development cooperation policy. 
</ol>


<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG align=left SRC  = "../images/eustep.jpg"> <i>Source: EUROSTEP News. Mise &#224; jour: 25 avril 1996</i><br>
<p>
