<html><head><title>Box 3</title></head><body bgcolor="#8fbc8f" link="#238e23" alink="#ooffoo" vlink="#4a766e"><hr><h3>Box 3: 'Ideal' ingredients of an agricultural technology information system and related contexts</h3><p>- a widely pervasive and self-financing set of mass-media (radio; television, printed media; video) used in dissemination but also in interactive modes;<p>- a solid and reliable network of communications (road; rail; air; telecommunications; electronic and magnetic media);<p> - a comprehensive and reliable network of input supply, backed up by practical, focused research; the same for the processing and marketing of outputs. All would operate in competitive environments, ensuring responsiveness to farmers' requirements, the provision of related advisory services and the earning of no more than normal profits;<p>- literate, articulate and assertive farmers, capable of interacting individually with elements of the ATS and of organising rapidly and flexibly into groups - whether based on e.g. common property, input acquisition, marketing, processing or the need to lobby policymakers or defend particular interests;<p>- a relatively small public sector extension service, geared to providing services through measures that ensure direct accountability to users: (a) which are not adequately provided by other components of the ATS but which might be charged directly to farmers, e.g. soil testing and related advice; (b) environmental services such as effluent monitoring, which might be financed partly through the fines levied on breaches of regulations; and (c) services to the private sector such as quality control in product processing, health and safety monitoring etc., all of which would be directly chargeable. (In practice, some of these functions might be performed by different regulatory agencies, but the principle of user charges remains intact.) <p><hr></body></html>
