<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/se.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Sweden
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Swedish Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Swedish Development Cooperation</h3>

Official Swedish bilateral and multilateral development cooperation started in the early 1950s, based on a
humanitarian tradition of aid to European countries during World War II, on a strong missionary tradition,
and in the 1960s and 1970s, on many solidarity movements with newly independent countries. The first
Minister of Development Cooperation was appointed in 1954. Public and Parliamentary support for the high
level of development assistance has always been strong. However, since 1991 the political consensus has
been challenged by right wing politicians. This is countered by large media supported information
campaigns by the Government and NGOs. The public, many non-governmental organisations and solidarity
groups, political parties and their youth organisations, and professional organisations are actively and
critically involved in development cooperation.
<p>
In 1968 Sweden set itself a budget target of 1 per cent of GNP, that was actually reached in 1974. This
meant a steady increase in available funds over the years, which sometimes resulted in underspending. Net
official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 2 460 million, which was 1.03 per cent of GNP. In
response to domestic economic constraints the cooperation budgets for 1993 and 1994 have been cut to 0.97
per cent of GNP. Multilateral assistance remains around one-third of the total aid programme. Like other
Nordic countries, Sweden is an important donor to UN institutions, a growing proportion is contributed to
the World Bank and IDA.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Development cooperation in Sweden is ruled by law. In 1962 Parliament approved a law for development
cooperation policy, accompanied by a detailed statement on its objectives. This has been followed over the
years by several specific laws for different components and programmes of development cooperation. The
basic objectives, however, have never been changed. 
<p>
The Minister for Development Cooperation, within the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA), is responsible
for development cooperation policy. The present Minister is a member of the Cabinet. When no Minister for
Development Cooperation is appointed, which happened in the past, a State-Secretary under the MFA is
responsible. The development cooperation budget is not spread over other ministries. One of the three
departments at the MFA, the Department for International Cooperation under an Under-Secretary, is
responsible for supervising the aid programme. It has three divisions, one for policy formulation, planning
and cooperation with multilateral organisations, one for bilateral aid, and a policy planning and budgeting
division. Implementation of the bilateral programme is done by a number of rather independent government
funded agencies under the administration of the MFA. Although over the years several proposals for re-
organisation of the aid administration have been made, some of which have been realised, the general
structure and the basic allocation of responsibilities have not been changed substantially. Presently, a
proposal is made for the merger of the four main implementing agencies: SIDA, BITS, SAREC and
SWEDECORP. A similar proposal was rejected in 1986. Swedish ministries are generally small, they work
through larger implementing agencies.  
<p>
The main executing agency is the Swedish International Development Authority (SIDA), covering
approximately two-thirds of the cooperation budget. SIDA is the oldest and largest implementing agency,
started in 1965. It is responsible for bilateral aid to the programme countries, including financial aid,
recruiting of Swedish experts and NGO-activities. SIDA has field offices in the recipient countries; it sub-
contracts consultants, private organisations and research institutes. The organisation is governed by a 14
member Board, including representatives from political parties, trade unions, NGOs, industry, SIDA and the
MFA. Members of the Board are also on the Standing Committee for Foreign Affairs of the Parliament. 
<p>
The Swedish Agency for Research Cooperation with Developing Countries (SAREC), started in 1975 as an
advisory council for the MFA and was installed in 1979 in its present independent form. SAREC supports
research in developing countries and international research programmes. It focuses on four broad areas:
public health, natural resources and the environment, natural science and technology, and political science. 
<p>
The third agency is the Swedish Agency for International Technical and Economic Cooperation (BITS) that
started in the 1980s. BITS was designed to promote economic and social development in developing
countries and to strengthen Swedish relations with the non-programme countries in particular. It administers
amongst others technical cooperation, mixed credits, and international training programmes. 
<p>
The Swedish International Enterprise Development Cooperation (SWEDECORP) was established in 1991
when Swedfund (for the promotion of joint ventures), and the import promotion office for products from
developing countries (IMPOD), together with parts of the industrial division of SIDA were merged.
SWEDECORP provides services in these three areas: the promotion of imports, the promotion of business
environment, and investments (mainly for joint ventures).
<p>
Three other government related institutes execute a number of specific tasks: the Swedish Institute promotes
cultural exchange activities; the Nordic Institute of African Studies conducts a research and fellowship
programme for Africa, in cooperation with Finland and the Institute for Development Education advises the
Government and trains Swedish development workers.
 
Policy planning is done by the Policy Planning Division at the MFA and by the General Policy Bureau of
SIDA. Since SIDA reports directly to the Government and the Parliament, its contribution to policy
preparation is considerable. Contacts with the MFA for policy coordination evidently exist. Policy planning
is assisted by studies by consultants, research institutes - government related and independent - and NGOs. 
<p>
Policy coordination for development cooperation is mainly an internal affair of the MFA, since the foreign
policy components of all ministries are managed and coordinated by this Ministry. Foreign policy, trade
policy and development cooperation policy are closely integrated. Interministerial consultations take place
between the MFA and the Ministry of Agriculture that handles specific aspects of environmental policy, and
the Ministry of Education that is responsible for the relations with UNESCO. 
<p>
In 1992 the Secretariat for Analysis of Swedish Development Assistance (SASDA) was installed. The
secretariat is located at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, but it has no formal organising and administrative
links with the Ministry. The secretariat, consisting of a small and independent group of people, is installed
by the Parliament for a two year period. Its very broad mandate includes the study on the effectiveness and
efficiency of Swedish development cooperation, strategic issues and on methodology. SASDA will present a
concluding report on twenty individual studies in September 1994.
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
Generally speaking, implementing agencies in Scandinavian countries have a 'styrelse', a steering committee
or 'Board' with a limited number of members, and a 'radet', a much larger 'council'. Although both
institutions have an advisory mandate only, they have great influence, due to the representative composition
of their membership and high status. Boards usually include members of Parliament and officials of the
administration.
<p>
All Swedish agencies have an Advisory Board, of which the members are partly nominated by the Minister.
The Boards' positions differ. SIDA's Board, chaired by the agency's Director-General, limits itself to broad
policy questions, meets monthly, and its 14 members represent Parliament, NGOs, solidarity committees,
farmers organisations and cooperatives. There used to be a separate Advisory Council for SIDA, consisting
of 60 - 70 members. The task of SAREC's Board, placed above the SAREC's Director-General, is to
review all major funding proposals. 
<p>
Until the beginning of the 1990s a Nordic Council of the Ministers of Development Cooperation of
Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden met bi-annually to discuss policy issues. Adjacent to these
meetings advisory meetings were organised of parliamentarians and researchers from the five countries. One
of these advisory meetings was a seminar Human Rights and Democracy held in Helsinki. The proceedings
were published in English. It is not known whether these meetings will be continued.
<p>
Development Cooperation policy is considerably influenced by Parliament. It decides about policy choices
and the volume of aid to be allocated to the main aid categories and countries. The budget and annual report
are presented to Parliament and actively discussed, in Parliament as well as in the Standing Committee for
Foreign Affairs. Parliament also lays down the frameworks for development assistance by determining the
objectives and the organisational structure. Over the years it installed several Commissions to examine
specific questions concerning the management of development cooperation.
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
One-fourth of Swedish bilateral assistance is disbursed through private channels. When budget cuts were
implemented in 1993, support to NGOs and emergency aid were excluded. Traditionally there has been a
very close relationship between the Government and the numerous Swedish NGOs, that have a very long
tradition. Forty NGOs in 1952 formed the Committee for Technical Assistance to Less Developed
Countries, the predecessor of the present SIDA. Apart from specific development NGOs, the churches,
trade unions, solidarity committees, municipalities, women organisations, civil rights movements (some
dating back to 1900), cooperatives and vocational organisations cooperate with their respective counterparts
in the South. All NGOs are eligible for government assistance; some 600 NGOs receive government
support. There is no formal body representing all NGOs to the Government. There are around 14 umbrella-
type NGOs that have framework agreements with SIDA, for instance the International Trade Union
Cooperation (LOTCO), the Olof Palme International Centre and the Swedish Missionary Council. The
Government has formed a Council of Popular Movements, an informal structure for consultations with the
MFA. Subjects for discussion with the Government are: financial dependency, direct funding, capacity
building of local NGOs, and maintaining public support for development cooperation.
<p>
Independent and government related research institutes cooperate strongly with the Government and its aid
agencies for policy preparation, implementation and evaluation. In addition to the institutes already
mentioned, there are 17 institutes that according to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey qualify as Development
Research and Training Institutes.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
