<html>
<header>
<title>Development Co-operation Review of Ireland</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/ie.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review of Ireland<br>Summary and Conclusions<p>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>September 1994<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris Cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
<h4>This Report</h4>
The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.
<p>
The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.
<p>
This publication contains the conclusions as agreed by DAC following the review meeting on 21 September 1994, as well as the report prepared by the Secretariat team.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
Until recently, some 60 per cent of Irish aid was contributions to United Nations agencies, the World Bank group, and the aid programme of the European Union. Over half of bilateral official development assistance (ODA) financed experts and volunteers set to a limited number of African countries. Irish aid was small in volume and declining as a per cent of gross national product (GNP), with the ODA/GNP ratio fluctuating between 0.28 per cent in 1986 and 0.16 per cent in 1992.
<p>
A watershed in the evolution of the aid programme was reached in 1993 when a "Programme for a Partnership Government" was adopted. This set out Irish government policy objectives in all areas, including overseas development. Based on this, a detailed four year Strategy Plan: "Irish Aid: Consolidation and Growth" was published in July 1993. The plan establishes an ODA volume target of 0.40 per cent of GNP to be reached by 1997, an increase in priority countries from four to six (all in Africa), increased funding for APSO (the volunteer-sending agency), stronger cooperation with NGO's through increased allocations for co-financing, the setting-up of an independent advisory body on aid issues, as well as the creation of an Irish Aid Advisory Committee to advise the Minister of Foreign Affairs.
<p>
By 1994, the results of the changes can already be seen. ODA volume increased in 1993 by 31 per cent in real terms to reach 0.20 per cent of GNP; the aid administration has been strengthened in numbers, new field offices have been opened, and systematic training is now being provided to staff; and the creation in 1994 under the aegis of the Irish Parliament's Joint Committee for Foreign Affairs, of a Sub-Committee for Development Cooperation.
<p>
The report goes on to provide information on the structure of the aid system in Ireland, its administration, management, evaluation, and effectiveness. Particular attention is paid to the technical cooperation programme, the role of non-governmental organisations, and a case study of Irish aid in Zambia. 
<p>
<HR>
