<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="../images/fi.jpg"<p>
<H4>Ministry for Foreign Affairs<br>Department for International Development Cooperation</h4>

<hr size=3>
<h4>FINLAND'S DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION IN THE 1990s<br>Strategic goals and means</h4>

by Ministry for Foreign Affairs, 1993

<p>
Source: <A HREF="http://www.vn.fi/vn/um/kyo/home.html" target="_top">http://www.vn.fi/vn/um/kyo/home.html</a></center>
<br>

<hr size=3>

<A NAME=menu>

<a href=#intro>Introduction</a><p>
<a href=#changes>Changes in the Development Cooperation Climate</a><br>
<ul><li><a href=#global>Changes in global politics and economics</a><br>
<li><a href=#percep>Changing perceptions of development cooperation</a><br>
<li><a href=#climate>Changes in the climate in Finland</a><br></ul>
<a href=#premise>General Premises and Conditions for Finnish Development Cooperation</a><br>
<ul><li><a href=#why>Why is Finland involved in development cooperation</a><br>
<li><a href=#what>What kind of development does Finland support</a><br></ul>
<a href=#goal>The Substantive Goals of Finnish Development Cooperation</a><br>
<ul><li><a href=#econo>Promoting economic development and reducing poverty</a><br>
<li><a href=#enviro>Environment, population and development</a><br>
<li><a href=#democ>Democracy and human rights</a><br></ul>
<a href=#opinion>Public Opinion and Development Cooperation</a><p>
<a href=#action>Action Plan for Finnish Development Cooperation in the 1990s</a><br>
<ul>
<li><a href=#resource>Development cooperation resources</a><br>
<li><a href=#multi>Multilateral development cooperation</a><br>
<li><a href=#bi>Bilateral development cooperation</a><br></ul>
<a href=#humani>Humanitarian Assistance</a><p>
<a href=#supplies>Development Cooperation Supplies from Finland</a><p>
<a href=#audit>Internal Auditing and Evaluation of Development Cooperation</a><p>
<hr size=3>
<a name=intro><h4>INTRODUCTION</h4>

Finland has had a development aid programme financed out of public funds for nearly thirty years now. During this time, Finnish development cooperation policy has emerged from a large number of individual policy statements.  As the overall picture of development cooperation at both the national and the international level is changing rapidly, there is a more pronounced need for a comprehensive new steering instrument. Both the nation's political leaders and the machinery responsible for development cooperation need a steering tool comparable to the strategic planning systems familiar in the business world.<p>

The present document is the highest level of this new strategic planning system, defining the general goals of development cooperation and the means to achieve them. The shaping and processing of the lower levels do not necessarily assume the same public significance; they are designed for use over a shorter term than the present principles and, following these general goals, define the individual targets by country, sector and organization.  Thus sectors important for Finnish development cooperation - such as agriculture and forestry, food aid, water supply and other areas basic to human development - may well have detailed action plans of their own within the framework of the present document, explaining why the latter does not go into such fundamental issues.  Rather, it establishes a hierarchy of goals and means to clarify and guide operations and ensure their goal-orientation, while also permitting more flexible adjustment to changing circumstances or viewpoints.<p>

In speaking of developing countries and development cooperation, the document bases itself on the OECD definitions in force at the time of writing.  The strategy does not, therefore, apply to other foreign aid given by Finland outside the scope of development cooperation.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=changes><h4>CHANGES IN THE DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION CLIMATE</h4>


<a name=global><li><h4>Changes in global politics and economics</h4>

The end of the Cold War has altered the relations between the great powers and their allies.  The effect on other countries, too, has been profound and intense.  In relations between the developing and developed countries, the first sign was the solid progress made in solving certain regional conflicts. In the longer term, the new situation in world politics has permitted various universal problems to be viewed from a new standpoint.  Thus, as well as concern for natural resources, trade and indebtedness, other issues such as <br>
- the environment <br>
- demographic problems, including mass movements of population <br>
- problems connected with drugs, terrorism and organized crime, and <br>
- epidemics <br>
have become priority concerns in terms of the interdependence between developing and developed nations.<p>

The factor common to all these problem groupings is that they cannot be solved other than through cooperation between the industrialized and developing world.  In practice, this means that the <strong>financial burden</strong>, among other things, must be shared by the two groups.<p>

The end of the Cold War has also meant that development cooperation can no longer be justified by the same <strong>security policy arguments </strong> as before, when the great powers and their allies often gave aid to developing countries in order to keep them 'in the same camp' or prevent them allying themselves with the other side.  Developing countries also have to <strong>compete with the CEE countries and the CIS </strong> for political attention, markets, and first and foremost development funds.  There is no longer the same solidarity between developing countries as was created by political means in the '60s and which served them well as late as the '70s, during the debate about 'a new international economic order'.  Today, the developing nations fall into several different groups both economically and politically: there are countries already integrated into world economics and approaching the standing of a developed nation, countries which can look forward to integration in the near future, and - mainly in Africa - countries for which this is only a remote possibility.  There is no economically and politically homogeneous 'developing world' any more.<p>

Views of what comprises development and how it can be achieved have varied greatly since the Second World War.  A process began with the oil crises in the '70s that drew the developing countries into a rapid debt spiral and led economists to study macroeconomic policy.  According to the familiar <strong>neo-liberal development model </strong> - which has won wide support, particularly since the socialist option fell into disrepute - there are four basic factors in development:<br>
- a sound macroeconomic base<br>
- the widest possible integration into the world economy <br>
- investment in human resources (education, training, health, nutrition, etc.) and <br>
- an economic system that promotes free competition.<p>

This model is, however, justifiably criticized, partly because, if it is applied, it may well conflict with other components such as equality, environmental demands or cultural values.  It also fails to sufficiently recognize that development is not just an economic and social phenomenon, but derives most emphatically from history, culture and politics.<p>

The changing world picture has also altered ideas about the relationship between development cooperation and other aspects of relations with developing countries. The idea that dominated, say, Nordic development cooperation thinking until way into the '80s, i.e. that developing countries should be the objects of a global social policy, is now discredited and being replaced by belief in the interdependence of the whole of mankind.  This view leads us to examine the relationship between development cooperation and other policy areas affecting the developing countries (those on agriculture, trade, competition, labour, immigration, etc.).  Reducing these contradictions, that is, <strong>promoting coherence </strong> is one of the main problem issues of the '90s in the relations between OECD countries and developing countries. The outcome may be a change in the scale of development funding in the future, assuming that the same goals can also be reached by means other than development cooperation. <p>


<a name=percep><li><h4>Changing perceptions of development cooperation</h4>

In the past, discussion of the developing countries' own economic policy was pushed into the background by the desire of colonies for economic as well as political independence, a form of economic thinking that stressed dependence on the industrial countries as the initial cause of the developing countries' problems ('schools of dependency'), and the assumption that investment was the key to development.  Things began to change in the '70s, with the oil crises, and particularly in the '80s, as indebtedness forced the developing countries to re-examine their economic policies and the project-by-project approach led to failure in a growing number of cases, ultimately in part because of the economic and social policy pursued by the recipient country concerned. Restructuring the economies of developing countries also seemed to have had an impact on the preconditions for effective development cooperation. Donor countries' support for structural adjustment, including a shift to a more open economy and integration into world trade, came to be as important a goal of development cooperation as well planned and executed projects. At the same time, the negative social effects of structural adjustment began to be felt, though initially, at least, donor countries failed to pay enough attention to them.<p>

During the '80s, development cooperation authorities gradually changed over to a form of financing in which the 'unit' was not a project, but rather economic policy at various levels, or in different sectors of the economy, and in which <strong>certain economic conditions </strong> were attached to funding granted ('<strong>policy-based aid'</strong>). This formed an integral part of the broadly accepted principle that all countries are ultimately responsible for their own development, and that it is primarily the policy adopted by the developing country concerned which determines the course of its development.  Programme assistance tied to economic policy must be viewed as support from donor countries for economic structural adjustment in the developing country concerned.<p>

Today, conditions are attached to other social features, and not just to economic policy.  All the OECD countries are committed to promoting respect for human rights, democratic government and the rule of law in developing countries.  Many developing countries are indeed carrying out reforms to these ends, prompted by changes in the international political arena.  Donors have begun to discuss the possibility of using <strong>negative sanctions </strong>, i.e. withholding aid, if the recipient country does not meet their expectations in this respect. Indeed, there has been growing acceptance of the use of negative sanctions within the donor community in recent years. Decisions made within the European Community's political coordination system to withhold development assistance because of unsatisfactory human rights or progress towards democracy are clear examples. <p>

The term <strong>sustainable development </strong> is best known in an environmental context, where it means protection of the environment and the rational use of natural resources. In development cooperation, however, sustainable development can also be viewed from an economic, social and governmental standpoint.  It includes the idea of ensuring adequate resources and well-being in the long term, also for future generations.  The impact of an individual project or programme must remain viable even after all outside aid has come to an end.  In practice, this means basing operations primarily on the recipient country's own resources and know-how. This may presuppose the creation or reinforcement of governmental or technical institutions ('capacity building').<p>

An interesting new feature in international development cooperation is the rapid growth in <strong>humanitarian assistance </strong>. Though the distinction between humanitarian assistance and development cooperation proper has never been exactly defined, the former is obviously on the increase. The reason could well be the growing perception among the citizens of developed countries, as a result of more efficient information, of humanitarian needs, wars, natural catastrophes or political change.  In any case, humanitarian assistance takes on a political dimension which is often more explicit and immediate than in other development cooperation.<p>


<a name=climate><li><h4>Changes in the climate in Finland</h4>

Finland cut its development cooperation appropriations in 1991, just when its long-awaited and consistently pursued quantitative goal of 0.7% of GDP, as recommended by the UN, had been reached,. Several other OECD countries have also had to reduce their funding.<p>

This change in a policy pursued persistently for some fifteen years compels us to reassess the policy foundations, goals and achievements of our development cooperation. The present strategy document has been prepared as part of this process.<p>

The recession has also altered the climate because the development cooperation administration has to adjust to the retrenchment and efficiency programmes currently under way in public management.  In this respect, too, the formulation of a strategy should provide us with some useful tools.<p>

Among the factors dealt with in the section on 'Changes in global politics and economics', assistance to CEE countries and the CIS and funding for global environment programmes, in particular, have indirectly caused changes in the climate within which development cooperation operates. With the present cutbacks in the public sector, it is practically inevitable that these programmes compete for appropriations with development cooperation, even though they could with equal justification be seen as only one expression of international responsibility and interdependence, and thus as approaches parallel to development cooperation. All Finland's foreign aid must be managed efficiently to allow decision-makers and citizens to distinguish clearly between the various forms it takes.<p>

Possible membership of the EC is another factor that will influence the climate for Finnish development cooperation in future.  It is, however, likely to have substantially less direct impact on our development cooperation than on our trade with the developing world or our political relations with developing countries. In principle, at least, Finland should not have any difficulty in accepting EC approaches. Political cooperation between the EC states (EPC) may well have indirect effects on development cooperation, but they cannot be precisely forecast.  The biggest impact of EC membership would be on how development cooperation is financed.  According to preliminary estimates, Finland's contribution to development cooperation financed out of the EC's regular budget would be around 1.5%, or FIM 250 million, a year.  In addition, an estimated FIM 350 million would have to be channelled through the European Development Fund (EDF).  This gives a total of some FIM 600 million a year, though this could well change considerably as the exact date of accession and other relevant information can be used in calculations. The effect of EC foreign policy coordination on Finland's overall relations with developing countries would gain considerably in importance as a result of accession.  This would be most obvious, perhaps, in human rights issues, together with the enhanced demand for coherence between development cooperation policies and other aspects of relations with developing countries, including trade policy.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=premise><h4>GENERAL PREMISES AND CONDITIONS FOR FINNISH DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION</h4>


<a name=why><li><h4>Why is Finland involved in development cooperation?</h4>

The enormous discrepancies in wealth and well-being between the developed and the developing countries are not acceptable by any human standard. They constitute a threat to the prosperity and security of all nations. Finland, together with other developed countries, is doing what it can to reduce and eliminate these discrepancies through its foreign and economic policies.<p>

Finland is working to combat global environmental problems, using development cooperation as one, but certainly not the only, means. Similarly, Finland supports the developing countries in their efforts to reduce population growth and control massive movements of population caused by over-exploitation of nature's regenerative capacity. <p>

Finland supports international cooperation in solving the problems faced by developing countries, thereby furthering global security and well-being.<p>

Development cooperation is one of the most important channels for interaction with developing countries. It offers an opportunity for growing international awareness and interaction between peoples and societies.<p>

In favourable conditions, development cooperation can also serve as a step towards broader commercial, cultural and other interaction between nations and peoples.<p>

The <strong>general objectives guiding Finnish development cooperation </strong> can be formulated as follows: Development cooperation is that part of foreign policy through which Finland strives, by transferring material and human resources to the developing countries,<br>
- to promote sustainable development and well-being in developing countries;<br>
- to contribute to the establishment of peace, equality, democratic conditions and human rights in these countries; and <br>
- to further interaction between Finland and the developing countries.<p>


<a name=what><li><h4>What kind of development does Finland support?</h4>

The states, international organizations and other bodies with which Finland is engaged in development cooperation must commit themselves to the following three objectives:<br>
- to reduce the widespread poverty in developing countries;<br>
- to combat global threats to the environment by helping the developing countries to solve their environmental problems; and <br>
- to promote social equality, democracy and human rights in the developing countries.<p>

If a cooperation partner fails to adhere to these objectives, Finland will use constructive dialogue in an attempt to influence the situation and, if this is not possible, will reconsider continuation of the cooperation relationship.<p>

In both multilateral and bilateral development cooperation, Finland applies the following principles:<p>


<i><strong>Responsibility of the developing countries for their own development</i></strong><p>

The main principle of Finland's development cooperation is that a developing country is responsible for its own development.  Thus the donor's role is always merely a supportive one.  Any other premise would not allow the achievement of sustainable development.<p>


<i><strong>The will to develop</i></strong><p>

One precondition for sustainable and economically viable development is that the developing country, its citizens and the organizations and institutions operating there all have the will to develop.  This is also, in each case, the precondition for Finnish assistance.<p>


<i><strong>Sustainable development</i></strong><p>

Emphasis on the responsibility of the recipient country also implies that development cooperation supports the creation of economically, environmentally, socially and administratively sustainable structures or functions.  Development cooperation must also aim to make itself superfluous, and the existence of structures or functions built up with its assistance must not be dependent on external support.<p>


<i><strong>Structural change</i></strong><p>

The global economy has been going through a process of structural change since around 1980 as a result of the oil and debt crises.  The economies of the developing countries will not survive these crises unless fundamental reforms are made in both poor and rich countries, e.g. in industrial policy and marketing mechanisms, and in the role played by the state in economic life.  These structural reforms are outlined in the adjustment programmes for individual countries, in the form of action by the countries' own political leadership and by international donors, especially the financing institutions.  The guideline is to achieve economic balance externally and internally and to promote export-driven growth.<p>

Finland supports action by the developing countries to reform and adjust their economic structures to the demands of sustainable development, using both bilateral and multilateral channels, assuming that structural adjustment and environmental concerns, equality and cultural considerations can be reconciled.<p>


<i><strong>Development cooperation and other relations with developing countries</i></strong><p>

Finland engages in development cooperation fully aware that this is only one component in its overall relations with the developing countries, though an important one both now and in the future. As interdependence grows, Finland will increase the coherence of its policies vis--vis the developing countries (e.g. policy on trade and competition, agriculture, labour, immigration and refugees, and culture) and reconcile these with the goals of development cooperation better than at present.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=goal><h4>THE SUBSTANTIVE GOALS OF FINNISH DEVELOPMENT 
COOPERATION</h4>


<a name=econo><li><h4>Promoting economic development and reducing poverty</h4>

The preconditions for economic development can be defined as investments in human beings and the use of market forces.  Finland is working towards the latter goal by supporting structural change in the economies of developing countries, together with economic reforms aimed at exploiting market forces and developing price mechanisms.<p>

In supporting activities designed to promote economic growth and structural change in the developing countries, Finland stresses measures related not only to growth but also to greater distribution of well-being, together with alleviation of the adverse effects that will inevitably accompany structural adjustment.<p>

In supporting private enterprise and the necessary infrastructure investments in the developing countries, Finland will avoid any distortion of competitive conditions and thereby the creation of unsustainable production. Support will be channelled especially to small-scale enterprises and to farming and forestry that is economically and environmentally sustainable. Impact on labour will be taken into account and labour-intensive solutions favoured.<p>

Finland aims to promote planning and decision-making systems based on popular participation, on the principle that every individual has the right to help make decisions that affect him/her.  In local economic decision-making, the necessary preconditions will be created by supporting the formation of associations or organizations of businesses, employees and farmers, or of cooperatives.<p>

Because most of the poor in developing countries live in rural areas, action to develop the countryside must play a central role in strategy to alleviate poverty.  In practice, this means projects giving the rural population access to natural resources (i.e. land and water) and to production technology, as well as access to markets for their products.<p>

When targeting both its bilateral and its multilateral assistance, Finland will continue to give priority to the poorer countries and disadvantaged population groups in developing countries .<p>


<a name=enviro><li><h4>Environment, population and development</h4>

In a poor developing country, sustainable development means finding the right balance between growth, environmental considerations and income distribution. This is a task for the developing country itself. Assistance will be targeted at activities promoting this end. Finland will channel its support to areas where this problem has been satisfactorily solved, or where Finland can help to solve it.  Hence, Finland will <p>
- stress consideration for environmental factors in all development cooperation projects, not merely to combat existing threats but also to create the preconditions for security and well-being based on multiple use of natural resources;<br>
- pursue the principle of equality between genders in all development cooperation projects and also strive to utilize fully female and male resources and redevelop them equally;<br>
- support population policy programmes;<br>
- support training and education;<br>
- when targeting resources, give particular stress to projects aimed at the sustainable development of basic services and farming and forestry in rural areas;<br>
- develop its know-how in implementing forestation projects according to the principles of sustainable development and thus promote the solution of global environmental problems.<br>


<a name=democ><li><h4>Democracy and human rights</h4>

Democracy is the only lasting basis for the rule of law. In the long term, it has also proved more effective than other options as a basis for economic and social development.  Each nation must find its own way to democracy and respect for human rights, building on its own history and political situation. Finland respects the principle in international law of non-interference in the internal affairs of another state, and will thus use the means available to development cooperation to consolidate democracy and human rights.  Hence, Finland <br>
- supports a pluralist and open social order in all countries, including broad political participation and the right to a distinctive national or minority culture;
- supports the values and practices characterizing society based on the rule of law, such as conformity to law, the rejection of corruption, and the political and legal accountability of decision-makers;<br>
- requires all its development cooperation partners to comply with international agreements on human rights and basic freedoms;<br>
- promotes projects that encourage consolidation of both the forms and the substance of democracy at all levels of social life; and <br>
- supports the principles of freedom of speech and independent media in recipient countries.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=opinion><h4>PUBLIC OPINION AND DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION</h4>

Effective, long-term international cooperation is impossible without broad public support.  In a democratic and pluralist society like Finland, it is obvious that a number of competing opinions prevail on development cooperation policy. It is the function of the authorities to ensure that public opinion on development cooperation is founded on as complete, many-sided and impartial information as possible.  It is precisely this requirement regarding the impartiality of information provided by the authorities that points up the effectiveness and efficiency of development cooperation as a factor of crucial importance in the process of shaping public opinion.<p>

As development cooperation is a relatively new function of public authorities and is exercised mainly abroad it tends to remain alien to public opinion.  That is why it is so important for the authorities to provide frank and free information, and for civil servants to contribute to public debate on development cooperation.<p>
<hr size=3>
<a name=action><h4>ACTION PLAN FOR FINNISH DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION IN THE 1990s </h4>


<a name=resource><li><h4>Development cooperation resources</h4>


<i><strong>Financial resources</i></strong><p>

In April 1992, the Finnish Government decided to temporarily reduce funds available for development cooperation to a level corresponding to 0.4% of GDP for the period 1993-1995. This is below the Nordic (0.98%), EC (0.43%) and EEA (0.46%) average for 1991.  The Government has also announced that it intends to restore the level of appropriations to 0.7% of GDP by the year 2000. This target was reiterated at the 1992 UNCED meeting and in other Government statements. <p>


<i><strong>Other resources </strong></i><p>

The administration of development cooperation will remain a part of the Ministry for Foreign Affairs even in the future. The aim is to delegate as much as possible of the practical administration of assistance to the recipient countries.  The Finnish missions in the countries and the organizations concerned will function as the focal points, giving the Ministry an opportunity to concentrate on planning and monitoring.  This kind of delegation presupposes more efficient steering of operations, which is also one aim of this strategy.<p>

The new situation poses new demands for the training of development cooperation officials and our understanding of conditions in recipient countries. Therefore new training programmes will be essential.<p>

Existing expertise in the civil service, particularly in the sectoral ministries, boards and other public institutions, must be used as effectively as possible in development cooperation. The Ministry for Foreign Affairs will be responsible for development cooperation as part of the foreign policy, for its financing and selection of targets, and for supervision and coordination of its implementation.<p>

The sectoral ministries and their various departments and institutions will be responsible for carrying out development cooperation projects subject to the resources in their respective fields and as agreed with the Ministry for Foreign Affairs.  This will form part of a general and constantly widening range of international relations in the specific area of administration.<p>

As well as using public management services, Finland will also continue to procure goods and services from the private sector in its development cooperation.  Modes and methods designed to produce the best possible results for all those involved must therefore be created and developed for collaboration between the development cooperation authorities and the private sector.<p>

Finland aims to develop personnel with a wide range of experience of developing countries and other international skills for the use of public service, business & industry, non-government organizations and international bodies.<p>


<a name=multi><li><h4>Multilateral development cooperation</h4>

Multilateral development cooperation includes <br>
- development cooperation through UN bodies and organizations;<br>
- development cooperation through international development financing institutions;<br>
- debate and decision-making on development cooperation in these bodies; and <br>
- debate within the OECD on development cooperation policy.<p>

If Finland joins the EC, Community development cooperation will become one channel for Finnish multilateral development cooperation.<p>

As one of the general objectives of development cooperation policy, multilateral assistance promotes Finland's foreign policy objectives within the UN and the international development financing institutions.<p>

Multilateral assistance provides an opportunity, through international organizations and financing institutions, for universal and politically unaligned action, calling upon broad expertise in a variety of sectors and areas.  In addition, an increasing number of problems, such as environmental degradation and AIDS, recognize no frontiers, so efforts from the entire international community are needed to solve them.  Development cooperation objectives and targets adopted internationally are also achieved through other forms of cooperation with developing countries, e.g. in trade and culture.  The normative work by international organizations lays a foundation for a coordinated approach to development issues.<p>

Finland's multilateral development cooperation consists on the one hand of participation in the work of the decision-making bodies of the UN and other international organizations and financing institutions, and on the other of provision of financial and other assistance to be implemented through these bodies. In the UN, development cooperation policy is discussed in the General Assembly and in its subsidiary bodies. Decisions are based on the one-country-one-vote principle.  In the case of development financing institutions, operational policy is made by the boards of directors and in periodic negotiations on capital replenishment, and also at annual shareholders' meetings. The decision-making system is based on voting power, which is determined by each country's contribution to the capital stock and on the principle of working in - and as - a constituency.<p>

The most important difference between multilateral and bilateral development cooperation activities is that the former is much more visible and comprehensive internationally, and this naturally heightens its foreign policy significance.  The nature of the UN system, and to some extent that of international development financing institutions, adds to this effect.  Further, policies on programmes and financing are influenced by the various organizations' decision-making bodies, and not directly through agreements with recipients, as is the case in bilateral activities. The significance of multilateral cooperation can be assessed not only in terms of foreign policy but also in terms of its effectiveness or appropriateness, compared with direct bilateral assistance.  It also provides feedback that can be utilized in the implementation of bilateral programmes.<p>

Finland supports the principles laid down in the United Nations Charter and UN ideals in both political and economic fields. Finland therefore expects the highest possible quality from UN bodies and organizations in the planning and implementation of development cooperation and related administrative functions.  The above also applies to other channels of multilateral assistance, as relevant.  In international development financing institutions, Finland considers it particularly important for sufficient weight to be attached to the views of recipient countries.<p>

Finland selects the channels for its multilateral assistance according to its own development objectives.  In deciding the organizations through which Finnish multilateral assistance will be channelled, the most important consideration, therefore, is how effectively each organization will achieve these objectives.  Decisions regarding channelling of multilateral assistance will be made in connection with the national budget, incorporating the provision that multi-year commitments can be made.<p>

The entire field of multilateral assistance, particularly the UN system, is undergoing rapid change and restructuring, prompted by the ending of the Cold War and its effects on the UN's role and operating potential in general.  In the reform of the UN system, Finland's objective is to restore to the UN its role as laid down in the Charter, that is, to make it one central forum of worldwide political dialogue.  Finland takes the view that achieving this goal would strengthen the UN system as an efficient channel of development cooperation.  The <strong>UN specialized agencies </strong> should concentrate on their own special fields of expertise, i.e. the normative functions originally intended for them, the administration of which has suffered over the years from expansion of the operational functions, i.e. actual development cooperation.  Finland supports a greater concentration of the administration of the <strong>UN's operational activities </strong> and also aims to assist international development financing institutions and UN bodies to reach better mutual understanding regarding the division of labour between them in the field of development cooperation.<p>

Because achieving the objectives of multilateral development cooperation depends essentially on coordination between donor countries, Finland underlines the importance of better coordination within the UN, the development financing institutions and the Development Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD.<p>


<a name=bi><li><h4>Bilateral development cooperation</h4>


<i><strong>Regional and sectoral orientation</i></strong><p>

In its bilateral development cooperation, Finland considers choice of regions and countries of prime importance.  The choice of sectors takes place only after this.  In the case of the latter, decisions are laid down in strategies for the individual recipients, based on the particular development priorities of the countries concerned and Finland's ability to offer quality resources in the key sectors thus selected.  There must therefore be sufficient flexibility in the choice of sectors.<p>

Choice of countries also has a broad political dimension. In order that all relevant aspects could be taken adequately into account, decisions in principle concerning recipients must be made at the political level.<p>

The forms and priorities of cooperation will be based on the special features of each geographical area and each recipient country.  Development cooperation can be a useful way of strengthening cooperation among developing countries, provided that they themselves are committed to it.<p>

In the UN, its specialized agencies and development organizations and in the financing institutions Finland contributes to the international debate on development issues and to the preparation and approval of common norms, principles and action programmes.  These also provide a framework for bilateral development cooperation.<p>


<i><strong>Country priorities in bilateral cooperation </i></strong><p>

The present priorities in Finland's bilateral development cooperation are the result of choices made over nearly thirty years.  They reflect one distinct basic principle, that development cooperation should concentrate on the poorest countries (in terms of per capita GDP). Only few exceptions to this general rule have been made.  The poverty criterion continues to be the prime argument in selecting recipient countries.  Any other grounds would be hard to reconcile with the ethical ideology on which our development cooperation rests.  Our development cooperation relations so far, the experiences of it, and the importance of sustained effort should continue to be the primary criteria in the choice of recipients.  Another important precondition for the choice of recipients is a country's own expressed desire to develop, which should be in conformity with the main goals of this strategy.<p>

In addition to the poverty criterion Finland will take the following factors into account:<br>
- the compatibility of the recipient country's development policy with the goals and means of this strategy; and <br>
- how effectively Finland can administer assistance in the country concerned.<p>

The Government decides the countries with which Finland will engage in extensive, long-term development cooperation <strong>(primary cooperation countries).  Project-based assistance </strong> may also be provided to other developing countries.  The actual project is then the prime criterion for selection, though the choice of recipient may not essentially differ from the criteria for primary countries.<p>

Within authorizations granted by Parliament, the Government confirms annual commitment authority for future development cooperation in individual primary countries, and commitment authority for project-based assistance to other developing countries and regional programmes. The Government and Parliament can also make recommendations on these issues in their handling of the budget bill and the annual development cooperation report. Parliament plays an important role in development cooperation and can state its position on matters such as strategies for individual countries.<p>

Permanent, long-term cooperation with primary cooperation countries may also call for commitment and some level of involvement in promoting economic reforms and structural change in the individual countries.  This may take the form of involvement in the countries' international loan arrangements, programme assistance or involvement in other ways in the promotion of such international schemes.  This also requires wide knowledge and understanding of the recipient country's economy and social issues.  In the interests of consistency, the various donor countries must be ready to coordinate their development assistance contributions to a given country.<p>

<i><strong>Issues related to the substance of bilateral cooperation</i></strong><p>
Further to the general principles of Finnish development cooperation dealt with above, in the section 'What kind of development does Finland support?', the following deals with various specific questions likely to be crucial for development cooperation in the '90s (either because of their general importance or because they involve new considerations), on which Finland should therefore take a clear stance in principle. <p>

<strong>Programme assistance </strong> (see above under 'Changing perceptions of development cooperation') has become an increasingly important element in development cooperation in the '80s, side by side with conventional project-based aid. The term is used to mean balance of payments or budgetary support, or support to a specific sector which is not tied to any particular projects, but the preconditions for which are normally changes in the recipient country's general economic and sectoral policies.  If an economic reform programme has been, or is being, drawn up for any of Finland's recipient countries, Finland endeavours to participate in its preparation and implementation, according to the basic principles laid down in this strategy document. Finland's own programme assistance will be coordinated with the recipient country and the international donor community.<p>

Broad support for the <strong>public </strong> sector of developing countries is an important object of development cooperation, both to bring about the rule of law and efficiency, and to prompt economic and social change.  Because programme assistance is designed to promote the recipient country's administrative, economic and ultimately financial independence, it should be supplemented with action to further the country's ability to formulate, plan and implement economic policy on its own.<p>

Keeping in mind what has been said above (in the section 'Promoting economic development and reducing poverty'), Finland considers it important to improve the general conditions (legislation, training) in developing countries, especially for small and medium-sized enterprises.<p>

The developing countries' ability to utilize the <strong>technological advances </strong> being made around them is a fundamental condition for their future development.  Finland will encourage the building-up of technological knowledge and capacity to this end in the countries it assists.<p>

Finland considers that one important social, political and economic goal of development cooperation is to raise <strong>the status of women </strong> and to increase their opportunities to participate and influence decisions.  This is important for the advancement of democracy and human rights, population and family planning, and economic and social development in general.<p>

Culture is considered a vital development resource. Finland will support <strong>cultural projects </strong> in developing countries that play an important role in creating or preserving the country's national identity and cherishing its cultural heritage.<p>

Objective and independent <strong>research </strong> will be developed in accordance with the priorities of the strategy and as development cooperation needs require.  In research, too, the aim is to establish effective contacts between Finnish research institutions and those in developing countries themselves.<p>

<strong>Environmental considerations </strong> will be taken into account in the appraisal of projects financed by Finland.  Attention will further be paid to the contribution made by projects to the development of rural areas, the satisfaction of basic needs, and consolidation of the infrastructure in recipient countries.<p>


<i><strong>Non-government and missionary organizations</i></strong><p>

Finnish non-government and missionary organizations are development cooperation channels that can be used to achieve goals that may be difficult to reach by official means.  The most important of these are:<br>
- implementation of such projects in developing countries that would be difficult to implement or influence through official channels;<br>
- the extension of contacts between Finland and developing countries to countries where there is no official development cooperation; and <br>
- giving personal experience of development cooperation to large numbers of ordinary people.<p>

Finland therefore implements some of its development cooperation activities through non-government organizations as long as the projects conform to the current rules and do not conflict with the general goals of the strategy.  Special attention is then given to:<br>
- choice of project and mode of execution;<br>
- ensuring that the aim is to assist a target in a developing country and not to consolidate the Finnish organization; and <br>
- the organization's ability to achieve its stated goals.<p>

Assistance to <strong>international non-government organizations </strong> operating in several countries or worldwide follows the same principles as in the case of Finnish organizations, except that <br>
- funding must be more selective and advance screening of the organization more thorough, because these projects are on the whole more difficult to monitor, even retroactively, than those of a Finnish organization; and <br>
- the cost-sharing principle must be exercised more flexibly and more to suit the particular situation than with Finnish organizations.<p>

The same principles also apply to <strong>non-government organizations operating in developing countries </strong>.<p>


<i><strong>Economic and industrial cooperation</i></strong><p>

One specific form of project cooperation funded is the kind of economic activity or planning that will have the effect on development aimed at in this strategy, and that will promote trade or other economic cooperation between Finland and developing countries.  Such forms of funding include interest subsidy on commercial loans, the Fund for Industrial Cooperation (FINNFUND), the promotion of imports from developing countries and funding for economic, industrial and technological cooperation.  The principles of this strategy also apply, as relevant, to this form of financing.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=humani><h3>HUMANITARIAN ASSISTANCE</h3>

Humanitarian assistance is a fast-growing part of the overall field of development cooperation (see above in the section 'Changing perceptions of development cooperation') though it is hard to make distinctions between this and development cooperation proper.  The main way in which humanitarian assistance differs from development cooperation is that the main reason for assistance is human distress.  It should, however, be pointed out that an emerging need for humanitarian assistance can be mitigated or reduced by means of development cooperation.  Reducing economic and social inequalities also reduces the possibility of violent conflict; alleviating poverty and reducing population growth decrease the likelihood of environmental catastrophes causing displacement of populations and refugees; etc.  It is also often necessary to utilize development cooperation means at different stages of humanitarian assistance.<p>

A decision to provide humanitarian assistance is made in the manner called for by its foreign policy context.<p>

UN bodies are used as the main channel for humanitarian assistance, together with the various non-government organizations specializing in humanitarian assistance that coordinate their activities with them. Finland considers it urgent and important to reform and rationalize the administrative mechanisms responsible for the UN's humanitarian assistance. Finland will also make its own efforts to improve the coordination between countries providing humanitarian assistance.<p>

Humanitarian assistance to refugees will as far as possible also be provided to prevent the refugees from having to move any further away from their home regions than is absolutely necessary.<p>

Finnish products will be used for humanitarian assistance whenever they are internationally competitive in price, quality and terms of delivery.<p>

Increasing attention has to be paid to the kind of development cooperation that will prevent situations calling for humanitarian assistance from arising and to improving the disaster preparedness of developing countries.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=supplies><h3>DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION SUPPLIES FROM FINLAND</h3>

Purchasing the goods and services needed for development cooperation from Finland both increases contacts between Finland and developing countries and reduces the inevitable negative effects of development cooperation on our balance of payments.  Supplies must come from Finland as far as possible, assuming that <br>
- the interests involved do not decisively influence the choice of and preparations for projects and programmes;<br>
- the price, quality, other characteristics and terms of delivery of the commodities concerned are what the recipient country needs;<br>
- development cooperation funds are only used to buy the kind of commodities that would be competitive internationally in any case.<p>
<hr size=3>

<a name=audit><h3>APPRAISAL AND EVALUATION OF DEVELOPMENT 
COOPERATION</h3>

As stated earlier (in the section 'Popular opinion and development cooperation'), the efficiency and effectiveness of development cooperation are crucial in shaping public opinion in donor countries.  This in turn largely decides the kind of political backing that development cooperation can expect from Finnish society.<p>

The development cooperation administration must therefore improve both its internal auditing and its evaluation mechanisms.  These goals are parallel to some extent, though evaluation concentrates more on long-term results and is more outwardly oriented.<p>

Internal auditing must provide the development cooperation administration with continuous information about the legality, appropriateness and efficiency of the activities, and highlight any changes needed.<p>

Evaluations must<br>
- be carried out by impartial parties;<br>
- be conducted as openly as possible and their findings made public;<br>
- produce results which can be used in planning, administering and deciding about development cooperation; and <br>
- be applicable to all forms and channels of assistance.<p>
<hr size=3>
   
