<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/fi.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Finland
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Finnish Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Finnish Development Cooperation</h3>

Finnish development cooperation started in the early 1960s and has traditionally been based on the political
consensus that linked foreign policy, economic, and ethical interests. The ethical motives, both religious and
humanistic, hold that the satisfaction of people's basic needs is a general human right. Changes in the
international political situation and a severe domestic economic recession force the Government to re-
orientate its development cooperation policy. Traditional political consensus is under heavy pressure.
Following drastic cuts in ODA in 1993, changes in the composition of Finnish aid are called for from
different directions. From inside the administration growing commitments to international credit institutions
generated an abrupt shift in the multilateral-bilateral aid ratio. Secondly, Finnish EU membership will put an
disproportional large claim on current development funds. It is yet unknown whether traditional ethic
motives will hold up against the new foreign policy and commercial interests. Still, public support for
development cooperation is strong.
<p>
Net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 644 million, which was 0.62 per cent of GNP.
After a fast growth in the past decade, the Government imposed massive budget cuts which made the
percentage drop to 0.40 per cent of GNP in 1993. The ODA of the approved development cooperation
budget for 1994 will amount to 0.30 per cent of GNP. Finland used to disburse about 40 per cent of its
ODA through multilateral channels, mainly UN organisations. However, in recent years this percentage has
fallen to less then 20 per cent, with a growing proportion going to the World Bank.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Official Finnish development cooperation is not based on an organic law. Various development cooperation
programmes are laid down in a number of specific laws. In the 1991 coalition government a Minister for
Development Cooperation was included for the first time. He serves within the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
and is responsible for the Department of International Development Cooperation (FINNIDA), which is
located in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The former function of Under-Secretary of State for
Development Cooperation was maintained after the installation of the Minister. FINNIDA is in charge of the
overall policy for international cooperation, and administers the major part of the aid programme, i.e. 70
per cent of ODA (1994). The remaining 30 per cent is mainly administered by the Ministry of Health and
Social Welfare on behalf of refugees in Finland.
<p>
In 1991 FINNIDA was reorganised along functional lines in order to strengthen its policy coordination
functions. The unit for policy coordination is now in charge of overall mid-term planning and budgeting as
well as with assisting the Director-General and the Under-Secretary of State for Development Cooperation.
The latter is in charge of policy-related matters, at the same time being an advisor to the Minister.
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
In Finland, advisory boards and committees are a common part of the administrational set-up. There is a
Board for Customs Affairs under the Ministry of Finance, with representatives of industry, trade unions and
the farming community. For foreign affairs there are advisory Boards on UN affairs, disarmament
questions, and on human rights.
<p>
Finland has an Advisory Board for Relations with Developing Countries. Parliament decides after the
expiration of the mandate of each Board whether a new advisory board will be installed. The current Board
(KESU) was appointed by the Government in May 1992 for a three year period. The KESU has 10
members, who are nominated by the different political parties represented in Parliament. Members do not
necessarily have to be experts in the field of development cooperation. Some are Members of Parliament, or
journalists, researchers, civil servants and NGO-representatives. The chairman usually has the same political
background as the Prime Minister. The Board has a part-time Executive Secretary, who is an official of the
Policy Coordination Unit of FINNIDA. Former Executive Secretaries have also been placed outside the
Ministry. 
<p>
The current Board has a different mandate than the previous ones (the 'TALKE, I-IV', the first Board
TALKE I was installed in 1979). While the TALKE, I-IV advised on economic relations between Finland
and developing countries, an enlarged mandate permits the KESU to advise on all aspects of Finland's
relations with developing countries. The broader mandate of the KESU may reflect the need that is felt in
Finland to re-orientate development cooperation and to define its future role within the changing
international and domestic economic circumstances. The new Board is engaged in establishing relations with
other departments of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the political departments and the Department of Trade.
After installation a new Board can nominate a group of advisors. The advisors of the current Board are all
officials from other departments of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. 
<p>
The Board may take up topics at its own initiative. The role of KESU is an intermediary one between
FINNIDA and politics. The Board not only gives its views to the Department. FINNIDA also provides
Board members with information on development cooperation, in order to keep their parties and other
groups in society well informed. Most of the advisory work is done during discussions at the Ministry.
These take place about eight times a year. At those meetings the Board or officials of the Ministry present
papers. KESU also comments on draft versions of FINNIDA's new strategies. In the preface of the 1993
Strategy the Minister wrote that the involvement of KESU provided "the text of the strategy statement with
the necessary political realism and parliamentary balance". Another task that illustrates the intermediating
role the Board can play, is its commenting on the annual budget for development cooperation. The budget is
only very generally specified when approved by Parliament. Further elaboration is carried out by FINNIDA.
The KESU can influence choices and specify details. 
<p>
Apart from the meetings at the Ministry, one or two times a year a seminar is organised for the members of
KESU and / or a larger public. Sometimes they are organised in cooperation with the Institute for
Development Studies of the University of Helsinki. Board members are also invited to meetings and
seminars organised by FINNIDA or others, and they receive reports and other documents prepared by the
Department. In April 1994 the KESU organised a seminar on Finland's relations with developing countries
and the European Union, where amongst others the acting Director General of EC/DG VIII held a
presentation. KESU intends to organise a seminar on human resource development.
<p>
The Board may have research conducted on its behalf, and previous Boards (TALKE's) have done so. Since
the KESU has no financial resources, the Board is financed through a special fund for Committees that is at
the disposal of the Minister for Development Cooperation. Apart form the work on the budget and the
discussion on the new Finnish Strategy, KESU has recently delivered statements and position papers on,
amongst others, cultural cooperation with developing countries, Finnish ODA - eligibility of refugee-related
costs and the implementation of the decisions of UNCED The latter statement was submitted to the Ministry
of the Environment. For 1994 the KESU intended to work on the effects of potential EU membership on
Finnish development assistance, and on a Finnish strategy for trade with developing countries. 
<p>
Until the beginning of the 1990s a Nordic Council of the Ministers of Development Cooperation of
Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden met bi-annually to discuss policy issues. Adjacent to these
meetings advisory meetings were organised of parliamentarians and researchers from the five countries. One
of these advisory meetings was a seminar Human Rights and Democracy held in Helsinki. The proceedings
were published in English. It is not known whether these meetings will be continued.
<p>
In Parliament, there are two Sub-Committees involved with development cooperation a Foreign Affairs
Committee and a Finance Committee. Since the recent cuts in budget the influence of Parliament on Finnish
aid has been reduced. The Foreign Affairs Committee is not supposed to deal with budgetary matters and
the Finance Committee is not supposed to make detailed statements on substance. 
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
NGOs in Finland such as trade unions and church based NGOs, traditionally have been strongly involved in
matters of international peace and development cooperation. Initially they were more East-West orientated
than North-South. The Percentage Movement is both a strong lobbying party towards the Government as
well as towards Parliament and the broad public. Approximately 60 NGOs are organised in an umbrella
organisation, the Service Centre for Development Cooperation (KEPA), that amongst others co-organises
public events on development cooperation. In 1994 FINNIDA conducted a major evaluation of NGO
development cooperation. The NGO related share of aid has been protected under the recent budget cuts.
Commitments through NGOs amounted to 2.6 per cent of ODA in 1992. The Government intends to
increase cooperation with NGOs. Among the topics of discussion between NGOs and the Government are:
the revision of Finnish development cooperation against the background of new international political
situations and domestic economic problems and the commercialisation of development aid. 
<p>
In 1992 FINNIDA organised in cooperation with Finnish consultancy firms and NGOs a large public event
on the future of Finnish development cooperation, "People and Development". This will be repeated in
1994.
<p>
According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey, 17 institutes qualify as 'Development Research and Training
Institutes'. Two institutes can be said to play a role in the policy debate on development cooperation: the
earlier mentioned Institute for Development Studies and the Centre for Training and Development.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
