<html><head><title>Planned Parenthood Challenges 1996/1</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img align=left hspace=3 src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo.gif"><h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i><br clear=left><hr><h1 align=center>Tackling unsafe abortion in Mauritius</h1><h3 align=center> by Dorothy Nyong'o and Geeta Oodit</h3><img align=left border=1 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=175 height=122 src="p37.jpg"><br><p> <b>  Family planning has been established in Mauritius for nearly40 years, and the programme has been very successful inlowering fertility and in improving maternal health. Butdespite a high contraceptive prevalence rate of 75 per cent,there is a still serious problem of unwanted pregnancy andunsafe abortion. The Mauritius Family Planning Association(MFPA) has campaigned to have the abortion problem discussedmore openly by the public and parliament and to address thecauses of unwanted pregnancy.</b><p><font size=2>The Minister of Women's Rights, Mrs Sheila Bappoo, speaking at the Mauritius Conference on Unsafe Abortion.</font><p>   Many of the young unmarried women attracted to the rapidlyexpanding industrial sector get involved in sexualrelationships and some end up pregnant. Most of them have hadlittle or no education on sexuality. In Mauritius abortion iscurrently not permitted on any grounds. But of course thisdoes not prevent often dangerous backstreet abortions takingplace.<p>   The MFPA recognized this as an important issue because itposes a threat to women's health and women's lives.  Oneemerging phenomenon is the increasing incidence of infertilitywhich may be closely linked to unsafe abortions.<p>   In 1993, MFPA decided to tackle the unsafe abortion issue, abold step in a country where not only is abortion illegal, butthere is also strong religious pressure against modern familyplanning methods, especially from the Catholic Church. A studycommissioned by the FPA showed that many women are not usingavailable health services, either because these are notreadily accessible, or because they are not happy with thequality of the services.  They therefore rely on lesseffective and traditional methods of family planning such aswithdrawal or calendar methods.  In fact, between 1985 and1991 contraceptive prevalence surveys revealed that while theoverall contraceptive prevalence rate had increased, so toohad the reliance on withdrawal as a method.<p>   The study also revealed that women were resorting to all kindsof dangerous means to abort, and many of these women weremarried and did not want any more children. Others were youngunmarried women.<p>   The FPA organized a symposium in 1993 to publicize and discussthe results of the abortion study.  Key people from differentbackgrounds, with different views, feelings, beliefs, andtraditions, were invited to come and speak openly about theissue.  The major outcome of the symposium was that theresearch findings spoke for themselves, and even the mostvocal opponents, the most conservative personalities, admittedthat there was indeed a problem to be considered.<p>   Despite their relatively small numbers, Catholics have exertedstrong influence on policy-making in Mauritius, and representthe main opposition to modern contraception and abortion. When MFPA publicized the results of its research, there wasreaction from the Catholic Church followed by a request fromthe head of the Catholic Church for a copy of the report. Because the study had been designed with utmost care, and theresults were glaring - indicating in fact that abortions weremostly practised by Catholic women who rely heavily on naturalfamily planning - and MFPA was very open with the study, therewas no further reaction from the leadership of the CatholicChurch.  MFPA is, however, developing further strategies toaddress the opposition.<p>   The advocacy campaign is two-pronged.  On the one hand, itaims at having abortion legalized on health grounds at least -to safeguard the health of the mother.  The FPA is taking alead role in setting up a mechanism for achieving thesestatutory changes.  A board composed of doctors, lawyers,psychologists and other specialists has been set up to reviewthe abortion law and propose appropriate changes that would beacceptable.<p>   On the other hand the FPA is advocating for the improvement offamily planning services, particularly for better services foryoung unmarried women and men.  It is calling upon thegovernment to invest more in high-quality reproductive andsexual health services, so that women and young people getbetter care and better services that would sustain continuedand effective acceptance and use of family planning.<p>   MFPA has developed very close links and collaborative effortswith the media, and gained their full support on the abortionissue.  The media have generated greater awareness on themagnitude of the problem through press articles, stories ofwomen, coverage of services.  The advocacy efforts of the MFPAwere first directed at the media.  Meetings were heldregularly with media personnel to sensitize them on the issue. Almost every week the press carried an article on abortionbased on the findings of the Association's studies, and theyreported the arguments in favour of legalized abortion. Widepublicity was also given on radio and TV which increasedpublic interest in the issue.<p>   The Association has worked closely with parliamentarians, andeven met with the then Prime Minister, who was convinced ofthe seriousness of the problem.  As a result of informationprovided by the FPA survey, a motion was tabled in theNational Assembly in 1994 calling for legalization of abortionon health grounds, but no discussion ensued as a result of itscontroversial nature and lack of support from Catholic groups. In March 1994, MFPA hosted an IPPF African Regional Conferenceon Unsafe Abortion, which led to a more widespreadunderstanding of the extent of the problem in the region. Following the conference, one parliamentarian took a bold stepand tabled a second motion in the National Assembly for the"legalization of abortion in cases of rape and incest".  Thatmotion was never debated.<p>   But by the time the Mauritius Conference on Unsafe Abortionwas held, bringing together more than 100 participants from 20African countries, the public mood had been stirred in favourof the talks. The deliberations were widely covered by thenational and international media, setting the stage foraffirmative action to address the issue of unsafe abortion.<p>   MFPA worked very closely with the Ministry of Women's Rightsand succeeded in getting this Ministry to recognize abortionas an urgent issue needing a change in the law.  This wasclearly stated in the Ministry's White Paper on women anddevelopment, a policy statement that was prepared for theFourth World Conference on Women held in Beijing in September1995.  <p>   As a direct result of the advocacy campaign, the policyclimate in Mauritius has changed favourably.  The public ingeneral is more conscious about unsafe abortion and theenvironment is conducive to further discussion, research andgreater changes.  The Ministry of Health has now decided tocollect more data on abortion.  There have recently beenelections, and the new Government seems more open to reform.The MFPA is determined to maintain the momentum, and sees itsrole more stimulating as it contributes to the wave of change.<p>    <hr><p>©Copyright IPPF<br><font size=-1>Picture: &copy;Jeremy Hamand/IPPF </font><hr><img align=left src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo2.gif"> <a href="index.html">PPC 1996/1 Contents</a><br><a href="../index.html">IPPF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
