<html>
<header>
<title>Institutional Issues in DANIDA Projects: A Synthesis</title>
</HEADER><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<h3><center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/danida.gif"><p>
Institutional Issues in DANIDA Projects: A Synthesis.
<p>
(DANIDA Evaluation Summary No. 1992/6)
<p>
For more information on <a href="daneval.htm">DANIDA's Evaluation Unit</a></h3>
</center><p>

<hr>
<p>
<h3>Introduction</h3>



DAC's Evaluation Expert Group decided in 1989 to make institutional issues a cross sectoral theme
for all evaluations during 1990-91. A synthesis Report has been prepared which summarizes the
experience with institutional aspects of development co-operation, which can be extracted from 19
project evaluation reports completed by Danida during 1990-91. 
<p>
The experience relates to four key issues: Screening and choice of institutional partners; the
correspondence between project objectives and institutional design; the instruments used for
capacity-building; and institutional sustainability. The Report examines these four issues for three
sectors: the productive sectors; physical infrastructure; and social infrastructure / human resource
development. Finally, it suggest a few perspectives on institutional development. The Synthesis Report
has been prepared by COWIConsult.
<p>
<h3>The Extent of Institutional Screening and Choice during Project Design</h3>
<p>
The choice was in most projects made implicitly. The choice of institutional implementation
arrangements was justified only in those instances where the institutional environment was known in
advance of the project design because of earlier Danida projects in the same sector and country. 
<p>
Most of the evaluated projects were designed in the late 1970s or the early 1980s when awareness of
institutional issues in development co-operation was limited. Danida's preparation of projects eligible
for
loan funding gave almost full design responsibility to the recipient government. Thus, none of the loan
financed projects was based on explicit screening of options for institutional partners in the recipient
country.
<p>
In general, institutional screening and explicit choice of implementation arrangements have clearly
been
underutilized as instruments available to Danida during project appraisal and design as well as during
Danida's general interaction with the national institutions of developing countries.
<p>
<h3>Appropriateness of Project Institutions in view of Project Objectives</h3>

There are in principle several models for institutional implementation arrangements at different levels
of
society. The projects reviewed tended to be implemented through central government boards and
corporations (parastatals), line ministry offices, or ad hoc project organizations.
<p>
The 19 evaluation reports do not give conclusive evidence on the effectiveness of the five models.
Almost
all projects experienced problems with the institutional implementation arrangements in relation to their
objectives. Four problems were quite typical:
<p>
1)  Projects that were integrated vertically into the existing government administration tended to
develop
    a structure of parallel implementation. This had many reasons, including: Economic and financial
    crises in the recipient country, forcing Danida to finance a growing share of recurrent costs;
shortages
    of qualified staff which was offset by Danida advisers; differences between Danida's and the
govern-
    ment's management, budgeting and reporting procedures; and insufficent host institution
involvement
    during project planning.
<p>
2)  Projects requiring inter-institutional co-operation and co-ordination faced severe problems because
of
    lack of horizontal and vertical integration. This applied both to projects that were sought integrated
    into the government administration and to projects implemented by ad hoc autonomous project or-
    ganizations. Thus, excessive complexity in institutional arrangements is a prime cause of institu-
    tional constraints and weak implementation. Irrespective of the desirability of co-operation and co-
    ordination, the weak public sector institutions in Danida's partner countries usually cannot cope.
    Besides, they often lack incentives to invest time and energy in various co-ordination committees,
    because the decisive decisions are taken in other forums.
<p>
3)  The success of projects implemented by parastatals depended to a large extent on government
    policies and priorities. This is especially relevant for commodity / financial assistance projects.
<p>
4)  Projects implemented by separate ad hoc organizations or by joint venture arrangements were well
    implemented with respect to technical effectiveness and efficiency but tended to experience
problems
    with respect to integration and handing over of activities to the host country institutions. It may
be
    necessary to use an autonomous project organization as a vehicle for project implementation. It
should
    be combined, however, with institutional support instruments aimed at integration of project
activities
    into the existing government administration when the project is finalized.
<p>
<h3>The Effectiveness of Project Support Instruments for Capacity-building</h3>

Only about half of the projects evaluated included technical assistance, and none of the projects aimed
solely at institutional development. Still, projects rely on various support instruments, directed at
institutions at different levels of society (central government; regional and district administrations; local
institutions at field level; etc.) according to the specific objectives of the capacity-building exercise.
The
overall - and not too surprising - finding was that the projects tended to give priority to the
achievement of
technical / operational objectives at the expense of institutional development. Secondly, several projects
aimed their institutional support instruments mainly at the field level, where they developed 
effective operating units. Institutional support aimed at staff at "headquarters" level was found in some
projects only, and then mainly in the form of a counterpart arrangement.
<p>
Thirdly, the most frequently applied capacity-building instruments were on-the-job training and
organized training. These institutional support instruments were in most projects aimed at enhanced technical /
operational capabilities at peripheral levels of the partner administration, instead of at increased planning
and
management capabilities at headquarters / national level.
<p>
Capacity-building at local level aiming at increased user group participation in planning and
implementation of project or other government activities was not found in any of the projects
evaluated. A few projects relied on user group participation, but it was confined to participation in
implementation of decisions already taken at central level or by outsiders.
<p>
<h3>The Institutional Sustainability of Project Activities</h3>

None of the projects had used institutional sustainability as a guiding principle and criterion for the
design of project implementation arrangements. Institutional sustainability was not a primary concern
in any of the project phases. The sustainability of project activities was, however, considered
extensively by the evaluation missions on some of the projects. Thus, institutional (and other forms
of) sustainability has now become part of the Terms of References for project evaluation missions, but
apparently still not for all of the missions and staff involved in project design and implementation.
<p>
Institutional sustainability was almost never evaluated as an issue in its own right. It was seen
primarily as an aspect and effect of the financial situation. Thus, lack of financial sustainability was
a major problem in many projects, irrespectively of sector. In some projects Danida had started
funding a growing portion of the recurrent costs, to secure implementation of project activities. 
<p>
On technical sustainability, the evaluation reports indicated that the technology chosen in most projects
was appropriate, except that systems of operation and maintenance were inadequate or missing. Social
sustainability was a problem in a number of projects, mainly because the users had not been involved
in the identification and preparation of project activities or because they could not afford the service
provided. This was, for example, the case in some electrification projects.
<p>
There were few sector-specific differences in the choice of institutional implementation arrangements,
in the use of support instruments for capacity-building and in the likelihood of sustainability. The
decisive institutional issue was in all sectors found to be the direct interaction between the institutional
actors involved in project implementation.
<p>
<h4>Perspectives on Institutional Development </h4>

Based partly on an earlier evaluation of institutional aspects of Danish project assistance, the Synthesis
Report suggests 15 measures, which donor and other development agencies could apply in the design
and implementation of development projects. The aim is to secure integration and ownership of
projects by institutions of the recipient country. The institutional demands on the donor staff and
project designers include that they:
<ul>
<li>Institutional Screening and Choice
<ul>
<li>Undertake - before project design - a thorough screening of the available options for institutional
    implementation arrangements, and then make an explicit choice of national partner institutions in
    accordance with the project objectives.
</ul>
<p>
<li>Institutional Project Design
<ul>
<li>Aim at simplicity and focus in project design so that project objectives raise the smallest possible
demands on institutional implementation arrangements.
<li>Clarify the institutional development objectives that are relevant for the project: effective project
implementation; sustainable project impact; technical capacity-building; and political capacity-building
(e.g. transparency or participation).
<li>Seek the involvement of the intended beneficiaries in the design and planning of institutional    
implementation arrangements; and aim at a change in emphasis in the planning and organization of
public service delivery from a supply-driven to a demand-oriented approach.
</ul>
<p>
<li>Capacity-building and Institutional Project Support
<ul>
<li>Ensure continuity in technical assistance to the selected partner institutions, and flexibility in the
adaptation of the instruments of institutional support to the changing needs of the partner institutions
for capacity-building.
</ul>
<p>
<li>Institutional Sustainability
<ul>
<li>Demand accountability in the implementing institutions, both as a means of performance control
and to promote participation of the intended beneficiaries.
<p>
<li>Seek maximum involvement of the intended beneficiaries / user groups in the operations,
management and, where relevant, funding of project implementation
</ul>
</ul>
<p>
These measures are "ideal" in their demands on development agencies. They are objectives to be
remembered and considered in the complex daily work with institutional aspects of development
co-operation.
<p>
<h3>Danida's comments and Follow-up</h3>

Danida acknowledge the problems of securing sustainable institutional implementation arrangement
for development projects, enabling the recipient countries to obtain full integration and ownership of
donor funded projects by its own institutions.
<p>
Danida is in agreement with the recommendations as described in the report and has already taken
action on promoting activities relating to institutional issues in project design and implementation.
Workshops have been held, and several "Issue-papers" are in the process of being written, in order to
create more awareness about the subject in Danida.
<p>
The problems are recognized by most of the international donors and development organizations, and
Danida will continue the necessary international cooperation within DAC and other fora to further
strengthen the knowledge regarding institutional issues in development cooperation.
<p>
<HR>
