<head>

<title> Sri Lanka Peacemaker</title>

</head>

<body>



<b>PRESS and NEWS RELEASES</b><p>



<b>Sri Lanka peacemakers tour UK</b><p>

        

CAFOD, one the UK's major aid agencies, has invited a prominent 

peace and development husband and wife team to undertake a 

speaking tour of England and Wales in May.<p>

        

During their UK tour Joe and Lourdes William hope to persuade 

people to lobby the British government to call for both the Sri 

Lankan government and the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Ealam to 

persist in seeking peace despite the recent break down in 

negotiations and the failure of the "cessation of hostilities" 

agreement.<p>

        

Sri Lanka has a population of 17 million people of which 600,000 

live in refugee camps.<p>

        

The civil war is between the country's Sinhalese and Tamil 

populations. The Tamil minority group wants its own separate 

state.<p>

        

Joe William is the head of the relief and rehabiliation division 

of SEDEC (CAFOD's sister Church agency) in Sri Lanka.<p>

        

He is deeply involved in the peace process as executive secretary 

of the National Peace Council which he helped establish.<p>

        

His wife, Lourdes Mary Therese William joined SEDEC in 1991 as a 

media officer, following years of experience as a teacher and 

counsellor.<p>

        

SEDEC's emergency programme is primarily assistance to Tamil 

Refugees in camps, spending US$2-3 million per year.<p>

        

The National Peace Council has called on the government and the 

LTTE to agree a framework for negotiations, extend the cessation 

of hostilities into an official and comprehensive ceasefire 

agreement and implement a monitoring process in which foreign 

observers form part of the monitoring teams.<p>

        

President Chandrika Kumaratunga told a meeting of the World 

Bank's Paris Donors Aid Group, which pledged $850 million aid to 

Sri Lanka on March 27, that she would go to any lengths to put 

the peace process back on track.<p>

        

For further information contact Mary McCollum tel: 0171 733 7900 or MMCOLLUM@CAFOD.ATTMAIL.COM.<p>

        

<hr>

