<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>Capacity Development in the Environment - A practical aid to sustainable development?<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 12, 1996</h3>

<I>Agenda 21, the global action plan for environment and development adopted by world governments at the Earth Summit in 1992, brought the terms sustainable development and capacity building into popular usage. Like sustainable development, capacity building is a catch phrase which is poorly defined, widely used, and often confused and abused. For those in aid agencies charged with supporting capacity building in developing countries, more precision is required, and more detail on the how to of capacity building.  This briefing attempts to give the practitioner a clearer understanding of the issues underlying capacity, starting with an overview of the broad capacity development agenda and then focusing on the specific issue of the environment</I>. 
<p>
<H3>From Capacity Building to Capacity Development</H3>

Capacity building is the key to Agenda 21s successful implementation. According to Agenda 21, nations (with appropriate support) will have to build capacity to identify and solve their own environment and development problems, supported in appropriate ways by external agencies.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Box 1. Definitions</h4></center>
<p>
<B>Capacity - A dictionary definition</B> (Collins Concise Dictionary, 1989)<ul><li>the ability to understand or learn<li>the ability to do or produce</ul><p><B>Capacity Building - Agenda 21s definition</B>  (Chapter 37, UNCED, 1992.)<p>
"Specifically, capacity building encompasses the countrys human, scientific, technological, organizational, institutional and resource capabilities. A fundamental goal of capacity building is to enhance the ability to evaluate and address the crucial questions related to policy choices and modes of implementation among development options, based on an understanding of environment potentials and limits and of needs perceived by the people of the country concerned".
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
Capacity building is not a new concept. It is simply taking over as the new umbrella term for a mixture of approaches, such as training and technical assistance, used by development assistance agencies.
<p>
Initially, efforts focused on the overall capacity of the state in developing countries, and sought to improve the design and functioning of individual organizations. Through technical cooperation, training, and financial support, development assistance aimed to build the ability of state organizations to become specialized, and to manage a programme of public investment. At that time, this construction of capacity was known as institution building.
<p>
Organization building and institution building are often used interchangeably because their boundaries blur. 
<ul>
<li><I>Organization building</I> (in its strictest sense) refers to technical cooperation activities which address questions of capacity in single organizations or clusters of organizations, through improving human skills and changing their management structure and systems.
<li><I>Institution building</I> involves broader capacity activities that attempt to address how organizations function within society, how they identify and solve problems, how they encourage changes in patterns of behaviour and values in society, and how they build support for their priorities and concerns, in other words, promoting social change. 
</ul><p>
Institution building eventually took over from organization building as the dominant term, and capacity building is now starting to take over as the umbrella which describes them both. 
<p>
Up to the 1970s, there was a slight change in terminology from institutional building to institutional development. Building implied there was nothing there in the first place, and by failing to acknowledge existing systems, infrastructure, and ways of doing things, was seen as insulting and arrogant. Development implies improving existing structures.
<p>
In sum, up to the 1980s, technical cooperation was aid agencies dominant contribution to institution building, and most of it was really only organizational development. 

<H3>Mixed Success</H3>

The dominant model for technical cooperation was the expert-counterpart model. In this model, a highly paid expatriate expert performed a job alongside a poorly paid local counterpart, while giving the counterpart on-the-job training. Generally, this approach failed. It was expensive and the salary differentials caused resentment and tension.  Despite the mission to train and hand-over, the level of training was too abstract for new skills to be retained once external guidance had ceased. It was donor-driven and undermined ownership and decision-making.  Finally this approach was limited by concentrating solely upon individual state organizations (ministries, departments, parastatals etc), rather than all development actors, including ordinary people, the private sector and non-governmental organisations.
<p>
The concept of sustainable development places a further imperative on the need for an approach which crosses departmental, ministry and sectoral boundaries, and from the local to the international, involving the major stake-holders.
<p>
In reaction to these perceived failures, an approach known as development management shifted the emphasis away from the improvement of individual organizations, towards the management and implementation of development programmes as a whole, and onto the objectives of social development and basic human needs. Key changes included a shift to decentralized bureaucracies; bottom-up instead of top-down; nations themselves driving socio-economic change, not donors; and involvement of all groups in society, not just government.
<p>
This approach is strongly reflected in the OECD Development Assistance Committees (DAC) principles for capacity development (now the accepted term within the DAC), which recognise that traditional approaches have been largely counter-productive for the development of local capacities. (See Donor Assistance to Capacity Development in Environment, Development Cooperation Guidelines Series, DAC, 1995).
<p>
The history, definitions and principles behind the term capacity building will be endlessly debated. One useful perspective is to see sustainable development as the goal, and capacity development as the means to achieve it. But for those concerned with the how-to-do-it of capacity, experience is only now being brought together.

<H3>Capacity Development in Practice</H3>

Capacity development is now targeted at the political, economic, social, and legal institutions that promote an open market economy, economic policy making and implementation, good governance including plural political systems, judicial, legislative and state administrative systems, the media and civil society organizations. 
Looking at the lessons from capacity development, aid agencies have not proved effective at supporting successful initiatives. Evaluations by USAID, the World Bank, and the British ODA show that capacity development projects are far less successful than other projects or project components. The reasons for the poor performance are both related to the nature of aid agencies themselves, and the inherent problems of capacity development:
<ul>
<li><I>The bureaucracies, systems and procedures of aid agencies tend to be inflexible</I>, rely on rigid project cycle frameworks designed for short-term intervention, and judge success by previously set goals, inputs and outputs. Capacity development requires a flexible process-driven approach, which encourages learning, adaptive management and experimentation, a long-term commitment, the building of human skills and competencies, and a deep sensitivity to local culture, politics and context. It cannot be programmed in detail from the outset.
<p>
<li><I>Capacity development projects are still donor driven</I>. Donors have a poor understanding of local realities, and often push imported and inappropriate organizational and institutional models. One example is the promotion of off-the-shelf environmental laws and frameworks.
<p>
<li><I>Capacity development is inherently difficult</I>. There is still a poor understanding of how to develop capacity well and by consequence there are few benchmarks for evaluating how much capacity has been developed.  This may explain the high rate of perceived failure.
<p>
<li><I>Capacity development initiatives lack appreciation by the public and politicians</I> as they are long-term and generally only a means to other development goals, with less tangible outputs compared to short-term visible physical projects. They also do not benefit powerful interest groups such as contractors, and therefore enjoy little political support.
<p>
<li><I>Capacity development requires special human skills</I> for dealing with organisational development, change and turbulence. But there is uncertainty as to how to develop these skills, which go beyond standard management and administration training. Many management and consultancy services are available, but their quality and relevance is doubtful.
</ul><p>
In sum, there are clear contradictions between the way aid agencies operate (inflexible, heavily programmed, quantitative indicators and visible short-term goals, inputs and outputs), and the qualities and mechanisms needed for capacity development (flexibility, loosely programmed, iterative, quantitative and qualitative process indicators, objectives which develop over time, and less visible or very long-term results). 
<p>
Most aid agencies accept that they should not actively be doing capacity development; their role is to support it through designing flexible funding and development management mechanisms. But even restricted to an enabling role, the problems of supporting capacity development remain huge, particularly for the environment.

<H3>Capacity Development in the Environment</H3>

The term Capacity Development in the Environment (CDE) was only recently coined, and is defined by the DAC as follows:
<p>
<i>Capacity in the environment represents the ability of individuals, groups, organizations and institutions in a given context to address environmental issues as part of a range of efforts to achieve sustainable development. The term capacity development in the environment (CDE) describes the process by which capacity in environment and appropriate institutional structures are enhanced.</i>
<p>
In other words, CDE is part of any societys struggle to achieve sustainable development, and to implement the conclusions of the Earth Summit. Key elements of CDE are summarised in Box 2.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Box 2.  Key elements for Capacity Development in the Environment</h4></center>
<ul>
<li>CDE aims to promote <I>sound environmental considerations</I>; to reinforce processes that lead to self-reliance, equity and justice in ways that enhance environmental management; and to strengthen institutional pluralism in civil society.
<li>CDE requires consideration of all the different <I>stakeholders</I> in an environmental issue, taking full account of gender; 
<li>CDE is <I>process</I> rather than product oriented, and the process is owned and driven by the community in which it is based;  
<li>CDE involves a <I>variety</I> of management techniques, analytical tools, incentives and organisational structures for achieving a given policy objective.</ul>
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
Aid agencies now need to apply these basic DAC orientations for CDE to the particular field of environmental activity in which they are attempting to develop capacity. As the DAC orientations describe, this may range from research, planning, and NGO training, to impact assessment, environmental economics tools, information and monitoring, national strategies, appropriate technologies, awareness and education, policy dialogue, participatory methods, conflict resolution, and support to the private sector to internalise the environment.

<H3>What must Donors do?</H3>

The role of donors in the process of CDE is limited and only those who directly hold a stake in the environment can make processes sustainable according to the DAC. The process should be driven by the recipient country, and full involvement of local communities is stated as a prerequisite. Other important enabling factors are described as the competence of government to formulate appropriate policies, make timely decisions and implement them effectively, and a fully accountable and democratic government. Common sense would suggest that competent governments dont need their capacity developed. This points to a dilemma.  Effective capacity development requires some existing competence or capacity. For example, even completing a Logical Framework requires a degree of management expertise that those in greatest need of capacity development do not have.
<p>
The challenge for donors lies in changing the conceptual, organisational, and financial modalities of aid, to fit with capacity development needs.  To do this, donors must rethink many apparent trends and patterns in development assistance, such as:
<ul>
<li>Demands for greater public accountability, which result in donor defined priorities, increased conditionality, and a desire for projects with visible results (product not process);
<p>
<li>Rigid and highly structured programming tools, such as Logical Framework Analysis, which some argue are inappropriate for capacity programmes, and are designed more to meet the needs of donors than recipients;
<p>
<li>Down-sizing or withdrawing of country offices, which further alienates donors from local problems and perspectives;
<p>
<li>Cut backs of staff and budgets in aid agencies, leading to an overloading, and loss of specialist knowledge;
<p>
<li>An uncertain future for aid, and a pressure to demonstrate results, which shortens the commitments donors can make, and which drives them towards capacity development where capacity already exists, lessening the risk of failure.
</ul><p>
Some of these challenges may in the short term be politically intractable. It is not surprising therefore, that donors are searching for practical methods and approaches or tools to help them with CDE. In this difficult policy context seven major challenges face donors seeking to support CDE:
<ol>
<li>To design country-driven multi-stakeholder programmes in CDE (these by nature need to be loosely structured, open, and flexible);
<p>
<li>To broaden financial mechanisms to make them more flexible, to include longer-term financial commitments, programmatic approaches to funding, and support for trust funds and umbrella agreements;
<p>
<li>To promote programme funding that necessarily involves fewer clear cut outputs and less easily monitorable and quantifiable targets;
<p>
<li>To encourage greater adaptability to local conditions through delegation and decentralization;
<p>
<li>To allow for longer and more flexible time horizons to accommodate a process approach;
<p>
<li>To enhance internal donor capacity through training and broadening skills in specialist subjects related to CDE, from mediation to environmental economics;
<p>
<li>To devise new indicators for CDE and develop new tools for building CDE.
</ol><p>
As yet, there do not seem to be any tool-kits for developing the capacity for what might be called adaptive management. This is management which learns and adapts, thinks creatively and makes good judgements in the face of complexity and change, rather than seeking to command and control. These qualities develop with years of patient practice and experience, and as a result of the development of professional skills at the level of the individual, as well as of the organization.
<p>
From the adaptive management perspective, evidence of capacity development would include:
<ul>
<li>That amongst the various stakeholders there was learning and the development of new professional strengths, gained through experience or training;
<p>
<li>That there was an institutional ability to recognise and use this learning in improving programme practice;
<p>
<li>That there was an increased overall effectiveness of the organisation to carry out its programme work.
</ul>
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Box 3: Capacity Development Techniques</h4></center>
<p>
There is a range of approaches, techniques, and new institutional arrangements, which, with the skill, experience, openness, and good judgement of the practitioner can be used to support capacity development in the environment. For example:
<ul><li>Institutional arrangements through which support is channelled:<ul><li>Locally controlled trust funds and small scale funding mechanisms that do not require detailed accounting.<li>Building-up local organizations who take-over the institution-building support role.<li>Improve evaluation frameworks - moving beyond the checklist approach.<li>Emphasize the building up of individual skills and competencies (professionalism) as well as organizational and institutional ones.</ul>
<p><li>Development management techniques:Techniques for planning, strategy and analysis: stakeholder analysis, participatory techniques, EIA, environmental assessment, environmental profiles National Conservation Strategies, National Environmental Action Plans and Sustainable Development Strategies.<p><li>Tools for implementation: 	Appropriate policy making processes, conflict resolution, roundtables.<p><li>Tools for monitoring and evaluation: New participatory process and output indicators.</ul>
</td></tr></table>
</center>

<H3>The Next Steps</H3>

For capacity development to become a practical aid to implementing sustainable development policies, there is a need for greater understanding of capacity development in the field, and its links to policy and practice; practical techniques, methods and approaches for developing capacity; and practitioners with the capacity themselves to use these techniques, methods and approaches wisely, creatively and selectively.

<p>
<I>This briefing was prepared by Koy Thomson, Assistant Executive Director of IIED. He is an advisor to UNDPs Capacity 21 Programme, and is responsible for managing and developing IIEDs programme for capacity strengthening for environment and development.  He was the NGO advisor to the UK Delegation to the Earth Summit.</I>
