<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 21 November 1996</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
Back in the late 1960s when I was at University the military, western
governments and the private sector were dirty words. Undergraduates sought
to emulate Ch&#233; Guevera and it was the thoughts of Marcuse, Chairman Mao and
Marx that were earnestly debated.
<P>
Today all of this has changed. Conservative parties are flourishing, the
private sector has become the motor of development and graduates are
burning the midnight oil to understand marketing, advanced economics and
all else that is necessary to achieve an MBA.
<P>
Many argue that this is all cyclical and sometime early in the next
millennium social values and capital will achieve a new balance. Perhaps,
some in the Caribbean suggest, this may emerge in a post-Castro Cuba if it
can construct a socialist market economy within an open civil society.
<P>
But today, the tensions still continue to grow between those who believe
that the state should retain a controlling role and those who believe that
the market will determine roles in a world in which thinking about borders
and sovereignty are being revolutionised by information technology and
globalisation.
<P>
This will in all probability be the background theme in the debate that is
just beginning on the EC Development Commissioner's green paper on
post-Lom&#233; relations, which was finally agreed by the EC College of
Commissioners on November 21 as this column was being written. The
document, which I intend to write at length about next week, basically
emphasises: the need to consider differentiating European approaches by
region or sub-region of the ACP while leaving it up to the ACP to decide
whether they stay together as a group; a key role for the private sector;
and a visibly effective and efficient results-oriented aid programme.
<p>
Apart from the obvious questions this will raise about relations between
ACP States and how the region determines a negotiating strategy that is to
its benefit, much of the core debate is likely to centre on trade issues,
market access, preference, transitional mechanisms, competitiveness, open
markets and - above all - the ability of the private sector to deliver
timely and positive results. This debate will not be easy as it is in
effect about ceding power and responsibility.
<P>
It is frequently alleged by some in government in the Caribbean who
maintain the need for a centrist, statist approach that it is not viable
working with the Caribbean private sector. They assert: private sector
associations are dominated by a few large companies; the Caribbean private
sector as a whole has no coherent view; most in the private sector are
commission agents; and in some nations expatriate interests still
predominate. These prejudices are often conveyed to those in Brussels or to
governments elsewhere in order to continue to bolster the argument for
maintaining government-to-government exclusivity in treaties such as the
Lom&#233; Convention.
<P>
Last week an <A HREF="ccelowe.htm">independent report</A> written by a Caribbean researcher, Michelle
Lowe, was published on behalf of the Caribbean Association of Industry and
Commerce (CAIC). This study, which was funded by European and Caribbean
members of the Caribbean Council for Europe, looks at the requirements of
the Caribbean private sector of the EU in the period up to 2000 and after
the Lom&#233; Convention expires. Unlike any previous document it brings
together the views of the largest and smallest private sector associations
and their members; it incorporates the opinions of powerful sectoral
associations such as those for tourism, rice and rum; and it embraces the
views of chambers and others in the French Departments, the Dominican
Republic and even Cuba.
<p>
The two-part report contains some important recommendations. These include:
<UL>
<LI>identifying new mechanisms to facilitate a dialogue between the EU, regional governments and those in the business sector and civil society;
<p> 
<LI>the creation of new intermediaries in the private sector to deliver programmes through the private sector in a timely manner;
<p> 
<LI>the creation of new financial instruments through which the EU can give direct support to the private sector;
<p> 
<LI>the identification of new mechanisms that enhance backward and forward linkages between tourism and Caribbean economies through private sector mechanisms;
<p> 
<LI>the creation of a special relationship between the French DOM, as Europe in the Caribbean, and the Caribbean ACP States; and 
<p> 
<LI>the creation of stable mechanisms that ensure a successful transition out of preference.
</UL>
<p>
These and many other issues are dealt with at length in the report which
makes clear that the need is for governments, whether they be in the region
or in Europe, to demonstrate a full commitment to the concept of
decentralised co-operation if Caribbean economies are to achieve
competitiveness in the next millennium. CAIC is in the process of
circulating the document to Caribbean governments and regional
institutions. It is to be hoped that its conclusions are incorporated into
the region's post-Lom&#233; IV negotiating position.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on November 25, 1996</i><p>
Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments on content or style
to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter
Ballantyne</a>, Information Programme, ECDPM</H6>
