<DOCNO>WT17-B17-83</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA007-000070-B001-261</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.ecdpm.org:80/euforic/cce/coljan17.htm 193.128.6.150 19970222015841 text/html 7689
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 01:58:21 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Fri, 17 Jan 1997 14:05:44 GMT
Content-length: 7515
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 17 January 1997</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>In December l996, the EC published and circulated a green paper produced by
the EC's Development Commissioner setting out a series of options for post
Lom&#233; arrangements between the EU and the ACP.
<P>
Since that time (and in some cases before) member states of the Union have
been developing their own position papers, although few have yet been
formally endorsed as policy in the countries concerned. EU member states
vary in their approach with France and Britain likely to be most supportive
of an extension of the existing arrangements subject to new conditionalities, new approaches to financial resources and the need for
any new trade arrangements to be WTO compatible. The Dutch and to some extent the Germans and the Belgians, seek convergence in EU development and foreign policy. Thus they question the concept of a special relationship
for the ACP, many aspects of the present Treaty and expect that whatever
resources are available will be used in a more efficient and innovative
manner. For their part, Scandinavian nations appear to be placing their
emphasis on aid for the poorest. In common with all EU member states they
see much of the debate focusing on Africa. Separately the European
Parliament wants to see a modernised Lom&#233; after 2000. Despite this, the
opinions of member states are not widely known in the Caribbean, nor has
the region made them aware of its thinking.
<P>
During the latter months of the Dutch presidency, or possibly during the
first months of the Luxembourg presidency, member states will formally
agree a negotiating mandate. This leaves the Caribbean region with little
time in which to determine its position and that of its social partners and
weave this into a Cariforum and then an ACP negotiating mandate.
<P>
There are many pressing issues that cross traditional boundaries between
government and social partners such as the private sector, the trades
unions and environmentalists that need consensus before more technical
questions are considered.
<P>
It is therefore pleasing to learn that the next Caricom intersessional of
heads of government in late February will concentrate on developing a post
Lom&#233; stance for Cariforum, the wider than Caricom group that embraces the
ACP Caribbean. 
<P>
The meeting will have a broad-based agenda but it is to be hoped that the
meeting will address six specific areas requiring a clear and unified
position. These are:
<UL>
<LI>What is the best way to incorporate a region-specific approach into an
ACP negotiating mandate and a post Lom&#233; arrangement? By almost every
measure the Caribbean region's requirements are different from most of its
partners in the ACP. By 2005 the region will be seeking to incorporate
itself together with its partners in the ACS into the FTAA, possibly via
NAFTA parity. This will bring into question the sustainability of any
non-reciprocal or preferential trade arrangements that might be established
with Europe after the year 2000. Changed relationships after 2000 also
raise questions about what Lom&#233; instruments need to be created that specifically benefit the Caribbean as it prepares for transition to open
markets. This is not to argue against maintaining ACP solidarity but to
suggest that the development needs of the Caribbean are likely to be
different to those of its partners in the ACP. As such it points to the
need for new instruments that offer material assistance with transition in
a manner that encourages a region-specific approach and regional
integration.
<P>
<LI>Will a post Lom&#233; arrangement require a new regional political balance
being achieved? Historically the Caribbean beneficiaries of the Lom&#233;
relationship were the nations of Caricom. Today the Dominican Republic,
Haiti and maybe in time Cuba, expect equal treatment from a post Lom&#233;
arrangement. This may change the nature of the region's requirements and
its negotiating stance. It will particularly impact on the development of a
negotiating mandate in respect of trade. A case may have to be developed
for special and differential treatment for the smaller anglophone nations.
How well is the region prepared for this?
<P>
<LI>The post Lom&#233; debate offers the opportunity for the Caribbean to
determine what new instruments it needs. The post Lom&#233; debate offers the
opportunity for the Caribbean to determine what new forms of assistance it
needs. The EC has already indicated that it is prepared to consider new
ideas in respect of the environment, research and development; training;
investment promotion and attraction; finance; and for the private sector
and other social partners. This points to the need for the region to
identify and agree on the nature of existing constraints and future
aspirations and develop an ACP compatible but region-specific range of
future requirements.
<P>
<LI>The private sector's view will be a key component in this process. The
private sector is recognised as being a key element in this process. CAIC,
the rum industry, the rice industry, the sugar industry and by mid-year,
the tourism industry, will have or will shortly have post Lom&#233; positions.
These need to be incorporated into the region's negotiating position in a
manner that ensures that the Caribbean can use post Lom&#233; assistance to
enhance and secure its competitiveness in more open markets. This suggests
that in the post Lom&#233; negotiating process a new balance must be established
in the private sector/public sector relationship.
<P>
<LI>Outside players such as the US and the WTO will need to be considered in
this equation. As events in respect of bananas have clearly shown it is
unlikely that in the late l990s the post 2000 negotiations will be regarded
by the US and others in the benign way of previous Lom&#233; discussions. The
position of the US and others in the WTO or ACS on a successor arrangement
needs to be determined.
<P>
<LI>Beyond this there are many specific issues including: the post Lom&#233;/DOM
relationship with the region; the future requirements of the OCT in the
region; and provisions regarding co-operation with neighbouring states and
most especially, those with Cuba in particular and the ACS in general.
<P></UL>
Resolving these questions will not be easy as they cross the fault lines in
the region which are frequently papered over or ignored. In this respect
the probable presence of the Dominican Republic's farseeing new President,
Leonel Fernandez, at the Caricom intersessional may do much to bring the
new thinking in the Hispanic Caribbean alongside that of Barbados' Prime
Minister, Owen Arthur, as the two appear to share many similar views.
<P>
The meeting may therefore determine whether new thinking or old will
influence the region's future relations with Europe.
<p>
<HR>
