<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>National Non-Uniform Day Acknowledgements</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><a href="nnud_contents.html"><img align=right hspace=10 src="unicef_pix/nnud_leaf.gif"></a><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif" WIDTH="160" HEIGHT="53" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=left><BR clear=left><br><HR><BR><P><CENTER><B>Data File -Development costs for Kashishi Village<BR></B></CENTER><P><I>750/- (Tanzanian shillings) = &#163;1.00 (Sterling)</I><BR><BR>Kashishi Village in Geita District in north-west Tanzania is a typical Tanzanianvillage They believe in being self-reliant. They grow their own food, raisecash crops, use their skills to improve their village and support villagedevelopment programmes like the ones described here. The development programmeis decided upon by the villagers. They oversee each part of the programmeand raise the money needed. <BR><BR>There are 3,740 people living in 400 households. A household can consistof more than one family and several wage earners. Every 10 households formsa group called a cell, there are 40 cells in the village. The income perhousehold ranges between 40-60,000/- (&#163;53.33-&#163;80.00) per annum.<BR><BR>People in the village contribute money to the development of the villagewhich is a local tax. In 1994 700,000/- (&#163;93.33) was paid in tax, 20%of this is supposed to come back to the village.<BR><BR><B>Preliminary calculation</B> <BR>All answers in: a) Tanzanian shillings (/-)  b) Pounds sterling (&#163;)<BR>a.	How much does each household contribute to this tax? <BR>b.	How much money of the 1994 budget should be returned to the village?<BR> <BR><HR><BR><B>A. The school needs benches<BR>Need:</B> There are many more children going to school.<BR><B>Action:</B> Every cell will provide the wood to make a bench - marketvalue 4,500/- (&#163;6.00)<BR><B>A1.</B> If each cell produces a bench how many benches will the schoolreceive?<BR><B>A2.</B> What is the total market value of these benches? <BR><BR><B>B. Wages for Village Health Workers<BR>Need:</B> Every village has two Health Workers, salary equivalent 2,500/-(&#163;3.33) per month each.  <BR><B>Action:</B> Each household to  give 2 kilos of corn, <BR>7-8 bags of flour (equivalent to 2,500/-).<BR><B>B1.</B> What is the cash value of one Health Worker's salary for theyear?<BR><B>B2.</B> What difference does it make to a Health Worker to receive incomein kind e.g. corn and flour, rather than in cash? Try to list at least fourpoints.<BR><BR><BR><B>C. Wages for two Pre-school teachers<BR>Need:</B> Two pre-school teachers to be appointed. Pay 5000/- (&#163;6.67)per month each.<BR><B>Action</B>: 49 children are ready to attend.<BR><B>Cost:</B> The pre-school needs to raise 15,000/-  (&#163;20.00) a monthfor the teachers' salaries and a daily meal for each child. Parents willcontribute 345/- (46p) a month for each child attending the pre-school.<BR><B>C1</B>. How much will all the children's parents contribute in totalper month?<BR><B>C2</B>. How much extra cash will there be for other expenses?  <BR><B>C3</B>. What other expenses do you think need to be considered?<BR><BR><BR><B>D. Houses for teachers<BR>Need</B>: The village needs more teachers and there is not enough accommodationfor them. <BR><B>Action</B>: To build one teacher's house per year for four years.<BR><B>Cost</B>: Each household to contribute 195/- (26p) towards the cost.Council will provide corrugated iron for the roof. 32 pieces are needed.One sheet costs 5-6,000/- a piece (&#163;6.67 - &#163;8.00). The taxes paidby the village should help the council provide this.<BR>The market value of a house is 368,000/- (&#163;490.67)<BR><B>D1</B>. What will be the total contribution made by the households towardsthe cost of a teacher's house?<BR><B>D2</B>. What is the lowest cost of roofing this house?<BR><BR><B>E. More clean water<BR>Need</B>: The village needs another well.<BR><B>Cost</B>: Either 75,000 (&#163;100.00) for a deep well or 35,000/- (&#163;46.67)for a shallow well.<BR>Problem: the village has no more money.<BR><B>E1</B>. Which well do you think the village should have?<BR><B>E2</B>. Suggest ways in which the villagers can get another well? <BR><BR><BR><HR>&copy;Copyright: UNICEF 1996 <HR><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif"WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom>Unicef Home Page</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
