<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>New approaches to addressing environmental problems in urban areas of the South<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 11, 1996</h3>

<I>This technical briefing paper aims to show how the costs of improving the urban environment in cities in the South need not be high.  In addition, the lower the capital costs  the greater the possibilities for cost recovery. The paper also considers various cities that have implemented innovative environmental improvement programmes and analyzes the cost of improving water and sanitation</I>. 
<p>
<H3>The capital costs of conventional urban projects</H3>

The capital costs of addressing the most serious environmental problems in cities in Africa, Asia and Latin America are often assumed to be very high.  Half or more of a citys population may lack  piped water to their homes while an even higher proportion lack adequate provision for sanitation and drainage, and a service that regularly collects their household wastes. In many cities, between a quarter and one half of all household wastes remain uncollected.  Meanwhile, most city authorities lack the power and resources to invest in city infrastructure and they often fail to enforce environmental regulations. Thus, to the problems of inadequate provision for water, sanitation, drainage and garbage collection are added uncontrolled dumping of liquid and solid wastes from commercial and industrial enterprises and little or no control of air pollution. 
<p>
If the costs of addressing these environmental problems through conventional public works approaches are added up, they appear to be beyond all possibility of financing. For instance, a conventional sewage system can cost US$1,000 or more per household - so the cost of installing sewers for (say) half the population of a city of 1 million people implies a total cost of US$100 million (Assuming 5 persons per household). In most cities, there would be little possibility of recovering this from user charges, especially if the sewage system reached the low income areas. In addition, the costs of building sewerage systems are often even higher in the poorer countries, where the need for improved sanitation is greatest, as a higher proportion of the population needs to be reached all specialized equipment and much of the technical expertise and building materials must be imported and as poor transport and communications systems hinder the speed and efficiency with which the sewer system can be constructed.

<H3>Alternative approaches</H3>

There is an alternative approach to the conventional, contractor built project based on Northern models and technologies.  This is to consider what can be done to improve conditions, building on systems that already exist in the city, making maximum use of local resources, skills and managerial capacities.  For instance, if much of a citys population relies on water vendors who provide expensive water of questionable quality, then improving the quality of water sold by vendors, ensuring competition between vendors (to keep prices down) and reducing vendors costs may be the most appropriate response (Cairncross, Sandy, Water supply and the urban poor in Jorge E. Hardoy and others (editors) The Poor Die Young, Earthscan, London, 1990). Or, if it is very expensive to extend a water pipe to a low income settlement on the periphery of a city,  using local groundwater resources or building a communal tank that is regularly filled by water tanker may be considered. However, in most cities, if all measures are taken to keep down capital costs and make maximum use of local resources, it is often possible to provide water piped to each home or house yard and still recover most or all costs.
<p>
There are many examples of initiatives in different cities that show remarkable transformations in the quality of the living environments at relatively low cost, including some where much of the cost was recovered, even in low income areas.  These include the many initiatives to improve water, sanitation, health care and the environment in illegal settlements in Guatemala City (supported by UNICEF) including water supply projects that achieved full cost recovery (Espinosa, Lair and Oscar A. López Rivera, UNICEFs urban basic services programme in illegal settlements in Guatemala City, Environment and Urbanization Vol.6, No.2, October 1994). They also include community installed and managed sewers such as in Orangi in Karachi which reduced costs so much (to between a fifth and a sixth of the cost that the municipal authority would have charged them for doing this work) that the low income households could afford to pay the costs (Orangi Pilot Project, NGO Profile: Orangi Pilot Project, Environment and Urbanization, Vol.7, No.2, October 1995).
<p>
Although very diverse, initiatives using this approach have certain common characteristics to keep down capital costs. Most made maximum use of local resources, including the knowledge, management capacity and labour of the low income groups themselves. In many, individuals and community organizations took on some or most of the work that would normally be undertaken by external contractors, which greatly reduced costs per person. (External contractors often make large profits from externally funded projects, partly because of inadequate management by funding agencies). Many used technologies that were cheaper than conventional contractor built or public works built projects - for instance, integrating drains into schemes to improve roads, installing shallow sewers or using on-site sanitation, such as Ventilated Improved Pit (VIP Latrines). The main sources of cost saving were a combination of two or more of the following: 
<ul>
<li>cheaper technologies; 
<li>replacing some of the work done by external contractors by self-help, mutual help or cheaper community organized labour; 
<li>some or most of the organization and management undertaken by community organizations and/or local NGOs; and 
<li>individuals, households and community organizations contributing free labour.  
</ul><p>
On the cost recovery side, as capital costs were kept down, so the possibility of low income households being able to repay the costs was increased.  This was further increased by allowing them to repay capital costs over an extended period - for instance, as households received a standard monthly charge for a new water, drainage and garbage collection system, part of it was used to repay the capital costs over a number of years and part was for the operation and maintenance of the new system. 
<p>
Community based solutions can also provide paid work for many local inhabitants - for instance community organized garbage collection, street cleaning and drainage maintenance.  Garbage collection systems based on door-to-door collection with large (usually imported) garbage trucks are often expensive and also difficult to provide to many illegal or informal settlements because they lack all-weather roads or the roads are too narrow for the trucks to get close to the houses. But there are many examples of community based systems which can greatly improve garbage collection, support local jobs and encourage the reclamation and recycling of waste materials with costs per household served being much lower than a conventional collection system.
<p>
Examples of projects with cost recovery that greatly improve environmental quality in low income areas are generally ones considered by the households who benefit from them as their projects and ones where the households recognize that external funding is limited.  No low income household will accept low-cost solutions to which they have to contribute a lot of the management and labour input if they believe they can negotiate a more expensive, contractor built solution from governments or international agencies. 

<H3>New approaches at municipal level</H3>

Similarly, no city government will accept low-cost solutions if they believe they too can negotiate a more expensive, contractor built solution from international agencies. But if city authorities also recognize that external funding is limited, they too can be encouraged to adopt less capital intensive solutions.  
<p>
One of the key principles in keeping down capital costs is the substitution of good local management for capital investment.  Perhaps the most dramatic example is in the management of water within the existing water collection and distribution system.   Many cities are facing growing costs for increasing water supplies as all easily tapped local sources have been used up (or polluted) and  tapping new sources involves large and expensive capital projects.  But, in the very city where increasing water supplies is so costly, there may be high levels of waste in water distribution and use. For instance, in many African and Asian cities, as much as 50 to 60 percent of the water entering a water distribution system is lost or unaccounted for.  Yet, in a well managed system such as that in Abidjan, the proportion of water that is unaccounted for is below 15 percent (World Bank, World Development Report 1994: Infrastructure for Development, Oxford University Press, Oxford, 1994).  Thus, in many cities, investment in better leak detection and mending and in overall maintenance can greatly increase the available supply of fresh water, usually much more cheaply than any project to increase the volume of water available for distribution.  In addition, promoting efficient water use by end-users can have the same effect as increasing available water supplies - for instance through higher prices and, for the largest water users, incentives to reduce use.  One of the main constraints on this approach is simply that most international funding agencies make funding available for new projects rather than for improved management and maintenance - although this is changing.
<p>
Another key principle is the understanding that all cities are built and maintained by an enormous range of investment of capital, expertise and time, by individuals, households, communities, voluntary organizations and NGOs, as well as by private enterprises, investors and government agencies.  Yet, until recently, in many countries in the South, city problems were assumed to be the responsibility of national or provincial/state agencies. One of the critical changes between Habitat I in 1976 and Habitat II in 1996 is the change in emphasis away from what national governments should do to support the efforts and initiatives of those living and working in cities.  This includes supporting the effort not only of city authorities but also of individual households, community organizations,  NGOs and private sector institutions. City authorities have a particularly critical role not only in investment and management but also in encouraging and supporting the initiatives and innovations of the other groups within their city.  In most cities in the South, municipal authorities have limited power and resources and their effectiveness depends on their working with the resources and skills of other groups within the city.
<p>
There are also over 1,000 cities around the world that run healthy city projects, most with help from the World Health Organization and most of which do not include major capital projects. These are not really projects but processes through which city authorities work with other groups to identify the main health problems and their causes and develop responses using existing resources. Most healthy city projects include a wide ranging process of consultation with citizens, NGOs and businesses.  Most develop a long-range city health plan in which priorities are set and the actions of different groups and sectors are integrated.  Many include the setting up of special task forces to address particularly pressing problems.  This is not to claim that these initiatives remove the necessity for major capital investments - but they do encourage city authorities to better use and work with local resources.

<H3>The cost of conventional water supplies</H3> (This section draws heavily on Cairncross 1990, op. cit)
<p>
It is often possible to install, supply and maintain a water standpipe shared between households in a low income settlement, with full cost recovery achieved over a ten- year period at a weekly charge per household of US$1. A weekly charge of US$2 would generally pay for the full cost of individual water connections to each households yard whilst a weekly charge of US$3-4  would cover the cost of a supply piped to the home.
<p>
The cost of building urban water supplies varies widely, depending largely on the availability of water resources.  For instance, in monsoon drenched South-East Asia, a water supply with house connections costs only US$60 per capita, whereas in the arid Middle East it is likely to cost five times as much.  A typical figure for a Third World nation would be US$l20 per person served.  Costs can be cut by providing water to standpipes that are shared by groups of households. Public standposts cost roughly half as much to build as house connections per person served. The difference is not due primarily to savings in the cost of distribution pipes as the distribution system normally accounts for only one-third of the total cost of a water supply.  Rather, the lower cost is due to the fact that those who use them consume much less water than households with private connections so that they put less demand on the water abstraction, treatment, pumping and storage capacity of the system.  However, low income households may be prepared to pay more for water if it is piped to their house or yard because of the tremendous saving in time and effort of not having to fetch it from a public standpipe (and often queue each time water is collected).

<H3>Sanitation</H3>

The costs of building sewers and house connections are usually very high.  However,  this is not always the case; for example in Orangi, the huge low income settlement in Karachi mentioned earlier where over 80,000 households are connected to sewer systems as a result of community based sewer design, construction and maintenance programmes, and each household covers the cost of doing this (Orangi Pilot Project 1995, op. cit).
<p>
Development assistance agencies and external experts tend to think that sewer systems are the best solution partly because these are the accepted solution in the North. When well managed and linked to a reliable piped water system, they are also convenient and need very little maintenance from the users as no septic tank or pit needs to be emptied. However, the costs of installing sewer systems in most cities in the South, and the treatment plants and the greater water demand their use implies appear very high, partly because there is usually such an enormous backlog of households needing connections.  But there are other forms of sanitation that can greatly improve conditions although much more cheaply than conventional sewer systems.  Table 1 lists some of these and provides an idea of the capital costs per household. 
<p>
It is also possible to reduce capital costs by having incremental improvements.  For instance, in many cities in low income countries where residential areas are not too dense, VIP latrines within each housing plot may be the most appropriate solution - especially if piped water supplies are not available to each house.  These latrines can later be converted into pour-flush latrines which in turn are later connected to a low-cost sewage system.  It is also possible to develop sewer systems incrementally rather than having to finance a city wide system - for instance installing sewers in one settlement with its own septic tank. 
<p>           
Dense urban settlements allow economies of scale in the installation of sewage systems and Table 1 shows that small-bore and shallow sewerage may be as cheap or cheaper per household as VIP latrines. However, the assumption should not be made that sewers are necessarily the best.  In many low-income settlements, VIP latrines or pour-flush latrines can provide healthy, convenient sanitation - and may be preferred in settlements (or cities) where water supplies are unreliable or costly.
<p>
<center><h4>Table 1: Capital Costs Per Household of Different Sanitation Systems (1990 prices)</h4><table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td>	Type of System</td><td>US$</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Twin pit pour-flush latrines</td><td>		75  -  150</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Ventilated improved pit latrine	</td><td>	68  -  175</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Shallow sewerage</td><td>			100  -  325</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Small-bore sewerage</td><td>		150  -  500</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Conventional septic tanks</td><td>		200  -  600</td></tr>
<tr><td>	Conventional sewerage	</td><td>	600  - 1200</td></tr>
</table></center><p>
<I>Source: Sinnatamby, Gehan, Low cost sanitation in Hardoy, Jorge E. and others (editors). The Poor Die Young, Earthscan, London, 1990.</I>
<p>
Care must be taken when comparing the costs of different sanitation systems to also consider the cost of operation and maintenance.  For instance, choosing pit latrines that need to be emptied regularly is hardly a solution for improved sanitation if there is no efficient service for emptying them - and in many cities there are constant problems from overflowing pit latrines.  Full cost recovery may be possible, even in cities in relatively low income countries, especially if households can repay the capital costs over a number of years.  For instance, the Urban Sanitation Improvement Team in Lesotho arranged for a commercial bank, the Lesotho Bank, to provide loans for VIP latrines and the loan programme has received high levels of loan repayment (Mara, Duncan, Low-Cost Urban Sanitation, John Wiley and Sons, Chichester, 1996). Providing VIP latrines in Kumasi (Ghana) would require some subsidy - but not if loans were available at a real interest rate of 10 percent a year over a 20-year period (Whittington, Dale and others, Household Demand for Improved Sanitation Services: a Case Study of Kumasi, Ghana, UNDP-World Bank Water and Sanitation Program, Washington DC, 1992).
<p>

<H3>Constraints</H3>

<I>The main constraint on developing lower-cost solutions based on making maximum use of local resources, skills and managerial capacities is the capacity of external funding agencies to know how to work in this way</I>.  It is much easier to allocate funding to a national government agency or a contractor who then takes on responsibility for implementation. All external funding agencies are under pressure to keep down staff costs and many have to support projects in countries where they have very few staff.  <I>This approach also depends on local institutions with the capacity to manage this - whether local branches of national or provincial agencies, local authorities, NGOs or community based organizations (or more often a combination of these)</I>.  But where an external funding agency is uncertain about local management capacities,  a modest initiative can be tried and then expanded, if successful.  For instance, a community based programme to improve housing, infrastructure and services in one low income settlement that succeeds will greatly encourage the inhabitants of other similar settlements to try a comparable approach with the external funding agency able to draw on its experience in the first settlement (and the advice of those who were involved). 

<H3>Conclusions</H3>

Initiatives to address the most serious environmental problems in cities in the South need not have high capital costs and the more capital costs are kept down, the better the possibilities for cost recovery.  There are many examples of successful, low-cost initiatives, some of which are mentioned above. But what these require is good management on the ground - whether by local authorities, local NGOs or community organizations themselves. This is probably the most serious limiting factor.  However, there is potential to support these kinds of solutions in all cities.  Cities which now have successful, large-scale programmes appeared to lack local capacity before these began.  These kinds of programmes usually need to start small and then develop in scale and in the range of initiatives they include as the capacity to manage them develops. 
<p>
<I>This paper was written by David Satterthwaite, Director of the Human Settlements Programme at IIED. He is co-author of Environmental Problems in Third World Cities (with Jorge Hardoy and Diana Mitlin - Earthscan, London, 1992 and of Squatter Citizen: Life in the Urban Third World (with Jorge Hardoy), Earthscan, 1989.  He has worked with UNICEF, WHO and the U.N. Centre for Human Settlements on urban environmental issues and was an advisor on urban issues to the Brundtland Commission (The World Commission on Environment and Development).</I>
<p><hr><small>©Copyright:IIED 1996</small><p><TABLE BORDER=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="index.html"><img src="pix/home.gif" width=100 height=43 alt="Home Page"></a></TD><TD><a href="../bookshop/index.html"><img src="pix/order.gif" width=100 height=43 alt="Order Information"></a></TD></TR></TABLE></TR></TABLE></body></html>
