<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 14 November 1996</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
Sometime in the next few weeks a document may emerge from the European
Commission's Development Directorate in Brussels setting out the broad
thinking of its Commissioner, Professor Pinheiro, about options for a post
2000 EU/ACP relationship.
<p>
The document may not be the full Commission green paper (discussion
document) so widely expected and advertised since late l995, but instead a
much shortened and slimmed down version of the original eighty page paper.
What its status will be is still unclear as at least two other directorates
of the European Commission have expressed reservations about how it relates
to Europe's commitment to global convergence in its foreign and development
policy and its impact on the EU's trade and agriculture policies in the
context of the GATT.
<p>
These divisions within the European Commission before the debate between
the ACP and EU has even begun, do not bode well for the outcome. They point
to the likely fault lines that will develop in Europe as the different
directorates of the Commission and then Europe's member states try to
determine a common EU negotiating position with the ACP for when formal
discussions begin in l998.
<p>
At the heart of this argument is the question of whether Europe should
continue to pursue a partnership with the 70 ACP states by conferring on
them a special relationship or whether, post 2000, this widely different
grouping of nations should be drawn into a common EU approach which will
integrate over time all foreign, trade and development policy. It is a
debate that has far reaching implications for the creation and maintenance
of a common ACP negotiating position and the future of the ACP as a group.
<p>
Speaking about this in Brussels in the week past with senior officials from
a number of directorates I was struck by a growing sense of unease that
Prof. Pinheiro's  paper may raise questions not just about future relations
with the ACP, but about Europe's future approach to the world. Among the
disturbing  questions they posed were: Has the Development Directorate a
future? Is its post 2000 development role better located in an enlarged
International Relations Directorate in which sub groups with
responsibility, for instance, for the Caribbean, South Africa and Tropical
Africa, come to deal with the world by sub-regions? Is the Pacific's future
not with Europe at all but with the nations of the Pacific rim? Should the
delivery of aid programmes be undertaken by an independent agency dealing
with the world as a whole and leaving just policy issues to the Commission?
And will the Dutch Government, which will hold the EU Presidency in the
first half of l997, attempt to marginalise Professor Pinheiro's thinking by
insisting that policy towards the ACP must be convergent with all other EU
development and trade policy? 
<P>
Other more Caribbean specific questions raised included: Why does the green
paper not propose policies that embrace the future of remote parts of
Europe such as Martinique or Guadeloupe or the British or Dutch dependent
territories? How can solutions be proposed for the ACP when in the case of
the Caribbean for example, its future may be bound up with its neighbours
in Latin and Central America in the context of the Free Trade Area of the
Americas? And will Cuba be left isolated by the type of options proposed by
the reflection group?
<P>
For the Caribbean these questions are likely to haunt those who have to
determine first a Caricom and then a Cariforum position and its subsequent
integration into a negotiating mandate that is acceptable to African and
Pacific states while meeting other criteria for entry into the FTAA and
advanced relationships with Mercosur and Latin partners. They will also
worry those in the private sector who hope to establish the longest phase
out possible for preferential trade arrangements.
<P>
In Europe, Germany, France, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom are all
at advanced stages of thinking about the shape of any future arrangement.
While few public statements have been forthcoming it is clear that Germany
and the Netherlands are likely to promote the thinking on convergence
contained in the Maastricht Treaty while Britain and France may argue for
special and differential treatment for at least a fixed period after the
year 2000.
<p>
Caribbean Heads of Government have made clear that they regard the
maintenance of solidarity with the African and Pacific states as a
prerequisite for maintaining a strong negotiating stance with the EU. This
position, which might be accommodated in a framework arrangement that
embraces a policy of continuing partnership that takes account of regional
and sub-regional variations, will not be easy to achieve. The devil will be
in the detail.
<p>
However, problems of a completely different order arise if powerful EU
member states prompted by changing public opinion and diminishing resources
are not prepared even to accept the notion that the ACP should have a
special relationship with Europe. 
<p>
Unfortunately the background atmospherics are very mixed. Images of the
horror and suffering in Zaire and Rwanda set alongside pictures of
prosperous and well fed ministers seated in Rome at the World Food Summit
negatively affect popular sentiment on Africa. On the other hand, this is a
far cry from the widely welcomed remarks of Jamaica's Prime Minister, P J
Patterson. Visiting London in the week past, he made clear his vision of a
strong relationship with Europe in which Jamaica, through sound economic
policies and good government would with Europe's continuing assistance be
able to manage its way into a more liberal global economy.
<p>
Faced with all these contradictions, the Caribbean will have to give
careful thought as to how it encourages the ACP to take forward a common
negotiating position. 
<p>
<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on November 18, 1996</i><p>
