</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 29 January 1997</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
For the past two weeks the rum industry of the Caribbean has been fighting
what may be for some producers a life or death battle. It is doing so in
Brussels, Washington and Geneva against a little-known trade liberalisation
measure that threatens to devastate the industry.
<p>
How this has happened should be an object lesson for the region.
<p>
Early last December in Singapore, the World Trade Organisation met to
discuss the consolidation and creation of new measures aimed at
liberalising international trade and creating global competition in many
sectors. High on the EU/US agenda was an agreement on information
technology. Achieving this was not easy. So the US offered Europe, in a
side agreement outside of the meeting, something Europe had been pushing
for: a commitment to duty elimination on white spirits (principally gin and
vodka but also rum and other spirits) by the year 2000.
<p>
This agreement which is known as "zero for zero" would in effect confer
most favoured nation status on all white spirits suppliers and create in
just three years a global free market in white spirits matching that
already agreed for brown spirits (whiskey, bourbon etc.).
<p>
Knowledge of this new development only became apparent to the rum industry
in the region in a roundabout way and not through any formal government
exchanges with either the US or the EU. The effect was galvanising. The
Caribbean rum industry in the English speaking Caribbean, the French
Departments and even Puerto Rico and the United States Virgin Islands, all
immediately recognised that if rum were included, the US and EU markets
could be lost after the year 2000, to low cost producers in Latin America
and other parts of the world.
<p>
In both Washington and Brussels it was made clear by the industry and its
representatives that the inclusion of rum would devastate the industry
throughout the whole region. This was because large producers of sugar
cane, such as Brazil or Mexico, that utilise cheap labour, cheap molasses,
and in some cases cheap energy, are able to produce bulk rum at costs lower
than in the Caribbean and would be the ultimate beneficiaries of zero for
zero.
<p>
Caribbean producers pointed out that the vast majority of all Caribbean rum
is shipped to EU countries, the United States and Canada. In all three
areas Caribbean rum enjoys duty free entry, although in the case of the EU
up to 1996 the amount of rum entering duty free was restricted by quota and
remains so for "rum traditional" up to the year 2000. In addition, the
United States had repeatedly made the point that the US Caribbean Basin
Initiative was valid until the year 2005, thus ensuring Caribbean rum
preferences. Canada has indicated that access under Caribcan was of an
indefinite nature.
<p>
The threat to Caribbean rum was put succinctly by the West Indies Rum and
Spirits Producers Association's (WIRSPA) Chairman, Evon Brown.
<p>
<i>"It had been anticipated by rum producers in the ACP that the abolition of
restrictive quota practices, which the EU had imposed on the Caribbean and
other rum producers for almost 20 years, would be followed by a willingness
to discuss, in the context of a post Lom&#233; arrangement, a phasing out period
for the preferences enjoyed by ACP rum producers after the year 2000.
<p>
However, if, as a result of the recent understanding reached at the WTO,
these preferential arrangements now disappear precipitately Caribbean rum
industries would not have sufficient time to achieve the necessary
transition from producers of bulk rum to fully competitive producers of
branded added value product.
<p>
It is grossly unfair that having had our products restricted into Europe
and, prior to the US Caribbean Basin Initiative, into the USA, that the
time needed to develop these potentially larger markets will be denied to
us."</i>
<p>
The industry is now urging both the US and the EU to remove rum from zero
for zero and there are the first signs that Washington might be amenable to
such an approach from the EU.
<p>
Resolution of this issue is now in the hands of the trade negotiators in
Geneva. In the course of the next few days it will become apparent whether
technical discussions prior to full scale negotiations during March between
the EU and the US - will pave the way for rum being dealt with separately.
<p>
Caricom and some governments in the region have been quick off the mark in
responding but the manner in which the EU/US decision was made and the
absence of any thought on the part of the US, the EC or EU member states
about the consequences for the Caribbean region should give all in the
region pause for thought. All the more so as it comes hard on the heels of
the introduction of severe restrictions on the export of Caribbean rice to
the EU, and most probably a highly damaging WTO ruling on the US complaint
on the EU's banana regime.
<p>
The Caribbean is slowly gearing up to develop a post Lomi and Free Trade
Area of the Americas position after 2000 but the growing danger is that
moves to international trade liberalisation may sweep aside any hope of a
stable and phased transition for the region in the new millennium. 
<p>
The reality is that much of the Caribbean does not yet have the weight or
profile in Washington or Brussels. Strong lobbies such as that of Israel or
even Puerto Rico are not only able to make waves but have ensured that few,
if any, decisions that affect their interests are taken without
consultation.
<p>
Rum, rice and banana problems and conceivably after 2000, even those
arising from falling sugar prices, all point to the need for serious
consideration being given to: mechanisms for the speedy development of fast
and unified responses to external threats which are most likely to be
related to trade; the development of strong lobbies in North America and
Europe among Caribbean nationals or their descendants; and the investment
in the EU in particular, in diplomatic representation in key European
capitals matched by high levels of technical support.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on February 5, 1997</i><p>
