<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Bosnian peace deal may mean end of war</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<h2>Bosnian peace deal signed - but will war end?</h2><p>

<b>22 November 1995</b><p>

After a week of brinkmanship and posturing by all sides, a peace deal for the Balkans was initialled yesterday in Dayton, Ohio, by the presidents of Bosnia, Croatia and Serbia.<p>

"This ensures the continuation of a single Bosnian state," said Warren Christopher, the US Secretary of State.  "It is a victory for us all."<p>

But despite this optimism, it is also universally acknowledged that this peace will be a fragile one.  Even Mr Christopher warned: "This victory will not be secure unless we all get to work to ensure that the promise of this moment is realised."<p>

The difficulties were immediately highlighted by the reaction of the Bosnian Serbs to the agreement.  They were represented by Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic at the talks, but claimed to have been consulted by him only ten minutes before the treaty was signed.<p>

"What's been done is an especially big mistake," claimed Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of the self-styled Bosnian Serb parliament.  "Our delegation did not accept this plan, nor did it sign, nor will it sign these maps or the plan itself."<p>

The plan confirms what is essentially a draw between the warring parties.  While Bosnia will in theory remain a single state, it consists of two ethnically-constituted entities - a Muslim-Croat Federation and a Serb republic.<p>

There is to be a single government, however.  Elections will be held to a bicameral parliament and a president will also be chosen in free elections.  This central authority will control foreign policy, foreign trade and monetary policy.  But the frontier between the two sub-states will not be forgotten: each will retain its own armed forces.<p>

There were some important victories for the Bosnian government.  Their demand that war criminals be barred from political office was conceded - this will leave Ratko Mladic and Radovan Karadic without a power base once the fighting stops.  Whether they will ever face justice at the UN War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague is another matter.<p>

Additionally, Sarajevo will once again become a unified city.  The enclave of Gorazde will be linked to Bosnian government territory.  Free travel and the right of refugees to return to their homes is also in theory guaranteed.  However, many have no homes to go to, and would be unwilling to return to areas still under the control of the people who originally expelled them.<p>

But what chance is there of a lasting peace? At the negotiations, the Serb and Croat sides appeared to be making the ethnic divide as clear as possible.  The Bosnian Serbs are thought to be intending to secede soon to join Serbia proper.  If the arms embargo is lifted, there will almost certainly be a further weapons build-up by each side.<p>

The peace deal is to be implemented by 60,000 troops from the international community.  Most will come from NATO countries (including the US), but about 2,000 will also be Russian.  Their task will be to keep the military forces apart, whilst allowing for economic and social reintegration in Bosnia.<p>

The reaction in Sarajevo was muted.  Some soldiers in the trenches fired into the air, and in city cafes a few people celebrated.  But people mainly remembered past failed peace settlements, as well as the bleakness of a war which has killed 250,000 people and turned millions more into stateless refugees.<p>

<ul><li>For further information see <b><a href="bosnia_updates.html">previous updates on Bosnia</a><br>
<li><a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp_top.html">OneWorld Online's Special Feature on Bosnia</a>
<li><a href="../realaudio/palmer_bosnia/index.html">RealAudio interview with Oxfam's John Palmer</a> </b>about his work with refugees in Tuzla 

</ul>


