<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - The War in Bosnia</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<h1>The war in Bosnia-Herzegovina</h1><p>

<b>22 <font size=+1>N</font>OVEMBER  1995</b><p>
<center><h2>Bosnian peace deal signed - but will war end?</h2></center>
<p>



After a week of brinkmanship and posturing by all sides, a peace deal for the Balkans was initialled yesterday in Dayton, Ohio, by the presidents of Bosnia, Croatia and Serbia.<p>

"This ensures the continuation of a single Bosnian state," said Warren Christopher, the US Secretary of State.  "It is a victory for us all."<p>

But despite this optimism, it is also universally acknowledged that this peace will be a fragile one.  Even Mr Christopher warned: "This victory will not be secure unless we all get to work to ensure that the promise of this moment is realised."<p>

The difficulties were immediately highlighted by the reaction of the Bosnian Serbs to the agreement.  They were represented by Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic at the talks, but claimed to have been consulted by him only ten minutes before the treaty was signed.<p>

"What's been done is an especially big mistake," claimed Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of the self-styled Bosnian Serb parliament.  "Our delegation did not accept this plan, nor did it sign, nor will it sign these maps or the plan itself."<p>

The plan confirms what is essentially a draw between the warring parties.  While Bosnia will in theory remain a single state, it consists of two ethnically-constituted entities - a Muslim-Croat Federation and a Serb republic.<p>

There is to be a single government, however.  Elections will be held to a bicameral parliament and a president will also be chosen in free elections.  This central authority will control foreign policy, foreign trade and monetary policy.  But the frontier between the two sub-states will not be forgotten: each will retain its own armed forces.<p>

There were some important victories for the Bosnian government.  Their demand that war criminals be barred from political office was conceded - this will leave Ratko Mladic and Radovan Karadic without a power base once the fighting stops.  Whether they will ever face justice at the UN War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague is another matter.<p>

Additionally, Sarajevo will once again become a unified city.  The enclave of Gorazde will be linked to Bosnian government territory.  Free travel and the right of refugees to return to their homes is also in theory guaranteed.  However, many have no homes to go to, and would be unwilling to return to areas still under the control of the people who originally expelled them.<p>

But what chance is there of a lasting peace? At the negotiations, the Serb and Croat sides appeared to be making the ethnic divide as clear as possible.  The Bosnian Serbs are thought to be intending to secede soon to join Serbia proper.  If the arms embargo is lifted, there will almost certainly be a further weapons build-up by each side.<p>

The peace deal is to be implemented by 60,000 troops from the international community.  Most will come from NATO countries (including the US), but about 2,000 will also be Russian.  Their task will be to keep the military forces apart, whilst allowing for economic and social reintegration in Bosnia.<p>

The reaction in Sarajevo was muted.  Some soldiers in the trenches fired into the air, and in city cafes a few people celebrated.  But people mainly remembered past failed peace settlements, as well as the bleakness of a war which has killed 250,000 people and turned millions more into stateless refugees.<p>

<ul><li>For further information see <b>
<li><a href="../realaudio/palmer_bosnia/index.html">RealAudio interview with Oxfam's John Palmer</a> </b>about his work with refugees in Tuzla 

</ul>






<h2>Peace deal reached over Eastern Slavonia</h2>

Update from 14 November<p>

Eastern Slavonia, the last piece of Croatian territory still occupied by Serbs, is to re-integrate with Croatia proper.<p>

The deal, the first major stumbling block to be resolved at the peace talks in Dayton, Ohio, is a negotiated settlement between the Serbian and Croatian presidents.<p>

Eastern Slavonia was captured by local Serbs in 1991, after intense fighting which saw the near total destruction of the region's biggest city, Vukovar.  The region contains both fertile farmland and oilfields.<p>

The settlement was reached after a week of sabre-rattling by the two sides.  The Serbs initially rejected the Croatian proposal, and the Croats massed troops near the region.<p>

Eastern Slavonia is to be administered by an international force (which may well include US troops) for two years, after which it will revert to its previous status as a Croatian region.<p>

The major remaining question is the situation of the 200,000 Serbs who live in the region.  It is feared that many may flee to Serbia proper, despite human rights guarantees enshrined in the agreement.
<p>
After Croat toops recaptured the Krajina region in July and August of this year, 150,000 Serbs fled to Serb-held Bosnia and Serbia proper.  According to the UN, hundreds of elderly civilians were killed by vengeful Croatian troops.<p>

The  deal now allows the Dayton peace talks to focus purely on the issue of Bosnia's future status.  <p>

In a separate development, six leading Bosnian Croat officials were charged with crimes against humanity by the UN War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague.<p>

The six indicted were charged with the ethnic cleansing of Bosnian Muslims from central Bosnia during the Muslim-Croat conflict of 1992-93.  The Croats and the Muslims have since formed a federation in Bosnia. <p>

 <br><b><li>See OneWorld Online's <a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp_top.html">Special Report on Bosnia</a><br><li><a href="../amnesty/ai_yugoslavia.html">Amnesty International on the "disappeared" and the "missing"</a> </b><br clear=left>


<h2>War crimes a stumbling block at Balkan peace talks</h2>

<b>Update from 8 November</b><p>


The presidents of Bosnia and Serbia, and Croatia's foreign minister are meeting at a US Air Force base in Dayton, Ohio to discuss a peace plan for the Balkans.<p>

The talks have stalled this week on the issue of Serb war crimes.  The Bosnian government is pushing for the two Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadic and Ratko Mladic to go on trial for genocide.  Both have been indicted by the International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague.<p>

The Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic may also be implicated in war crimes through the participation of Yugoslav army generals in the ethnic killings at Srebrenica.  <p>

Judge Richard Goldstone, chief prosecutor of the War Crimes Tribunal, has complained to Washington about delays in  releasing intelligence information about the Srebrenica massacres, when 5000 Muslim men disappeared.  The US denies that it is withholding evidence of crimes to prevent Milosevic's indictment.<p>
 
A further sticking point between Serbia and Croatia is Eastern Slavonia - the only part of Croatia still occupied by Serbs.  US officials now believe that a breakthrough on the issue is in sight, however.<p>

In Europe US soldiers are training for the proposed NATO peacekeeping mission - which will eventually comprise of 60,000 well-armed troops.  <p>
Agreement may also soon be reached on the thorny issue of Russian participation in the force - Russia has identified in the past with 'fellow Serbs' it claims have been suffering under NATO oppression.<p>


<h2>Update from 13 October</h2>

As the latest of Bosnia's 32 ceasefires was declared yesterday, there were unconfirmed reports that fighting had continued in the northwest of the country.<p>

Bosnian government and Croat forces, fresh from their recent successes against the Serbs were reportedly on the move again.  Serb guns fired several hundred shells in 'self-defence'.<p>

Meanwhile NATO is preparing for the biggest deployment of military might seen in non-Communist Europe since the end of World War II.  Up to 60,000 heavily-armed peacekeepers will be sent in before the winter.<p>

The force will guarantee - perhaps by force of arms - the expected US-mediated peace treaty.  Negotiations for the treaty will resume in Washington by November, and a signing ceremony is expected to take place in Paris.<p>

The present ceasefire is intended to last 60 days, or until an agreement is reached - whichever is the later.<p>

<h2>Update from 12 October</h2>

<b>At one minute past midnight last night, the warring parties in Bosnia stopped fighting.</b><p>

The war is now three and a half years old, and fighting has continued right up to the ceasefire deadline.  Croatian and Bosnian government forces made last-minute gains in the northwest, approaching the towns of Prijedor and Banja Luka.<p>

But the cessation of official military violence has been overshadowed by the continuing violence against civilians.  Reports are continuing of Serb expulsions of the remaining Muslims in the Banja Luka area.   <p>

 According to frightened refugees from the region, Zeljko 'Arkan' Raznatovic - a former bank robber and nationalist thug - has arrived with an army of around 2000.<p>

According to British newspaper 'The Guardian', these extreme nationalist Serbs - who wore different uniforms from the local Serb rebels - loaded all Muslim and Croat men between the ages of 17 to 65 on to buses.  They have not been seen since.  <p>

The UN High Commission for Refugees is concerned about reports that women and children were made to cross a fast-flowing river near the front line, in which several people drowned.<p>

Arkan's sadistic brutality is thought by many to be the ultimate responsibility of the Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic.  Arkan's 'Tigers' were recruited from Serbia, and he is thought to be funded by the Yugoslav army.  <p>

Milosevic denies that he has any control over Arkan's actions.  But if he is proven to be involved in this latest outbreak of 'ethnic cleansing', he faces indictment as a war criminal by the UN International War Crimes Commission in the Hague.

<h2>Update from October 10</h2>

<b>Bosnia's much-heralded ceasefire - due to come into force at midnight last night - was delayed after the Bosnian government's conditions were not met.</b><p>

The ceasefire agreement included the restoration of gas and electricity supplies to Sarajevo.  The gas comes from Russia by pipeline.<p>

Meanwhile, further last-minute Serb atrocities were reported against the few Muslims still left in Serb-held Bosnia.  Serb paramilitaries led by the notorious Belgrade gangster 'Arkan' Raznjatovic have been rounding up women, children and the elderly and expelling them from Serb regions.  <p>

'Arkan' is reported to be controlled by the Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic and the Yugoslav army.  There are now few if any Muslims and Croats at liberty within northern Serb regions.<p>

The men have reportedly suffered a worse fate.  Relief workers in the region claim that hundreds have disappeared into Serb detention camps in northern Bosnia - a region made infamous with the discovery of 'concentration camps' in 1992.<p>

According to the British newspaper The Guardian, 3,500 women, children and elderly Muslims have arrived from the Serb areas of Bosanski Novi, Prijedor and Sanski Most.  Many are "deeply traumatised", and unable to "put a coherent sentence together".<p>

As news of fresh atrocities arrived, the UN International War Crimes Commission for former Yugoslavia began hearing evidence from its first witnesses in the Hague.  On trial is Dragan Nikolic, commander of a Serb detention camp in 1992, who is charged with the murder and torture of detainees.<p>

The 1992 Serb campaign in the Prijedor and Sanski Most regions has been officially described by the UN as genocidal.  When Srebrenica fell to the Serbs in July, up to 8000 men disappeared and are believed killed.  The United States has demonstrated evidence of mass graves in the area.<p>

While Muslim and Croat men from northern regions are still missing, it is feared that they may also have been killed.


<h2>Update from October 5</h2>

 <b>The long-promised Balkan breakthrough was inching closer this week - but only barely.<p></b>
 
According to the US special envoy to the region, Richard Holbrooke, the Bosnian government has made a "serious proposal" for a ceasefire.<p>

This may involve a watering down of Bosnia's previous demands: that land routes to Sarajevo and Gorazde be opened, and that Banja Luka - the headquarters of the Serb army and Bosnia's second largest city - be demilitarised.<p>

These demands were widely criticised as unrealistically high, especially as the government's advance against the Serbs in the western Bosnia ground to a halt last week when the Croats withdrew.  There have since been reports of skirmishes between Bosnian government and Croat troops.<p>

Meanwhile NATO jets have again been in action against the Serbs.  Aircraft bombed three missile batteries after radar systems 'locked on' to them - an action that NATO regards as hostile, as it indicates that a missile may be about to target the plane.<p>

Earlier this week the Bosnian Serbs asked the UN for permission to move some artillery pieces back inside the Sarajevo exclusion zone, after renewed fighting broke out with government troops.  It was refused, but artillery exchanges did take place.<p>

However, there were signs of peace surrounding the issue of Eastern Slavonia - the only region of Croatia which is still in Serb hands.  Serb and Croatian representatives reportedly agreed "guiding principles" for a settlement at a meeting in the border town of Erdut.<p>

These principles would include the administration of the region by a transitional authority, complete demilitarisation and an ethnically-mixed police force. <p>

Crucially, it would appear that the Serbs have agreed that Eastern Slavonia will remain part of Croatia.

<h2>Update from September 20</h2>

<b>The United Nations has officially 'discontinued' the air attacks on Bosnian Serb targets.  It declared satisfaction that the Serbs had removed their heavy weapons over 20 miles from Sarajevo.<p></b>

The Serbs have also suffered severe reversals in the north and west of Bosnia.  The army of the Croat-Muslim federation has taken advantage of the damage inflicted on the Serbs by NATO war planes to mount a big offensive.<p>

It is now overrunning territory that has been in Serb hands from 1992.  The attack has cut the areas of Bosnia held by Serbs from 70%, a few weeks ago, to about half now.<p>

Bosnian government troops are now near to the sites of the infamous Serb concentration camps, which shocked the world in 1992.  Many of these soldiers are survivors from the camps, who remember watching friends and relatives being murdered.  Some vow to search for mass graves in their old villages - looking for those who, they believe, were killed when their Serb neighbours first rebelled. <p>

However, the United Nations has voiced fears about the apparent Serb collapse.  Britain's Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind has suggested that the president of Serbia proper, Slobodan Milosevic, will feel forced to intervene in Bosnia to prop up the Bosnian Serbs.  <p>

If this were to happen the war could be further internationalised, he warned.

<h2>Update from 30 August</h2>

<b>The war in Bosnia entered a dramatic new phase on the morning of Wednesday 30th August.</b><p>

To the evident jubilation of people throughout Bosnia, NATO war planes carried out a massive bombardment of Serb military targets.<p>

Aircraft attacked in four waves, hitting Bosnian Serb command centres, air defence radar and ammunition dumps.  UN artillery on Mount Igman near Sarajevo also pounded Serb positions.<p>

The attack was a response from the UN to a Serb mortar attack on Sarajevo on Monday.  At least 37 people were killed and 88 wounded when a heavy mortar slammed into a crowded market in Sarajevo.

UN officials claimed that the raids would continue until the Serb threat to Sarajevo was lifted.  It was also claimed that while care was taken to avoid civilian casualties, extensive damage was caused to Serb military positions.<p>

The Bosnian government and people appeared united in their praise of the NATO action.  The Bosnian prime minister said: "The air raids restore the credibility of the international community."  Sarajevo civilians enjoyed what amounted to a break in the Serb stranglehold over their city, knowing that snipers would not be targeting them.<p>

The Bosnian Serb leadership remained defiant, however, pledging to fight back.  They backed up this claim by shooting down a French Mirage jet near Pale.
<p>

<p>


<a href="index.html">Back to OneWorld News Service</a><b><br clear=left><a href="../owo_options.html"> Search Index</a><br>
<a href="../index.html"> OneWorld Online Home Page</a><p>
</body>
</html>

