<h1>News Updates</h1>
<ul>
<br><font size=-1>Left: The scars of battle in Tuzla.  The town is now home for thousands of refugees from the ex-'safe area' of Srebrenica. <br><br><br><br><br>Photo ©: Mark Allison/Oxfam
</font>
<br clear=left><br>

<li><b><a href="../oda/press/mar20_2.html">Britain will show peace pays in Bosnia, says Lady Chalker:</a></b><br>
The British Government's overseas aid arm, the ODA, has announced a package of aid for Bosnia worth up to £17 million.<p>

<li><b><a href="../afpic/update/130196.html">Aid convoy successfully reaches Bosnia:</a></b><br>
<b>Action for Peoples in Conflict</b> have sent their first convoy to the devastated town of Bosanska Krupa, near Bihac in Bosnia.<p> 

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_bosnia_jan23.html">Step up search for Bosnian war criminals, urges Amnesty:</a></b><br>
Concerns have been raised by </b>Amnesty International</b> that the multinational peace Implementation Force in Bosnia is failing to search for and arrest indicted war criminals.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk3_bosnia.html">Bosnian children learn to live with scars of war</a></b><br>
The Dayton agreement has brought peace to Bosnia, but many children are still trapped in memories of the traumas they suffered.  <b>Gemini News Service</b> reports on efforts to help them.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_bosnia_jan16.html">Don't rush return of Bosnian refugees, warns Amnesty:</a></b><br>
Following the recent detention of 16 people by Bosnian Serb forces near Sarajevo, <b>Amnesty International</b> is warning the international peace force 'I-FOR' that returning refugees may still be in danger.<p>

<li><b><a href="../news/wk50_bosnia.html">The Dayton Accord for Bosnia: Peace or just plaster?</a></b><br>
Will peace now come to former Yugoslavia, after nearly four years of bloodshed - or is the peace treaty negotiated in Dayton and signed in Paris yesterday merely plastering over unmended cracks? 
<p>

<li><b><a href="../news/bosnia.html">Bosnian peace deal agreed at Dayton - is the war over?</a></b><br>

The peace treaty for the Balkans has at last been concluded.  But the Bosnian Serbs have already rejected it.  Will it end the war?<p>

