<html><head><title>NI Issue 272 - Simp;y - a guide to therapy</title></head><body bgcolor="#8FBC8F"><h3><img hspace=10 vspace=10 width=100 height=88 border=1 src="../ni_pix/nilogo.gif">New Internationalist Issue 272</h3><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../NIinfo.html">  New Internationalist</a></i><hr><center><img hspace=10 vspace=10 hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_title.gif"></center><p><h3>Healing should be a two-way process between practitioner and client - any therapy which encourages your involvement will bring more satisfying results.</h3><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_information.gif"><br clear=leftWhen choosing a practitioner :<p><b>DO </b><li> check qualifications, training and time spent in practice <li> check whether the practitioner is registered with a recognized organization which has a complaints and disciplinary procedure <li>try to ascertain that the therapy is safe, plausible and appropriate<li>check their attitude to other forms of medicine<li>ask for an estimate of length of treatment and costs.<p><b>DON'T </b>go to anyone<li>who makes miraculous claims <li>who suggests you give up consulting a conventional doctor <li>who doesn't involve you in drawing up your treatment programme<li>with whom you are uncomfortable.<p><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_acupuncture.gif"><br clear=left>Developed over 4,000 years, holistic Chinese medical theory grew along with Taoism - which sees individuals as a microcosm of the universe. Apart from acupuncture, treatments include herbal medicines (using over 4,000 different herbs), food therapy, exercise (such as T'ai Chi Ch'uan) and massage.<p>Diagnosis Depletion of chi (life force or energy) by excess and intemperance is responsible for imbalance and disease. Chi circulates in the body through invisible channels beneath the skin, along which are the 2,000 or so known 'acupoints' stimulated by acupuncture to release blockages and replenish energy. Assessment is very detailed, based on observation, listening, smelling, asking questions and reading the pulse at six different points.<p><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_allopathic.gif"><br clear=left><img hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right src="health_thumb.gif">The main brand of medicine in the West, gradually replacing other kinds of medicine in countries of the South. Often referred to as 'conventional medicine', even though it became scientific only in the twentieth century. The majority of medical drugs and treatments in use today have been developed over the past 30 years.<p>Diagnosis Based entirely on symptoms, zeroing-in on trouble spots. Has an arsenal of machinery. Doctors are mainly interested in clients' medical histories rather than their wider lives. Usually has the shortest consultations and the highest cost of all primary-care options.<p><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_ayurveda.gif"><br clear=left>Ayurveda, the Sanskrit 'Science of Life', is an ancient Indian school of medicine which includes psychological, cultural, religious and philosophical concerns. Like Chinese medicine it seeks to balance the body's energies.<p>Diagnosis Ayurveda focuses on removing the causes of disease rather than treating symptoms. It restores balance through herbal remedies, cleansing routines, yoga, meditation and diet. Nothing of importance to the client's well-being is omitted - from relationships to the astrological chart, age, mood, time of day and climate.<p><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_homeopathy.gif"><br clear=left>Founded in the eighteenth century by Samuel Hahnemann, a German physician disenchanted with the crude medical practices of his time. Stimulates the body to use its own healing resources to fight illness. Medicines are incredibly diluted forms of naturally occurring substances. If taken in larger quantities they would cause similar symptoms to the ones they are deployed against. <p>Diagnosis Homeopaths see symptoms as indications of a disease pattern, not the disease itself. Consultations involve the practitioner selecting the right remedy tailored to match the client's constitution, after taking a detailed personal history.<p><img hspace=10 vspace=10 src="festival_naturopathic.gif"><br clear=left>Naturopaths combine insights from other holistic systems such as Ayurveda and Chinese medicine with conventional medical training. Remedies, if used at all, are herbal and the main emphasis is on regulation of diet.<p>Diagnosis Naturopaths act more as teachers than doctors helping clients to learn how their bodies can heal themselves. Consultations combine building a holistic profile with a routine medical examination. Irises may be examined and blood, hair and sweat tested for toxins. Treatment involves changing aspects of lifestyle that have caused imbalance.<p><hr width=71%><p><b>Don't be a passive pill-popper. Combine your own knowledge about yourself with that of the therapist you choose.</b><p>Information sources: The Encyclopaedia of Alternative Health Care by Kristin Olsen, (Piatkus, London 1992); Health Education Authority Guide to Complementary Medicine and Therapies by Anne Woodham, (HEA, London 1994).<p><hr>©Copyright: New Internationalist 1995<hr><a href="../index.html"><img hspace=10 vspace=10 hspace=2 width=35 height=30 src="../ni_pix/nilogo3.gif"> NI Home Page</a> <a href="contents.html"><img hspace=10 vspace=10 hpspace=2 width=30 height=50 src="cover272_thumb.gif"> Issue 272 Contents</a><hr></body></html>
