<HEAD>

<TITLE>Food Policy Management Programme (FPM) in the Central Sub-Region
of West Africa</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>Food Policy Management Programme (FPM) in the Central Sub-Region
of West Africa </H3>

<P>
by <I>Ad Oomen</I>
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
page 6</I> </CENTER><HR>

<P>
Food security is no longer seen as an exclusive concern of national
governments. It has to be conceived in a regional context. The
FPM has been established by the five governments in the central
sub-region of West Africa (Burkina Faso, C&ocirc;te d`Ivoire,
Ghana, Mali and Togo) and ECDPM to ensure that regional issues
are embodied in their national policies and programmes.
<P>
However what has to be emphasised is that the FPM is not a process
by which regional policies are adopted and implemented at the
national level. There are, in fact, no regional policies as such.
On the contrary, policy-making remains at the national level.
But the expectation is that under the FPM, national policies will
be more effectively informed and influenced by the experiences
and problems of other countries in the sub-region. Thus the ultimate
aim of the FPM is to develop a regional food security policy that
is conceived as the aggregation of the national policies and programmes
rather than one which emerges from a regional policy-making institution.
<P>
The focus of the FPM is less on policy content than on the process
of policy formulation and implementation in the sub-regional context.
This process involves the establishment in each country of a team
of decision-makers (from Ministries of Agriculture, of Finance,
and of either Trade or Livestock) who ensure both interdepartmental
coordination at the national level and the development of effective
relationships with researchers, the private sector and other relevant
actors in the country. 
<P>
These national teams engage in a regular and disciplined process
of communication and consultation at the regional and sub-regional
levels. This process includes the preparation of working papers,
national and regional workshops, and plenary meetings. Through
this process, national policy makers are able to exchange specific
information derived from their working experiences.
<P>
At the heart of the FPM, therefore, is capacity building for food
policy management at the national level including the establishment
of effective relationships with all interested actors. These relationships
constitute, in effect, a networking of these actors. But it is
a network which, unlike many other networks, is action-oriented
and not simply information-oriented. It is from these more robust
foundations within each country that a more effective regional
approach to food security may emerge.<HR>

<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <I>Updated on
April 15, 1996</I></H6>

