<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>PAF5</TITLE>



<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Klaus Hoefsloot">

</HEAD>



<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">



<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>



<CENTER><H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE <BR>Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 5

Friday 15 March 1996 </H3></CENTER>



<CENTER><H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>1 GREAT LAKES   LOCAL NGOs IN CONFLICT PREVENTION</B>

<P>

Following on from  the Kigali gathering of international and local

NGOs which took place on February 24th, a meeting was held on

Monday of this week to examine the European end of the programme.

  Monday's meeting was attended by <I>Eurostep</I>, Aprodev, Novib,

NCOS, Miserior, and Hassan Ba from Synergies Africa, who is largely

responsible for the initiative.  The three main themes from the

Kigali meeting were discussed -

<P>

1 The process of consultation now taking place with NGOs in the

Great Lakes on how local NGOs can be effective agents for conflict

prevention in the region.

<P>

2 The research project which was proposed in Kigali. This will

involve one African and one European researcher will investigate

the capacity and potential of local NGOs in the areas of greatest

conflict in the continent.  These were defined as Sierra Leone,

the Horn of Africa, the Great Lakes, and possibly also Southern

Africa.  The Brussels meeting on Monday set up a small working

group to come up with terms of reference, and a budget, for the

research.

<P>

3 The need for European agencies to promote the idea that local

NGOs can be effective in conflict prevention and that they should

be supported in this endeavour.  Networks based in Brussels including

<I>Eurostep</I>, Aprodev, and (it is hoped for the future) EuroCidse,

should lobby the appropriate EU institutions on these ideas.

<P>

<B>2 BURMA COMMISSION INVESTIGATION ON FORCED LABOUR</B>

<P>

The European Commission investigation on forced labour in Burma

has asked organisations and individuals to come forward with any

evidence they have about the issue.  The deadline for initial

submissions is March 20th.  David Arnott, of the Burma Peace Foundation,

has told us that if you would like to testify to the hearing you

should immediately fax the Commission describing your knowledge

of forced labour in Burma, and also outlining any documents which

you have ready to go.  You should mail any documents, videos,

photographic material etc.. which you have available now, (further

documents can be submitted at a later date).  The Commission has

not yet decided what forms the inquiry will take, so people should

indicate any options which they feel would be appropriate, including

fact-finding missions to the area.  Contact the Commission at

-

<P>

European Commission<BR>

Directorate General 1B, External Relations<BR>

(Directorate 1B, D, Division 3)<BR>

Rue de la Loi 200, <BR>

B - 1049, Brussels, Belgium    <BR>

fax  + 32 2 299 1047

<P>

David Arnott also requests that anybody applying to the Commission

also informs the Burma Peace Foundation (fax no. + 41 22 738 9419)

and the International Confederation of Trade Unions - Department

of Trade Union Rights (fax no. + 32 2 224 0297).  

<P>

The inquiry is important because the continuation of EU trade

preferences to Burma under the General System of Preferences depends

on the result.  If the Commission finds Burma guilty of practicing

forced labour, this could cost the Burmese government $30 million in

lost tariff reductions.  It would also be a serious embarrassment

to the regime and would contribute greatly to the pressure brought

about by international isolation.  We know that there are plans

to bring victims of forced labour to Brussels to testify, and

we will pass on more information about this issue when we can.

 

<P>

<B>3 SOCIAL WATCH FOLLOW UP TO THE SOCIAL SUMMIT </B>

<P>

How much of the action plans from the Social Summit and the Beijing

Conference on Women has actually been implemented?  The answer

will be contained in a new publication - the Social Watch report

- the first issue of which will be launched in Brussels on 29

March.  It contains information from civil society organisations

about what has happened in their countries since the action plans

were adopted.  In the first issue (known as the baseline edition

zero) <I>Eurostep</I>'s Mirjam Van Reisen has written the chapter

on the external policy of the European Union.  She will also be

addressing the meeting which launches the report.  There is also

a chapter by Greetie Lubbi of Novib on social policies within

the EU.  In future editions there will be opportunities for individual

NGOs worldwide to share their experiences.  Contributions can

be deposited over the Internet, creating an international exchange

of information on the implementation of the action plans.  

<P>

The report is published by Instituto Tercer Mundo in Montevideo,

Uruguay, with facilitation by Novib.  It will be available from

Novib.  Contact Caroline Wildeman at the Secretariat. 

<P>

<B>4 CONFLICT PREVENTION</B>

<P>

We have received a report on the activities of FEPAC - the group

of 120 European Members of Parliament which debates issues surrounding

conflict prevention.  FEPAC sees this as a key issue in the development

of a Common Foreign and Security Policy.  The first report is

more of an initial brochure than a serious examination of the

issues.  However, it promises that future reports will make available

the informed debates of FEPAC.  The first such report will be

published in June 1996.

<P>

<B>5 NGOs HOW EFFECTIVE ARE THEY?</B>

<P>

Earthscan has published a report called &quot;Beyond the Magic

Bullet :  Non-Governmental Organisations - Performance and Accountability&quot;.

 As the title suggests, the book looks at the claim that NGOs

are more effective agents for development than governments and

official aid agencies, and finds that the real impact of the NGO

sector is not well documented.  This is partly because NGO performance

assessment and accountability methods are weak, and partly because

NGOs are caught up in the world of official aid, which pushes

them towards certain forms of evaluation at the expense of others.

 There are also ideas about how NGOs can improve, based on the

need to develop the way they measure and account for their performance.

<P>

Copies cost &#163;9.95 plus 10% postage and packing and come from

Earthscan, <BR>

FREEPOST 1, <BR>

120 Pentonville Road, <BR>

London N1 9BR.  <BR>

Tel + 44 171 278 0433

<P>

<B>6 UNITED NATIONS AFRICAN INITIATIVE</B>

<P>

Today is the launch of the United Nations System-wide Special

Initiative on Africa which promises a target and coordinated effort

to improve development results in Africa, and the expenditure

of $25 billion over the next 10 years.  We went to the press conference

this morning in Brussels where it was admitted that most of the

$25 billion will come from existing resources.  However there

will also be new funds.  Both the IMF and World Bank have been

involved in the development of the initiative.  Cooperation between

the different parts of the UN system has been highlighted as a

key objective.<HR>

<P>

<H6> <i>Updated on May 22, 1996</i><br>

