<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Development Policy of the Netherlands</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/nl.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Exemplary in Concept and Reach:<br>The Development Policy of the
Netherlands<p>
<I>Paul J. Bendix</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 3, May-June 1996: pages 24-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<b>
Cosmopolitanism and a large and prosperous middle class are a
leftover from the Netherlands' colonial past. They also assure
its development cooperation top ranking for quantity and quality.
The strong position of development cooperation enables coordination
with the policies of other ministries. And higher education institutions
and NGOs play any important role.</b>
<P>
The Netherlands has a special place among the OECD donor countries,
not only in its conception of itself, but also from the view point
of developing countries. It is a former major (and controversial)
colonial power, an integral part of the NATO military alliance,
and a committed EU member. For all that, together with Canada
and Scandinavia it is one of the &quot;likeminded countries&quot;
that are the vanguard of deveopment policy. This special status
is explained by the small country's centurieslong role as a worldwide
trade and colonial power. The success of its overseas activities
and flourishing foreign trade created a large, prosperous middle
class that is still its determining social force. At the same
time, the largescale migration to the Dutch colonies brought about
an intellectual climate of cosmopolitanism. And that was later
stamped by the traumatic experiences of decolonisation and the
occupation of the Netherlands during the Second World War. The
economic difficulties of recent years have so far had only a slight
effect on the Netherlands' development cooperation. Political
parties? commerce and industry, and social groups continue unreservedly
to award development policy high ranking in the spectrum of the
country's policies. The following reasons are given for that:
<ul>
<li>compensation for the colonial past;
<li>the influence of Calvinism and its fundamental principle
of combining riches and success with &quot;good deeds&quot;;
<li>general acceptance of the role of the state as the authority
of social balance at home as well as in relation to the Third
World.</ul>
<P>
However, the rightwing liberals' surprise victory in the provincial
elections of March 1995 won, among other things, with the use
of xenophobic slogans, signals a possible unravelling of this
national consensus. The reorientation of foreign policy to primarily
economic policy goals that is now under way and the reduction
of the development cooperation budget in favour of military peacekeeping
missions also point in this direction.
<P>
<B>Development administration structure complicated, but functional</B>
<P>
The responsibilities for the Netherlands' development cooperation
are assigned in a very unusual way. Political responsibility is
carried by the Minister for Development Cooperation, who has Cabinet
rank but no ministry of his own. For the planning, control and
in part the implementation of development cooperation he calls
on the DirectorateGeneral for International Cooperation
(DGIS), one of the three departments of the Ministry for Foreign
Affairs. On the whole, this complicated structure has so far functioned
well. In particular, by this means development cooperation is
smoothly integrated in Netherlands embassies in recipient countries.
But interministerial disputes over domains have arisen in individual
cases. For example, when in 1992 the Netherlands Development Minister
called on Indonesia to observe human rights, and Indonesia rejected
this interference, the Netherlands Foreign Minister was placed
in a difficult situation. The development policy specialist Jan
Pronk, who was Development Minister from 1973 to 1977, has held
the portfolio again since the end of 1989.
<P>
The Finance Minister largely acts alone in shaping relations with
the IMF and the World Bank, and is responsible for export credit
guarantees. The Economics Minister is competent for GATT/WTO and
UNCTAD and collaborates on mixed financing projects. But he does
not, as in some other donor countries, represent the interests
of industry. The Agriculture Minister, on the other hand, represents
mainly the interests of agroproducers and has his own attaches
in Netherlands embassies.
<P>
The relatively high status of development cooperation in the Netherlands
is shown by the fact that a coordination committee (COCOS) chaired
by the head of the DGIS meets monthly, and a Cabinet subcommittee
on development cooperation (ROS) presided over by the Prime Minister
convenes three times year.
<P>
The Netherlands has no special implementation organizations. About
100 members of embassies, assisted by 50 regionally located sector
experts, handle mainly development cooperation tasks. Other important
insitutions are:
<ul>
<li>the Netherlands Development Organization (SNV),
which has been largely independent of the DGIS since the beginning
of 1991. Besides seconding development aid workers, it carries
out implementation tasks with a volume of about 30 million guilders
a year;
<li>the wellknown Centre for the Promotion of Exports
from Developing Countries (CBI), which other donors
regard as a model;
<li>the Netherlands Development Finance Company (FMO),
roughly equivalent to the German Finance Company for Investments in Developing Countries (DEG);
<li>the four NGO umbrella orgnizations: ICCO (Protestant),
CEBEMO (Catholic), NOVIB (ideologically independent), and HIVOS
(Social Democratic/humanistic), for cofinancing and implementations
tasks;
<li>the Netherlands Organization forlnternational Cooperation
in Higher Education (NUFFIC), with competence for the initial
and advanced training of developing country nationals and implementation
of university and college projects; and
<li>the National Information Committee for Development Cooperation
(NCO), which continues to receive official funds for the promotion
of Third World groups and for development policy education work
despite occasional fierce arguments with the development cooperation
administration.
</ul><P>
<B>Linking development cooperation to net national income</B>
<P>
The Netherlands achieved the UN target of 0.7 per cent of GNP
for official development assistance (ODA) back in 1975. Since
then it has always been among the top group of the DAC donor countries.
In the 1980s, its ODA-GNP ratio ranged between 0.9 per cent and
1.1 per cent.
<P>
There has been parliamentary consensus since 1973 that total government
spending on development cooperation, that is, not only ODA according
to OECD/DAC criteria, should be 1.5 per cent of net national income
(NNI). This benchmark has largely hindered reduction of development
cooperation in the wake of budget cuts. But it also limits the
growth of development cooperation and hampers initiatives or the
setting up of new programmes. Besides that, the development cooperation
budget encompasses what are essentially non-ODA components. These
include, for example, the debt service for development cooperation
financing obtained on the capital market, the costs of caring
for refugees from Third World countries, and, recently, aid for
Eastern Europe and the CIS states. This led to the 1.5 per cent
criterion being questioned in principle in November 1992 during
a parliamentary debate on the 1993 budget.
<P>
The Netherlands does not differentiate between Technical and Financial
Cooperation. Since 1990 aid has been disbursed exclusively as
grants.
<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends</b></caption>
<tr><td><td>1979/80<td>1984/85<td>1989/90<td>1993/94
<tr><td>ODA in bill. guilders*<td>3.1<td>3.9<td>4.7<td>4.8
<tr><td>ODA in bill. US$**<td>2.4<td>2.5<td>2.7<td>2.6
<tr><td>ODA as % of GNP<td>0.95<td>0.97<td>0.94<td>0.81
<tr><td>
