</tr></table>
<p>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 2: Trends in geographical distribution (as
% of bilateral ODA)</b></caption>
<tr><td><td>1982/83<td>1987/88<td>1992/93
<tr><td>SubSaharan Africa<td>33<td>39<td>38
<tr><td>South and Central Asia<td>22<td>20<td>16
<tr><td>Rest of Asia/Oceania<td>14<td>17<td>4
<tr><td>Arabia/Europe<td>6<td>6<td>14
<tr><td>Latin America/Caribbean<td>25<td>18<td>28
<tr><td>Source: OECD/DCA
</table>
<P>
<B>Regional concentration</B>
<P>
Following a parliamentary debate on the fragmentation of development
cooperation, the number of recipient countries was reduced to
about 45 in the South and 10 Eastern European and CIS states.
The division into three country categories remained. These are:
<ul>
<li>&quot;programme countries&quot;  India, Pakistan and Bangladesh,
with annual disbursements fixed in agreement with the recipients);
<li>&quot;regional countries&quot;  funds can be distributed
among seven defined regions according to need and the quality
of national policies. The regions are the Mekong, Nile/Red Sea,
Sahel/West Africa, East Africa, Central America, Andes and Surinam;
<li>&quot;sector countries&quot;  where international organizations
and NGOs take over the implementation of bilateral rural development
measures.</ul>
<P>
This regional distribution, however, has recently been overlaid
by four new categories: normal cooperation countries; treaty countries
that have signed a sustainable development agreement (Benin, Bhutan,
Costa Rica); conflict and rehabilitation cases (Angola, Eritrea,
Cambodia, Sudan, Somalia, Palestine); and finally transition countries
(Eastern Europe, the CIS, South Africa, Namibia). Indonesia ended
its development cooperation relations with the Netherlands in
1992.
<P>
On the whole, a relatively stable regional, and a balanced sectoral,
distribution of development cooperation can be noted.
<P>
<B>Strong multilateral commitment</B>
<P>
Like the Scandinavian countries, the Netherlands gives more support
to multilateral organizations than do the big OECD donors. The
aim here is to broaden the group of favoured recipient countries
and influence the policy of the respective organization, especially
in alleviating poverty. Due to the way the Netherlands apportions
its contributions, and its voting power, it is easier for it to
do this under the rules of the UN system than through the finance
institutions. However, its critical assessment of the efficiency
of certain UN special organizations has recently led it to make
selective cuts in disbursements to them, while increasing its
commitments to the World Bank group and the regional banks and
their funds.
<P>
<B>Developmental concept is changing</B>
<P>
The Netherlands has neither a concept for development cooperation
in the sense of the German &quot;fundamental&quot; principles
nor a law covering it. Nevertheless, it has a clear and differentiated
conceptional guideline in the shape of the detailed introduction
and explanation of the summary of government spending on development
cooperation which is presented to Parliament every year. This
document includes the expert opinions of the <I>National Advisory
Council for Development Cooperation </I>(NAR), evaluation findings,
and specific policy papers which have attracted attention during
the course of the year. In this respect, the &quot;budget memoranda&quot;
are like a development cooperation concept that is reassessed
every year.
<P>
To be sure, there have seldom been radical changes in concepts.
In 1990, Development Minister Pronk tabled in Parliament the White
Paper &quot;A World of Difference&quot;, which expressly placed
sustainable poverty alleviation in the centre of development aid.
<P>
Moreover, four main crosssector tasks were defined and secured
in personnel terms. These are environmental protection, promotion
of women, developmentrelated research, and promotion of the urban
poor. These also serve as benchmarks for bilateral development
cooperation measures.
<P>
Pronk tabled another White Paper in 1993 titled &quot;A World
in Dispute&quot; in which he explained the new allocation categories
and country criteria mentioned above. He also renewed his approach
of the cross-ministry linking of development policy with other
policy areas.
<P>
<B>NGO participation</B>
<P>
What is also noteworthy in terms of concepts is the Netherlands'
system of financing NGO projects exclusively through the four
NGO umbrella organizations. Along with that is the successful
integration and participation in development cooperation of all
relevant social groups, including academics and scientists, via
the NAR. Its expert opinions are attentively noted by politicians
and the public.
<P>
<b>Literature</b>
<P>
Bendix, P J. (1987): Die Entwicklungspolitik der Niederlande.
Berlin, DIE. OECD/DAC: Development Cooperation Review series,
No. 4: The Netherlands. Paris 1994. A World of Difference (1990):
A new framework for development cooperation in the 1 990s. The
Hague.
<P>
<B>Paul J. Bendix </B>worked with the German Development Institute
(DIE) from 197686. Since 1991 he heads a section for development
policy with the German Development Service (DED) in Berlin.
<p>
<HR>
