<HEAD>

<TITLE>Cooperation in Africa: Generating Action at the Unit-Level</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>Cooperation in Africa: Generating Action at the Unit-Level
</H3>

<P>
by <I>Jeggan Senghor</I> 
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
pages 3-4</I> </CENTER><HR>

<H4>Introduction</H4>

<P>
The 1990's have seen a resurgence of interest in cooperation and
integration in Africa. However the focus of policy and research
on the subject is still overwhelmingly on issues and problems
associated with the 'top-down' regional institutions and processes.
<P>
Yet policy and programme decision-making and implementation must
also inevitably involve a 'bottom-up' process of actions by 'unit-level
actors'. It is what national governments do that effectively determines
whether economies become more interlinked in an integration framework.
<P>
This is not to belittle the importance of regional organisations
such as the PTA, ECOWAS, SADC, and the many other sub-regional
institutions which have been established. But unless their pronouncements
are paralleled by policy and institutional changes at the national
level, they will amount to little more than political platitudes.
<H4>Policy Priorities</H4>

<P>
Since independence, and increasingly over the past one-and-a-half
decades, African governments have confronted a range of mind-boggling
political and economic problems, all of which required major policy-
decisions. In the economic field, the recognised shortcomings
of post-independence development strategies that neither delivered
economic growth nor improved the conditions of the poor, have
combined with the deter- ioration in the global economic environment
to make it essential that governments give priority to short term
crisis management of their economies. The formulation and implement-
ation of disciplined macro-policies under structural adjustment
programmes has been the overwhelming priority of governments.
<P>
African governments and the external financial institutions and
donors that support them have become increasingly aware that simply
addressing short term policy priorities will never permit the
longer term objectives of social and economic development to be
achieved. The central problems of human resource development,
and technological change in agriculture and industry must be brought
as rapidly as possible on to the policy agenda. And included in
this agenda must be greater regional cooperation and integration,
both as a desirable political end in itself and as a necessary
condition for achieving higher rates of economic growth and development.
<P>
If a beginning is to be made to address this agenda of long term
issues such as including regional cooperation, then those involved
in development policy management in govern- ment, in research
institutions, and elsewhere must articulate programmes of action
that reflect priority needs and are politically credible. The
perspective must be of a process at work in which correct macro-
policies are in place but where these are simply the back- round
against which policies and programmes to address long term issues
are formulated and implemented. Measures to promote regional cooperation
must themselves be phased.
<H4>Sequencing</H4>

<P>
At this point in time, there are three vital next steps in terms
of national policies and national institutional development which
are required in the sequential process leading to greater regional
cooperation.
<P>
<I>Central Government Institutions</I>
<P>
The rush since independence to create new institutions at the
regional level to promote increased cooperation has diverted attention
from national-level requirements for cooperation. The political
commitment of Heads of State must be reflected in national governmental
institutions. Both for reasons of institutional identification
and for bureaucratic effectiveness. 
<P>
The present common practice of making a unit within the ministry
of finance, or of foreign affairs or of trade and industry, responsible
for overseeing regional cooperation, is no effective alternative
to a separate ministry. It fails to give high profile recognition
to the seriousness of the government's commitment to regional
cooperation.
<P>
At the bureaucratic level, there are two shortcomings to this
practice. First, the mainstream responsibilities of these ministries
understandably tend to dominate their activities and leave regional
development issues as the residual legatee of their time and effort.
Moreover, the staffing, authority level, backgrounds and qualifications
of personnel in these ministerial units tend to be far below what
is required to make them effective.
<P>
Second, regional issues frequently cut across the sectoral and
functional responsibilities of line ministries. Although they
can be handled through interministerial committees, these rarely
prove to be effective because their composition and powers are
limited.
<P>
The solution to these problems is to rise above them and establish
a separate ministry for regional cooperation answerable directly
to the head of state and headed by a senior minister. It would
ensure that regional policies were integrated into all aspects
of national policy that they were implemented according to plan.
<P>
The staff would have to be selected with the specific needs of
regional integration in mind. They must be both narrowly technocratic
and at the same time adopt broad perspectives and a multidisciplinary
approval to development and its relationship to regional issues.
They would still work through interministerial committees and
in many cases would be linked to a cell in the main sectoral ministries.
<P>
It should be emphasised that the alternative of a decentralised
regional unit is only a second-best proposition. It would involve
establishing national units of the regional organisation in each
member country. But this would not reflect the need for visible
demonstration of national commitment to regional cooperation.
Moreover, it is hard to believe that it would ever become an accepted
part of the national bureaucratic process. Thus it would be in
danger of being even more marginal to the determination of government
policies than the units in existing ministries.
<P>
<I>Involving Private Economic Operators</I>
<P>
If greater economic cooperation and integration is to have any
real meaning, the results must include increased trade across
national boundaries, increased investment, and possibly increased
movement of workers. Already considerable cross-border economic
activity takes place reflecting in some cases historical trade
and labour supply links which go back many centuries. Some of
this cross-border activity is informal and even illegal, and it
is often in response to distorted prices.
<P>
With the removal of these distortions under recovery and adjustment
programmes, these flows make increasing sense in economic terms.
They need to be encouraged by easing unnecessary and costly border-crossing
restrictions and by introducing more meaningful tariffs and other
taxes on imports and exports.
<P>
It follows that the second priority will be to establish institutions
that enable  private economic operators -- industrial firms, farmers,
traders, transport undertakings -- to participate in the formulation
and implementation of policies that generate this increased cross-border
economic activity. This has to be a bottom-up process in which
an enabling environment of prices, exchange rate policy, tax policy,
profit opportunities, infrastructure provision, legal regulatory
framework, and financial institutions is created to induce private
enterprises to engage in generating increases in the flows of
regional trade.
<P>
Mansoor's contribution in this Bulletin reports on the way in
which the private sector has been brought into the cross-border
policy-making process in East and Southern Africa.
<P>
<I>Civil Society</I>
<P>
It is sad, that although it is the people of each country that
are expected to be the ultimate beneficiaries of regional cooperation,
they are at present mere spectators. Without their involvement
and support it is unlikely that any progress can be made, especially
as the benefits of cooperation are predominantly in the longer
run. In the short run, costs and concessions to other members
of a regional organisation tend to predominate. If a government
is to sustain political support for regional programmes long enough
for the benefits to accrue, then it will require a wide base of
interest groups throughout civil society.
<P>
Establishing a political constituency of support is, therefore,
a necessary condition for subsequent developments in regional
cooperation. It requires in the first place that the people and
their representatives in associations, professional societies,
farmers' groups, women's' groups, and so on, as well as in political
parties, should be better informed on regional issues. Governments
must be more willing to make known data and other information
relating to regional cooperation. In addition they must encourage
their own civil servants as well as outside researchers, journalists,
and others to engage in analytical and controversial discussions
on regional issues.
<P>
This does not mean an abdication from leadership by the government.
Long term development objectives such as regional cooperation
will never be achieved without political leadership. But at the
same time, these objectives will never be achieved on a sustainable
basis unless there are organised constituencies and lobbies to
support, encourage and goad governments into action.
<H4>Concluding Comment</H4>

<P>
Regional cooperation as a credible national objective must be
reflected more strongly in national institutions if progress is
to be made. As a sequential process this paper has suggested three
priorities requiring the most immediate attention. Not only will
these strengthen the national base from which increasing regional
cooperation can take place, they will have a knock-on effect in
terms of improving the efficiency and effectiveness of the regional
institutions themselves.<HR>

