<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Disaster Preparedness</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Disaster Preparedness<br>European Union Steps up its Support<p>
<I>David Nyheim and Edgar Thielmann</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 5, September-October 1995: page 16</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
Disasters can be broadly defined as any extreme events, whether
of natural or human origin, which overwhelm vulnerable populations.
There is no doubt vulnerability is frequently a reflection of
poverty and that consequently vulnerability reduction is largely
a product of social and economic development. While countries
like the Philippines and Bangladesh are in geographically vulnerable
locations, there is no doubt that their main susceptibility comes
from their weak social and economic structures. Housing quality,
preexisting health and nutritional status, social welfare infrastructure,
and economic resilience determine the magnitude of a disaster's
effect and its longterm consequences.
<P>
The loss of life due to natural disasters worldwide over the last
40 years has amounted to about six million people, with an affected
population of over 800 million people. Immediate material damages
have been estimated to about 20 billion US$. Mortality due to
manmade disasters, such as civil conflict, is much higher, with
some sources estimating more than 20 million people killed after
World War II.
<P>
Overall, for both natural and manmade disasters a steady decline
in the resistance of the populations to disasters becomes evident,
with an increase of mortality over time.
<P>
However, external emergency assistance is too often neither on
time nor particularly appropriate. This is not due to any sluggishness
on the part of distant agencies, but is the result of inadequacies
in communication, assessment of need, accessibility and other
difficulties.
<P>
External relief assistance in the later phases also frequently
creates parallel structures to local efforts. This is particularly
visible in the provision of healthcare in relief, and the deployment
of short-term mobile hospitals and supply of external pharmaceutical
products. Local healthcare structures are consequently weakened,
leaving communities more vulnerable than before. Similarly, rushing
in excessive amounts of food before an effective assessment of
local market conditions and agricultural prospects has been carried
out can create dependency and undermine local economies.
<P>
On the other hand, it has been estimated that the loss of GNP
from disasters in developing countries is some 20 times greater
than in the industrialized North. Standards in health, education,
and other social sectors deteriorate in affected countries, further
polarising social and economic divisions, pushing the poor further
into poverty and increasing the marginalisation of those already
discriminated against because of religion, race, gender, class
and other factors.
<P>
Despite significant disaster assistance and aid in the last decades,
disasters increasingly set back both social and economic development.
Current disaster management policies and development programmes
appear unable to reverse this trend. Explanations for this may
be sought in the rigid nature of most current relief/rehabilitation
and development activities. Disasters are viewed as simple &quot;blips&quot;,
to be rectified by emergency interventions, on an otherwise linear
development curve. Relief and development are treated as independent
entities, rather than as linked in a continuum.
<P>
The ECHO Disaster Preparedness Programme of the European Union
seeks to bridge the reliefdevelopment gap by supporting activities
geared towards vulnerability reduction and capacity building on
both the local and national levels. Increasing the efficiency
of relief, as well as limiting the impact of catastrophes on the
process of development, largely depends on good disaster preparedness
on-site, and adequate local capacities for sustainable recovery.
<P>
ECHO has therefore chosen to focus on three strategies for disaster
preparedness in both natural and manmade disasters:
<P>
<ul>
<li>promotion and development of human resources,
<P>
<li>strengthening management and institutional preparedness
structures, to increase response capabilities in emergencies,
and
<P>
<li>support to communitybased lowcost technology field projects.</ul>
<P>
Development of human resources is recognised as being a key element
for sustainable preparedness. ECHO's contribution in this field
covers training programmes which range from inventory management
to public health and nutrition.
<P>
Many of the inefficiencies of relief are due to the fact that
they are planned ad hoc and lack proper institutional structures.
At disaster sites, local communities inevitably perform the most
immediate relief work. Strengthening local structures will only
increase their efficiency and that of external relief.
<P>
Severe resource constraints in most disasterprone developing countries
mean that lowcost options for disaster preparedness are the most
feasible. The scope of this part of ECHO's programme extends to
worthwhile, cost-effective initiatives with a local community basis.
Projects under this heading include lowcost applications of disaster
mitigation technology.
<P>
In the last quarter of 1994, ECHO selected 15 preparedness projects
in disaster prone regions in Asia, Latin/Central America, and
Africa, for an amount exceeding two million ECU. Projects have
been selected upon several criteria, including environmental considerations,
the active participation of women in the decision-making process,
long-term sustainability, and cost-effectiveness vis&agrave;vis
the number of beneficiaries.
<P>
ECHO disaster preparedness projects range from assisting communities
in organizing village-level groups to set up radio-based early warning
systems, and training for relief management in Bangladesh (approximately
500 000 beneficiaries), to increasing the physical and structural
earthquake resistance of hospitals in Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador,
and Chile.
<P>
Given that over 90 per cent of ECHO's humanitarian activities
are in conflict zones, applicable preventive strategies need to
be developed. With the Burundian government, for example, and
in collaboration with Unicef, ECHO is supporting the implementation
of a peace-education programme, offering social-psychological support
to children, youth, and adults (over 100 000 people). For 1995,
the budget allocated by ECHO for preparedness activities is of
5 million ECU.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on November 15, 1996<BR>
</I>This article is made available on EUFORIC by kind permission
of the publishers - E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach
10 08 01, D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax:
+49 69 7501-4855.<BR>
Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape
browser. Please address comments on content or style to <A href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter Ballantyne</A>,
Information Programme, ECDPM</H6>
<HR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
