Content-length: 13369
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Bridging Emergency Aid  and Development</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Bridging Emergency Aid  and Development:<br>The GTZ and Emergency Assistance<p>
<I>Petra Windisch</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 6, November-December 1996: pages 12-14</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>The concept of a clearly definable, linear progression from
emergency aid to  rehabilitation and development no longer works
in many partner countries. The people  there are living more often
and longer amid lasting crises and disasters. So the  separation
of humanitarian aid and development cooperation is largely invalid.
Where  humanitarian aid must be converted to selfsupporting structures,
the development  project proves ever more frequently to be a permanent
double commission: emergency  aid and development.</B>
<P>
No event in recent times has so shaken  people across the world
as the genocide in  Rwanda. The disaster that overran the  Central
African country even put the  situation in crisis-torn Somalia
out of their  minds for a while. This is not to mention the  places
in the world that do not make the  headlines although they have
also long  been crisis areas. Rwanda and Somalia  have become
a synonym for these  countries; a synonym for disaster. And this
 word in turn is almost a synonym for a  developing country.
<P>
Statistics confirm that almost 90 per cent of  all disasters occur
in developing countries.  Disasters, regardless of their type,
can  therefore in many cases no longer be seen as  isolated events
in a country which apart from  that is &quot;in development&quot;.
The concept of a  clearly definable, linear progression from 
humanitarian aid to rehabilitation and  development no longer
works in many  countries. The people there live amid ongoing 
crises and disasters that can no longer be  eliminated in weeks
or months. So the  separation of humanitarian aid and  development
cooperation is largely invalid in  many countries.
<P>
Other than in the 1970s and 1980s, when  great droughts caused
crises, civil wars are  today the most frequent reason for situations
 of extreme distress. Worldwide, there are  currently 47 internal
conflicts, more than at  any time since the end of the Second
World  War. These political disasters often trigger  massive human
rights violations and huge  refugee flows. These occurrences can
 now hardly be coped with by such  traditional aid approaches
as shortterm  food supply or medical care. Ethnicsocial  conflicts
such as those in Rwanda, Burundi  or Bosnia also demand from the
German  Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ)  new approaches
in development-oriented  emergency aid.
<P>
Thus by its presence on site the GTZ was  able to react quickly
and flexibly when within  only a few weeks about two million 
Rwandans sought refuge in Zaire and other  countries. In line
with their self-image, GTZ  workers supported the aid inputs of
other  organizations in complementary and  subsidiary ways. An
example of such  supportive emergency aid is the controlled  supply
of firewood and the introduction of  woodsaving cooking stoves
in some refugee  camps in East Zaire. In agreement with the  UNHCR
and other aid organizations,  professional know-how could thus
be  mobilised quickly in those areas where other  organizations
had less experience.
<P>
In refugee situations such as in Zaire the  GTZ experts pay early
attention to creating a  balance between the refugees and local
 people. Experience over many years in 
the partner countries has shown that local inhabitants react enviously
to refugees, who are often better provided for. The sudden flow
of refugees strained the local supply structures in Zaire so badly
that immediate support was necessary. Thus the GTZ helped to restore
the water supply in Goma and keep the road between Goma and Bukavu
in operation. The German-Zairean projects for the local people
on Lake Kivu were continued.
<P>
<B>Dual task of emergency aid and development</B>
<P>
The focal point of GTZ emergency assistance is only in exceptional
cases pure humanitarian survival aid in the first days after the
outbreak of a disaster. The GTZ assumes an important role in the
rehabilitation phase and its transition to long-term reconstruction.
The idea of converting humanitarian aid to development cooperation
as soon as possible is not new. The UN and other organizations
have long been grappling with the concept of the disaster-to-development continuum. However, the harmonised transition of humanitarian
aid to selfsupporting development, in which the victims reassume
full responsibility for their lives as soon as possible, is not
easy. The concept is also threatening to become empty words in
the developmental debate. At the same time, because of the numerous
disasters it is all the more urgent to implement it. There is
otherwise a danger that the self-help efforts of the people affected
- a basic prerequisite for development cooperation - will in the
long run be stopped and the people in the crisis region made dependent
upon the drip-feed of international aid.
<P>
Close cooperation of development and humanitarian organizations
and local structures is especially necessary in the critical phase
following humanitarian survival aid in which the traditional aid
organizations have alleviated the worst misery. The rehabilitation
phase in particular is now regarded as an important but also difficult
link to forge between the acute aid phase and the restoration
of basic living conditions to their possibly predisaster level.
The GTZ's emergency aid is often focused on the latter phase.
Its principles, which are not always easy to maintain, are sustainability
and participation. In this sense, GTZ development experts have
provided and are still providing development-oriented emergency
aid, behind the headlines of disasters, in many African, Asian
and Latin American countries and also in Bosnia, Armenia or Azerbaijan.
<P>
<B>Blurred lines between development and disaster aid</B>
<P>
How the boundaries between the various types of traditional
and development-oriented aid blur becomes clear in Sudan, Somalia,
Liberia or Sierra Leone. On account of its longtime experience
in these countries, the GTZ supports others like Guinea by providing
medical care for the refugees from Liberia they have taken in
for years. In Sudan, further training programmes are preparing
refugees for their repatriation. In Northwest Somalia, a food
security programme is giving employment to many people and offering
them the opportunity to pay for some of their food again. Development-oriented
emergency aid must also be more active in developing instruments
to prevent crises.
<P>
NGOs have a firm place in these approaches to new types of
projects. When it comes to reconciling hostile groups, they can
make important contributions to social development in the affected
countries. In this sense, the GTZ cooperates with a Rwandan NGO
that seeks to implement crisis prevention in a practical way.
The emergency aid project is being linked with a planned project
to reconstruct the judicial system in Rwanda. The approach is
aimed at helping to reduce the Rwandans' mistrust of each other.
<P>
The demobilisation of soldiers and guerrilla fighters and their
reintegration into civil life is another way to reduce the risk
of new outbreaks of violence. Demobilisation and reintegration
are therefore part of a crisis prevention after a political disaster
that must be got under way as soon as possible  that is, by way
of emergency aid. Training and employment projects for demobilised
soldiers should facilitate their return to civil life. The GTZ
is supporting such project approaches in, among other countries,
Mozambique and Ethiopia. The approaches cannot be categorised
as classic development cooperation nor as humanitarian aid. But
they illustrate the GTZ's bridging function between humanitarian
aid and Technical Cooperation in the case of civil war disasters.
<P>
In emergency situations where a lot of international aid organizations
are present, operations often run without the participation of
the local administration, NGOs or selfhelp groups. District public
health systems or regional administrations are often simply ignored.
Instead of including them, parallel supply structures are often
set up for the victims. Not least out of a lack of knowledge of
the region, chances of resorting to existing capacities are missed.
This robs the local organizations of the possibility of solving
the emergency situations of their own accord. This is an important
area of responsibility for the GTZ, whose original task is to
qualify the people and organizations in the partner countries
to solve development problems themselves.
<P>
In a crisis it is also the GTZ's task to strengthen local capacities
for emergency aid and rehabilitation. Thus in Benin it is supporting
the education authorities in the inschool care of the children
of refugees from Togo. In Ethiopia and Rwanda development experts
are advising the competent offices for reconstruction and the
reintegration of refugees. In Cambodia, smallholders received
at short notice via the Agriculture Ministry pumps for irrigating
their rice crops. By this means an attempt was made to strengthen
the farmers' potential for self-help and avoid dependency on food
aid.
<P>
International spending on emergency aid is increasing constantly.
In 1994 the European Union alone disbursed about Ecu 755 million
for humanitarian aid in more than 60 countries. In the same year
bilateral emergency aid accounted for about 10 per cent of total
ODA - two per cent alone for the Rwandan crisis - exceeding the
1984 volume fivefold. The danger is growing that already tight
international budgets for development cooperation will drop further
at the cost of less sustainable emergency aid. That is why worldwide
the call is getting louder urging development organizations to
get to grips with crises and disasters more intensively than before,
with ever greater focus on prevention. Development cooperation
instruments such as cost-benefit analyses or impact assessments
must be used adjusted specially to emergency situations.
<P>
<B>Reliable indicators</B>
<P>
Development-oriented emergency aid projects have in many cases
restored some self-responsibility for their lives to the people
in Bosnia or Rwanda. However, the contribution a development-oriented
emergency assistance makes to stabilising and normalising a critical
situation is seldom measured. That is why in future the contribution
of development programmes and projects to a comprehensive coping
with disasters should be defined more precisely and designed more
transparently.
<P>
It is certainly even more difficult to answer the question
of what development cooperation can do to help prevent crises
and disasters. Some critics accuse development cooperation of
a failure in general here. Others, however, assume that the possibilities
of bilateral development cooperation in crisis prevention and
disaster precautions have not yet been exhausted. Also here it
is true that there has so far been little systematic recording
of both the positive and negative impacts of development cooperation
on the partner countries' susceptibility to crises. Development
experts will have to learn how to come to terms with the fact
that crises and disasters occur time and again in many countries,
nullifying within days and weeks developments that have been started
with great effort. That is why it is even more important to develop
suitable prevention instruments and incorporate them in project
concepts. Early warning systems must be bundled and so designed
that they give political decisiontakers timely indication of their
options for action.
<P>
A central task for the GTZ will in future be to alleviate the
consequences of disasters by building the bridge from classic
humanitarian aid to development cooperation. Another and no less
important task will be to define more precisely and optimise the
contribution of our development programme to crisis prevention
and disaster precautions.
<p>
<HR>
