<HEAD>

<TITLE>PAF8</TITLE>

</HEAD>



<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">



<P>

<CENTER></CENTER>

<CENTER>

<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>

Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 8 Friday 19April 1996 </CENTER>

</H3>



<P>

<CENTER>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>

115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>

Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>

E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>

</H4>

<HR>



<P>

<B>Budget Discharge</B>

<P>

The Union's financial account for 1994 were formally approved

and cleared in Strasbourg this week, but not before MEPs had voiced

strong worries at loopholes in the system.

<P>

The debate held on Tuesday on the discharge to be given to the

European Commission for management of the Community budget for

1991 and following years demonstrated that Parliament is now taking

much more seriously its role and responsibilities on budgetary

matters.

<P>

During the debate it was pointed out that, in order to clear the

accounts absolutely correctly, a radical reform of the system

is needed. The Commission does not have the necessary resources

remarking that only 7% of the corrections made in cases of irregularities

are the result of precise calculations, the rest being 'guesswork'

or, in the best cases estimated.

<P>

Mr. Wynn (Labour, UK) recommended refusal to grant a discharge

for the European Development Fund for 1994, speaking of an 'incoherent

mess'. The EP has been trying unsuccessfully for years to have

this fund budgetized, but the Court of Justice has decreed that

EDF expenditure is not Community expenditure, but simply member

State expenses managed by the European Commission.  the MEP also

pointed out that the member States have the easy role, since they

'write the rule book', whereas the Commission takes the blame

when things go wrong.

<P>

Mr. Fabre-Aubrespy (Europe of Nations) criticised the rejection

of the discharge for the EDF and asked why this discharge had

been granted during previous budget years. Ms. Ewing (Scottish

MEP, European Radical Alliance) called for assurance that this

rejection will not entail delays or cuts in the allocation of

funds to ACP countries.

<P>

European Commissioner for the Budget Erkii Liikanen noted, in

response to MEPs, the need for better implementation of the innovation

introduced by the Maastricht Treaty (Article 188C), namely the

statement of assurance (SOA) established by the Court of Auditors

on 'reliability of the accounts' of the Commission and the 'legality

and regularity of the underlying transactions'.

<P>

Mr. Liikanen said he regretted the rejection of discharge for

the EDF management in 1994 and felt that this means the EP does

not have anything to say in the use of the European Development

Fund. However, he indicated that the Commission essentially shares

the Parliament's views and will continue to work towards including

the EDF in the budget.

<P>

During the vote on Wednesday, the Parliament endorsed the view

of Rapporteur Wynn, refusing the discharge for the 1994 financial

year of the EDF as it considered illogical to approve execution

of a budget on which it has no possibility of intervening (being

founded on national contributions from member States).

<P>

<B>Chocolate Directive</B>

<P>

On Wednesday, the European Commission adopted its proposal aimed

at modifying the directive relating to cocoa products and chocolate.

All member States will have the choice of authorising their 

<P>

chocolate manufacturers to incorporate vegetable fats other than

cocoa butter in chocolate up to 5% of the total weight of the

finished product on condition that this is clearly mentioned on

the label of the product (a 

<P>

mention in the list of ingredients would not be sufficient). Member

States that wish to maintain the obligation to use only cocoa

butter - and no other vegetable fat - will be free to do so.

<P>

The UK, Denmark, Ireland, Portugal, Austria, Finland and Sweden

already authorise the use of alternative fats.

<P>

According to Martin Bangemann, this proposal plans to reconcile

three major principles: subsidiarity, the free movement of goods

and consumer protection. The Commission nonetheless expects that

its proposal (subject to codecision procedure) will give rise

to difficult debates at the Council and Parliament.

<P>

There are in fact many and divergent interests at stake: those

of member States, chocolate manufacturers, cocoa producer countries

and countries that export vegetable fats other than cocoa butter.

The ACP cocoa producer countries have not failed to voice their

opposition for some while now to extension of the minority rule

of 5% which, they say, would threaten their cocoa bean exports

with collapse (the reduction would be from 80 000 to 200 tonnes

and annual receipts lost are estimated at $290 million). This

would cause cocoa prices to collapse on international markets.

<P>

Given the lobbying by cocoa producer countries, Burkina Faso and

Mali, C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire, Ghana, Cameroon, shea butter exporters

to the EU also expressed their strong concern given the risk of

seeing exports receipts, which are essential to their economy,

dry up.

<P>

The Commission envisages partially compensating the loses of the

revenues of those countries through the STABEX. The European citizens

will have then to contribute to cover the interests of the big

industries.

<P>

The decision of the Commission is contrary to its commitments

taken at the International Cocoa Agreement.

<P>

<B>Fisheries Council</B>

<P>

The Fisheries Council will meet on Monday 22 April in Brussels.

The ministers will again debate the problem of driftnets, as well

as research into fishing; they should approve the tariff quotas

for 1996 and the regulation opening the way to greater quota flexibility

for catches. The Commission will set out the recommendations of

scientist on reducing fleet capacities for the period 1997/99.

<P>

<HR>

