<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>National Non-Uniform Day Acknowledgements</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><a href="nnud_contents.html"><img align=right hspace=10 src="unicef_pix/nnud_leaf.gif"></a><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif" WIDTH="160" HEIGHT="53" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=left><BR clear=left><br><HR><P><CENTER></CENTER><H2><CENTER>Photo Captions</CENTER></H2><font size=-1><a href="unicef_pix/nnud_1.jpg>Pic. 1</a> Kikanai and Mshangama<BR><BR>Kikanai aged 8, and his brother Mshangama aged 20, are Maasai. Their villageis in north west Tanzania. The Maasai people used to be nomads, followingtheir herds of cattle across the grasslands. Now many of them have settledand they grow maize and cassava, as well as having cattle herds which theyoung men follow. Kikanai does go to school but it is a two hour walk away.<BR><BR>Pic. 2 Nyafuru and Amos<BR><BR>Nyafuru, aged 10 and her cousin Amos, aged 7,  live in a village on theshores of Lake Victoria. Their fathers are fishermen. Four men go out ina boat every day to check their fishing nets. They catch 50-60 fish at atime which they sell in the local market. Most of the fish are bought bya large supplier who freezes them and sells them in Kenya and the Netherlands.Nyafuru's name means, 'I ate that fish', because her mother ate a furu fishsoon after she was born.<BR><BR><a href="unicef_pix/nnud_3.jpg">Pic. 3</a> Rehema and Emanuel at the Kuleana Children's Rights Centre<BR><BR>Rehema is 13 and Emanuel 14  years old. They have both ran away from homeand have lived at the Kuleana Children's Rights Centre in Mwanza for twoyears.  85 children between the ages of 4 and 14 eat and sleep at the Centre.Both Rehema and Emanuel go to school nearby. In the afternoon they can gointo Mwanza and earn some money.<BR><BR>Pic. 4 Salome<BR><BR>Salome is 10. She lives in the village of Sima. Salome has a brother andsister older than her, and three sisters younger. In the morning she goesto school and in the afternoon she helps her mother by collecting water,washing her younger sisters, and then minding her youngest sister whileshe plays with her friends. Salome's parents are farmers, they grow maize,cassava, oranges, mangoes and cotton.<BR><BR>Pic. 5 Baby Adam with Kinani<BR><BR>Adam, aged 5 months was born with a club foot. Kinani, aged 25, is a memberof a team of volunteers who have learnt how to help people who are disabled.They live in the village of Nungwi on Zanzibar. There are not many aidsfor disabled people in Tanzania. Now people like Kinani are going to thevillages to help them and put them in touch with doctors and specialistswho might be able to help them.<BR><BR><a href="unicef_pix/nnud_6.jpg">Pic. 6</a> The Akinamama Msimamo Co-operative Group<BR><BR>Maryam is Secretary of this women's group on Zanzibar. With a loan fromthe Ministry of Women and Children they have built a chicken farm and theysell 150 eggs a day. There are 16 women in the group and they all help withthe chickens and share in the profits. They also grow vegetables to selland have opened a small school to teach women to read and write. Their familiesare now much healthier and they can buy their children what they need forschool.<BR><BR>Pic. 7 Mwera Primary School, Zanzibar<BR><BR>Yusra, Feisal, Reziki and Ali are all aged 10 and they are in Standard 3at Mwera Primary School. They go to school from 7.15 until 12.50.  At schoolthey learn Swahili, the official language of Tanzania, maths, science, geography,religion, Arabic, and civics and they have just started to learn English.In the afternoon from 2pm to 4pm they go to Koranic school. They do notsee each other out of school as they live far apart. <BR><BR><a href="unicef_pix/nnud_8.jpg">Pic. 8</a> Gertrude and Rosalyne<BR><BR>Gertrude, aged 9 and her younger sister Rosalyne, aged 6, go to OlympioPrimary School in the capital of Tanzania, Dar es Salaam. The school isunusual because all the lessons are in English, not Swahili. Their parentsgo to a lot of trouble so they can go to this school because they do nothave classes at the same time. Rosalyne's lessons are from 7.30 am to 11am and Gertrude' lessons are from 11 am to 3 pm. Their parents have to buyall their books as well as their uniform.<BR><BR><a href="unicef_pix/nnud_9.jpg">Pic. 9</a> Produce<BR><BR>Some parts of Tanzania are very fertile. The pictures show the wide rangeof produce you can buy in the market in Mwanza, a big town in north eastTanzania. There are green leafy vegetables, tomatoes and peppers, rice,beans and lentils and spices like cloves. Tanzanians also use roots to maketraditional medicines. The staple foods are ugali, which is a type of porridgemade from maize or cassava flour and water, and rice.<BR><BR>Pic. 10 Transport<BR><BR>Most people in Tanzania travel by bus or bicycle. Roads are not tarmackedoutside the main towns. There are flights to several airports on Air Tanzania,and ferry boats on the large Lakes Victoria, Tanganyika and Nyasa. Busestravel long distances on bumpy roads which are very dusty in the dry seasonand often flooded in the wet season. In many parts of Tanzania you willsee disabled people on the streets in their especially adapted tricycles.<BR><BR>Pic. 11 Roads<BR><BR>There are very few good tarmacked roads in Tanzania. Most of the roads aredirt roads with many pot holes. November to May is the rainy season whenmany roads become very muddy or even flooded. Some roads get blocked byrocks and soil which are swept down hill by the heavy rain. While we maydislike the rain to Tanzanians it is a blessing because it helps the cropsgrow.<BR><BR>Pic. 12 Animals<BR><BR>Tanzania has many national parks, including the Serengeti and the NgorongoroCrater. In these game reserves wild animals roam freely and fairly safely.Tourists must keep to special roads so they don't disturb the animals. Tanzania'stourist industry is not as well developed as that of Kenya.<BR><BR>Pic. 13 Play<BR><BR>Children everywhere love to play. Many of the games they play are the samethe world over, like skipping and rolling a hoop. Some children make theirtoys out of whatever materials they can find. The rhymes the children singwhen they are skipping or playing singing games may sound different butwhen translated they are very similar to the ones that you play.<BR><BR>Pic. 14 People working<BR><BR>These photographs all show women going about their work in Tanzania. Asin many countries women do not have the same employment opportunities asmen, and in Tanzania women have often not had the same chance to go to school,although that is changing. Women often have to create their own ways ofmaking money, like the women's co-operative which has started an egg farmwith a loan from the government, helped by UNICEF.</font><BR><BR><HR>&copy;Copyright: UNICEF 1996 <HR><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif"WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom>Unicef Home Page</A><HR></BODY></HTML>
