<head>
<title> INDIA</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<font face="arial, helvetica">
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> INDIA</h2>

<a href="in-map.html"><b>Map of ACTIONAID's Programmes in India</b></a>
<p>

<hr><b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	950 million

<p>Population growth rate	1.8% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	122
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	78%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	50%

<p><hr><h3>Programme Overview</h3>

<p>ACTIONAID's first ever programme began in India in 1972. There were 88 sponsored children by the
end
of that first year, now there are nearly 40,000 and the programme is now ACTIONAID's largest, with
seven regional offices. 

<p>By the end of 1996, ACTIONAID aims to be working with 86,962 families in a total of 55 development
areas.  Most of ACTIONAID's projects in India are developed in partnership with local voluntary
organisations. They concentrate on health, education, agriculture and income generation initiatives,
working particularly with marginalised communities such as indigenous hill tribes in the south of the
country. ACTIONAID also focuses on helping people with disabilities, and their families, to increase
their
integration into society.

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in India</h3>
<b>ACTIONAID:</b>

<p><ul><li>supports initiatives in a rural area in the south of India through the Integrated Rural
Development Trust (IRDT), which covers 36 villages. All planning and implementation is done with the
sanghams - village associations. Projects have included a savings and credit programme, training in
income
generation skills such as diamond cutting, soap making, tailoring and carpentry, and agricultural
advice for
farmers.

<p><li>is working with more than 17,000 families with disabled members on projects that aim to help
disabled people live a more fulfilling life within the community. Initiatives include developing
creativity and
skills among disabled children, health awareness talks for families, improving sanitation facilities
in homes
and providing access to physiotherapy and medical treatment where necessary.

<p><li> is improving access to education for poor communities in remote rural areas. Low-cost schools
are
built in rural villages and we ensure that the curriculum is relevant and appropriate to the
children's needs.
ACTIONAID has brought out a series of work books and teachers' notes entitled Cock-a-Doodle-Doo.
Originally in Tamil, the series is now available in many regional languages.
</ul><hr>

<p><b><a href="../cause/coca1/thirst.html">To quench a thirst </a></b>
<p>

Communities in southern India are using very different methods to solve their crippling drought
problem.
Find out how ACTIONAID is helping them.
</font>

