<html>
<head>
<title> SOMALILAND</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> SOMALILAND</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/somalia.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=258 height=442 alt="Map of Somaliland"
align=left>
</p>
<hr><b>Key National Statistics (for Somalia)</b>

<p>Population	9.8 million

<p>Population growth rate	2.5% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	211
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	29%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	27%	

<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID originally began work in Somalia in 1980, supporting refugee and relief development
programmes, but was forced to withdraw for a year in 1991 when the security situation deteriorated. 

<p>In 1992, ACTIONAID re-established a programme in Sanaag Region in the self-declared Republic of
Somaliland. Work here is reaching approximately 20,000 people. The political situation continues to
be unpredictable in Somalia and Somaliland, with active sporadic fighting in some locations.
ACTIONAID is working closely with the clan groups in the region, helping to create a more secure
environment.
<br clear=all>
<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work In Somaliland:</h3>

<p><ul><li>ACTIONAID has been working with local communities helping to rebuild and repair following
the war. It has helped to improve country roads so trading can recommence, establish a sports club
for the young, clear rubbish from the streets and establish a tree nursery to replace trees lost in
the war.

<p><li>water supply is of primary concern in an area that has only 30cm rainfall per year. Since the
war, ACTIONAID has helped to rehabilitate wells in the region and install a new system for Erigavo
town serving 18,000 people.

<p><li>healthy animals are the key to survival for the nomadic, herding population of Somaliland.
ACTIONAID is training veterinary assistants and providing thousands of doses of affordable medicines
so herds can thrive.
</ul>
</font>

