<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>The Helplessness of Development Policy</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>The Helplessness of Development Policy:<br>An Assessment of Aid in the Modern World<p>
<I>Reinold E. Thiel</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 6, November-December 1996: pages 24-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>

<B>Development Policy is in a  crisis. Aid budgets are  shrinking
all over the world, and the  overall results
of North-South assistance are  disappointing. In view of other economic  factors influencing  development, such as  trade and private  investments, aid
threatens to be
assigned only a marginal  role in international economic  relations.</b>
<P>
Nobody should believe that the target of  spending 0.7 per cent
of GNP on  development cooperation will ever be  reached. Not
by Germany (which  reached 0.31 per cent in 1995) nor by all 
the industrial countries together  (averaging 0.27 per cent in
1995).  Chancellor Helmut Kohl was badly  advised to still promise
0.7 per cent at  the 1992 UN Conference on the  Environment and
Development in Rio de  Janeiro.
<P>
The average rate of the industrial  countries has fallen continuously
in  recent years: from 0.34 per cent (1992)  through 0.31 per
cent (1993) to 0.27 per  cent in 1995. You have to go back to
 1982 to find 0.38 per cent average. This  level is now a distant
dream. So how did  so unrealistic a goal as the 0.7 per cent 
target ever come about?
<P>
The idea of development aid came into  being after World War II
out of a feeling of  a general duty to the world's wellbeing 
and in an attempt to contain socialism. At  that time the aid
share of GNP grew  constantly and, in 1961, reached a  fabulous
0.61 per cent. The Pearson  Report which evaluated the first 20
years  of development aid for the World Bank  suggested committing
all industrial  countries to the 0.7 per cent goal. But  when
the General Assembiy of the United  Nations made it binding in
1970 the  actual rate had already dropped back to  0.3 per cent.
<P>
A few small countries still do achieve  the rate. In 1995 it was
Denmark (0.97  %), Sweden (0.89 %) Norway 0.87 %)  and The Netherlands
(0.80 %). France is  next with 0.55 per cent. That is due to its
 special interest in the former colonies  which receive most of
these allocations.  With 8.4 billion dollars in 1995, it was the
 second largest donor.
<P>
<B>Japan far ahead of other major  donors</B>
<P>
But the other big ones? The United  States (with 7.3 billion
dollars)  achieved a shabby 0.10 per cent in  1995. Japan, the
biggest global donor  with 14.5 billion dollars, managed to  allocate
0.28 percent. The USA has  announced further cuts. And Great 
Britain, just ahead of Japan with 0.29  per cent, but far behind
it in absolute  disbursements with 3.2 billion dollars,  seems
to have long forgotten its  former colonies.
<P>
Why are the funds for development aid  being cut more and more?
One of the reasons is, of course, that the old industrial  countries
are in a grave economic  structural crisis and have to save. 
Another reason are these countries' aid  activities for the formerly
socialist states.  The argument that aid to the Third World  should
not suffer because of this is  unrealistic  you can spend every
 deutschmark or dollar only once.  Germany has put up the biggest
amount  of money for Eastem Europe: 2.4 billion  dollars in 1993,
or 0.13 per cent of GNR  But the true dimensions only become 
apparent when you look at the transfers  of the Federal Republic
of Germany to its  own developing lands, those of the  former
GDR: around DM 150 billion  annually, 5 per cent of GNP.</B>
<P>
This figure makes clear how  inadequate the funds spent worldwide
 on development are. The amount the  Federal Republic spends on
its eastem  federal states to benefit 15 million  people is 40
per cent higher than the  entire development aid of all donor
 countries for all recipient countries and  their more than three
billion people.  Given such dimensions, what can  development
aid achieve?
<P>
This is the third and decisive reason  for the shrinking of
development aid - the  realisation that it has achieved hardly
 anything in three and a half development  decades. Even though
life expectancy  has risen and child mortality dropped,  which
may have been achieved by  continuous transfers from outside 
in  most cases no selfsustaining system  has come into being.
True, some  countries in East and Southeast Asia  have had spectacular
economic growth.  But the rest stayed poor. In Africa the  GNP
fell 10 per cent from 1970 to 1990.
<P>
<B>Need for near explanations</B>
<P>
In the 80s, the lost development  decade, it became obvious
to all  concerned that strategies had failed.  New explanations,
new development  concepts were demanded. The Asian  &quot;tiger&quot;
economies had developed, the  African countries had not  the one
thing  needed to be explained as much as the  other. The old theory
that world market  conditions (the socalled &quot;external  framework
conditions") were to blame no  longer held water if South Korea
and  Cameroon, countries of like size, in 1955  both had a per
capita GNP of about 200  dollars but South Korea has now  reached
8,000 dollars per capita while  Cameroon is stagnating on 820.
Both  had the same world market to contend  with.
<P>
The major new insight was that there  had to be driving or
braking forces inside  the countries, that there had to be  &quot;internal
framework conditions&quot; more  important than previously assumed.
It  can be shown with the &quot;little tigers&quot; of  East Asia.
They had industrialised,  closed their internal markets to imports
 (Japan is still in dispute with the USA  because of this) and
started export  offensives. The strategy had been  organised by
planning authorities which  copied the model of Japan's foreign
 trade ministry, MITI, and left it to the  private sector to implement
a  statecontolled market economy.
<P>
Why could the same not happen in  Cameroon or Ghana, which
had  systems of rule as authoritarian as  those of Korea or Taiwan?
The  explanation is incomplete if it explains  only how the development
happened but  not why.
<P>
In all &quot;newly industrialised countries&quot;  in Asia
there is a tradition of  Confucianism, a tradition of an  awareness
of responsibility and  success, of discipline, hierarchy, making
 sacrifices for family and future. Similarly  to the &quot;inner
asceticism&quot; of  Protestantism described for Europe by  Max
Weber, the German sociologist and  political economist, the Confucian
 asceticism leads to ostentatious  consumption being frowned upon,
to  profits being accumulated and  reinvested. That can be translated
into  an economic formula: a high savings  rate is the prerequisite
to economic  development.
<P>
<B>The new strategy: structural adjustment</B>
<P>
But the Western donors were not ready to learn from these experiences.
 Although here, too, the influence of  internal factors was now
rated higher in  the new explanation models, the strategy  derived
from this was different to the  Asian one. Since in most Westem
 industrial countries policies of  deregulation, state reduction
and market  dominance, based on neoliberal  economic doctrines,
were followed, this  approach was also supposed to help the  developing
countries. The successes of  the tiger economies, contrary to
all the  evidence, were reinterpreted as the  success of free
market economics.
<P>
In the mid-80s the World Bank and  International Monetary Fund
launched  their strategy of structural adjustment  programmes
aimed at reducing state  spending and at the same time  stimulating
economic development. The  means were dismissal of personnel 
from state employment, cancellation of  subsidies and privatisation
of  unproftable state enterprises, cutting  state budgets' deregulation
and  liberalisation of markets, creation of  investment incentives
for foreign capital.  But by and large these programmes  remained
ineffective. They only  addressed the symptoms and were  restricted
to the purely economic domain,  to budgets, finances and the market.
 With the same incapable general  administrations and the same
corrupt  power elites they could not make  improvements. The reform
approaches  had to become more political.
<P>
<B>Good governance - the  new catchword</B>
<P>
A new debate began under the  heading &quot;good governance&quot;.
The  strategy for the &quot;Fourth Development  Decade&quot; adopted
by the UN General  Assembly in 1990 called for greater  involvement
of all people in political  and economic life and respect for
 human rights. A June 1991 paper of  the World Bank names as the
most  important fields of reform the  accountability of government,
legal  security and transparency of state  decisions.
<P>
German development policy took part  in this discussion early
on. In July 1990  the scientific advisory council of the  development
ministry demanded that in  future &quot;stronger attention
be paid also to the political systems of our partner countries&quot;
and made some detailed suggestions on this. The ideas in the study
were developed further in the ministry.
<P>
In January 1991 Carl-Dieter Spranger took over the ministry, in
October he announced the &quot;new political criteria of German
development cooperation&quot;: 
<P>
<ol>
<li>Respect for human rights;
<li>Participation of the population in the political process;
<li>Assurance of legal security;
<li>Market-friendly economic order;
<li>Development orientation of state actions.</ol>
<P>
Since then German development cooperation has been oriented to
these criteria. Countries whose internal structures do not meet
them are to receive no more help in future. Countries wanting
to start the reforms are to receive German help to do so. Other
donor countries have laid down similar criteria.
<P>
That amounts to a fundamental change in development policy. If
one had in the past tried to teach farmers of a region modern
production methods, only to experience that the wrong farm price
policies of the partner government wiped out the results, today
one would sooner bank on a reform of agricultural policy. If in
the past one provided crafts people in the informal sector with
better tools, now one would try to liberalise the licensing policy
of the responsible industry ministry and at the same time build
up a banking system that also provides small loans to crafts people
enabling them to buy their own tools. In Ghana, for example, a
World Bank programme to reform the tax administration led to not
only wage eamers, but also the rich having to pay taxes, doubling
tax revenue in four years.
<P>
The introduction of administrative courts, the strengthening of
auditing authorities, the reorganisation of administrations but
also the support of selfadministering agencies and selfhelp organisations
belong with the measures now favoured. (That there are still the
old projects, too, is explained by the fact that one cannot just
break them off but that they have to run out slowly.)
<P>
<B>Fighting poverty and liberalisation</B>
<P>
Together with the introduction of the &quot;new criteria&quot;
the aims of German development policy were newly defined. Fighting
poverty rather than straightforward development was to be a stronger
focus of the entire development cooperation. The strategy to be
employed for this had been worked out in a long process: &quot;Fighting
Poverty by Help Towards Self-Help&quot;. Above all, this strategy
addresses the poor themselves. Their own initiatives in selfhelp
groups are to be supported and strengthened, their unused labour
to be productively employed. In addition to this &quot;target
group oriented&quot; component it is expressly emphasised, however,
that &quot;changes in poverty-causing societal structures&quot;
have to be striven for. With this second aspect the drive against
poverty fits into the discussion about the need for structural
changes, the discussion about &quot;good governance&quot;.
<P>
<B>World Bank adopts poverty reduction strategy</B>
<P>
The World Bank now also emphasised that fighting poverty needed
&quot;promotion of the productive use of a resource the poor have
in abundance, namely their labour&quot;. And in the World Development
Report for 1995 one reads that it was decisive for &quot;economic
policy to be oriented on a more comprehensive scale to the needs
of the poor. Fighting poverty is not primarily a task of projects
narrowly aimed at poverty....lt is a task for economic policy
as a whole.&quot; The strategy might be summarised in the formula
'labourintensive development'. This is aimed esspecially at the
informal sector with its many small enterprises in which capital
is rare but labour plentiful.
<P>
But with that, development policy stands alone. The policy
of global market liberalisation, which is at the same time the
mainstream of intemational economic policy, works in the opposite
direction. Worldwide free trade is supposed to lead to everyone
in the world being better off. That was the aim of the GATT negotiations
concluded in 1994. But even in the run up the OECD had waned than
the agreement would benefit the rich but harm the poor. For the
European Union OECD projected additional eamings, for Africa an
annual loss of 2.6 billion dollars.
<P>
It is not hard to predict what is going to happen. If the
small backyard enterprises in Third World countries could produce
free of bureaucratic restrictions, which is the aim of a deregulating
development policy, but if at the same time the intemational corporations
can throw their cheap products on to all markets free of tariff
barriers, which is the aim of a deregulating world trade policy,
the jobs only just created in the developing countries will very
quickly disappear again because they will not be able to stand
up to this competition. The technological unemployment we are
experiencing in the industrial countries with such depressing
consequences will spread to the poor countries of the Third World
before they have even had a chance to build up industries themselves.
Company profits will grow but the number of jobs will fall: jobless growth.
<P>
<B>Sustainable development</B>
<P>
All this without even mentioning so far the major concept that
turned up in development policy discussion in recent years: &quot;sustainable
development&quot;. In that respect development policy is probably
proving even more helpless.
<P>
Sustainability means not consuming more than will grow back,
not using up one's basic resources. A study group of the German
parliament tried to find out what consequences this has to have
for policies, but it did not cause them to be changed. The industrial
countries live and consume in a way that constantly increases
their consumption of the environment, with no regard to the principle
of sustainability. Everyone knows it but we are not able to leave
a path we have set out on, as if we were locked on to rails. So
how can we tell Third World countries to go a different way to
our own? All developing countries want to catch up in development
and that at the same time means catching up with the level of
environmental damage. All donors support it. One can read in any
newspaper that once as many cars per capita are running in China
or India as in our countries the earth's atmosphere and climate
will be ruined once and for all. But has one ever heard of development
policymakers having helped even one partner country to build a
transportation system compatible with the environment? The occasional
subway system is not enough. Everyone knows the answer. Volkswagen
and Mercedes are building car plants in the developing countries.
<P>
The summary is that development policy has learned a few things.
The strategies adopted today are better than ever before. But
we have to acknovledge at the same time that our superior concepts
are helpless against the currents of international trade and economic
policies. Here, too, the World Bank, as it almost always is, is
right: development policy, fighting poverty and sustainability
are &quot;tasks for economic policy as a whole&quot;. Economic
policy will not care about them. 
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on January 14, 1997<BR>
