<html>
<header>
<title>New Research on Civil Society</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<pre>

</pre>
<center><IMG SRC ="../images/handshke.jpg">
<h3>A New Solution? Investigating Northern Support to East European and Southern Civil Society<BR>
Outline of On-going Research at the North-South Institute</h3>
<H3>RESEARCH UPDATE FOUR: February 1997</H3>
For further Information, contact: Alison Van Rooy <a href="mailto:avanrooy@web.net">avanrooy@web.net</a><br>or visit the Web site of the North-South Institute: <a href="http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil" target="_top">http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil</a>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<A HREF="vanrooy.htm">Original Project Description</A>
<p>
This Research Update, the fourth in a series, is intended to
inform a network of colleagues interested in research on civil society.
Other updates, and further information, is available at:
<A HREF="http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil" target="_top">http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil</A>

<H3>FUNDING FOR NEXT PHASE!</H3>

We are pleased to announce the generous contribution of the International
Development Research Centre toward the next phase of the research.  The gift
of nearly $99,000 will generate the body of the research: theoretical
sections, case studies, and major recommendations, to be completed in June
1997.  Funding efforts continue to cover costs for production, translation
and launch, currently set for September 1997 in Budapest.  Interested
contributors are asked to contact avanrooy@web.net.


<H3>NEW RESEARCH UNDERWAY</H3>

<li>Democracy Center, USAID.*  A new study underway on civic advocacy
organizations commissioned by USAID has two overarching objectives: 1)
determining the "state-of-the-art" and "best practices" of other bilateral
donors, as well as international, US and indigenous civil society
organizations; and 2) determining the extent to which advocacy training
materials have been developed and used.  For further information, contact
Leslie Fox at LFOXWDCJOC@aol.com or: 4220, 43rd Street NW, Washington, DC,
20433 USA.	
<p>
<li>Hemispheric Partnership Initiative.*  A Canadian-Latin American
partnership has been struck to analyze and develop NGO and popular
organizations' policy regarding civil society and democratization in the
Americas.  The partnership aims to document and systematize its learning in
a form that will both enhance its members' efforts, and be shared with other
organizations engaged in working for social change.  For more information,
contact: Areli Carre_n, PRODEMO, Humboldt 46, Centro 62000, Cuernavaca,
Mor., MEXICO, tel (73) 14 07 78, fax (73) 18 29 74, email
areli@infosel.net.mx, ced@ laneta.apc.org.

<H3>MAKING THE MOST OF THEORY</H3>

The following table of contents outlines the main ideas we are tackling in
the research's theoretical chapters.  As the academic literature on civil
society becomes increasingly dense, we aim to approach theory in a way which
meets the needs of practitioners.
<p>
Civil Society as Idea 
<ul>	What is civil society? 
<ul>		History of the Idea: Nothing New but Very Much Changed<br>
		The New Analytical Hat Stand <br>
		What definition is used here?  What's in, what's out, why? </ul>
	How does it develop? 
<ul>		The Evolution of Civil Society?<br> 
		The Creation of Civil Society?</ul> 
<ul><p>
Civil Society and the Aid System 
<ul>	Why is the North involved with civil society in other parts of the world? 
	<ul>	Promoting Development<br> 
		Promoting Democracy<br> 
		Hidden Agendas?  The other reasons for donor interest in civil society </ul>
	What is the aid system doing to affect civil societies? 
<ul>		What official and voluntary aid channels are being used? <br>
		What is the nature of that support? <br>
		What other forces are working on civil society? </ul>
	What has been the impact on Northern support organizations? 
	<ul>	Is there a new reality for aid derived from the emphasis on civil
                society? <br>
		Does the aid system need civil society to stay in business? </ul>
	What Next? 
</ul></ul></ul>
<p>
<hr>
