<html>
<header>
<title>New Research on Civil Society</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<pre>

</pre>
<center><IMG SRC ="../images/handshke.jpg">
<h3>A New Solution? Investigating Northern Support to East European and Southern Civil Society<BR>
Outline of On-going Research at the North-South Institute</h3>

For further Information, contact: Alison Van Rooy <a href="mailto:avanrooy@web.net">avanrooy@web.net</a><br>or visit the Web site of the North-South Institute: <a href="http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil" target="_top">http://www.web.net/~nsi/civil</a>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<A HREF="vrooy4.htm">RESEARCH UPDATE FOUR: February 1997</A>
<p>
This note is meant to notify colleagues working in development research
about work-in-progress by The North-South Institute.  Here follows a brief
outline of the work; you may also wish to visit our website.
<p>
Comments, soit en francais ou en anglais, are welcome! We look forward to
learning more about your own work in this field.
<p>
Increasingly, Southern, East European and Northern researchers are writing
about the role of expanding civil societies.  For some Northern donors (both
official and non-governmental), the "discovery" of civil society has
promised a new solution to the enduring problems of development, and many
have devoted official development assistance dollars to a broad range of
civil society projects.  Yet questions remain whether this kind of
assistance is different from existing interventions, whether the process of
civil society growth is understood by donors attempting to intervene, and
whether the commitment to strengthening civil society is hence a genuine
change of approach.  
<p>
The North-South Institute is undertaking a two-year project to explore the
role of Northern governmental, multilateral, and non-governmental agencies
and foundations in supporting Southern and East European civil societies.
Assisted by a cross-disciplinary and international team, researchers will
present policy-relevant recommendations to agencies interested in improving
the effectiveness of foreign intervention in civil society.  The objectives
of the research are therefore to:
<ul>
<li>Generate New Knowledge and Analysis in a North-South-East Partnership
<li>Influence Official and NGO Policy
<li>Expand North-South-East Research and Policy Networks
</ul><p>
In order to meet these goals, the research program consists of several
components:
<ul>
Overview: What is, and Why Talk about, Civil Society?  The research will
produce for debate a state-of-the-art overview of current thinking and
practices underpinning foreign support to civil society and will link
Northern, Southern, and Eastern perspectives.  This overview will form the
first three chapters of the book.  (An initial discussion paper on these
themes was presented at a workshop on civil society research at the
Institute of Development Studies, Sussex, and at the first meeting of the
project research team in June 1996.  The paper is titled Civil Society: The
Development Solution? and is available on request).
<p>
Four Country Case Studies: Peru, Hungary, Kenya and Sri Lanka.  Four
country case studies have been commissioned from regional analysts to
explore the implications of official and non-official Northern support to
civil society in each country.  These analysts have designed a common
outline and method for the studies, which will contain an overview of the
formation of civil society in that country, reasons for change and current
trends, and will explore the extent of foreign intervention designed to
support its activities.  The emphasis will be on the process of sustaining
civil societies; not simply a accounting of organizational growth or
numbers.  Detailed chapter outlines are also available on request.
<p>
International Seminar.  The four case study authors, in addition to the
four-member advisory group, will join together at the completion of the
studies to present, analyze, and debate their findings.  Donors, funders,
academics, and civil society activists will be invited to attend the
seminar, tentatively scheduled for March 1997 at the University of Sussex.
Their debates will shape a series of specific policy recommendations which
will form the final chapter of the book.  An alternative proposal now being
explored is to host an initial meeting in England to refine conclusions, and
to hold a second meeting, possibly in Budapest in October 1996, to formally
present findings to the donor community for debate.
<p>
Active Communications Strategy.   An edited volume in French, English, and
Spanish, including overview, case studies, and seminar results will be
published by The North-South Institute in September 1997.  The book will be
the focus of an active communications strategy to encourage further debate,
both during research and after publication, and will include policy
meetings, articles, workshops, and an electronic conference site will soon to be moved to the Institute
homepage at <a href="http://www.web.net/~nsi" target="_top">www.web.net/~nsi</a>
</ul><p>
The research will build on existing substantive work on civil societies
carried out by The North-South Institute: Bridges of Hope? Canadian
Voluntary Agencies and the Third World; The Challenge of Democratic
Development: Sustaining Democratization in Developing Societies;
Democratization and Popular Participation in Africa; The Rocky Road to
Democracy: A Case Study of the Philippines; and Choosing the Right Policy
Levers: Drawing Lessons from the Government of Canada's Interventions in
South Africa.  This new project draws from this research base and looks to
funding from a broad community in order to further explore the policy
implications of donor support to Southern civil society.  
<p>
Further inquiries about the research can be made to the project coordinator,
<a href="mailto:avanrooy@web.net">Alison Van Rooy</a>.  Her recent work on civil society, ODA, and the role of
NGOs includes A Partial Promise: Canadian Support to Social Development in
the South (1995), presentations to parliamentary and non-governmental groups
about trends in NGO work, and The Altruistic Lobbyists: The Influence of
Non-Governmental Organizations on Development Policy in Canada and Britain
(D.Phil. 1994).  Her doctorate, funded by a Rhodes scholarship, was
supplemented by a research fellowship at the Department of Foreign Affairs
and International Trade where she wrote on improved practices for
consultation with civil society.  Trained in development studies at Trent
University, she won a number of awards for her work, including research and
evaluations of Canadian NGOs.  She was a Canada World Youth participant to
Sri Lanka, and has been involved as a development educator for young people.
<p>
<hr>
