<html><head><title>Planned Parenthood Challenges 1996/1</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img align=left hspace=3 src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo.gif"><h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i><br clear=left><hr><h1 align=center>Advocating change in Palestine</h1><h3 align=center>    by Philip Wolmuth</h3>    <img align=left border=1 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=220 height=138 src="p23.jpg"><br><b>With the Peace Process moving slowly on, albeit with anuncertain destination, the partial withdrawal of Israelitroops from the Occupied Territories, the establishment of aPalestinian Authority and the first Palestinian elections inJanuary 1996, this is a time of change and uncertainty in theWest Bank and Gaza Strip.</b><p><font size=2>Image: A panel from an exhibition which opened in PFPPA Jericho clinic in November 1995. The exhibition promotes sexual and reproductive health and explains key family planning concepts using stories and poems used in talks with local men.</font><p><hr width=71%><p>    The Palestinian Family Planning and Protection Association(PFPPA), which recently began implementation of a newstrategic plan, operates in a context in which the politicalsituation impinges on every aspect of life.  The problem ofyoung brides, for instance, grew during the <i>Intifada</i>, aschildren left school early, incomes fell, and a marrieddaughter meant one less mouth to feed.  In Gaza, life hasreturned to the streets with the withdrawal of Israelisoldiers, but border restrictions, which have drasticallyaffected the economy by preventing Gazans crossing into Israelto work, also recently prevented Lauren El-Issa, theJerusalem-based PFPPA Youth Programme Officer, from enteringthe Gaza Strip to oversee the programme for which she isresponsible.<p>    But despite the problems and uncertainties, a new sense ofoptimism is also discernible, particularly amongst the young. The schools and universities are full.  A degree of hostilityto family planning resulting from the highly polarized &quot;us&quot;and &quot;them&quot; situation of the Palestinian/Israeli conflict - andthe idea that the more of &quot;us&quot; there are, the better - seemsnow to be dissipating, reinforced by Palestinian Authoritysupport for PFPPA programmes.<h3>A new sense of purpose</h3><p>    The new PFPPA strategy, based on IPPF's <i>Vision 2000</i> StrategicPlan, is very much in tune with the new sense of purpose, andtakes its work well beyond the role of service provider.<p>    &quot;Our new women's programme is aimed at empowerment.  For thelast 30 years we have been talking to the woman - but thedecisions are not hers!  We must support her, but we must alsowork with the decision-makers - with men, with religiousleaders, with those in government and education.  Advocacy isa central part of all our new programmes.&quot;<p>    Speaking at the PFPPA Jerusalem office, Medical ServicesOfficer Khalida Saifi summarizes the new approach: &quot;On oneside we are preparing the services, and on the other side thepopulation&quot;.<p>    Development of the plan began with a round of branch meetingsin the West Bank and Gaza Strip in early 1995.  Followingthis, and with assistance from the Arab World Regional Office,the strategic plan was drawn up, with new programmes forwomen, youth, men, IEC and service provision all scheduled tostart in January 1996.<p>    In fact, many of the new programmes have been in operationfrom as early as September 1995.  In Gaza the Youth Programmeis well under way.  Eighteen to twenty-five year-olds havebeen recruited from student, community and sportsorganizations in five areas of the Strip to form discussiongroups.  Five members were selected from each of the 50-stronggroups for an intensive week-long training course held at thePFPPA offices in Gaza City in November.<p>    One of the lectures which formed part of this course was givenby Josef Joma, Agent at the Ministry of Religious Affairs inGaza.  The talk focussed on the mutual respect between husbandand wife which the Qur'an teaches, discussed the role offamily planning in the context of Muslim family life, andstimulated many questions from the floor, ranging from therights and wrongs of polygamy to the need for segregation ineducation (at the nearby Al-Azhar University male studentsattend classes in the morning, female students in theafternoon - an issue hotly debated in the run-up to studentcouncil elections in December).<p><h3>An enthusiastic response</h3><p>    Such a talk by a religious leader might have seemed surprisingnot so long ago, given the strongly conservative religiousculture of Gaza.  A youth group openly discussing relationsbetween the sexes, before and after marriage, is alsounexpected.  PFPPA staff, initially apprehensive about the newYouth and Women's Programmes plans to broaden discussion fromfamily planning to issues around women's empowerment andsexual and reproductive health, have been amazed by theenthusiastic response.<p>    In the same week that Josef Joma addressed the youth meetingin Gaza City, an IPPF-sponsored video on the problem of earlymarriage was shown to a mixed audience in the PFPPA offices inHalhul, on the outskirts of the West Bank town of Hebron.  Thediscussion which followed demonstrated clearly the need foradvocacy beyong the traditional constituency of FPA clients.<p>    The women in the audience immediately identified with thePalestinian women interviewed in the video - the woman with 12children who was married at 13 and had her first child a yearlater; the mother whose husband wants to marry off their 12-year-old daughter; the pressures from husbands and otherfamily members to produce as many children as possible.  Alsofamiliar was the impoverished father of 11 children who hadthought they would make him rich, and the elderly man whosephilosphy was simple: &quot;Whenever a husband comes along with hispocket full of money - give him the daughter!&quot;.<p>    Across the West Bank and Gaza the new strategy is stimulatingwide-ranging debate.  Village women are meeting to discussissues they have never discussed openly before; young peopleare asking questions they were afraid to ask; and the trainingof government and NGO health workers in sexual andreproductive health counselling is being started.<p>    At a recent meeting in the small hill village of Tkooi, closeto Bethlehem, for instance, a psychological counsellor led adiscussion on women's oppression, psycho-physiologicalproblems and stress at one of the fortnightly meetings in thevillage organized by Rida Istifan, a PFPPA field worker.  Atthe same time, women had gathered in the mosque of a nearbyvillage to hear a lawyer, brought in by the PFPPA, explainwomen's economic and property rights - rights of which manyhave been entirely unaware.<p>    Although only a few months into its three-year life, the newstrategy has received an enthusiastic welcome, with advocacy -&quot;preparing the population&quot; - playing a pivotal role.(ends)<p>   <i><b> Philip Wolmuth</b> is a British photographer and journalist whorecently visited Palestine and Jordan.</i> <hr><p>©Copyright IPPF<br><font size=-1>Picture: &copy;Philip Wolmuth/IPPF </font><hr><img align=left src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo2.gif"> <a href="index.html">PPC 1996/1 Contents</a><br><a href="../index.html">IPPF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
</DOC>
