<html>
<header>
<title>Democratising Administrative Reform in Benin, Burkina Faso, and Mali</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Democratising Administrative Reform in Benin, Burkina Faso, and Mali</h3>
by <i>Wamara Fofana</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 3(1) August 1995: pages 7-8</i>
<p>
</center>
<hr>
From independence, the countries of Francophone Africa have emphasised the need to
establish effective structures of state administration to take over from their ex-colonial
administrations. This process was necessarily very rapid and to some extent can be judged
with hindsight to have become excessive and in many respects inefficient. Thus, during the
l970's steps were taken with the help of ILO and UNDP to improve the general quality,
training, organisation and management of administration both at central and local levels of
government.
<p>
These efforts were largely superceded during the l980's by the dominant involvement of the
IMF and the World Bank. This involvement was exercised through their support for structural
adjustment programmes. Important parts of these programmes were measures to reduce the
total budgetary cost of the civil service primarily through major reductions in the numbers
employed. Voluntary and targeted redundancies, abolition of employment irregularities, and
pay freezes, were introduced, together with the creation of salary administration departments.
The almost single-minded concentration on the reduction in the budgetary cost of civil
servants left little room to meet local conditions and social aspects of the adjustment process.
<p>
However, out of a situation in which governments have been caught between the Bretton
Woods institutions which largely set the economic and structural adjustment policy agenda
and the popular masses who have suffered from these policies, has arisen an environment of
both greater economic liberalisation and greater political democratisation. 
As a consequence, the three countries jointly accepted the need to achieve three broad
preconditions for the successful modernisation of their public administrations:
<p>
First, ensuring the commitment of the government to civil service reform with the
concomitant redefinition of the role of external agencies; second, ensuring the commitment
of the civil servants themselves to reform; and, third, ensuring the participation of civil society
in the process of reform.
<p>
<h3>Roles of External Agencies</h3>

In all three countries, external agencies have played far too prominent a role in previous
attempts at civil service reform to give any expectation that these reform programmes could
be successfully implemented. They have resulted in a uniform and simplified model of reform
being introduced based on the prejudices of international experts and in which the uniqueness
of each country's historical and socio-cultural circumstances are ignored. Moreover, the
external assistance to civil service reform has been highly costly and has continued for
inordinately long periods especially when set against the results achieved (e.g. the UNDP
project in Mali lasted from l970 to l991). This poor cost-benefit ratio has been aggravated by
the involvement of several external agencies in each country and the consequent growth of
a multiplicity of coordinating bodies as in Burkina Faso where four coordination structures
have been established for just one single project. Moreover, in recent years under structural
adjustment programmes, the exclusive objective of reducing staff numbers and the total wage
bill has resulted in the erosion of support for reform by officials and their union
representatives. In Benin, for instance, the term administrative reform is now identified with
redundancy programmes.
<p>
There is no hope for civil service reform being effectively introduced and sustained unless,
to begin with, there is an assertion of political will by the government. Both President Soglo
in Benin during his election campaign and President Compaor&#233; in Burkina Faso at the
UN Social Summit stressed the importance of administrative reform in their countries. The
Prime Minister of Mali has done likewise and all three governments have gone on to elaborate
on the need for reform and the priorities within their reform programmes.
<p>
Furthermore, all three governments have recognised that the assertion of the political will for
reform must be translated into concrete acts. Their economic policies have emphasised
limitations of state expenditures, and the modification in favour of priority sectors of the
economy. In addition, organisational actions have been taken to reflect the importance of
administrative reform. In Benin and Burkina Faso, for instance, a minister has been put in
charge of Administrative Reform or Civil Service Modernisation. It has also been recognised
that reform requires that all ministers should recognise their responsibility within their
departments for designing and implementing reform programmes.
<p>
<h3>Mobilisation of Civil Servants</h3>

Experience shows that civil service reform cannot be undertaken without the active
participation and cooperation of the civil servants themselves. This can be achieved through
joint statutory bodies such as the Advisory Board for the Civil Service. These arrangements
permit officials to be represented on management bodies by elected representatives in an
environment of equality. Of course, these arrangements can cut both ways and 'collusion'
between staff representatives and management may develop. This discredits the process and
may lead, as in Mali, to the radicalisation of civil servants and their rejection in 1991 of
agreements on a revised civil service organisational framework.
<p>
Elaborate institutional arrangements have been established in Burkina Faso to systematise and
strengthen the participation process. A Management Council of departmental directors with
staff representation has been established in each Central Directorate of the External
Departments and is responsible for the planning and monitoring of the execution of measures
to enhance the management of human, material and financial resources within the Directorate.
Similarly, an Advisory Board of the Ministerial Sectors has been established in each ministry
for reviewing sectoral policies and reviewing staff management and the general performance
of the Department. Even more ambitious is the introduction of an annual Public
Administration Conference for providing continuous evaluation of administrative action in
response to the "demands of a modernised civil service which is closer to the popular masses
and resolutely oriented towards progress" (the Prime Minister). The objective of the annual
conference is to bring together policy-makers and technocrats. All of these institutional
initiatives in Burkina Faso have been designed to ensure that officials feel that the problems
of their department and their ministry concern them. The tentative judgement is that they are
proving to be successful in this objective. 
<p>
The upgrading of civil service expertise is recognised to be of central importance for
achieving the objectives of reform programmes. Once again Burkina Faso provides a good
example of initiatives which have been taken in this regard. The second annual Administration
Conference held in January of this year recommended that a Working Committee be set up
to produce proposals for achieving this upgrading including the establishment of a National
Centre for the Promotion of National Expertise. It also recommended that proposals be drafted
which would provide greater incentives for officials to improve their technical capacities
through attendance at scientific conferences, preparation of papers for publication, and greater
involvement in the preparation, execution and evaluation of projects.
<p>
At the regional level, in November 1994, heads of civil service departments from twenty
countries met as the African Civil Service Observatory (OFPA) and launched an initiative for
the creation of an African Civil Service Network. Its aim is to coordinate the action of
national networks of practitioners, researchers, trainers and independent consultants. In future
these will include expatriate experts thereby creating a think-tank on civil service reform.
<p>
<h3>Participation by Civil Society</h3>

Socio-professional associations and other non-governmental organisations are growing in
number and in influence in all three countries. This is a sign of the rebirth of civil society as
a necessary counterweight to government as a pillar of a democratic society. Their members
have an interest in ensuring that the civil service provides an efficient structure of state
activities within which they themselves can operate. It is, therefore, important that
governments both provides them with better information about civil service activities and
mobilises them whenever they can help to improve civil service efficiency.
<p>
These objectives can be achieved through the establishment of permanent machinery of
consultation and through mechanisms designed for specific purposes. For instance, in order
to generate this partnership, Burkina Faso has collaborated with the cinema industry to
produce films which feature the practices and behaviour of civil servants. One film was
awarded a prize at this year's African film festival. Similarly in Benin, the Friedrich Ebert
Foundation has collaborated with the national television industry, to produce sketches for the
government which expose the attitudes of civil servants with respect to users and inviting
them to mend their ways. Also in Benin artists were invited to produce posters for decorating
office walls. 
<p>
Initiatives such as these need to be reinforced by, for instance, regular opinion polls and the
availability of mechanisms through which the users of government services can make their
opinions known to government. Moreover, the membership of government advisory bodies
needs to be broadened to include many more professional and experienced people from the
private and non-governmental sectors. In Mali, for instance, a 1992 survey of 164 advisory
bodies confirmed that "there was an over-representation of civil servants, an under-
representation of qualified persons from the private sector, and a near absence of
representation from associations." Since then a Committee on Civil Service Modernisation has
been established on which, in addition to administrative officers and unions, there are
representatives from associations of civil service users.
<p>
Special one-off efforts have also been made to mobilise the capacities and interests of civil
society. Thus, in l994 the government organised a four-day workshop to prepare the ground
for an 'institutional development plan.' The workshop included not only government officers,
but members of the legal profession, businessmen, independent consultants and representatives
of Mali's development partners. Similarly, last year Benin also established a National
Committee on Administrative Reform which included not only political and administrative
representatives, but also resource persons from outside of government and user representatives.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

The raison d'&ecirc;tre for all these institutional and procedural arrangements is the
increasing recognition by the three governments and, I believe, more generally in Africa, that
the actors and the stakeholders in civil society must all be seen as active and essential
participants in programmes of civil service reform. But this, in its turn, reflects a growing
recognition that civil service reform must be addressed as a long-term and continuous process
and not as a problem which can be addressed by quick-fixes particularly when these are
imposed by external agencies who fail to acknowledge or to appreciate the unique socio-
political-economic characteristics of each country.
<p>
