<DOCHDR>
http://www.ecdpm.org:80/euforic/dpmn/951mk_gb.htm 193.128.6.150 19970213143245 text/html 15164
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Thu, 13 Feb 1997 14:32:24 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Tue, 26 Nov 1996 08:13:18 GMT
Content-length: 14989
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>Civil Service Reform: A Commonwealth Perspective
</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Civil Service Reform: A Commonwealth Perspective</h3>
by <i>Mohan Kaul</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 3(1) August 1995: pages 4-6</i>
</center>
<hr>
The principles of democratic development and good governance have been reiterated on several
occasions by the Commonwealth Heads of Government. A sound and accountable administration
has been identified as of key importance for achieving these objectives. To this end the
Commonwealth Secretariat's Management and Training Services Division has been actively
engaged in working with member governments.
<p>
Despite the fact that all countries have had to confront common global changes - political, social,
economic, technological and environmental - our work with governments has shown that,
notwithstanding their many common elements, civil service reform programmes are very diverse.
Their diversity has arisen largely from the political evolution of the different countries. But,
cutting across this diversity, there has been in almost all Commonwealth countries, a
reassessment of the role of government in the planning and management of economic and social
policies and an upsurge in liberal-market economic policies. This has, of course, had a major
impact on the conception of the role of the civil service. It is now seen as less of a 'doer' and
more of a 'facilitator' of economic activity. 
<p>
<h3>Common Themes and Strategies in Reform Programmes</h3>

The basis for reforms across Commonwealth countries have derived from a set of common
themes. Seven elements can be identified: 
<p>
<h4>Policy Development and Coordination</h4>

The lack of effective structures to mobilise policy analytical skills, rather than the actual absence
or shortage of these skills, has been identified as a key weakness within the public service in
many developing and developed countries.
<p>
In some countries this has been addressed by strengthening offices of President/Prime
Minister/Cabinet through the establishment of policy units (United Kingdom, Jamaica, Australia,
New Zealand, Zambia). In other countries inter-ministerial committees and special committees
of secretaries and task forces have been set up for special policy issues (Zambia, Malaysia).
National forums involving private and public sectors have been established in other countries
(Malaysia - Malaysia Inc.; Ghana - National Renewal Programme). Some countries have also
facilitated the setting up of independent policy analysis institutions.
<p>
<h4>Policy Implementation</h4>

A number of approaches are being adopted by developed and developing countries alike to 're-engineer' the structural relationships between policy formulation and implementation by
distancing the responsibility for implementation away from a strengthened policy core at the
centre of the machinery of government.
<p>
The establishment of statutory boards in Singapore, executive agencies in the United Kingdom,
and the experience of corporatisation in Australia, have allowed a clear delineation between the
functions of policy formulation and policy implementation. In this way, areas of relative freedom
from bureaucratic constraint have been created in which a more business-like climate can be
generated. Establishing an operational unit around a clearly demarcated set of functions, allows
the development of operational goals, uniting staff with a clearer sense of mission.
<p>
In the Commonwealth developing countries in particular, many governments are also devolving
responsibilities to territorial (e.g. regional) levels. Zimbabwe is decentralising responsibility to
local government in areas of health, education and social service welfare. Nigeria has created
federal-state advisory and coordinating councils and Sri Lanka has established elected provincial
councils with certain powers.
<p>
Reforms in the New Zealand education sector illustrate the principle of decentralisation. The
intent of the reforms is to abolish the Department of Education which had previously dominated
both policy-making and the delivery of education services.
<p>
<h4>Managing Human Resources</h4>

Improved human resource management systems in the public service are required to encourage
and reward team and individual performance. Increasing departmental and agency autonomy
allows for innovations in producing, measuring and rewarding individual performance. This
greater autonomy, however, has to be undertaken while maintaining the traditional civil service
standards of integrity, merit and professionalism. This is recognised as a critical issue in South
Africa where there is concern that affirmative action programmes to ensure wider employment
of under-represented groups do not weaken these standards.
<p>
Some governments are successfully experimenting with flexible working conditions (Australia,
New Zealand); moving collective bargaining from the entire public service to the workplace
(Australia, United Kingdom); and the application of private sector law to the public sector (New
Zealand). 
<p>
Some of the most successful Asian economies emphasise the importance of recruiting talented
people and improving their skills through constant training. Hong Kong and Singapore carry out
aggressive recruitment at entry level, entice high-flyers for further training, and generally pay
salaries comparable with the private sector. Singapore has maintained a systematic focus on
efficiency as the sole criterion for retaining or retiring senior civil servants, with seniority no
longer the basis for promotion. Many of Singapore's permanent secretaries are comparatively
young. An instructive example of current developments in this field is provided by the Malaysian
government's aim to establish key national institutions capable of providing highly targeted
training to strategic personnel.
<p>
Imaginative training initiatives have also been initiated in a number of countries. In Mauritius
and the United Kingdom training is being tailored to rank, and in Singapore, Ghana, Australia
and Trinidad and Tobago, customer service training for staff has been introduced.
In the Canadian public service, staff training and development is given high priority with close
attention paid to its cost-effectiveness.
<p>
Efforts to 'right-size' the civil service are spurred by the need to curb growth in public
expenditure and to ensure a lean and effective service. To this end Malaysia established a
Steering Committee on Reduction in Size of the Public Service to consider changes to the
administrative system, institutions, posts and personnel. A major component of the Civil Service
Reform Programme in Zimbabwe is the reduction of its size.
<p>
<h4>Organisational Culture</h4>

An increasing recognition is apparent of the importance of developing a customer- orientation,
clarifying public service accountability, developing a better interface with the public, introducing
quality management approaches and developing a public sector ethos. These objectives require
the creation of a working culture based on quality, performance and transparency. Reforms are
aimed at developing the organisational culture to manifest itself in stronger employee
involvement, rewards for team work and individual perfection and consultation with clients and
users. Public sector values are being formalised in codes of ethics within government.
<p>
Singapore was the first civil service to introduce work improvement teams (WITS). These were
developed from the quality control circles employed by successful and innovative private sector
companies to allow groups of staff from varying levels to openly discuss obstacles to quality and
to devise practical solutions for service improvement. The Botswana Government introduced a
productivity and quality improvement programme in l993 by creating WITS within various
institutions and departments. The Malaysian programme to enhance positive attitudes provides
a good example of a practical approach to the establishment of appropriate values within an
entrepreneurial public sector.
<p>
<h4>Commercialisation and Developing Partnerships with Private Sector and NGO's</h4>

Civil service reform has been greatly influenced by the questioning of the role of government
in providing services. Reviews of government functions have asked whether a task should be
done at all, whether it should be done by government directly, by contractors paid by
government, or by the private sector. 
<p>
The United Kingdom Treasury has produced detailed guidance on market-testing for use by
departments with each department having to identify candidates for testing. Contracting-out has
been well-tested within government.
<p>
Although specialist services have always been purchased from the private and NGO sectors, it
is the development of market-testing techniques which is providing a strategy to assess the
ability of the market to provide goods or services historically considered to be at the core of
government. At the same time there is a need to avoid disadvantaging the competitive position
of government entities. In this respect, the Australian State of New South Wales has taken steps
to ensure a level playing field for the public sector.
<p>
In Trinidad and Tobago, departments have been asked to determine whether a service might be
more effectively provided by an external agency. Services already contracted out include
maintenance services for new police stations, security services, and mail delivery between Piarco
Airport and the General Post Office.
<p>
The development of partnerships with NGO's and the private sector has emerged as a key
element in implementing some development policies and programmes. For instance, the
Bangladesh government is working successfully with the GRAMEEN Bank to develop
programmes that target benefits to poor sectors of society. India has also had successful
experience with the NGO role in implementing education and rural development programmes.
<p><h4>Financial Planning and Control Systems</h4>

Major structural and institutional reforms have taken place in the area of financial management,
making it more performance and output oriented. Other developments in this area include the
provision of efficiency dividends to departments (United Kingdom, Australia), payments by
departments for internal government services (Australia), and 3-year forward plan estimates
(Malta, Australia).
<p>
The financial management reforms in New Zealand have illustrated most strongly the
significance of adopting appropriate accountancy methods. Accrual accounting supplements cash
accounting systems to ensure that the financial information available to management is current
and provides meaningful analysis of resource usage within a department. 
<p>
Capital charging ensures that the opportunity costs of tying up capital within departments are
fully captured. In fact capital charging is to be found more widely (e.g. United Kingdom) and
reflects the growing concern to ensure that fixed assets are fully utilised and regarded as
investments requiring careful husbandry. The purpose of these financial procedures is to
introduce full-cost pricing and market discipline where government services are to become fully
contestable, thereby encouraging greater efficiency and economy.
<p>
<h4>Information Technology</h4>

Information technology has been included as one of the key strategies for public service reforms.
It is now seen as an essential facilitator of service improvement particularly when governments
world-wide are facing an increasing trend towards knowledge-based production and the
communications revolution. Expenditure by governments on computers and management
information systems have risen rapidly in many countries and now represent major items in their
budgets.
<p>
Significant automation programmes have been implemented in Australia, Singapore, United
Kingdom, Malaysia, Malta, and Mauritius. Revenue collection, financial management and inter-departmental communications have benefited particularly from these programmes. Information
technology has also been used to provide a better interface with customers by developing one-stop/non-stop service centres and public information systems in Malaysia. 
<p>
Many governments have developed policy statements on the unfolding use of computers and
information technology (e.g. Canada) and have established units within government to promote
their use (Singapore, Malaysia, Malta, United Kingdom).
<p>
<h3>Conclusions</h3>

Reducing the size and changing the role of government while remaining effective and efficient
in meeting the complex challenges which these objectives involve, has been the overriding
purpose of public service reforms in Commonwealth countries. But while the broad objectives
in each country are similar, no unique solution or approach has emerged as a 'model' to be
universally adopted. Moreover, there are as many lessons to be learned from the successful
experiences of the developing countries as from those of developed countries. Each country
needs to identify its priorities according to the local circumstances, drawing upon the mix of
experiences from both developed and developing countries. 
<p>
In short, countries have to develop local solutions to global challenges. Moreover, success
depends on an incremental approach; a step-by-step process within the framework of a clear
long-term vision. 
<p>
There must also be a recognition that people are at the heart of public service and therefore that
managing human resources must be at the centre of civil service reform programmes -- not
technology, not market forces. But while people are at the heart of change and its architects and
beneficiaries, they can also be the losers and therefore the opponents of change. Thus, the
implementation of reforms is a very sensitive and difficult task. In this context it is important that
successful individuals who understand and support change should be involved in the reform
process. Governments need to empower those who are working for change. 
<p>
Finally, the civil service must not only be part of the process of international and national change
which is taking place. The civil service must be at the forefront of the process -- guiding,
initiating, innovating and managing change.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <i>Updated on February 20, 1996</i><p>
