<HEAD>
<TITLE>Liaison News, January 1997</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/ngdoc.gif" height=120> 
<H3>Liaison News: <BR>
NGO news on North-South action in the EU<BR>
No. 23, December 1996-January 1997</H3>
<H3>Forum on ethics in humanitarian action, Dublin, 9 and 10 December 1996</H3>
</CENTER><HR>
<P>
<I>What are the ethics of humanitarian assistance? That was the question occupying the minds of leaders of Europe's main humanitarian emergency NGOs in a debate with top-level scientific experts, politicians and institutional 
decision-makers like European Humanitarian Affairs 
Commissioner Emma Bonino, Ireland's Development Minister 
Joan Burton, the Director of ECHO (European Community Humanitarian Office) 
Santiago Gomez Reino, the Chairperson of the 
Liaison Committee of Development NGOs to the EU, Agostinho Jardim 
Gon&ccedil;alves, and VOICE Chairperson Luc Heymans.</I>
<p>
The Forum was scheduled some time ago, but the current crisis in the 
Great Lakes Region added to the topicality of the issues addressed, including:
<ul>
<li>what are the fundamental underlying aims and values of 
humanitarian intervention?
<li>how do NGOs preserve their neutrality in conflict situations?
<li>are NGOs really neutral and even-handed, or is it all a myth?
<li>which individuals and institutions should be backed and which 
opposed in a conflict situation? 
<li>how can humanitarian action be ring-fenced from foreign policy pressures?
</ul>
<P>
The Forum was jointly organized by ECHO (European Commission) 
and VOICE, the specialized network of 70 relief NGOs operating within 
the NGDO-EU Liaison Committee.
<P>
This joint Forum also showed the importance of NGOs' role in the 
EU's humanitarian actions. In 1976, some 95% of emergency assistance was 
delivered through governments; by 1990, that figure had fallen to just 6%.
<P>
Selected extracts from some of the many speeches are cited below:
<P>
The Irish Development Cooperation Minister, Joan BURTON, stressed 
that NGOs had to carry their message to governments and the EU, saying that:
<P>
&quot;* it is critically important that humanitarian agencies, donors and 
recipients can agree and reaffirm the core values of humanitarian action, namely to 
prevent and relive the suffering of victims of conflicts or natural disasters;
<p>
* I remain convinced of the enduring relevance of the principles of 
independence, neutrality and impartiality in the post-Cold War context;
<P>
* dissemination of these values in donor and recipient countries is 
critical to ensuring that public support for humanitarian NGOs on broader 
political and social issues does not become confused in the public mind with 
independent, impartial humanitarian work in the field.&quot;
<P>
Santiago GOMEZ REINO rapidly reviewed his achievements as the 
founding Director of ECHO in what was also something of a swan song for him. 
He is moving from ECHO in January 1997 for promotion to the European 
Commission's DGIB as Deputy Director General, responsible for external 
relations with the countries of the Southern Mediterranean, 
the Middle East, Latin America and Asia.
<P>
Agostinho JARDIM GONCALVES, Chairperson of the NGDO-EU 
Liaison Committee, recalled the achievements of the Call of the December 1995 
Madrid Humanitarian Summit and commented on the strengthening of the 
relations between the Liaison Committee and VOICE on the one hand, 
and between VOICE and ECHO on the other.
<P>
Justin KILCULLEN, Director of the NGO Trocaire and leader of the 
Irish platform of NGOs, warned that NGOs risked losing their independence 
by being mainly officially-funded. He stressed that &quot;emergency and 
development&quot; aspects were closely intertwined.
<P>
Jacques LEBAS, a doctor and course tutor of the &quot;health and 
humanitarian action&quot; course at the University of 
Paris VI, listed five guiding principles of humanitarian action: 
even-handedness, universality, independence, ability 
and witness.
<P>
He said that: &quot;even-handedness for humanitarian organizations also 
means not taking policy stances on government policy or the activities of 
warring factions in the field. (....)
<P>
Humanitarian organizations increasingly tend to discard neutrality in 
the name of morality. Neutrality is often subsumed during conflicts in the 
dictates of State sovereignty and may make assistance and relief 
dependent on the goodwill of the combatants, factions or those in 
effective control&quot;.
<P>
On the principle of universality, &quot;humanitarian relief is also going 
beyond the national framework, and challenging the sovereignty of States: the 
`sans fronti&egrave;res' movement has made interference in the affairs of States one 
of the weapons in its armoury&quot;. The media-driven global village in which 
we live &quot;exhorts us all to act, intervene, testify everywhere&quot;.
<P>
The principle of independence is &quot;in fact beset by financial 
constraints, those of cooperation with States or 
international organizations, and cooperation with the media&quot;.
<P>
&quot;Ability&quot; means constituting an effective code of conduct in 
humanitarian action.
<P>
Finally, humanitarian action today also has a duty to bear witness which 
challenges &quot;any relief worker confronted with a victim reduced to silence 
and denied humanity&quot;. He concluded that:  
<P>
&quot;emergency situations are too often used as an excuse for disregarding 
the feelings of first-line victims, as if emergency conditions warrant 
everything and sometimes anything&quot;.
<P>
Fernando NOBRE, a doctor and leader of the Portuguese NGO AMI, 
sounded a warning note: &quot;After more than 20 years working in the 
humanitarian field, I am distressed by NGOs' loss of idealism. We have become too 
professional, too pragmatic, and too purely political&quot;. 
<P>
He said that humanitarian NGOs were in thrall to the media, which had 
created competition between NGOs with their banners and logos swarming 
into refugee camps and crisis-hit regions.
<P>
On day two, European Humanitarian Affairs (and fisheries and 
consumer protection) Commissioner Emma BONINO gave her 
eagerly-awaited talk to NGOs in the no-nonsense 
terms we have come to expect from her:
<P>
&quot;Should humanitarian organizations police and mete out justice in 
refugee camps? No, they do not have the means and it is not their role. They must 
be mindful of their limits. Our identity must be independent of foreign 
policy. We must communicate with public opinion. But should not gender and 
human rights issues also be part of humanitarian action? Should there be a separation between the humanitarian, political and military roles?&quot; She 
concluded &quot;You may not be able to solve all the problems, but you can be 
proud of what you do. Without you, the problems would be worse&quot;.
<P>
During the ensuing discussion, Pierre Laurent (M&eacute;decins du Monde, 
France) condemned the lack of humanitarian law, given that the Geneva 
Conventions no longer matched the realities of today's world. Emma 
BONINO agreed that there were lacunas in the law that should be 
made good.
<P>
Another signal contribution came from Mikael BARFOD, a senior ECHO 
official, who cautioned that &quot;humanitarian aid had to be looked at as 
inseparable from development questions&quot;. 
&quot;But humanitarian aid will suffer if development assistance is relegated to 
second place, if it fails to reduce susceptibility to crises and if humanitarian 
aid is not followed by development assistance&quot;.
<P>
&quot;Our ethic in humanitarian aid is a matter of development and the 
relations between poor and rich countries&quot;.
<P>
The Dublin forum was an important milestone in a process of discussion because, as VOICE Chairperson Luc HEYMANS stressed: &quot;after so many rewarding exchanges, all participants will be going back to their NGO as catalysts to advance the debate on the ethical aspects of humanitarian action&quot;. A second Forum may be held in 1997.
<P>
<P>
