<html>
<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Child Sex Tourism</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b><center><h1>Legislation against Child Sex Tourism</h1></center>


<h2>Sex tourism Bill blocked by British Government</h2>








<b>A Bill to outlaw 'sex tourism' - the sexual exploitation of children abroad - has been blocked by the British Government.  <p>
The British Home Secretary, Michael Howard, claimed that a law making tourists liable for child abuse committed in other countries ran counter to Britain's legal system.
</b><p>
<br clear=left>
<font size=-1><i>©Copyright: <b>Ahmed Jamal.</b> 
 'Beach Boys of Sri Lanka',<br>
Highly Commended in the <a href="../owbt/owbt_awards94.html#beachboys">One World Broadcasting Trust Awards 1994.</a></i></font>
<p>

<p>

Michael Howard, the British Home Secretary, told campaigners that since the courts require witnesses to give evidence in person, and the British police have no powers to investigate crimes in other countries, the Bill - introduced by the peer Lord Hylton in the Lords - was "seriously flawed".<p>

However, Jo Bindman, speaking to <b>OneWorld Online</b> from the End Child Prostitution in Asian Tourism (ECPAT) campaign group, argued that legal technicalities had not hindered the process in other countries.  Australia and New Zealand, whose legal systems share many common features with Britain, have recently passed anti-sex tourism laws.  Last month in Sweden, a man was given a 3-month prison sentence for having sex with a 13-year-old boy in Thailand.<p>

Pressure from Members of Parliament, campaign groups and the public seems to be forcing the Government to change its attitude to the issue.  In response to criticism of his intransigence, Michael Howard is now planning to introduce legislation targeting sex tour operators - rather than individuals.<p>

The Government hopes a law against sex tour organisers would help the fight against the sexual exploitation of children abroad.  However, Bindman claims that many pedophiles, who do not use organised sex tours, will escape the new law.  ECPAT believes that at least a million children in Asia are being sexually abused by tourists - and that 12% of those tourists came from Britain.<p>

<p>
<a name="childprostitution">
<p>

<h2>UK Government measures are inadequate to protect overseas children</h2>
 
<i>Based on information provided by the <b>Coalition on Child Prostitution and Tourism. </b></i>
<hr width=80%>

The Coalition on Child Prostitution and Tourism, a coalition of 5 major UK charities, welcomes today's announcement by Michael Howard of an urgent review of legislation which could be used to prosecute people who arrange or plan to take organised tours overseas to sexually exploit children.
<p>


Anne Badger, Campaign Co-ordinator of the Coalition, said after the announcement, 'We welcome this review but are concerned that it will not go far enough.'
<p>

The Government's proposals to amend the laws on Conspiracy and Incitement still do not permit the prosecution of British citizens for the offence of sexually abusing children overseas, but only for the offence of conspiracy or incitement while in the UK. meanwhile the many abusers who do not use organise sex tours escape without penalty under this law.
<p>

Michael Alison, the Conservative MP who raised the issue in the Commons today said, 'It is plain that the government is contemplating legislation and is willing and able to do so if practicalities permit.'
<p>

Llin Golding, Shadow Minister for Children and the Family, commented, "The failure today of the Government to accept the need for legislation to allow for the prosecution of those tourists on their return to the UK, as laid out in Lord Hylton's Bill, is deeply disappointing."
<p>

The Coalition support's Lord Hylton's Sexual Offences (amendment) Bill which was due to have its second reading in the Commons. This Bill, which would enable the prosecution at home of any British citizen who commits a sexual offence against a child abroad, will now be opposed by the Government this Friday, ensuring its failure.
<p>

Laws permitting extra-terrestrial jurisdiction have already been passed in most major tourist-sending countries, including Australia and New Zealand which have legal systems similar to that of the UK. Sweden successfully prosecuted one of its citizens under such legislation on 22 June this year.
<p>

the Coalition believes that the Swedish case clearly demonstrates that extra-terrestrial legislation is viable and calls on the Government to include this in its proposals to combat this modern form of slavery in next session's Criminal Justice Bill.
<p>

For more details or to arrange an interview with Anne Badger, Campaign Co-ordinator for the Coalition, or other Coalition staff, please call:
<p>

+44-(0)171-924 9555 Anne Badger or +44-(0)171-620 0713 Eileen Maybin daytime
<p>
<p>

<a name="howard">
<p>

<h2>Statement from Michael Howard, the British Home Secretary</h2>

"The Government shares the abhorrence felt by the vast majority of people about the sexual exploitation abroad of young children.  The introduction, by Lord Hylton, of his Sexual Offences (Amendment) Bill has done much to highlight the issue and we have listened very carefull to all that has been said both inside Parliament and more generally.  We are anxious that effective action should be taken to deal with this problem.  That must involve action by the foreign governments concerned, but that alone is not enough.  We must also do all that we can.<p>

"<b>Despite its admirable aim, Lord Hylton's Bill is, in the Government's view, seriously flawed and does not provide a workable or effective solution to the problems posed by sex tourism.  The Government cannot therefore support it.</b><p>

"We are, however, urgently examining the scope of the law in each of the United Kingdom jurisdictions to see what steps could be taken to deal with those who, in this country, conspire or incite others to commit offences abroad.  This would enable us to deal with those who organise sex tours, or encourage others to travel abroad for the purpose of sexually exploiting children.<p>

"Any legislation which might be brought forward to achieve this aim would need careful thought to ensure that it would be effective.  We would hope to have proposals for legislation ready as soon as the details can satisfactorily be resolved."
<p>


<a name="background">
<p>

<h2>Background information</h2>
<i>Based on information provided by the <b>Coalition on Child Prostitution and Tourism. </b></i>
<p>
<hr width=80%>
<h3>Q; What is the Coalition? </h3>

<ul>The Coalition is the UK branch of the International ECPAT (End Child Prostitution in Asian Tourism) campaign, which was established in 1991. <p>

The Coalition is made up of five major UK agencies:
<ul type=disc><li>Anti-Slavery International
<li> CAFOD
<li> Christian Aid
<li>the Jubilee Campaign
<li>Save the Children Fund (UK). 
</ul><p>
The agencies have recently decided to extend the Coalition's term until August 1996. 
<p>
</ul>

<h3>Q: Why is it so urgent to introduce this legislation?</h3>

<ul>ECPAT believes that <b>tourism is a major contributory factor in the growth of the sexual exploitation of children</b>. Poorer countries have become the target for tourists, businessmen and paedophiles from Europe, Australasia, Japan and North America. ECPAT monitored 160 child sex arrests in Asia over 3 years and found that 12%, the fourth largest group, were British. 
</ul>

<h3>Q: Which major tourist-sending countries are introducing legislation to make child sex tourism illegal?</h3>
<ul>
<i>Already introduced: </i>
<ul type=disc><li>Australia
 <li>Belgium 
<li>France 
<li>Germany 
<li>New Zealand (July '95) 
<li>Norway 
<li>Sweden
<li>USA.
</ul>
<p>

<i>In the process of considering legal change: </i>
<ul type=disc><li>Canada
<li>Ireland
<li>Italy
<li>Japan. 
</ul>
<p>
<i>Which major tourist-sending countries are NOT introducing this legislation? </i>

<ul type=disc><li>The UK 
</ul>
<p>

<b>The UK is the only major tourist-sending country to have rejected the opportunity to introduce extra-terrestrial jurisdiction in cases of child sexual abuse.  </b><br>
Last year in the UK, an amendment to the last Criminal Justice Bill by Lord Archer of Sandwell, similar to the Hylton Bill, was defeated in the House of Lords (14 June 1994).
<br>
Lord Hylton's Sexual Offences (Amendment) Bill gained mass support during its three readings in the House of Lords. An Early Day Motion no. 1267 tabled by Sir Ivan Lawrence, Chairman of the Home Affairs Committee, calling for extraterritorial jurisdiction, collected a remarkable 213 signatures in a very short time. 
</ul>

<h3>Q: What about the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child? </h3>
<ul>
Article 34 of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child requires states parties to take steps against the exploitation of children in prostitution and pornography. The UK has ratified the Convention - and the Coalition believes that the UK Government should be more active in honouring its obligations under the Convention. 
<p>
For more on the UK Government's record on ratifying the Convention, see <a href="../scf/scf_press.html">Implementing the Convention on Children's Rights</a>
</ul>

<h3>Q: How many children are involved? </h3>


<ul>Estimates of the number of children involved are very difficult to obtain because of the illegality of child sex in all countries. However, ECPAT estimates that <b>at least one million children in Asia alone </b>are being commercially sexually exploited in brothels, bars and from the streets.
<p>

The demand for younger children is increasing due to the mistaken belief that children offer a lower risk of HIV infection. In fact children's small bodies are very susceptible to abrasion and thus to infection during sexual acts.
<p>
</ul>
<h3>For more information: </h3>
The Coalition has produced a resource pack which is available from the office base at Anti-Slavery International <br>
Tel. +44(0)171-924 9555

<p>
<li><b>Material from the resource pack will be available on <i>OneWorld Online </i> in the near future.</b>
</ul>
<hr width=80%>
The text on this page was re-edited by the <i>OneWorld Online </i>team based on material provided by the <b>coalition on Child Prostitution and Tourism.</b>
<p>

<a name="theft">
<p>


<h2>Theft by consensus</h2>

<h3>By Anuradha Vittachi, Editor, OneWorld Online</h3><p>

<hr><p>

<b>A child's sexuality is her (or his) own. It does not belong to her parents or her country - or to the world at large. Where it is stolen from her by adults, there should be no doubt that a theft has taken place. <p>

But the British Government, which points outraged fingers at car thieves and petty burglars, is shrugging off its importance.  On July 14, the Sexual Offences Amendment Bill - a private members' bill to prosecute British men who have illegal sex with children abroad - was scheduled to have its second reading in the House of Commons but was opposed by the British Government. </b><p>
<font size=-1> A child prostitute in Bombay. Photo ©Copyright: Mark Edwards</font>
<hr><p>

<h3>What if the child complies?</h3>

Paedophiles sometimes argue that if the child has consented to a sexual act, that makes it acceptable. But this argument is simplistic. After all, for a child to believe that she is entitled - and expected - to refuse sexual exploitation, she must be supported in this belief by the consensus of adults around her.  Where her family, her community, her country, and even the international community support an opposite belief - that the use of her sexuality for an adult's gratification is permissible - the child herself cannot be expected to resist. <p>

On the contrary, these societies have made it plain to her that pleasing an adult through sexual acts is the way to survive: a form of obedience under duress.  In such cases, it is obvious that the extent of her compliance indicates not some kind of pleasurable personal choice, but merely the extent to which she is being exploited.<p>

If this analysis is correct, then children will tend to be most sexually exploited where they are most vulnerable - and that is clearly the case. In Britain, evidence is currently emerging of the regular sexual exploitation of children in many care institutions. Elsewhere in the world, too, grave economic and political disempowerment coincide with the systematic use of children to gratify adult sexual appetites.<p>


Where a community is very poor, some parents openly rely on their daughters and sons to provide the major part of their family income through selling sex.  And the community is often willing to turn a blind eye to what goes on in the shadows while child sex brings money into the area.  <p>


Pagsanjan, a small town of 20,000, used to be the best known place in the Philippines for pedophiles. Most people knew what was going on and looked the other way. The <i>Christian Science Monitor</i> interviewed Hannie Rogers, a Dutch-Indonesian woman who had recently moved to Pagsanjan and couldn't believe what she was seeing.  "It made me angry because I knew these men could not get away with anything like this back where they came from," she said. "I saw how these children were exploited by people from First World countries."<p>
<hr width=50%><p>


<b>The Philippines has long been a magnet for sex tourists. The Marcos Government actively used Filipino children as tourist bait - and tourists were duly lured from the wealthier parts of the world: the United States, Europe and Japan. </b><p>
<hr width=50%><p>


One tour operator explained that he would charter a bus, collect about $100 per Japanese tourist and drive over to an exclusive club where they would be at least 200 numbered girls or young women. The tourists would choose their partners for the night by writing down their numbers. They paid an average of  $60 a night, of which only $10-20 trickled down to the girl. The rest was divided between the club owner, the tour operator, the Filipino guide and the Japanese guide. 


<h3>Violence </h3>

Sometimes the psychological sadism - inherent in any relationship where one person calculatedly uses another - spills over into more brutal forms of physical sadism. <p>

In Brazil in the 1980s, Renee Bridel and Jean-Paul Collomp reported that 12-15 year old children were taken to centres called 'maisons d'abbatage' in remote parts of the country. The houses were guarded by police dogs and barbed wire: armed guards forbid acccess to anyone not known to the owner. <p>

Here the children were said to be drugged heavily and forced to submit to as many as 80 sexual acts with men a day, and beaten if they resisted. They were later sent to other centres where they were treated less sadistically - but threatened with being sent back to the first centre if they disobeyed.<p>

<h3>Pornography and Child-selling</h3>

Children are exploited worldwide not only for use as prostitutes, but as subjects of pornography. They are also traded: bought and sold for sex.  Defence for Children International (DCI) has described recruiters who seek out children to buy for delivery to brothels. They also describe auctions where girls were sold.  In Karachi in 1983, a slave market was held where women and girls kidnapped from Sri Lanka and Bangladesg were sold into prostitution.<p>

<b>How many children are sexually exploited for commerical purposes worldwide is not known. Estimates vary from hundreds of thousands to millions of children. </b><p>

The lack of knowledge stems only partly from the difficulty of tracking down such clandestine dealings. It also arises from two other difficulties. First, if organisations like governments or powerful vice rings are profiting from child sex, then the motivation to make thorough, large-scale investigations is hampered. And second, countries and comminities often don't want the murky relaities hidden in their shadows to be pulled out into the light of day. They prefer to make the murk 'disappear' by denying it exists - or by making out it exists only in aberrant cases, rather than facing the fact that it is part of their social system. 

<h3>How to help</h3>

<b>But children need - and are entitled - to have the brilliant spotlight of the world's attention focus on their sexual torture.</b><p>
  

One group of women who wanted to deter sex tours went to the airport and met the tourists as they disembarked, waving placards to show they knew what the tourists were up to. The customers' embarrassment was enormous: they are unlikely to want to go through that again. <p>

The women at the airport did something very important. They  tore away the sense of an 'open secret' - the  kind of secret that everyone half-knows about, but feels uncomfortable about investigating. We have a prickling sense that we have touched an area that is taboo and so we back away. This is the taboo that allows evil to be perpetuated: it holds the rationalisations for evil in place. <p>

Alf Anderson, in a report for the Norwegian Department of Justice, demanded "a media-storm and the rage of world opinion". And the International Association of Democratic Lawyers (IADL) stated: "Those who are guilty of crime against children must be made aware that one day they will be made responsible, and that every kind of publicity will be procured to throw light on the serious outrages they have committed."<p>

<b>Sexual exploitation must not be allowed to go on any longer in the shadows, whether behind barbed wire or under the guise of 'hospitality' bars.  But until the world is made to look and to care, we will indulge in the luxury of pretending that a few deranged monsters attack a few unfortunate child victims - while the sexual exploitation continues of hundreds of thousands of children all over the world.</b>  <p>
<hr width=80%>
<i>Some of this material was previously published in <b>Stolen Childhood: In Search of the Rights of the Child </b> (Polity Press, 1989).</i><p>



<p>


