<html>
<head>
<title>SCF - UN convention</title>
<!!keys: UNICEF+rights of the Child+children+UK Government>
</head>
<body>

<br clear=right>
<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="scf_info.html"> Save the Children Fund</i></a>
<hr>
<p>

<p>
<h4>IMPLEMENTING THE CONVENTION ON CHILDREN'S RIGHTS </h4>
There is no developed mechanism in the UK Government for taking children's issues forward.  There should be:
<p>
<ul><li>child impact statements for new legislation
<li>a Children's Rights Commissioner
</ul>
<p>
The UN Convention is not explicitly mentioned in legislation other than in the Children (Scotland) Bill.
<p>
The Government has not publicised the Convention sufficiently and it is doubtful whether many children and young people are aware of what it is and what it says.
In Northern Ireland Save the Children has published material to inform children and young people about the Convention.
<p>
<h4>GENERAL PRINCIPLES</h4>
<b>ARTICLE 2 - is about non discrimination.  The principle is that all rights apply to all children without exception.  The state is obliged to protect children against any form of discrimination.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b><br>
Clearly some groups of children and some families do still face discrimination.  These include Gypsies and Travellers, people with disabilities and members of ethnic minorities. Discrimination, whether deliberate or not, can mean families are not able to use the basic services that should be available to everyone and which the majority in society takes for granted. Rights, for example to health care, are meaningless if cultural or language differences make it impossible to use the health care system.  A survey in Scotland for example found that 28 percent of women from ethnic minority households had difficulties communicating with their GP. (See Save the Children Keynote on Health)
<p>
There is currently no race relations legislation in Northern Ireland.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work</b> tackling discrimination and helping minority groups gain access to services includes:
<p>
<i>The London Gypsy and Traveller Unit</i> which works with Traveller families and young people and raises awareness of their needs. The unit also concentrates on specific issues - for example the Safe Childbirth for Travellers campaign.
<p>
Hopscotch - a central London project working with Asian women and children.
<p>
<i>The Healthy Communities</i> project in the North East which is looking at how the health needs of the ethnic minority community in Elswick in Newcastle can be met.
<p>
<i>Playchoice</i> - a project in Birmingham which works to improve disabled children's access to mainstrean childcare provision like nurseries and playgroups.
<p>
<i>The Deptford Family Resource Centre</i> - a community project in the heart of Deptford which employs West African and Vietnamese outreach workers to ensure the project meets the needs of all the community. 
<p>
<i>Save the Children in Northern Ireland</i> is involved in research into the links between racism and poverty.
</ul><p>
<b>ARTICLE 12 - Children have a right to have their opinions heard and taken into account.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b><br>
This principle is applied only in childcare legislation (the Children Act for example).  It should be applied in legislation affecting children and in legal and administrative procedures. It should also be applied in schools.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
The Langley Children's project in Middleton near Rochadale is the base for a Children and Young People's Forum, run by children and young people themselves. 
<p>
In Northern Ireland the Save the Children Youth Unit recently organised a major conference on the issue on participation. 
<p>
</ul>
<h4>FAMILY ENVIRONMENT AND ALTERNATIVE CARE</h4>
<b>ARTICLE 9 -  children have a right to contact with both parents if they are separated from one or both of them.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b><br>
One reason for separation is that a mother or father has been imprisoned.  For the children, the separation can be traumatic, with the youngsters serving a "second sentence".  It is vital that prison visiting times are made as easy as possible for the children and that they are allowed as much time as possible with their mother or father.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
Holloway prison visiting scheme - a project run jointly with Holloway prison which allows children to spend all day with their mother.  The scheme was the first of its kind in the country.
<p>
Save the Children has also helped develop child friendly prison visiting centres at Crumlin Road prison in Belfast and at Norwich prison.  It has published a guide for prisons or organisations wanting to use the centres as an example to follow.  This has now been adopted by the Prison Service as advice to all Governors.
</ul><p>
<b>ARTICLE 18 -   The Government has a duty to acknowledge the joint responsibility of both parents for the care of their children and to provide the support services necessary.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b>
<br>
The Children Act 1989 places a duty on local authorities to identify "children in need" and to provide appropriate services for those children.  But the Government's own Children Act Report 1993 highlighted serious deficiencies in preventive family support services.  A report by the Audit Commission , <i>Seen But Not Heard 1994</i>, pointed to poor co ordination between social services, health and education authorities.
<p>
The UK has one of the lowest levels of publicly funded pre school services in Europe.  There should be a place in day care or nursery education for every 3 and 4 year old whose parents want it.
<p>
Out of school and school holiday provision for children is patchy.  There should be a much more comprehensive system so that the needs of children are met.
<p>
Major cuts are taking place in the youth service.  A survey by London Youth Matters for example found that over four years spending in London had been cut by more more than 16 percent. The youth service should be restored.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
Much of what Save the Children does is family support work. Projects include:
<p>
Rusholme in Manchester - The Trinity House Centre<br>
Cynon Valley in Wales - The Cynon Valley Project<br>
Middleton near Rochdale - The Langley Children's Project<br>
Battersea in London - The Patmore Centre<br>
Blackburn in West Lothian - The Blackburn Young Families Project<br>
Strabane in Northern Ireland - The Strabane Family Centre<br>
<p>
Family support means working with families and local communites to provide services that are needed.  These include day care and after school care, but can also include youth groups, health education sessions, literacy training and vocational training for adults. 
</ul><p>
<h4>BASIC HEALTH AND WELFARE</h4>
<p>
<b>ARTICLE 24 -  Children have the right to the highest level of health possible and to access to health and medical services.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment</b>
<br>
Children's health is put at risk by poverty, discrimination or lack of access to services.  Clearly some are not having their right to health realised.  For example:
<p>
<ul><li>if your parents are in the lowest income group you are three times more likely to die before you are four than children whose parents are better off.
<p>
<li> if your parents are in the lowest income group you are twice as likely as other children to die of respiratory problems before you are 14.
<p>
<li>if your parents do not understand English well you are much less likely to see a GP regularly. 
<p>
<li>if your parents are poor and you live far from the nearest clinic you are unlikely to benefit as much from the local health service.
</ul><p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
The Pennywell Neighbourhood Centre in Sunderland has made health care available for people on the Pennywell estate.  The project provides a base for doctor's surgeries, a child health clinic and family planning services for men and women.  The Centre is at the heart of the community, meaning that health and other services, are within easy reach.
<p>
The Healthy Communities project in Newcastle works with people in the West End of the City to find out how their health care needs can be better met. 
<p>
The Deptford Vietnamese Health Project was funded for three years to work with the Vietnamese community to look at ways of improving their access to health care.  The project provided training for health professionals and produced a report outlining how the local authority and health authority could do more to help Vietnamese people.
<p>
The Hopscotch project is actively improving access to the health service for Bengali women in Camden in London.  A female doctor uses the project as a base for surgeries.  The project has also helped produce audio tapes of health information (in drama form) in Sylheti (a Bangladeshi dialect)
<p>
The Community Health Project in Belfast works with community based health groups to ensure greater access to health services. It is also researching into inequalities in health.
</ul><p>
<b>ARTICLE 26 - the right to benefit from social security.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b>
<br>
There are cases where children lose this right.  In 1988 the Government withdrew the right of 16 to 17 year olds to receive income support.  Those not in full time education or employment were instead promised training and a training allowance.  This promise has not been fulfilled and thousands of youngsters were left without an income.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
Save the Children works with young people, most of them unemployed, in many parts of the country.
<p>
The Lifechance projet in Oxford and the BYPASS project in Bolton both work with young people who have recently left care.
<p> 
BYPASS also runs a drop in centre in the middle of Bolton and is able to advise young people about their entitlements to benefit.
<p>
The Possilpark Befriending project in Glasgow helps young people who, for one reason or another, lack adult support.
<p>
Save the Children in Northern Ireland is working with young people to equip them with research skills to carry out research into young people's economic activity in West Belfast.  The long term aim is to act as a stimulus to generate economic activity. 
</ul><p>
<b>ARTICLE 27 - The right to benefit from an adequate standard of living.  The state should take measures to help parents and others ensure that right.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b>
<br>
One in three children growing up in Britain today is growing up in poverty.
<p>
Support to parents and families is vital but the Government's own assessment (Children Act Report 1993)  says that preventative family support services in the UK leave much to be desired. 
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
SEE UNDER <b>ARTICLE 18</b>
</ul><p>
<h4>EDUCATION, LEISURE AND CULTURAL ACTIVITIES</h4>
<b>ARTICLE 31 - children have a right to play.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment:</b>
<br>
For every £100 spent by the Department of National Heritage, only 3p is dedicated to children's play.  Play facilties and youth provision have been cut in recent years.  Provision was cut back in 62 percent of local authorities in 1993/4.
<p>
A right to safe play is essential and yet streets are less and less safe and play areas are often under threat.  Poor families can rarely afford to buy toys.
<p>
For every £100 spent by the Department of National Heritage, only 3p is devoted to children's play.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
All Save the Childrens projects offering day care and after school care provide good opportunities for children to play.
<p>
Many run school holiday play schemes, for example the "Breakout" scheme in Pennywell.
<p>
Many Save the Children projects run toy libraries, for example:
<p>
Trinity House in Manchester, The Knowsley Training and Resource Centre in Kirkby, and the Pennywell Neighbourhood Centre in Sunderland.
<p>
Save the Children in Northern Ireland  recently published a major Report and Agenda on Children's Right to Play in Northern Ireland.  The organisation then appointed a play development worker to promote children's right to play.
<p>
</ul>
<h4>SPECIAL PROTECTION MEASURES</h4>
<b>ARTICLE 30 - minority communities have a right to enjoy their own culture and practice their own religions and language.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment</b>
<br>
This is a basic right.  The Criminal Justice and Public Order Act, which will make it progressively more difficult for Gypsy and Traveller families to find safe authorised caravan sites, will make it harder and harder for this group to enjoy their own culture.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
Projects working with Gypsies and Travellers include:
<p>
The London Gypsy and Traveller Unit<br>
The Buckinghamshire Traveller Project<br>
The West Midlands Partnership Project<br>
<p>
Save the Children also runs the Equality Learning Centre which provides information and support for people working with young children.
</ul><p>
<b>ARTICLE 40 - institutional placements for young offenders should be avoided wherever possible.</b>
<p>
<ul><b>Comment</b>
<br>
The secure training centres to be introduced by the Government for young offenders aged 12 to 14 will be contrary to the spirit of the Convention.  Children will be locked up even though the need from this is far from obvious (Save the Children research Jan 1994)  Time spent in the centres will harm the children involved and is unlikely to be effective in preventing re offending.
<p>
<b>Save the Children's work:</b>
<br>
The Dumbarton project in Scotland works with young people to challenge offending behaviour.
<p>
The Contract project in Newcastle is a consultancy  and research unit looking at alternatives to custody.  It works with local authorities and other bodies in the North East.
</ul><p>
<h4>HISTORY OF CHILDREN'S RIGHTS</h4>
Eglantyne Jebb, who founded Save the Children, drafted the first ever charter of children's rights in 1923.
<p>
In 1924 her work was adopted by the League of Nations as the Declaration of the Rights of the Child.
<p>
In 1959 the UN General Assembly adopted the second Declaration of the Rights of the Child. 
<p>
In 1989 the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child was adopted by the UN General Assembly.
<p>
In 1991 the UK Government ratified the UN Convention
<p>
In January 1995 the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child will report on the UK Government's performance so far.
<p>
Declarations are often called "soft laws".  They are statements of general principles but they don't oblige any of the Governments accepting them to actually do anything.
Conventions are binding and need an active decision on the part of individual states to agree or ratify them
<p>
<h4>NOTES FOR EDITORS:</h4>
<ul><li>Save the Children's press office will automatically fax copies of the UN report to newsdesks.  Please let the press office know of any individuals who want the material sent to their own fax number.
<p>
<li>The UN Convention on the Rights of the Child was adopted by the General Assembly on 20 November 1989.  It includes sections on health, education, standards of living, abuse, discrimination and children's rights to have their opinions taken into account.
<p>
<li>The first Declaration of Children's Rights was written by Save the Children's founder, Eglantyne Jebb, and adopted by the League of Nations in 1924.
<p>
<li>Save the Children can provide briefing material on sections of the Convention and on areas likely to be covered by the UN Committee session in Geneva.
</ul>
