<html>
<header>
<title>Civil Service Reform: Hurdles and Helps</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Civil Service Reform: Hurdles and Helps</h3>
by <i>Joan Corkery</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 3(1) August 1995: pages 9-11</i>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

At independence, African governments inherited administrative structures which were geared
overwhelmingly to the requirements of the ex-colonial powers. There were few links to
indigenous systems of government and they were concerned more with the extraction of natural
resources than with economic and human development. Moreover, newly independent countries
were not only confronted with the need to establish a whole machinery of government but with
doing so in an environment of unprecedented economic and technological change. To this
maelstrom of change there was added, over the past decade or so, a further cataclysmic change,
namely the widespread and fundamental ideological change regarding the role of the state in the
process of economic development. This change brought with it a new-found emphasis on the
private sector as the primary engine of growth within the framework of free markets and prices.
<p>
But the switch in strategies which this neo- liberal ideology brought was soon recognised to be
in danger of going too far and becoming counter-productive. Apart from the role of the state in
providing basic services of law, order and justice, defence, infrastructure, education, and health
it was also acknowledged that for institutions of the free market to work, government institutions
must also work.
<p>
Moreover, the actual development of the enabling policy framework within which non-government sectors can operate more efficiently is seen to require more - not less - emphasis on
the availability of a strong institutional capacity to manage economic policy -- its
implementation and monitoring as well as the actual formulation of policy. So civil service
reform and capacity building are again back on the priority agenda of development policy. But
how best to proceed in the current circumstances in African countries still remains a very
difficult question.
<p>
<h3>Hurdles on the Course</h3>

First, there is a paradox. The more comprehensive and complex the process of reform the greater
the management capacity required to implement it. Yet those countries in greatest need of such
reform are often, and not surprisingly, those with the weakest capacity to manage the process.
Assigning more senior and experienced officers to the needs of civil service reform inevitably
results in short-changing other areas of policy and institutional reform which are also extremely
important if the objectives of economic development are to be achieved. Difficult choices in the
allocation of scarce managerial capacity are inevitable. It is already the case that the limited,
albeit important, area of managing macro-financial policy tends to be given priority in this
regard. Of course it can be argued that the primary purpose of civil service reform is precisely
to increase the efficiency of the service and thereby increase its capacity to manage all aspects
of economic and social policy. Thus, it could be asserted that it should be accorded 'highest
priority.' However, correct this might be in the long-run, it does not reduce the difficulty of
making day-to-day decisions particularly when most governments are likely to judge their life
expectancy in the short-run rather than in the long-run.
<p>
Second, there is the need to ensure that reforms are feasible within the existing political,
economic and cultural environment and, particularly, to ensure that they are supported by civil
servants themselves. Once again there is a paradox. This arises from the fact that, on the one
hand, reform implies major changes (often adverse) in the financial rewards, career expectations,
security of tenure, and other conditions of work of civil servants which inevitably generate an
atmosphere of uncertainty and unease within the service. Yet, the success of reform programmes
requires theat civil servants are actively involved and support them.
<p>
They, from their knowledge of the workings of public administration can contribute significantly
to the introduction of reform measures that make sense and are effectively implementable. Lack
of their support can also lead to delays and even in extreme cases to blockage of the process of
reform. The effective implementation of reforms also requires that there should be a high level
of morale and sense of professionalism and of loyalty by officers by service, all of which can be
jeopardised by reform measures.
<p>
Third, because most civil service reform programmes have been introduced as components of
structural adjustment programmes, they have been - or seen to have been - imposed from outside
by the IMF and the World Bank. Also, in the context of the macro financial focus of these
programmes, the reforms have focussed almost exclusively on reducing the budgetary cost of
the civil service through reductions in staff and salary levels.
<p>
The final hurdle to reform is the dearth of recent experiences anywhere with public service
reforms on the scale deemed necessary in African countries. Models derived from developed
country experiences are largely irrelevant, particularly because, within their more sophisticated
institutional practices and procedures, any changes which are introduced have typically been
supported by various institutional 'safety nets' which are not available in Africa. Furthermore,
private sector management practices which have been imported in some countries have not
always transplanted successfully, partly because the parallel reform of monitoring and review
procedures called for by the introduction of these practices is not taking place simultaneously.
<p>
<h3>Helps -- Conditions for Successful Reform</h3>

Despite the hurdles to reform, it is still possible to identify some of the elements that are
common to several of the more successful programmes. These programmes are illustrated by
reference to countries in Anglophone Africa but it is interesting to note that the elements for
success correspond closely with those identified in Francophone Africa by Fofana in his
contribution to this Bulletin.
<p>
First is the need for explicit political support for reform measures over an extended period. This
provides the necessary conviction that the reforms will be sustained over time. Mrs. Thatcher's
long spell as prime minister in the United Kingdom during the 1980's provides an obvious
example of a strong commitment to sweeping reforms which permitted changes to be made in
organisational structures and behaviour which were previously considered unattainable. In Africa
it is noteworthy that Ghana and Uganda which have both had some success in civil service
reform, have had political stability and continuity of leadership for a decade or more plus overt
support from the leadership for the reform programme.
<p>
But, and this is the second requirement, political commitment must be buttressed by the
existence of an implementing agency with sufficient prestige and authority as well as the
necessary intellectual and technical capacity, to formulate and execute the reform programme.
There is evidence that this is happening. In Zambia, responsibility for reform rests with the
Permanent Secretary of the Management Development Division in Cabinet Office. In both
Ghana and Uganda, the person responsible for civil service reform is Head of the Civil Service.
(It is interesting that in Ghana this official either has ministerial rank or is on a par with that
rank.) A Reform Coordination Unit and a Reform Administration Committee were established
in Ghana after a review in 1993 revealed weaknesses in coordination and appraisal and a limited
permeation of the culture of reform. 
<p>
Third is the need not only for clearly defined goals of reform, but for realistic strategies to
achieve these goals -- the means, the timing and the sequencing of actions. This realism must
reflect the political and institutional environment in a country. In Zambia for instance, nobody
questions the need for a leaner and more effective public service which will meet the
management needs of a modern government service in a period of major political change and of
serious economic difficulty. But the reality of the situation is that the civil service, as in many
other African countries, has provided a major source of employment for educated young people
and thus it is a critical judgement just how much 'downsizing' can be tolerated by the society and
the political system.
<p>
This leads to the fourth element for success which is the need for effective communication with
all the actors and stakeholders who have interests in the process of civil service reform and with
all the ministries and agencies which can contribute to the identification of issues and the
development and implementation of programmes of reform. But experience shows that such in-depth discussions often receive short shrift because of time pressures when there is a need to
show that 'something is being done,' and because of the widespread absence of appropriate
institutional procedures and of experienced people for facilitating such discussions. This latter
problem is typically aggravated by the activities of external donors and advisers who, to meet
the needs and priorities of the programmes in which they are involved tend to monopolise the
time and efforts of the experienced people who are available.
<p>
And this, in its turn, leads to the fifth and final condition for success namely that civil service
reform must be 'owned' by the national authorities if it is to be successful. External agencies such
as the World Bank have a role to play but this must be a supportive and advisory role more akin
to the specialist consultants which governments in industrialised countries have used to develop
their own reform programmes. On more than one occasion, senior World Bank officials have
strongly endorsed the importance of this secondary role for external agencies and the
implications which go with it. Amongst these implications is that the Bank must not present
governments with a template of reform measures but must recognise the crucial importance of
giving very careful attention to the proposals of local personnel - administrative and political -
who know what can and cannot be implemented within their countries. This approach, however,
requires that much more time be devoted to the design phase of programmes and to strategies
for their implementation -- an implication which, again, external agencies have not only fully
accepted but positively asserted as essential even though the modalities for making this
operational have yet to be put in place. A further implication relates to the traditional policy of
financing and assigning long-term expatriates to design and implement reform programmes, with
a counterpart working alongside. Although current development cooperation policy seeks to
diminish this practice, it is likely that some expertise will need to be provided for a number of
years. The strategy used must ensure that it is the local officers who are in charge or the
programme, with external agencies providing whatever additional technical support they require.
<p>
<h3>A Comprehensive Approach</h3>

These five pre-conditions may not be sufficient for success but there are indications that their
presence enhances the chances of achieving success. They should be seen as a 'package' in which
they mutually reinforce each other. Political commitment is of little use unless there is an
effective institutional capacity within government to formulate and implement a civil service
reform programme. Equally, it is important to recognise that this capacity does not only comprise
the officials directly involved. They, in turn, must be willing and able to draw upon the
knowledge and experience of other ministries and agencies and of people and institutions
throughout the non-government sectors of society. This will result in more technically sound and
more politically feasible reform measures.
<p>
If the first four pre-conditions are met, the fifth pre-condition of national ownership is more
likely to follow. For they will result in more balanced relations between those responsible for
a programme within the national administration and the external agencies who are support it. The
former are more likely to have a strong and tenable position; the latter will see less need for an
overly intrusive role. Having external agencies and individuals in supporting positions will avoid
the need for African administrations to take a confrontational stand in negotiating with external
funding sources; they can be de facto as well as the de jure owners of their programmes with
access to foreign expertise as it is required. However, it is essential not to underestimate the
change of attitude and approach the resulting process would imply for all the actors involved,
be they from external agencies or from national administrations.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <i>Updated on February 20, 1996</i><p>
