<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Guides to Institutional Reform at the National Level</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>Guides to Institutional Reform at the National Level</H3>

<P>
by <I>Moustapha Deme</I> 
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
pages 5-7</I> </CENTER><HR>

<P>
Three factors are mainly responsible for the limited success of
attempts at regional cooperation in Africa and the almost complete
failure of the more ambitious attempts at regional integration:

<UL>
<LI>the absence of political will; 
<LI>the absence of consistency between regional and national policies;
and 
<LI>the inefficiency of regional organisations.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The first two of these factors are the concern of this issue of
the Bulletin. Decisions at the regional level by heads of state
and government and by ministers have seldom been reflected in
decisions at the national level in the form of legislation and
regulations. In fact these national decisions are often taken
without reference to regional decisions.
<P>
Not only does this appear to reflect a lack of political commitment
to decisions taken at the regional level but also a failure to
develop the institutional measures which are required to follow-up
and manage these regional decisions. Unless these issues are addressed,
the frequently-asserted objective of closer regional cooperation
and integration will remain exactly that -- an assertion without
implementation.
<H4>What Should be Done? - Five Guides for Action</H4>

<P>
<I>Involve Civil Society more Fully</I>
<P>
In many countries, decision-making has been monopolised by politicians
and bureaucrats without reference to the interests of all actors
who will be affected by their decisions. In particular, the bureaucrats
have appropriated major responsibility for policy. They have made
themselves into a caste that controls the exercise of power and
contributes to the suppression of all counter forces. The political
class has become dependent on civil servants when it comes to
actions in the field of regional cooperation. Yet these civil
servants are themselves beholden for their actions to their families,
their tribes or to other social groups who oppose policies which
endanger their vested interests including those which advance
regional cooperation.
<P>
The most fundamental national institutional action is therefore
to reform the political process to ensure greater democratisation
of power. People must not take refuge in the non-formal sectors
of the country but must recognise themselves as part of the state
and its institutions and as part of the regional and sub-regional
groupings of which their country is a part.
<P>
This participation of civil society is needed in the preparation
of strategies and important decisions, as well as in their implementation.
More effective involvement by actors and stakeholders in regional
cooperation can be assisted  by their forming associations or
interest groups which can act as lobbyists.
<P>
The formation of  such groups can be seen as part of the process
leading towards greater coordination and dialogue between civil
society and the government, and more generally towards greater
democratisation of power.
<P>
<I>Improve Administrative Coordination</I>
<P>
Public servants in charge of government agencies tend to function
as if they were independent and coordination between different
administrative services is difficult to achieve. This is particularly
important in regional cooperation policy where national agencies
typically must surrender responsibilities to regional agencies.
<P>
Attempts have been made by some countries to address this issue
by establishing special institutions at the national level for
monitoring the implementation of regional agreements. For instance,
national commissions of ECOWAS and CILSS have been set up for
this purpose in their member countries. Certain countries (e.g.
Senegal) have tried to provide more effective follow-up mechanisms
by establishing ministries for regional cooperation while others
(e.g. Mali) have entrusted the task to the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs -- adding 'regional integration' to the name of the Ministry.
However none of these initiatives have shown convincing results.
<P>
An alternative approach has been attempted with some success in
the case of food security policy. This approach starts by addressing
the basic national weakness of poor coordination between government
departments. From a more robust national administrative foundation
it is expected that a more effective regional programme will emerge
(see box).
<P>
<I>Increase Administrative Decentralisation</I>
<P>
Structural adjustment programmes have emphasised the need to redefine
economic relationships in the country by returning economic power
to individual consumers, farmers, firms, etc. through market mechanisms.
A parallel need exists to decentralise administrative power to
the base of society by restructuring the state as part of the
democratisation process.
<P>
Experiences show that many attempts at decentralisation have had
limited success. They were adopted by the administrative elite
and the effect was to enlarge the mistrust of the population towards
the state.
<P>
The solution lies in a complete decentralisation that transfers
a maximum of responsibilities to sub-national authorities as well
as the financial and technical capacity which is required to undertake
them. Such decentralisation would enhance the economic and trade
management capacities of border authorities and inter-state networks.
It would also enhance cultural and social relations across national
borders which have in any case always been strong.
<P>
<I>Improve Capacity for Information and Analysis</I>
<P>
Good information about actors and stakeholders in regional cooperation,
about objectives and strategies, about costs and benefits for
each interest group and for the country as a whole over the short
and middle term and over the longer term, are essential for rational decision-making.
<P>
However, such information is lacking at the national level. It
suffers from the concentration of national governments on short
term crisis management and on purely national policy issues. As
a consequence there is an inadequate basis for proceeding from
agreements genuinely reached at regional level discussions to
the implementation of these agreements at national level.
<P>
This information and analysis should not only be generated by
governments. The whole range of national associations which reflect
the interest groups who stand to gain or lose by closer regional
cooperation need to be better informed. Only on this basis can
they sensibly participate in the national discussion which must,
in a democracy, precede decisions being taken by the government
on regional policy issues.
<P>
<I>Establish Arbitration and Follow-up Procedures</I>
<P>
Decision-making depends on the development of institutions and
processes for reaching compromises between differing interest
groups at the national level. These negotiations have to take
place at several levels with iterative procedures to permit the
renogiation of previous agreements.
<P>
In addition there is a need for follow-up and sanction procedures
in order to ensure that policies and programmes are implemented
as previously agreed. Arbitration procedures are also required.
<H4>Concluding Comment</H4>

<P>
The issues set out above for institutional reform at the national
level to achieve the objectives of greater regional cooperation,
call for responsibility and action at the highest level of the
administrations of member governments - presidency or prime ministerial
level - in accordance with national constitutions and making use
of the classical counter-forces such as parliament, the media,
and civil society.
<P>
The 'Five Guides' which are presented for institutional reform
at the national level will only be effective if they are paralleled
by a reform in the current institutional framework at the regional
level. Regional institutions are clearly essential but their number
could certainly be substantially reduced and their efficiency
increased. In fact their efficiency in undertaking the functions
of information, analysis, coordination, follow-up, evaluation
and stimulation would be enhanced if there were fewer of them.
<P>
Finally a strengthening of the institutions for regional cooperation
at the national level could be expected to have a beneficial impact
on the efficiency and effectiveness of the institutions at the
regional level. This is a positive-sum game.<HR>

<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <I>Updated on
April 15, 1996</I></H6>

