<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>The New Popularity of NGOs: Will the Enthusiasm Last?</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>The New Popularity of NGOs:<br>Will the Enthusiasm Last?<p>
<I>Martina Vahlhans</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 3, May-June 1994: pages 20-22</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>The growing importance of development NGOs in the 80s is often
explained by their &quot;comparative advantages&quot; over government
organizations. However, the lack of systematic evaluations of
NGOs' concrete accomplishment rather suggests other political
motivations underlying the NGO growth induced by government/donor
promotion. What are the motivations and what are the consequences?</B>
<P>
During the 80s NGO activities have grown worldwide in terms of
their size and scope, their number and their aid volume. NGO support
to developing countries almost doubled during the last 20 years
(1970: $ 2.7 b., 1988: $ 5.2 b), growing much faster than OECD
official aid on average. This growth is mainly due to an important
increase of official contributions by OECD governments to NGOs,
namely 1400% between 1975 and 1985. As a consequence today official
contributions present almost one third of all funding of the NGO
sector.
<P>
It has often been argued that this new popularity of NGOs is due
to their specific characteristics which give them &quot;comparative
advantages&quot; over government organizations in implementing
development  especially poverty alleviation  programmes. In fact
a closer look at the evidence for concrete achievements of NGOs
calls into question whether this is the reason for NGO growth.
<P>
<B>NGOs' comparative advantages</B>
<P>
The term &quot;NGO&quot; offers a broad umbrella for a kaleidoscopic
collection of organizations differing in size, form, orientation,
ideological affinity, resources and target groups. Thus &quot;NGO~
as a term is almost rendered meaningless. Practically the only
thing all these organizations have in common is being &quot;nongovernmental&quot;.
The term &quot;NGO&quot; thus does not indicate what these organisations
are, only what they are not. Despite of this lack of clarity the
term &quot;NGO&quot; has established itself as a fixed label within
development politics and practice.
<P>
Since the beginning of the 80s the term &quot;comparative advantages&quot;
has been commonly associated with the term &quot;NGO&quot; referring
to their performance in micro development and poverty alleviation.
More explicitly the term is related to NGOs' success in reaching
the (participation of the) poor; their flexible and experimental
interventions due to their small size, their learning process
approaches; their low costs and their effective work at the grassroots
especially in remote areas.
<P>
NGOs have in fact specific characteristics which governments have
not which make them more suited to the achievement of success
in poverty alleviation. Their relationship to their beneficiaries
is based on voluntarism which is the main factor allowing NGOs
to achieve meaningful participation. Furthermore NGOs recruit
and motivate highly qualified and motivated staff on the basis
of shared values and a belief in the social mission of the NGO.
This provides NGOs with a high degree of technical and often regional
expertise. Moreover NGOs are free to organize according to the
perceived organisational needs in relation to their activities.
This enables NGOs to be more flexible and respond better to the
specific needs than (highly bureaucratic) government organisations.
NGOs thus have in theory  potential comparative advantages over
government organizations.
<P>
However there is little systematic evidence to support the view
that NGOs always realize their potential comparative advantages.
The few substantial studies carried out even seem to call into
question NGOs' reputed comparative advantages. According to their
results most of the projects didn't reach the poorest of the poor,
in only a minority of the projects did the benefits clearly outweigh
the costs of the intervention, few projects had been serious about
participation and few projects were demonstrated to be financially
self sustaining in the long run. All this goes to show that NGOs
do not always realize their potential comparative advantages.
The new popularity of NGOs has therefore not arisen from a systematic
evaluation of NGOs' concrete accomplishment. This sets a serious
question mark against donors new interest in NGOs which have previously
been excluded by them.
<P>
<B>Donors' motivations</B>
<P>
The increase of official contributions to NGOs reflects a change
in the policies of government aid agencies and influential institutions
such as the World Bank. There are two obvious arguments for this
change. On the one hand at the end of the 60s even the previous
protagonists of modernization theories and the &quot;trickle down&quot;
effect had to acknowledge that their approaches had not succeeded
in bringing about development or poverty alleviation. As a consequence
in the 70s  a shift in official development policies took place
towards poverty alleviation and smaller projects allowing for
participatory approaches and better management. NGOs which had
long experience and success with small scale projects and working
with the poor seemed to be the ideal partners.
<P>
On the other hand the new interest of donors for NGOs reflects
the general ascendance of free market economics in the 1980s:
a shift from (neo) Keynesian towards neoclassical development thinking.
However, only the coming to power of conservative administrations
in the U.S., U.K. and former West Germany at the start of the
80s could bring about this marked shift in (development) policies.
Within the neoclassical paradigm emphasis is put on private initiative
as the crucial factor in development. The official development
policy climate has therefore been even more favorable towards
NGOs as &quot;private agents&quot; within development.
<P>
The rise of the NGO-model as a development strategy could therefore
have too much in common with previous fashions in international
aid circles. When donors expectations are not fulfilled or a new
paradigm calls for new policies the NGO model could be wiped off
the agenda as quickly as it has been placed on it.
<P>
Current donor policies have been based on the assumption that
the beneficial impact of NGOs can be scaled up and the sustainability
of official development projects enhanced. They have assumed that
this can be done by simply channeling more funds through them
and/or building NGO approaches into large development projects.
These new policies ignore the long history of conflict between
governments and NGOs and the underlying motivations as well as
the repercussions on the governments in developing countries and
NGOs themselves.
<P>
<B>Developing countries' governments</B>
<P>
Governments in developing countries have faced the following dilemma.
On the one hand they need donor funds or want to attract more
funding. On the other hand they do not always want to involve
NGOs not always being convinced of their important role. They
are often suspicious regarding NGO attempts to organize the poor
which could undermine the state's hegemony.
<P>
Government responses to NGO growth depend to a large extent on
the political regime and the extent of (de)centralization in a
country. In more liberal and democratic regimes such as India
where the model of relations between government and NGO is a corporate
one governments have reacted to NGO growth with demand for more
cooperation. In statist or autocratic regimes such as Indonesia
or Kenya governments have reacted to NGO growth with more control.
<P>
The Indonesian government reacted with more regulations for NGOs
by creating &quot;quasi NGOs&quot; (QUANGOs) and &quot;government organized
NGOs&quot; (GONGOs). In QUANGOs and GONGOs wives or close relatives
of famous politicians are often to be found. They do not only
serve public interest but make also sure that the government wishes
are taken into account. Even military generals might be found
on their committees in Indonesia. The Indonesian government seems
to be extremely suspicious of initiatives which are not controlled
by the state. Any successful self help initiative or NGO will be
either regulated or soon coopted into the quasi administration
directed by the government or even forced to abandon its activities.
The result is a disguised bureaucracy which looks like donors
want it to look without any comparative advantage such as flexibility,
participation, innovation and responsiveness over bureaucratic
government organizations. Moreover the promotion of NGO activities
seems to promote the mushrooming of QUANGOs and GONGOs in statist
or autocratic regimes such as Indonesia.
<P>
Many countries in Africa  especially Kenya, Tanzania, Zimbabwe,
Uganda and Ethiopia have also reacted with more control to the
recent growth of NGO activities, that is to say more regulation,
coordination, cooption and even dissolution. In Kenya the NGO
sector has become more complex and less transparent because of
the growing number of NGOs and NGO activities. This has led to
the misuse of the NGO title in order to obtain foreign funding
and/or government facilities. The Kenyan government has as a consequence
issued stronger regulations justified mainly by the lack of coordination
and the misuse of the NGO title. Some NGOs which had apparently
misused the NGO title were deregistered. In July 1983 the District
Focus Strategy was inaugurated empowering District Development
Committees to review  and accept or reject  all NGO project proposals.
However, by these means the Kenyan government can also steer NGOs
(or their projects) and weed out NGOs (or their projects) which
are nonconformist. The diversity and the innovative character
of NGO projects will be reduced. This trend is even enhanced by
the fact. that NGOs in Kenya  being often dependent on foreign
funding  have been copying fashionable approaches in order to
receive more funds.
<P>
Many governments in developing countries hence have reacted to
new donor priorities by retaining the economic advantage which
NGOs offer whilst countering the political disadvantages which
they can present. New donor policies have neglected governments'
desire to control in statist regimes and have overemphasized the
strengthening of NGOs' financial base at the expense of the political
one. Donors have therefore failed to capitalize on the potential
comparative advantages of NGOs and seem to achieve the opposite
of what they want to achieve: many governments in developing countries
have expanded their control and the operational space of NGOs
has thus been reduced. This trend will strengthen the existing
political economies of many developing countries rather than contribute
to the democratization of their development.
<P>
<B>NGO strategies</B>
<P>
The increased interest of donors in NGOs has also placed many
NGOs in a dilemma. On the one hand they can attract more funding
and increase their activities by designing projects which are
likely to be promoted by donors/governments. On the other hand
they endanger their autonomy and their identity as a &quot;nongovernmental&quot;
institution by extending their dependence on official funds and
their cooperation with governments and donors.
<P>
In the past the majority of NGOs have striven to work independently
of government agencies. It has been the common and obvious approach
as the definition of being &quot;nongovernmental&quot; suggests.
The increasing cooperation of NGOs with governments is also referred
to as one way of &quot;scaling up&quot; NGO activities. Protagonists
of this approach in the NGO community see the cooperation with
governments as a way of reaching more than a limited number of
people with their project activities. They also regard the often
unfavorable environment of NGO projects (mainly created by the
government) as the common cause for the unsustainability of NGO
projects in the long run.
<P>
In order to scale-up their activities NGOs have  in general  to
undergo certain changes: Standardization of working methods, adoption
of basic replicable project structure (as opposed to individually
designed projects), decentralization of the organisation and the
adoption of modern management, monitoring and evaluation techniques.The
above list can best tee summarized as the professionalization and
bureaucratization of NGOs. Moreover by working with governments
NGOs become on the one hand accountable to the governments for
their activities, on the other hand accountable to the beneficiaries
for the &quot;common&quot; actions such as Structural Adjustment
Programmes. NGOs become also more vulnerable to changes in the
government by working with them.
<P>
The impacts of such changes certainly entail high risks and dangers.
By working with governments NGOs are bound to sacrifice their
potential comparative advantages such as flexibility, specificity
and responsiveness to people's needs. If they cannot develop appropriate
methods to counterweigh these effects they could even lose the
contact to the grassroots and the trust of their potential beneficiaries.
Some see the increased cooperation of NGOs with governments as
a first step towards NGOs being used as a &quot;Public service
contractor&quot; instead of being catalysts and facilitators of
change as well as structural opposition. These critics consider
the role of NGOs as being advocates for greater political power
for the poor as well as a counterweight to the influence of the
rich and the well organized. NGOs should from their point of view
scale up their activities by &quot;policy advocacy&quot; thus working
for structural change.
<P>
However, it is essential that NGOs have to watch carefully the
level of official funding they receive. NGOs have to beware of
dependence on official funds otherwise they could be steered away
from their initial activities designed to remove the social and
political structures which hold the poor in their disadvantaged
position. NGOs dependence on official funding also implies that
donors/governments could control NGOs via the funds they channel
to them and as a consequence NGOs or specific projects in their
interest could be promoted at the expense of others, the nonconformist
ones.
<P>
All this is to show that donors' assumption of being able to scale up
the beneficial impact of NGOs and replicate their success by simply
channeling more funds through them is on the whole too simplistic
and therefore false. Moreover (induced) NGO growth may stand for
less diversity of NGOs ('projects) and lay the foundations for
NGOs as aid dependent parastatals instead of advocates for the
poor or a structural opposition.
<P>
<B>Outlook</B>
<P>
What conclusions can be drawn from this? The new popularity of
NGOs is not entirely due to their comparative advantages over
government agencies in implementing poverty alleviation projects
as it is sometimes advocated. Donors increased promotion of NGOs
is not due to a systematic revision of NGOs performance but rather
to changes in their overall approaches to development. This increased
promotion has had repercussions on governments of developing countries
and NGOs themselves: Many governments have increased their control
over NGOs while giving their administration a &quot;nongovernmental&quot;
image. New  sometimes dubious  NGOs have been created. NGOs have
increased their cooperation with governments jeopardizing their
original identity and potential comparative advantages. Induced
NGO growth therefore does not seem to lead to more democratization
or a strong civic society in developing countries as it is sometimes
argued. It would appear then, that the existing elites and political
economies in many developing countries will rather be reaffirmed.
<P>
Over and above all these considerations growing NGO activities
will apparently not solve the mass poverty problem. Donors might
therefore be disillusioned and turn to other policies neglecting
or even opposing NGOs.
<P>
Moreover the 1990s has seen a crumbling of the neoclassical paradigm.
The election of Bill Clinton in the US, the fall of Margaret Thatcher
and John Major's new economic policies since &quot;Black Wednesday&quot;,
Helmut Kohl's shift towards &quot;intelligent industrial policies&quot;
and donors' policy approaches in Central and East Europe point
to a new agenda. The swing is not back to the Keynesianism of
the 1950s and 60s, but the paradigm is shifting towards intelligent
economic intervention by governments in their economies.
<P>
The ascendance of a new paradigm suggests even more that development
policies promoting NGOs might be abandoned by donors in the near
future for other more alluring policies. When the history of development
aid in the 1980s comes to be written the part devoted to the comparative
advantages of NGOs and their relative success will probably not
be as important as today's enthusiasts  in donor and NGO circles
may imagine it to be.
<p>
<HR>
