<HEAD>

<TITLE>Cultural Dimensions of Development Policy Management: Editorial</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>Cultural Dimensions of Development Policy Management: Editorial
</H3>

<P>
by <I>Stanley Please</I> 
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(2) August 1994:
pages 2-3</I> </CENTER><HR>

<P>
&quot;Civilisations on the rise&quot; asserted the <I>Economist
</I>in a recent article, &quot;like to explain their economic
success not through some dreary shift in comparative advantage
or the pattern of technological change but by pointing to a set
of virtues unique to their culture. With the countries of East
Asia having scored one economic triumph after another for the
past two decades - and, by most guesses, set to do so for at least
another decade to come - some Asians&quot; continues the article,
'have begun proclaiming the superiority of 'Asian values' over
those of the West&quot;.
<P>
But how important are cultural values in determining the effectiveness
of development policy management.
<P>
All the contributors to this Bulletin argue that they are very
important indeed. Moreover one contributor, Daniel Etounga-Manguelle,
is convinced that they are at the heart of the failure of Africa
to develop institutions at both the micro and macro levels that
would be conducive to high rates of economic growth and poverty
alleviation.
<P>
Part of the reason for this unanimity lies in the concept and
definition of culture adopted by the contributors. This definition
goes well beyond a reference to artistic, literary, and architectural
creativity, education, and so on.
<P>
But how encompassing should the term be? Thierry Verhelst maintains
that the definition should, in effect, be an all-embracing one
although he warns about adopting too extreme an attitude. This
warning derives from his seeing culture in dynamic terms with
communities adapting their heritage to both internal and external
influences, in order to meet the &quot;challenges of their natural
and social environment&quot;. Thus culture is both determined
by and is a determinant of, individual and social behaviour.
<P>
To those who see the major weakness in African economic policy
since independence as deriving less from African culture and more
from the political power of those who gain from distorted policies
- the urban and non-agricultural sectors, the military, the employees
of inefficient state enterprises, and recipients of 'rent' incomes
from control and licensing systems - Verhelst's response is that
power relationships in political life are themselves a product
of society's culture.
<P>
But while the study of culture as a dynamic phenomenon might,
in one sense, explain everything about the success or failure
of a society to develop effective capacities for economic policy
management, in another sense it seems to explain very little in
terms of specifics. Certainly Verhelst gives no indication of
how cultural characteristics should or could be modified in order
to increase management capacity.
<P>
This shortcoming, however, is addressed head-on by Etounga-Manguelle.
He is confident that Africa is the 'sick child' of the developing
world because it has failed to recognise the weaknesses of some
of the practices and attitudes inherent in its cultural heritage.
It is these, he believes, &quot;which lie at the heart of the
institutional weaknesses of organisations in Africa&quot;. They
are &quot;fossilised standards and values&quot; which are imprisoning
Africa in an economic dilemma. While he accepts the Verhelst definition
and concept of culture, his emphasis is on the need to make culture
a tool for the improvement of economic management capacity at
both macro and micro levels.
<P>
Rejecting externally imposed changes such as &quot;structural
adjustment programmes&quot; imposed by the Bretton Woods institutions
as unsustainable, he asserts the need for internally designed
&quot;cultural adjustment programmes&quot;. Once again, as with
Verhelst, he maintains that programmes must be rooted in the cultural
history of society. But there must be a greater willingness to
reject or to modify those elements in this history which are impeding
African development.
<P>
But Etounga-Manguelle is not only a man of words. He is also a
man of action. He reports on programmes which his pan-African
organisation SADEG has already set in motion to contribute to
the 'cultural adjustment' which is required of Africans and of
African managers in order to improve the efficiency of their organisations.
He believes that experience is already demonstrating that 'cultural
adjustment' is not only necessary but eminently possible in Africa.
<P>
Julius Jeppe is equally convinced that the institutions and processes
of development policy management in South Africa will be affected
in major ways by the changeover in political power. These will
change to reflect the new dominance of Afrocentric culture with
its own distinctive characteristics compared with the Eurocentric
culture which has dominated in the past.
<P>
Already he sees signs of this change in the process by which the
ANC's Reconstruction and Development Policy document was formulated
as well as in its content, and also in many of the provisions
of the new South African Constitution. Both documents put emphasis
on the important roles of traditional communities and traditional
patterns of political power and processes. In these, consensus-building
is emphasised and the conflict and competitive characteristics
of western cultures are rejected.
<P>
Jeppe does not speculate what these changes imply for the future
quality of development policy management in South Africa. He is,
however, convinced that the impact will be pervasive on issues
such as land tenure, the development of an entrepreneurial and
risk-taking class and culture, and other critical elements in
the determination of economic policy and therefore of South Africa's
economic performance.
<P>
The term 'cultural dimensions of development policy management'
almost automatically focusses attention on the issues as they
arise in developing countries. Marinette Oomen emphasises the
error in this blinkered focus. The error is particularly important
in countries which are heavily dependent on flows of external
aid and technical assistance - most obviously African countries.
<P>
For these countries the cultural characteristics of donor countries
must be included in the concept. The aid relationship is not in
practice a partnership of equals. Both the content and style of
the relationship is donor-dominated.
<P>
More significantly, however, Oomen focusses on the narrower but
still very important issue of the culture which has developed
in the aid community -- in official aid agencies and NGO's and
in the agencies of donor and the recipient countries. Her analysis
and reflections are based in particular on a case study of Dutch
project aid in Mali.
<P>
Her paper makes uncomfortable reading with its suggestion of &quot;hidden
agendas&quot;, its concern over documents at all stages of the
project cycle being prepared by the Dutch and written in Dutch,
and its identification of documents which are supposed to define
project objectives, project achievements, and target groups, but
which seem more designed to mislead than to enlighten.
<P>
While she remains positive towards aid in general and Dutch aid
in particular, she believes all the talk about 'sustainability'
of projects and about beneficiaries 'owning' their projects and
programmes, will remain talk unless the weaknesses in the culture
of development assistance are modified along the lines of the
suggestions which emerge from her case study.
<P>
So where does this provocative discussion of cultural dimensions
of development policy management leave us? Should development
economists be pensioned-off and replaced in governments and in
aid agencies by students of culture -- presumably sociologists,
lawyers, anthropologists, political scientists, and historians?
<P>
Certainly, economists tend to view people around the world as
more alike than different; that they respond as individuals and
as groups in similar ways to market opportunities and to incentives
in terms of what they produce and purchase. Of course, 'similarity'
of responses does not mean 'identity' of responses. There is still
plenty of room for peoples' cultural characteristics and institutions
to play a role. But when it comes to policy-making, economists
believe - rightly or wrongly - that they focus on the most critical
and universal variables that determine individual, group and country
economic behaviour.
<P>
Moreover, for all the emphasis that contributors place on the
need for dynamism in a country's cultural characteristics if it
is to avoid economic stagnation and even decline, economists are
typically concerned that 'sensible' changes in policies and programmes
to generate growth and poverty reduction, will be resisted on
the grounds that the changes are not consistent with a country's
culture. This danger, as already noted, is of particular concern
where culture is defined to include powerful political interests
groups which have built up around distorted policies.
<P>
But these are questions which emerge from reflecting on the contributions
in the Bulletin in relation to policy management at the macro
level. At the micro level it is undoubtedly important that projects
and programmes are designed with the relevant cultural factors
playing a strong role. The litany of failed projects (e.g. the
'Wapenhans Report' on World Bank projects) which have often failed
due to the failure to note local cultural characteristics, is
just too long to be ignored.
<P>
Even at the micro level, however, reservations can be held about
too strong an attachment to the view that development must be
rooted in the culture of societies. Economic development necessarily
involves changing individual and group behaviour. With all respect
to Etounga-Manguelle's efforts and optimism, historically it has
at least to be noted that the dynamism which development required
has often, if not typically, come from non-indigenous and often
socially ostracised groups who do not have their 'roots' in the
country; the Jewish people in Europe, the Quakers and other non-conformists
in Great Britain, the Chinese in many east-Asian countries, the
Lebanese and Asians in various countries in Africa. In the United
States nobody had 'roots' in a traditional society except those
who were forcibly placed in reservations and were not permitted
to participate in the economic development process.
<P>
Verhelst and others can insist that: &quot;There can be no development
without roots&quot;. But it is equally valid to argue that &quot;there
can be no development if roots are too strong and inflexible&quot;
-- a proposition with which I do not believe any of the contributors,
including both Verhelst and Etounga-Manguelle, would disagree.
<HR>

