<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>On the Way to the Civil Society: Non-Governmental Organizations in Africa</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC ="../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>On the Way to the Civil Society:<br>Non-Governmental Organizations in Africa<p>
<I>Eva-Maria Bruchhaus</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 1, January-February 1994: pages 18-20</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<HR><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Non-governmental organizations were
founded in Africa later than on other continents. Meanwhile,
the early local groups have joined regional or national as
associations which are more and more pushing a political agenda.</B>
<P>
The first non-governmental organizations (NGOs) which emerged in
Africa were local branches of European relief organizations, such
as OXFAM, CARE, the leper aid society, to name only a few.
<P>
Certainly, indigenous versions existed as well, but they would
never have thought of calling themselves NGOs. These were small
clubs which were active in the social or charitable sector, started
by influential persons or the church, and funded by individual
domestic or foreign donations. For example, there was a group
in Dakar in the sixties which maintained a social center and later
developed into a respectable NGO with projects in various parts
of the country and partners all over the world.
<P>
<B>The drought as catalyst</B>
<P>
The North's willingness to help, and the inability of public services
in African countries to cope with the consequences of the first
great drought period in the seventies provided an ideal environment
for the emergence of countless initiatives and associations. Later,
they all came under the large umbrella of the so called &#171;non-governmental&#187;
organizations. Provided that they were duly registered as a nonprofit
organization  which was more or less difficult depending on country
and type of entity they could solicit and accept donations, import
goods duty-free, and implement their own projects.
<P>
In the course of this development, differences were blurred between
organizations which had been founded to execute development projects,
or rather obtain the funds for such schemes, and associations
which fall under the category of &quot;voluntary organizations&quot;,
with charitable, social, or cultural objectives. As they obtained
access to external financing, they changed into the so called FFUNGOs,
 &quot;foreign-funded non-governmental organizations&quot;. This
happened at the same time as the decision makers in the public
development institutions of the North began to question the competency
and responsibility of governments in the South. The &quot;private
agencies&quot;, as they were commonly called in those days, had
proven their capabilities during periods of famine: They had established
efficient logistic infrastructures nationwide and begun to support
village communities or other groups which were implementing local
projects. National church councils, charitable organizations,
and church coordinating agencies as well as secular organizations
managed more and more development projects, with more or less
professional expertise, sometimes even long term programs. Special
institutions were created to support local self help efforts; nongovernmental
training, research, consulting, and do documentation centers offered
their services.
<P>
Development assistance ministries and agencies in the North relied more and 
more at least verbally  on &quot;help for self help&quot;
and used the NGOs of the South as a go-between. The governments of the South tried
to divert part of the money flow for their own purposes by establishing the so called
Quasi-NGOs or restructuring existing organizations. National women's organizations, for instance, were politically usually a
&quot;mass organization&quot; of the ruling party, but
to enable them to solicit aid funds they received NGO status.
<P>
Now and then a government announces that in the future foreign
aid funds will be administered and distributed by some ministry,
but the justified fear that the money flow would slow down or
go to neighboring countries usually prevents it from actually
going through with this plan. In special situations however, such
as in Sudan, governments were successful in diverting a portion
of the aid to their own accounts through manipulations, for instance
an especially unfavorable rate of exchange for foreign NGOs.
<P>
As welcome as the non-governmental assistance was during the drought,
governments became suspicious of the NGO sector as it avoided
governmental control and established its own priorities. In former
Upper Volta  now Burkina Faso , dozens of NGOs soon became active
due to liberal registration regulations, and each one did its
own thing. To stem this uncontrolled growth many countries established
NGO coordination councils. Others created special departments
in the respective ministries in an attempt to control the activities
of the NGOs as well as obtain financing for government projects
through the NGOs.
<P>
<B>NGOs between privatization and nationalization</B>
<P>
Domestic organizations experienced a boom in the late seventies.
Money from the North certainly played a stimulating role, but
the merger of basis groups and self help organizations was a factor
as well. A new type of NGOs emerged which had much broader basis
support. Transnational networks were established, generally specializing
in a specific sector, such as promotion of exchanges between farmers
groups, or environmental protection, usually with a North south
component. One of the better known is the APICA (Association for
the promotion of African communal initiatives) with seat in Douala
and Abidjan as well as the &quot;6S&quot; (Se servir de la saison
s&ecirc;che en Savane et au Sahel - To use the dry season in the
Savannah and the Sahel) in Burkina Faso, founded by the dynamic
B. L. Ou&eacute;draogo. While these efforts were promoted or at
least tolerated in some countries, such as Kenya and Senegal,
the rigid one party regimes in other countries (for instance Mali
and Niger) viewed the emergence of such independent structures
with great apprehension and tried to force them into proscribed
forms.
<P>
When the first structural adjustment programs were initiated in
the eighties and the affected governments had to pledge to modify
their expenditures policies, the NGOs had a new role to play:
They had to fill the gaps which were created by their rationing
measures, for instance in the health care system, in the supply
of agricultural production factors, in reforestation, and literacy.
On the one hand, this meant a strengthening of their position
vis-a-vis the government; on the other hand, they were assigned
a role which could very well exceed their capabilities as well
as place them in conflict with their mission and their members.
For instance, a farmers organization may have to collect debts
which its members have incurred to pay for seeds and other inputs
but are unable to repay, because the harvest was too small as
a result of insufficient rainfall or locust devastation. Another
example is a church NGO which takes over a government project,
such as a very costly maintenance service for a village well,
for which the farmers do not have any money. The people affected
by such projects do not consider such help self-help, but simply
exploitation, and they are not going to endure it any more easily
just because it comes from a NGO rather than a government agency.
<P>
Privatization had another negative impact on the NGO environment.
Due to personnel cutbacks in the civil service sector,
especially in agriculture, well-educated people became unemployed.
They were often familiar with the rules governing cooperation
with partners in the North. What would be more obvious for these
experts than to found their own NGO to at least secure their own
survival? To be sure, very committed people have been inspired
to support local self help groups, but there are also more and
more NGO executives who are more concerned with their overhead
costs than the &quot;grassroots&quot; for whom they received the
money in the first place.
<P>
<B>Development and/or democratization</B>
<P>
Until recently, the activities of African NGOs were concentrated
on development tasks in the economic, social, cultural, and environmental
sector. They did not have many opportunities to play a political
role, beyond the very narrow limits permitted by their &quot;charitable
organization&quot; status. Some took quite some risks by helping
farmers obtain legal rights to their lands, fighting clitoral
circumcision, forced marriage, widow inheritance, and last but
not least arbitrary actions and torture. Their political role
was officially confirmed when they attended the &quot;International
Conference on Popular Participation in the Recovery and Development
Process in Africa&quot;, which convened in Arusha in February
1990. In numerous countries traditional NGOs as well as new, rather
politically orientated organizations have been involved in the
fight against one party systems and military regimes.
<P>
Today, both categories form the core of social movements in many
countries. Far more than the new and traditional political parties,
they shape the emerging civil society. At present it seems that
these new organizations are far less interested in &quot;development&quot;
than their political objectives. Some, for example, are concerned
with ending war or open violence, such as in Mali and Thank. Others
work to end violence against women and to secure their rights.
In addition, professional associations are proliferating which
not only represent their members' interests but also take a position
on political issues. Their courage is often admirable, as in the
case of the journalists union in Tchad, which has already lost
several of its leaders because of assassinations. At this time,
it is not possible to predict future developments or to forecast
whether these third generation African NGOs will stay the course
or turn to more traditional development sectors. This will probably
depend to some extent on the amount of financial support which they
can mobilize for their work. In any case, the multitude and diversity
of initiatives which were started during the past three years,
wherever it was possible, is evidence of a very lively association
life  &quot;la vie associative&quot; in the Tocqueville sense.
<P>
<B>The danger of over-extension and over-promotion</B>
<P>
There are NGOs which meet regularly with their moneylenders to
negotiate projects and financial framework terms for the next
phase. They can generally rely on a constant, often even increasing
volume of foreign aid, unless their financial behaviour is no
longer acceptable. Some NGOs, whose cooperation with the North
started with a subsidy of a few thousand Marks, a few years later
easily mobilize several millions annually. For some managers of
local NGOs,whose first trip from the village to the capital, or from
the capital to the countryside, was paid from the small group
budget, this means leaving behind not only grassroots moderation,
but also the autonomy to make decisions without regard to financial
aid. At the same time, the conviction is growing that all problems
can be solved with money.This, in turn, reduces the willingness
to fight for political solutions. In view of the sums which some
moneylenders invest in the offices, vehicles, salaries etc. of
a number of NGOs, it does not seem completely irrational to demand
that political satisfaction should be promoted as well at a time
when structural adjustment programs are severely criticized.
<P>
Massive financial promotion of NGOs usually occurs in times when
government agencies are forced to economize. Consequently, NGO
executives can afford to drive the same car (of course with four-wheel
drive and air conditioning) as the foreign expert next door, while
government employees do not even have enough money to buy gasoline
for their official cars. Offering them free rides is an easy way
to obligate them. Through their contacts with representatives
of foreign donor organizations at home, and numerous trips overseas,
some NGO executives manage the jump into politics, or start a
career as a worldwide &quot;resource person&quot; in matters of
self help movement, promotion of women, environmental protection,
human rights. This, in turn, presents an excellent opportunity
to establish new contacts for future financing.
<P>
Another danger lies in the increased competition among NGOs. Especially
during times of diminishing resources, this can lead to the promotion
of NGOs which have the best sales pitch, rather than the best
projects or the best programs. As a rule,
money from several large donors flows to these organizations for
decades, while smaller, unknown, but much fresher and more dynamic
organizations lack the necessary funds to pay for items such as
travel and printing costs to publicize their goals.
<P>
In order to be as effective as possible, African NGOs have to
try continuously to keep a balance between their basis, their
government, and their donors. This requires political courage,
a high sense of responsibility, self discipline, professionalism,
and financial moderation on the part of their managers. All participants
can help establish and preserve this fragile balance: The basis
 as far as it exists  controls the NGO executives so that they
cannot abuse their power; the government creates a suitable legal
framework and a positive climate in which the NGOs can blossom:
the moneylenders provide financial aid, while taking care not to
make the NGOs even more dependent. Particularly the last demand
seems illusory: All African NGOs are more or less FFUNGOs, and
as long as the prevailing macro economic framework conditions
continue to exist, nothing will change in this respect. But at
least this dependency should be kept at minimum. 

<p>
<HR>
