<HEAD>

<TITLE>The SADCC Experience</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><IMG src="../images/dpmf.jpg"></H3>

<H3>The SADCC Experience</H3>

<P>
by <I>Paul Goodison and Bernadette Nee</I> 
<P>
Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:
pages 12-14</I> </CENTER><HR>

<H4>Background</H4>

<P>
The system of functional regional cooperation established by 
SADCC at the beginning of the 1980s was significantly different
to the mechanisms for regional cooperation  elsewhere in Africa.
SADCC emphasis, given ideological differences and on-going political
and military confrontation was to coordinate development activities
in a limited number of sectors where clear benefits could be gained
from regional approaches. The organisational and institutional
arrangements were decentralised with the various governments responsible
for coordinating programmes in individual sectors and with only
a very small central secretariat (see box).
<P>
SADCC sought to build cooperation in areas of obvious mutual advantage
to at least two of its nine founding members and to avoid those
where controversy was likely and where the pressures towards organisational
dissolution would become unmanageable.
<H4>SADCC Organisational Structures</H4>

<P>
A major concern from the outset was to establish structures which
built up mutual confidence between the various governments. This
led to all major decisions being taken at a senior political level
and on the basis of consensus. Such decisions have, since the
inception of SADCC, been taken through sector specific Ministerial
level meetings and Heads of States meetings. 
<P>
These meetings have been backed-up by a small central bureaucracy
and a system of nationally based Sector Coordinating Units (SCUs)
which liaise closely with Sector Contact Points (SCP) in the governments
of each member state. At the national level, overall coordination
of the activities of the various SCPs is the responsibility of
the National Contact Point (NCP), which is normally the Ministry
of Finance or National Planning. 
<P>
Responsibility for coordinating the implementation of agreed programmes
is not with the central Secretariat, but with the SCU of the Government
having responsibility for coordination in that sector. As a result
of this highly decentralised structure, which actively involves
each Member State in some aspect of regional coordination, the
bulk of the work of SADCC actually takes place within the member
states themselves, through the SCUs.
<P>
This means that in SADCC countries the quality of the national
administration, its knowledge, expertise and motivation, is vital
to the success of regional cooperation.
<H4>The Role of Sector Coordinating Units</H4>

<P>
The SCUs formulate, monitor and amend the sectoral and project
components of the SADCC Programme of Action. The SCUs liaise and
consult with both the SADCC Member States (through the SCPs in
national ministries) and the international cooperating partners,
as well as providing leadership and technical services for the
implementation of sectoral programmes. A further important task
of the SCUs is to prepare sectoral strategies and to define criteria
for the inclusion of projects in the Programme of Action. The
SCUs are also involved in project identification, screening, appraisal
and design in close consultation with the member states where
the project is located. The SCUs may also assist in negotiations
on financing and other technical arrangements.
<P>
The SCUs, however, with the exception of region wide studies,
are not involved in actual project and programme implementation,
which remains the responsibility of the relevant national departments
in the country in which the activities are located.
<P>
Not only is responsibility for coordinating activities in individual
sectors allocated to individual governments, but the SCPs in each
country carry the primary responsibility for seeing that their
national interests are fully accommodated within regional programmes.
Indeed, the SCPs are the backbone of  SADCCs highly decentralised
structure.
<H4>The Role of the Sector Contact Point</H4>

<P>
Since the SCPs are the main interface between the SADCC regional
structures and national governments, it is essential that they
have a clear understanding of the &quot;institutional connections
between the national administration and the regional cooperation
body&quot; (Stronck). While the responsibilities of the SCP relate
both to regional sectoral policy formulation and the administration
and implementation of the SADCC programme of action, it is not
always clear where the responsibilities of the SCP end and those
of the SCU begin. Equally the SCP are not always familiar with
what realistically can be expected from the SCU, how to follow
up with the SCU and who in the SCU deals with the particular areas
of concern to individual national SCPs.
<P>
While the initiative for driving forward regional sectoral policy
formulation rests with the SCUs, which respond to the policy direction
provided by the relevant Council of Ministers, the national inputs
provided by the SCPs in each national administration provides
both a basis from which policy direction is given and a critical
mirror for specific proposals coming out of the SCUs.
<P>
With regard to the establishment and implementation of the project
based programme of action, the Sector Contact Points in national
administrations carry out a number of important functions. These
functions include: submitting projects to the SCU for inclusion
in the programme of action; following up with the SCU; securing
funding for the implementation of projects; compiling and forwarding
project progress reports to the SCU; providing, in association
with the NCP, national input into the programming exercises with
individual cooperating partners; and briefing ofministerial delegations.
<P>
In terms of fund raising and implementation of projects and programmes
in the SADCC programme of action, primary responsibility lies
with the SCP, where implementation is physically located primarily
in one member state. This is vitally important when considering
the administrative arrangements for SADCC cooperation with external
funding agencies.
<P>
The fact that primary responsibility for fund raising for projects
physically located in one SADCC country lies with the SCP of the
country concerned (and the other appropriate government departments
involved in external resource mobilisation) is not always understood
by the SCPs. The extent to which cooperation and consultations
with, on the one hand the SCU and on the other the national bodies
responsible for external resource mobilisation, as necessary,
is not always clearly understood by the SCPs.
<P>
As a result, of the six functions of the SCP identified above,
often SCP's only clearly understand their responsibilities for
project submission and reporting to the SCU.
<P>
This demonstrates the importance of detailed knowledge being developed
in the national administration (amongst the various SCP's) of
the formal institutional and procedural setting of  SADCC and
how it functions in the various national administrations. 
<P>
There is furthermore often a major problem at the national level
in ensuring that information flows and that line ministry officials
involved in the actual implementation of projects included in
the SADCC programme of action, understand just what the roles
of the various SADCC structures are.
<P>
This highlights a further point made by Stronck in considering
the national institutional arrangements for managing regional
cooperation, namely the importance of coordination, both formal
and informal, in ensuring that information flows and is acted
upon.
<P>
Informal coordination is often somewhat lacking within the SADCC
system at the national level, in part because the division of
responsibilities in the national administration is not clearly
understood by the various national actors involved in dealing
with SADCC. As Stronck has pointed out, such a clear division
of responsibilities is important for ensuring effective national
involvement in regional activities.
<H4>The Role of the National Contact Point</H4>

<P>
An NCP is responsible for bringing together national perspectives
on current policy debates in the SADCC. It is particularly important
at the present time given the transition which is under way to
a Development Community. It has a central role in ensuring that
the member state benefits fully from SADCC regional programmes
and that regional policy development supports the broad social
and economic development objectives established at the national
level.
<P>
In certain SADCC countries there is a problem in the self perception
of the role of the NCP. This is seen as limited to assisting in
the SADCC Annual Consultative Conference. There are occasions
when the NCP does not feel any responsibility for ensuring coherence
between national and regional policies nor for coordinating the
activities of SCPs and making sure that they fully carry out their
regional responsibilities.

<P>
<center><h3>SADC Sectoral Responsibilities</h3>
<table border=2>
<tr><td>
ANGOLA<td> Energy
<tr><td>
BOTSWANA<td> Animal Diseases &amp; Agricultural Research 
<tr><td>
LESOTHO<td> Land Utilisation and Soil Conservation
<tr><td>
MALAWI<td> Wildlife Forestry &amp; Soil  Conservation
<tr><td>
MOZAMBIQUE<td>  Transport, Communications, Information and Culture
<tr><td>
NAMIBIA<td> Sea Fisheries
<tr><td>
SWAZILAND<td>  Manpower Development
<tr><td>
TANZANIA<td> Industry and Trade
<tr><td>
ZAMBIA<td>  Mining
<tr><td>
ZIMBABWE<td> Agriculture and Food Security
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>
<P>
Unless at the national level the lead role of the NCP is strengthened
and problems of internal coordination between the NCP, SCP and
even Sub-Sector Contact Points are resolved then regional cooperation
is likely to be seen as increasingly irrelevant by middle level
management in SADCC Governments. This would be likely to have
serious implications for the future development of this unique
functional cooperation body.
<P>
This reinforces the point of Stronck, in a completely different
institutional context, of the importance of establishing a clear
division of competencies within the national administration, and
a mechanism for arbitration and conflict management between the
various national actors responsible for dealing with the regional
body.
<H4>Overview of Shortcomings</H4>

<P>
In many SADCC member states neither the national contact point
nor the sectoral contact points are particularly well equipped
to carry their regional responsibilities. In part this reflects
the fact that they commonly retain national as well as regional
responsibilities, although this is to be expected given the capacity
constraints facing many of the national administrations in southern
Africa.
<P>
Strengthening national inputs into regional policy debates is
likely to be crucial in the coming years as the SADCC seeks to
make the transition to a Southern African Development Community.
If the national capacity to take part meaningfully in regional
policy debates is not enhanced then the dangers of fragment- ation
will increase as the costs and benefits of the construction of
such a Community are unevenly spread. This issue will need to
be directly addressed and cannot be side stepped by placing emphasis
on the development of centralised regional structures, although
regional structures may also need to be further developed as the
demands placed on them by better functioning national structures
increase.
<P>
This gives added weight to Stronck's conclusion that &quot;If
the administrative system to manage domestic policy is lacking
in quality and performance, it cannot be expected that it will
be any better in managing regional policy&quot;.
<P>
However it is important for SADCC international cooperating partners
to bear in mind that as Stronck has pointed out the quality and
success of the national level in relating to regional bodies depends
on the &quot;internal coherence of the administrative apparatus&quot;,
which in turn is largely built upon a &quot;high degree of administrative
tradition and culture&quot;.
<P>
This is only now being developed in Southern Africa and it suggests
that external funding agencies should seek wherever possible to
ensure that they themselves understand the institutional arrangements
and procedures of SADCC (see box), and that their managerial arrangements
for regional cooperation are consistent with them.
<p>

<table border=2>
<tr><td><center><B>Understanding Institutional Arrangements / the Case of the
EU and SADC</B></center>
<P>
Despite the genuine commitment of the European Community (now
the European Union) to support regional cooperation and integration
efforts in the SADC region, its administrative arrangements for
implementing this commitment sometimes prove to be counter-productive.
The initial operational phases of EU-SADC negotiations to determine
a regional cooperation envelope, the sectoral components, and
the short-list of projects within each sectoral component work
efficiently. It is when the EU selects projects for financing
from this short-list that problems arise. These problems continue
through all the following phases of project preparation, appraisal
and implementation.
<P>
The difficulties arise because, once selected by the SADC Secretariat
as a regional project, responsibility under SADC procedures for
the detailed phases of execution, including financing, rest with
the agencies in the country in which the project is to be implemented.
This isnot always understood and acted upon by the EU desk officers
in Brussels and the EU delegates in the SADC countries. As a consequence,
substantial delays may occur in the commitment of funds and in
the implementation of regional projects.
<P>
More generally, EU delegations appear to accord low priority to
both the administrative management of EU support to regional cooperation
with SADC, especially preceding the signing of a financing proposal,
and to following regional policy debates in the sector for which
the country of assignment is responsible under SADC structures.
The EU, and donors more widely, should be relating to and providing
support for national institutions implementing programmes of regional
cooperation. They can most effectively do so by operating within
established regional frameworks when these are working efficiently
rather than following their own donor-oriented procedures.</td></tr>
</table>

<p>
<hr>
