<html>
<header>
<title>AAPAM's Contribution to Civil Service Reform</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
AAPAM's Contribution to Civil Service Reform</h3>
by <i>Ali D. Yahaya</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 3(1) August 1995: pages 15-16</i>
</center>
<hr>
Since its establishment in l962, the African Association for Public Administration and
Management (AAPAM) has concentrated its attention on improving the performance of the civil
services of Africa as an essential part of the need to advance institutional development and
capacity building in these countries. These efforts were reflected in the reforms which were
undertaken in several public services in the l960's and l970's.
<p>
The philosophy and rationale of these reforms was to be found in a reform model which focussed
exclusively on the public service to the neglect of other sub-systems which impact on the public
service. This narrow focus reflected the wider political ideology and economic strategy which
gave the state a dominant role in society and in the economy. But this ideology and strategy did
not prevent the economic crisis which overwhelmed Africa during the l980's -- it might even
have contributed to the severity of the crisis.
<p>
<h3>Reforms under Structural Adjustment Programmes</h3>

The outcome of this crisis was the introduction of structural adjustment programmes in many
African countries. These typically included measures to promote civil service reform. However,
the measures had basically the same focus as those from the reform programmes of the 60's and
70's with their exclusive concern for the public service and their ignoring of other sub-systems.
Their major difference with the past has been in their emphasis on two components which
complement each other -- public service efficiency and cost containment.
<p>
First, improved public service efficiency and effectiveness is sought through reorganisation and
restructuring of government so that it can play a more facilitating and catalytic role rather than
the role of service delivery. Thus this component concentrates to begin with on ensuring a clearer
definition of departmental and agency functions including the possibilities of abolition or of
privatisation of these functions. It goes on to address issues of manning levels, of procedures for
redundancy, of methods by which pay can be better related to performance, and in general to
address ways in which management systems can be strengthened through, for instance, revised
financial procedures, new technologies, and a new culture of service to the public. At the same
time, and very crucially, this component also concentrates on measures to improve the capacity
of the civil service to undertake policy analytical work including the development of a strategic
planning culture. 
<p>
Second, and related to the first component, is the focus on cost containment. This normally
involves both the downsizing of the civil service and thus to issues of redundancy, and relating
pay, promotion and other rewards more closely to performance.
<p>
<h3>A Broader Context for Civil Service Reform</h3>

But despite these far-reaching reform initiatives under structural adjustment programmes, the
rationale of the reforms is still anchored in the earlier and narrower perspective, namely of public
administration and management in the context of Max Weber's notion of rational bureaucracy
and the commitment to replicate this form of bureaucracy in Africa. Broader issues relating to
the values of the political system, the network of social partners engaged in a process of
interaction for the purpose of governance, and the development and strengthening of the private
sector and of civil society more widely, hardly feature in these reform agendas.
<p>
It is in recognition of this major limitation in previous efforts at civil service reform that the
Commonwealth Secretariat, the UNECA, and AAPAM are sponsoring the establishment of
Centres of Policy Analysis and Management Training in Africa. The intention is that these
Centres will bring together people both from the public sector and from civil society. Initially
they are to be established in Abuja, Nigeria; Dakar, Senegal; Nairobi, Kenya; Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania; Maputo, Mozambique; and Gaborone, Botswana. Government 'ownership' is a key
prerequisite for the establishment of these Centres.
<p>
<h3>The Programme of the New Training Centres</h3>

Building capacity for good governance lies at the heart of these new centres. The issues to be
addressed will include the form, the processes and the relationships, especially between the
public sector and civil society. High-level policy seminars will be organised to bring politicians,
managers, administrators, and academics together to discuss emerging policy issues both of a
wide developmental and macro nature as well as those at the sectoral and micro levels. Problems
of decentralisation, empowerment, the environment and natural resource management, as well
as the relationship between policy and stakeholders will be covered.
<p>
Appropriate training for senior managers will also be developed. This in particular will require
much closer collaboration with university-based institutes of administration and management.
AAPAM together with the other sponsoring institutions will participate in the Joint Board of
Studies of the universities to ensure that the perceptions of the new centres are fully taken into
account in determining the structure and content of degree courses. The exchange of faculty
members and the organisation of joint activities is envisaged. As a consequence it is intended to
avoid duplication of programmes while maintaining a high standard of service.
<p>
Finally, it must be reiterated that although the proposal to establish these centres is primarily
public sector focussed, the wider objective is to serve as a facility for forging a partnership
between the social actors in the political system; to develop centres that will bring the state and
civil society more closely together and thereby foster the linkages which are required to achieve
good governance.
<p>
<h3>Further Information</h3>

For further information on this initiative to generate partnership in development cooperation,
please contact:
<p>
Secretary-General, African Association for Public Administration and Management
(AAPAM)<br>
P.O. Box 48677<br>
NAIROBI, KENYA
<p>
<HR>
