<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Crises and Disasters: A Challenge for Development Cooperation</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Crises and Disasters:<br> A Challenge for Development Cooperation<p>
<I>Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development (BMZ)</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 6, November-December 1996: pages 8-11</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<Hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>The number of natural disasters and their victims has drastically
increased worldwide in recent years. True, there have not been
more disasters such as earthquakes and hurricanes. But those that
have occurred have caused greater damage because of higher population
densities or overuse of the land. The secretariat of the International
Decade for Natural Disaster Reduction (IDNDR) estimates that in
1992 natural disasters across the world cost national economies
a total of $ 60 billion, or 10 times the figure for 1960.</B>
<P>
Crises and disasters often destroy the development policy work
of many years. Countries torn by lasting conflicts lack the prerequisites
for effective, sustainable development cooperation. Thus crises
and disasters are not only a challenge to humanitarian aid, for
which in Germany the Foreign Ministry is responsible. They are
also increasingly becoming a problem of the Ministry for Economic
Cooperation and Development (BMZ) which is in charge of development
aid.
<P>
Humanitarian aid and sustainable development cooperation differ
not only in their objectives and methods, but also in their time
horizons and preliminary phases. Thus it can happen that humanitarian
aid runs out before development cooperation work has begun because
certain prerequisites are still lacking or must be appraised.
Such situations occur in particular following the end of armed
conflicts or crises.
<P>
That is why development policy is departing ever more frequently
from its real terrain and operating in a grey area between short-term,
purely humanitarian aid and the building of sustainable structures
oriented on the long-term. In this situation it has to secure without
gaps the transition from survival aid to reconstruction, thereby
relaying the foundation stone for self-supporting development.
<P>
The United Nations has coined the term &quot;continuum&quot; for
that. But &quot;continuum&quot; should not be interpreted as the
linear sequence of individual phases. In real life, humanitarian
aid, emergency aid measures, reconstruction activities and disaster
control work often take place at the same time.
<P>
<B>BMZ emergency and refugee aid to date</B>
<P>
In food aid, the BMZ has long pursued the strategy of strengthening
the capability of victims of crises and disasters to help themselves
and achieving transition to longer-term food security by running
food-for-work or cash-for-work programmes. However, the proportion
of pure emergency aid measures in this sector has also increased
steadily in recent years. Refugee aid projects have also for years
been financed in the context of Technical Cooperation. These projects,
such as the setting up of disaster control structures, reintegration
of refugees in their homelands, and reforestation in refugee areas
are already medium to long-term development cooperation. The BMZ
also finances similar projects as part of its cooperation on a
trust basis with the UNHCR and church aid organizations.
<P>
According to provisional figures, the BMZ in 1995 provided about
DM 300 million (1994: DM 305 million) for the sectors of emergency
aid, rehabilitation, alleviating the consequences of fleeing,
reintegration and emergency food aid. The latter accounted for
45 per cent, the largest share of the total. Southern Africa (especially
Mozambique and Rwanda), and Southeast Europe (Bosnia-Herzegovina),
with 56 per cent and 13 per cent respectively, were the regional
focal points.
<P>
Except for emergency food aid, however, these approaches were
unable fully to meet the demand of the &quot;continuum&quot;.
That is, the gradual and seamless transition from humanitarian
aid to reconstruction assistance and development cooperation.
In particular, major crises such as in Somalia and Rwanda have
shown in recent years that except in food aid the BMZ has little
scope to:
<P>
<ul>
<li>react fast and flexibly to crises;
<P>
<li>react to UN calls for aid (consolidated appeals); and
<P>
<li>cooperate with the emergency aid of experienced NGOs.</ul>
<P>
<b>"Food, Emergency and Refugee Aid&quot;</b> 
<P>
At the end of 1995, however, the budgetary law prerequisites for
BMZ emergency aid going beyond food aid were decisively improved
with a new budget item &quot;Food, Emergency and Refugee Aid&quot;,
even if the money allocated to it for 1996 was not enough to meet
its requirements. Due to price rises, the cash appropriation of
DM 116 million was only just sufficient to fulfil Bonn's legal
obligation to the International Wheat Agreement of 1986. With
full utilisation of the funds provided, only something in the
order of DM 2530 million remained for the new task of emergency
assistance beyond food aid.
<P>
The goal of the BMZ food aid financed out of the new budget item
is to contribute to the food security of the target groups (e.g.
drought victims, refugees, expellees) by supplying and distributing
grain, grain products and other food, and strengthening the recipients'
capability for selfhelp.
<P>
The objective of the non-food emergency aid financed from the item
is to contribute to coping with and overcoming distress situations
and to the care and repatriation of refugees and expellees. The
method is to create or restore a basic social and infrastructure
supply, especially in the sectors of drinking water, sewage disposal,
social services, housing and transport, as well as strengthen
self-help capabilities.
<P>
The emergency aid phase is marked by insecure general conditions
and uncertainty over the duration of the emergency. In the case
of natural disasters in politically stable countries, it is relatively
easy to restore normal conditions quickly. In the case of political
crises or even armed conflicts, often linked with refugee flows
and expulsions, the task is much more difficult. The BMZ's emergency
assistance therefore consists of measures that are no longer pure
survival aid, but also do not have to meet the strict criteria
of sustainability. Such measures are as a rule shortterm (315
months), pick up on previous humanitarian aid and slot into an
internationally agreed overall concept of disaster aid. The measures
are already manifesting structural impacts, are to lead to longerterm
programmes, and prevent greater consequential disaster damage.
<P>
Typical measures of such a developmentoriented emergency aid are:
<P>
<ul>
<li>securing basic supplies of food for refugees and providing
emergency accommodation;
<P>
<li>promoting self-help activities in emergencies in order to
maintain selfinitiative, e.g. through appropriate small-scale
funds or food or cash-for-work programmes;
<P>
<li>creating or restoring basic supplies in the sectors of drinking
water, sanitation facilities and accommodation;
<P>
<li>creating or restoring schools and basic health services;
<P>
<li>controlled firewood supply and firewood-saving measures
in refugee camps in order to stem environmental damage;
<P>
<li>food-for-work projects to build retention basins for drinking
water supply and waste water disposal for refugees and local people;
<P>
<li>distribution of seed to groups that were previously dependent
upon humanitarian food aid; and
<P>
<li>promotion of demobilisation measures.</ul>
<P>
The emergency assistance measures are implemented by the GTZ,
international aid organisations, NGOs or Federal government offices.
The BMZ makes efforts for good cooperation with the experienced
national and international organisations working in emergency
and refugee aid. It is also keen that the various organisations'
individual measures in emergency aid programmes complement each
other uniformly. In view of tight funds, concentration on a few
key regions is unavoidable. In 1996 these were Bosnia, Angola
and the Caucasus states of Georgia and Azerbaijan. Less extensive
measures were planned for Rwanda, Mozambique and Afghanistan,
among others.
<P>
<B>Disaster precautions and crisis prevention</B>
<P>
The greater the demands for emergency aid, the more important
become disaster preparedness and crisis prevention. If development
cooperation wants to do more than a repair job, it must together
with other policy sectors be much more preventively active in
order to reduce the developing countries' susceptibility to crises
and disasters. Disaster preparedness and crisis prevention are
therefore important cross-sector tasks of development cooperation.
Building on an analysis of the causes of conflicts and disasters,
development cooperation's existing instruments should be used
more intensively to eliminate them or limit possible damage. For
example: taking account of the risk of disasters in designing
infrastructure measures; setting up disaster control structures
and early warning systems; and measures to promote human rights
and democratisation. Various development cooperation instruments
such as Technical Cooperation, food security linked with agricultural
early warning systems, or initial and advanced training have already
anchored the preparedness for natural disasters as an important
task.
<P>
The environmental impact assessment obligatory for every project
now includes appraisal of natural disaster risks and consideration
of preventive measures.
<P>
At the beginning of the current Federal Parliament in 1994 the
BMZ declared crisis prevention a priority of its developmental
work in the next few years. It emphasised the criteria of human
rights, legal security and participation of the people. But at
the same time it identified pressure towards a marketfriendly
and social market order. These are areas the BMZ will purposefully
support in a country because of their importance for political
and social stability. This is how &quot;crisis prevention&quot;
can be realised in practice. But &quot;classic&quot; government
development cooperation, especially Technical Cooperation projects
dealing with the use of natural resources, is also applied to
the causes of crises. In the preparation and designing of all
projects that touch upon potential for social conflict, more attention
must be paid to aspects of prevention. In the different phases
of conflicts and open crises, the BMZ must differentiate in applying
its instruments. 
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on January 14, 1997<BR>
</I>This article is made available on EUFORIC by kind permission
of the publishers - E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach
10 08 01, D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax:
+49 69 7501-4855.<BR>
