<head>
<title> NEPAL</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> NEPAL</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/nepal.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=500 height=323 alt="Map of Nepal">
</p>
<hr>

<p><b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	22.5 million

<p>Population growth rate	2.6% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	128
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	39%
access to safe water
 
Adult literacy rate	26%

<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID has been working in Nepal since 1982. Programmes in four development areas are reaching
more than 100,000 people. 

<p>In the mountainous region of Sindhupalchowk, many of the projects are now self-supporting so, as
local people keep new facilities going, ACTIONAID is free to carry on the work in other villages. 

<p>In Nawalparasi and Sindhuli ACTIONAID is working with local communities on tackling environmental
problems, particularly deforestation, which have led to lower crop yields and food shortages. Work
began in Kanchanpur in 1995 with an emphasis on creating community organisations which, from the
outset, will assume full responsibility for planning and implementing the development activities
themselves.

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in Nepal:</h3>

<p><ul><li>A programme of teaching skills enables people to make and sell goods in local markets. For
example, villagers have been taught leather tanning and how to produce and market leather goods. The
income from this helps families to buy land or oxen, or to repay loans and reduce crippling interest
payments, which can vary from 40 -150 per cent a year with local money lenders.

<p><li>Only a third of families in the Sinhupalchowk area are able to grow enough food to subsist. By
introducing new crops - including those which replenish the soil - and varying growing periods to
avoid bad weather, the land is yielding more. Once harvested, crops are protected by rat traps and
seed bins. Community workers are trained in agricultural techniques and then their knowledge is
passed on to other villagers so the whole community will benefit.  

<p><li>exists one of the lowest literacy rates in the world with children in remote rural areas too
far from schools to attend on a daily basis or required to work long hours collecting firewood,
fodder or helping in the house, so that they do not have the time to attend. In response, ACTIONAID
has helped villagers to establish Community Learning Centres. Often no more than a cowshed, these
centres are used to provide literacy teaching for children and adults at times that are convenient to
them, including early morning and late in the evening.
</ul></font>

