<HEAD>
<title>Recipient Responsibility: Developing Countries Must Chart Their Own Development</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<h3>Recipient Responsibility:<br>Developing Countries Must Chart Their Own Development
<P>
<i>Per Grimstad</i></h3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 2, March-April 1996: pages 22 - 23</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Norway is a developed country with one of
the best aid records in the world. But the
government changed its aid policy five years ago. The new concept
is now based on the
principle of &quot;recipient responsibility&quot;.</B>
<P>
In the last fifty years, rich countries have donated approximately
one thousand billion US dollars in aid to the Third World. Nevertheless,
there are more poor people in the world than ever before and development
trends are negative in many developing countries. Not only that,
the situation seems to be worst in the countries that have received
most aid. In recognition of the fact that the development we hoped
for had not occurred, the Norwegian development cooperation authorities
changed their aid policy five years ago. The main concept of the
new Norwegian aid strategy is <I>recipient responsibility</I>, which
means that responsibility for ordering priorities and planning
and implementing development projects must rest with the recipient
countries themselves. If they wish to receive Norwegian aid, recipient
countries must reflect the same priorities in their own budgets
and development plans . And they must prove that they are doing
what they have said they will do.
<P>
We realised that we could not assume responsibility for development
in countries thousands of miles away. That our own genuine desire
to help was not enough. And that we were not the right people
to be telling developing countries what had to be done to promote
development.
<P>
The only players who can and must take responsibility for development
in the Third World are the poor countries themselves. They must
themselves plot the course they have to take to drag their countries
out of the economic morass in which they find themselves. This
may sound like a brutal resignation of responsibility but is in
reality essential emphasis on a responsibility that has always
existed.
<P>
It is the developing countries themselves who have the best knowledge
of local conditions and the direction in which they wish their
countries to develop. The responsibility of the rich part of the
world must be to support the poor countries' own efforts. And
we must take this responsibility seriously.
<P>
With recipient responsibility, local ownership of projects becomes
stronger, the likelihood of projects fitting into countries' long term
development plans increases and expertise remains in the developing
country after the project has ended.
<P>
At the same time, there is a stronger proprietary interest in
achieving results. The focus of developing countries' administrations
is diverted from fighting for the biggest possible piece of the
aid cake to concentrating on the country's own development. Since
the country must give priority to development measures in its
own budgets to a greater extent than before, it gives priority
to measures which fulfil its own needs rather than measures it
believes we will approve.
<P>
<B>It works, but it takes time</B>
<P>
Bangladesh is one example illustrating that recipient responsibility
works. Aid funding from abroad accounts for only 6 per cent of
Bangladesh's GNP This is not much compared with other developing
countries with long traditions as aid recipients. Forty per cent
of aid projects in Bangladesh are financed by Bangladesh itself.
This is a lot in comparison with other developing countries. Economic
trends are favourable, with low inflation, increased foreign exchange
reserves and growing access to local currency. Bangladesh still
has an extremely long way to go, but the fact that the negative
development trend has been reversed gives hope for the future.
<P>
Of course, I have no grounds for saying that the trend in Bangladesh
has been turned around because Norwegian aid authorities and certain
multilateral donor agencies are adhering to the principle of recipient
responsibility. This is precisely my point. The trend has been
turned around because the Bangladesh authorities have realised
that if their country is to achieve genuine development they must
take the responsibility themselves.
<P>
If we are to make recipient responsibility work, we must be patient.
There are many players in the aid arena and not all developing
countries' authorities are equally supportive of the principle
of recipient responsibility. For many bureaucrats in developing
countries, it is more tempting to cooperate with donors who make
fewer demands for effort on their own part.
<P>
Luckily, the international donor community seems to be gradually
accepting the principle of recipient responsibility. We are seeing
a change of attitude on the part of both donors and recipients.
Even though, at the moment, it is more a matter of words than
actions.
<P>
Although the principle of recipient responsibility is now gaining
acceptance, both among leading donors and in certain recipient
countries, we must not fall into the trap of believing that a
change in aid strategy will bring immediate changes in the status
of developing countries. The tasks are so enormous, the players
so many and habits so ingrained that we must realise that it will
take time.
<P>
<B>Our own needs must not prevent improvement</B>
<P>
We must give the developing countries the opportunity of utilising
their expertise in areas that are important for their development.
For example, many developing countries are highly experienced
in hosting delegations from donor organisations but seem unable
to establish functioning societies that will benefit their own
populations.
<P>
After fifty years of aid delegations, certain ministries and institutions
are capable of preparing and hosting several visits a week from
various donor countries and organisations in a highly professional
manner. Very well prepared, extremely well versed in the donors'
priorities, they seldom have problems in presenting proposals
that they know will find favour with the donors. At the same time,
they are unable to establish a properly functioning tax collection
system. Perhaps this is not surprising when such large resources
are expended in acquiring and administering aid and aid donors.
<P>
<B>Adjusting donor ambitions</B>
<P>
We, the donors, must reexamine our own ambitions. We must face
facts and realise the limitations of what we can achieve with
development aid. As I have said before, the rich countries cannot
take responsibility for the economic development of countries
on the other side of the world. We know how difficult it is to
predict and plan development, even for wealthy countries  which have a functioning democracy and a functioning government
administration, are far advanced on environmental issues, respect
human rights, have a free press and last but not least, have a
sound economic base. Even in our own countries, where all the
framework conditions which we so much want to help the developing
countries to acquire are in place, we see failed projects, corruption,
embezzlement and development which does not move at the planned
rate in the planned direction.
<P>
What we <I>can </I>do something about, and must take responsibility
for, is ensuring that Norwegian aid is administered in such a
way that it complements the developing countries' own efforts.
That we do not provide money for projects which are diametrically
opposed to the country's own real priorities. That we ensure that
aid funds are used for projects which ensure sustainable development,
strengthen human rights, show due regard for environmental considerations
and enable the developing countries themselves to build institutions
that will create functioning societies.
<P>
So, if necessary, we should block or postpone aid funds when projects
go wrong or corruption is rife.
<P>
The fact that we have made many mistakes in the past cannot lead
us to refrain from doing anything in the future for fear of making
new mistakes. The developing countries' problems are too serious
and our own obligations too pressing. No-one - in either rich or
poor countries - will benefit from continuing negative development in the Third World.
For the poor countries, it will lead to even worse disasters,
overpopulation and human suffering. For the rich countries, it
will lead to serious security risks and, last but not least, strong
pressures on the environment.
<P>
One of the visions of any aid organisation, governmental or non-governmental,
is to help make itself superfluous. The majority of Norwegian
bilateral aid is implemented by Norwegian companies, institutions,
voluntary organisations, research communities, cultural workers
and public administrative bodies. The Norwegian aid authorities
play the role of coordinator and allocator of resources. In the
longer term, our goal is for NORAD and the other aid organisations
to be able to withdraw, and for these Norwegian players and their
partners in cooperation in the host country to continue to cooperate
as equal partners. In the same way as international cooperation
takes place between Norway and other countries in other parts
of the world. 
<p>
<HR>
