<center><img src="../images/cedla.gif"></center><br clear><br>  
<H2><center>Spanish Foreign Policy in the Caribbean
<br>
</h2><H4>by <i>Jean Grugel</i></H4>
<h4>Full text of an article published in the<i>  European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies,</i><br>number 50, June 1991: pp. 135 - 153.
<p></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#abstract">Abstract/Resumen</a>
<li><a href="#intro">Introduction</a>
<li><a href="#cont">Contemporary Spanish Foreign Policy: Some Preliminary Comments</a>
<li><a href="#aims">The Aims of Spanish Policy in the Caribbean</a>
<li><a href="#econ">Economic Ties - Spain and the Caribbean</a>
<li><a href="#trade">Trade</a>
<li><a href="#inv">Investment</a>
<li><a href="#loans">Loans and Commercial Credits</a>
<li><a href="#aid">Aid</a>
<li><a href="#puente">El Puente: Spanish Mediation in Europe</a>
<li><a href="#special">The 'Special Relationship': Spain and Cuba</a>
<li><a href="#quinto">1992 and the Quinto Centenario</a>
<li><a href="#educ">Educational and Cultural Policy</a>
<li><a href="#spain">Spain and tbe Non-Spanish Caribbean</a>
<li><a href="#con">Conclusions</a>
<li><a href="#notes">Notes</a>
<li><a href="#ref">References</a>
</ul><hr>
<P>
<a name=abstract></a><H3>Abstract/Resumen</H3>
<P>
This article discusses contemporary Spanish  policy in the Caribbean,
focussing principally  though not exclusively on the  Spanish-speaking
Caribbean.  Spanish-Caribbean relations are conceptualised
 as unequal and the relationship rests  historically on ties
which developed between  an ex-imperial power and its ex-colonies.
 Nonetheless, Spain's projection in the  Caribbean is markedly different
from that of  other ex-colonial powers in the region in a  number
of respects and less obviously merits  being described as 'neo-colonial'.
After an  analysis of the aims of Spanish policy in the  region,
the article suggests that Spanish  policy makers fail to distinguish
sufficiently  between Latin America and the Caribbean. 
Major aspects of contemporary Spanish  policy are then discussed:
economic relations;  Spain's mediation in the EC of issues relating
 to the Spanish-speaking Caribbean; the 'special  relationship' with
Cuba; the Quinto Centenario;  educational and cultural policy,
and finally  relations with the non-Spanish speaking  Caribbean.
The article concludes that though Spanish relations have intensified
with the  Caribbean since the transition to democracy in 
Spain, Spain's international oblgations and  economic commitments
globally will condition  and limit any further projection in the
region.
<P>
El art&#237;culo es una investigaci&#243;n de la pol&#237;tica  exterior
espa&#241;ola en la &eacute;poca contempor&aacute;nea  en el Caribe,
concentr&#225;ndose en mayor parte  en el Caribe espa&#241;ol.
La relaci&#243;n se remonta  historicamente en la &eacute;poca colonial
y se  conceptualizan las relaciones entre Espa&ntilde;a y
el  Caribe como desiguales. Sin embargo, la  proyecci&#243;n espa&ntilde;ola
en la regi&#243;n merece  menos la descripci&oacute;n 'neo-colonialista' comparada
con las  pol&#237;ticas de otros ex-potencias imperiales hacia la zona.
Despu&eacute;s de analizar las metas  de la pol&#237;tica exterior espa&#241;ola
en el Caribe,  surgimos que los responsables de la pol&iacute;tica
 espa&ntilde;ola todav&#237;a no distinguen lo suficiente  entre el Caribe
y Am&#233;rica Latina. Luego el  art&#237;culo se centra en algunos aspectos
 importantes de la pol&#237;tica espa&ntilde;ola: las  relaciones econ&#243;micas;
la mediaci&oacute;n espa&#241;ola  dentro de la Comunidad Europea sobre
 asuntos caribe&ntilde;os; la relaci&oacute;n especial con  Cuba;
el <I>Quinto Centenario</I>; la pol&iacute;tica  educacional y cultural; y
relaciones con el  Caribe no-espa&#241;ol. Su conclusion es que las  relaciones
han intensificado desde la transici&#243;n  a la democracia en Espa&#241;a,
pero en la medida  que las obligaciones internacionales y  econ&#243;micas
de Espa&ntilde;a fuera del ambito  caribe&#241;o y latinoamericano siguen
 profundiz&aacute;ndose, condicionar&#225;n y limitar&aacute;n  proyecci&#243;n
espa&ntilde;ola en la zona del Caribe.
<P>
<a name=intro></a><H3>Introduction</H3>
<P>
The early years of the new decade should prove to be decisive
for Spain in a number of respects. Firstly, the transitional period
of integration into the European Community comes to an end; secondly,
it heralds the creation of a single European market which will
determine in large part the future direction of the Spanish economy,
social policy and even foreign policy; and thirdly, it marks the
celebration of the <I>Quinto Centenario, </I>the 5th centenary
celebrations of the Spanish 'discovery' of Latin America and the
Caribbean. Spanish policy towards the Caribbean, particularly
the Spanishspeaking Caribbean, will be determined in the course
of the forthcoming decade by these events. The process of European
integration will determine the framework of future cooperation
between Spain and the Caribbean  whether bilateral, multilateral
or grouptogroup (for example, European Community relations with
Latin America or the EECACP agreements). And the significance
attached to the Quinto Centenario indicates the symbolic importance
within Spanish foreign policy of the notion of a continuing Spanish
presen&#156; in Latin America and the Caribbean. Whether that
presence goes beyond the symbolic, at least in relation to the
Spanishspeaking Caribbean, is a major theme of this paper.
<P>
It should be clear that we conceptualise SpanishCaribbean relations
as unequal and that Spain is the dominant partner; the relationship
rests on the historical ties between an eximperial power and its
excolonies. However, this should not be taken to imply that the
Caribbean countries are simply passive recipients of Spanish policy.
The relationship is markedly different from that which obtains
between Britain or Holland, for example, and their excolonies.
Spain's overseas territories in the Caribbean won relatively early
independence from Spain (l) and the decadence of the Spanish economy
in the early twentieth century made it impossible to maintain
a significant presence in the zone. Nationalist movements were
forced rather to contend with the rising might of the United States,
which established itself as the dominant economic and military
power in the region after 1898. In order to distinguish themselves
from the English-speaking giant on the doorstep, the creole elite
of the Spanish Caribbean, many of whom retained family ties with
the Peninsular, began to emphasize their hispanic inheritance.
This was the beginning of a slow reconstruction of the relationship
with Spain.
<P>
It is important to distinguish at the outset between Spain's relationship
with the Spanish-speaking Caribbean and the Spanish presence in
South America as a whole. It is usual to locate Spanish relations
with Cuba, Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic within one of
two overarching frameworks:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Spanish relations with the islands of the Caribbean Basin,
whether Anglophone, French or Dutch speaking;</li> 
<P>
<li>Spanish relations within Latin America (i.e. Spanish or Spanish
and Portuguese) America.</li></ol>
<P>
While neither focus is completely exclusive of the other, significant
differences exist between these approaches which, if adopted by
ministries or government agencies in Spain, will influence policy
decisions and policy implementation. Spanish relations with Latin
America, especially after 1977, have been essentially about strengthening
cultural elements common to both, encouraging deeper political
dialogue, solidarity with antiauthoritarian and democratic movements
within Latin America, and conflict mediation  particularly in
Central America  despite the existence of some economic agreements,
loans, investment and aid. Spain cannot be said to have developed
an independent policy towards the Caribbean before accession to
the European Community in 1986; however, European relations with
the Caribbean have traditionally been about trade and aid, notwithstanding
the recent growth of political dialogue between the EEC and the
ACP countries of which many Caribbean states are members.
<P>
The Spanish Caribbean, then, has a double identity, thanks to
geography, economy, culture and language  both Latin American
and Caribbean. However, it is only in recent years that the Spanishspeaking
Caribbean has begun to assume consciously a 'Caribbean' identity.
In the case of Cuba, this occurred after the revolution and in
particular in the 1970s, when Cuban foreign policy assumed a consciously
'third world' approach (Erisman 1985); and the Dominican Republic
began to intensify regional relations in 1987, when the decision
was taken to apply for membership of the IV Lome Convention. Puerto
Rico is rather more complicated because of its status as a Commonwealth
of the United States. But Puerto Rican independence movements
and the Popular Democratic Party (PDP) presently in occupation
of <I>La Fortaleza </I>have long revindicated the island's hispanic
connections, and Governor Rafael Hernandez Colon has recently
taken steps to develop a policy for the Caribbean through the
Caribbean Basin Initiative (Heine 1988). Debate about the identity
of these states is much more, then, than simply an academic, philosophical
or anthropological question. In large measure future policies
in the Spanish Caribbean  in terms of economic and regional integration,
international alignments and external relations  will be determined
by the resolution of the issue of identity.
<P>
The resolution of this issue will also determine in large part
the policy demands to which Spain must respond. If the islands
are 'Caribbean', then this would suggest on the part of Spain
less emphasis on the promotion of bilateral links in favour of
grouptogroup negotiations with Western Europe and the European
Community in the future. Because Spain cannot be said to have
a coherent and thought out foreign policy towards the non-Spanish
Caribbean, any institutional contact outside the Spanish-Latin
American framework of relations with the region would almost certainly take place exclusively
within the context of EEC relations with the Caribbean.
<P>
From within Spain, it is almost inevitable to find policy makers
and academics who simply subsume the Spanish-speaking Caribbean
with Latin America without further qualification. This perception
distinguishes Spain from other European powers that tend to view
the two regions differently. Moreover, it radically alters the
nature of the relationship between Spain and her ex-Caribbean colonies
compared with other European powers and their respective excolonies,
offering Cuba, the Dominican Republic and even Puerto Rico certain
advantages, but also disadvantages. Let us take the disadvantages
first.
<P>
Once subsumed within the category 'Latin America', small Caribbean
islands, even Cuba which has enjoyed a diplomatic presence and
importance out of all proportion to its size because of its strategic
position in superpower relations, become low priority for Spain
and are able to offer little competition to the dominance, diplomatically
and economically, of the big Latin American countries (Argentina,
Venezuela, Mexico, Brazil and even Chile, Peru, Ecuador and Colombia).
If we compare media coverage for example within Spain of Latin
American issues or courses in higher education, with the partial
exception of Cuba, Caribbean concerns appear very low down on
the agenda. By the same token, Caribbean diplomatic and trade
missions are small.
<P>
However, the Spanish-speaking Caribbean has the <I>potential </I>to
become a central focus for Spain within the Spain-Latin America
subsystem in the 1990s for the following reason: Spanish foreign
policy is being brought more and more in line with the overall
direction of EEC policy. While this is seen as disadvantaging
Latin America generally, it could benefit the Spanishspeaking
Caribbean since the Caribbean is an established area of interest
within the EEC because of Holland and the U.K., institutionalised
in the EEC-ACP agreements. Spain should be able to 'sell' closer
economic ties and cooperation with the Spanish Caribbean to the
EEC by arguing that the islands form part of the Caribbean.
<P>
Prioritising cooperation with the Dominican Republic and Cuba
offers the additional advantage for Spain, in that she can thus
claim to be fulfilling the commitment which was formally undertaken
on accession to the EEC to act as a bridge for Latin America in
Europe. What we can see, therefore, currently emerging in Spanish
foreign policy concerning the Caribbean is a kind of double discourse,
conscious or not, aimed at Spain's EEC partners on the one hand,
and on the other for consumption within Latin America. Nowhere
was this iUustrated so clearly as with the negotiations over the
Dominican Republic's application to join Lome, the details of
which will be dealt with later in the article.
<P>
Finally, we should remember that institutional ties exist between
the present governing party in Spain, the Socialist Workers Party
(PSOE) and some political parties in the Caribbean through the
Socialist International, now an established player in Latin America
and one where PSOE possess a particular influence in determining
its Latin American policy; and that Cuba, since the days of Franco
and even perhaps since the war of Independence in 1898, occupies
a unique place in Spanish foreign policy. Taken together, these
factors indicate a more important role for the Caribbean within Spanish policy than
might initiaUy seem the case.
<P>
<a name=cont></a><H3>Contemporary Spanish Foreign Policy: Some Preliminary Comments</H3>
<P>
It is impossible to discuss Spanish foreign policy without first
making some reference to the impact of the regime transformation
which occurred in the mid-1970s. The demise of Francoism signaUed
the arrival of a new political class, forged under the dictatorship,
with proposals for fundamentaUy altering Spain's place in the
international system. In their analysis of contemporary Spanish
foreign policy, Pollack and Hunter identify the ideology of most
antiFranco opposition groups as 'democratic-internationalist' (Pollack
and Hunter 1987). Consequently, the emergence of Spanish democracy
is associated with the opening up Spain internationally, beyond
the relatively closed diplomatic parameters of the authoritarian
state (Holman 1989).
<P>
Latin America had occupied a peculiar position within the Francoist
global vision. While the dictatorship claimed an 'Americanist'
vocation through the concept of <I>hispanidad, </I>in practice
Franco's commitment to development in the region remained almost
completely symbolic and rhetorical, especiaUy after 1955. As a
result, policy makers came under pressure to execute a Latin American
policy which, if less grandiose in its designs, was more realistic
both in its appreciation of Spain as a mediumsized European power
moving towards European integration and of the issues in Latin
America to which Spanish policy should respond. This policy was
to emerge in the context of what ex-Foreign Minister Fernando Mor&aacute;n
called 'a new language, a language proper to Spanish democracy'
(Mor&aacute;n 1980). Particular demands were placed upon PSOE
because of its longstanding commitment to the principles of global
equality and social justice and its strong criticism both of the
foreign policy of the Francoist period and of the centrist governments
under Adolfo Suarez and Calvo Sotelo.
<P>
The main foreign policy debate with implications for the design
and implementation of Spanish policy towards Latin America and
the Spanish Caribbean relates to expectations about the operation
of the Spain-European Community-Latin America relationship. Some
elements of the 'Americanist' lobby in Spain  a term used loosely
to describe those organisations within the intellectual community,
the media, nongovernmental organisations and political associations
which argue for a more prominent and committed Spanish presence
in Latin America (Grugel 1991)  have suggested that membership
of the European Community has distracted Spain's attention away
from the region and weakened the strength of its commitments there,
deepening Latin America's isolation internationally at a particularly
difficult conjuncture because of the recession of the 'lost decade'
of the 1980s. Others, however, especially those directly associated
with party or government of fices, have tended to agree with the
Atlanticist/European lobby now dominant within the PSOE and prefer
to see the European Community as offering a forum through which
Spain can win concessions on behalf of Latin America. To this
end, it is argued, Spain has tried to dominate all the internal
bureaucratic positions within the EEC which relate to Latin America since accession. So far,
there are few concrete results from this policy except perhaps
some progress in cooperation with Central America, which was an
alreadyestablished policy. Although there is not the space to
go into detail on this issue, it is worth noting that the theory
of the <I>puente </I>or <I>portavoz </I>has been subject to severe
criticism (Celorio Prieto 1986; Lorca et al 1982). It is unlikely
that one member state can alter the established preferential agreements
of the European Community; even in alliance with the Mediterranean
bloc, Portugal, Italy and Greece, Spain still needs to overcome
the opposition of Germany and the United Kingdom. And Latin America's
chances of winning preferential treatment from the EEC, never
high, have worsened significantly with the transformation of Eastern
Europe which has become top priority for the Community. It should
be noted that the Dominican Republic's successful entry into Lom&#233;
IV was eventually achieved only through an alliance with France,
enabling the applications from Haiti and the Dominican Republic
to be dealt with together.
<P>
A final general comment on Spanish foreign policy should be made
and relates to the level of political and parliamentary debate
on foreign policy since 1977. Even a casual observer would be
aware of the interest in and identification with Latin America
present in Spanish society, the proof of which can be seen in
the existence of strong nongovernmental organisations operating
in the region (2), consistent media attention on regional issues,
the decision to locate the <I>Instituto de Relaciones Europeas
y Latinoamericanas </I>(IRELA) in Madrid, funded by and linked
to the European Parliament and a powerful academic lobby. Yet
this interest finds only a reduced echo in the parliamentary arena
and in party politics. During the initial stages of the transition,
the <I>Ministerio de Asuntos Exteriores </I>came under heavy pressure
for greater openness, scrutiny and democratisation in policy making.
Criticism tended to come from the Left, however, and with PSOE
in government and the Communist left in disarray, such criticism
has been less effective and more muted. In addition, in terms
of party politics, since Spain's entry into NATO and the EEC there
is far more homogeniety in terms of foreign and defence policies
(Pollack and Hunter 1989), all of which reduce the effectiveness
of the Americanist lobby.
<P>
<a name=aims></a><H3>The Aims of Spanish Policy in the Caribbean</H3>
<P>
In determining the aims of Spanish policy in the Caribbean, we
can usefully divide it into: policy designed for Latin America
as a whole which affects the Caribbean; and policy which relates
specifically to the Caribbean. We should note, however, that the
failure of Spanish policy makers to distinguish clearly between
these two makes this division in practice somewhat artificial.
Let us look first at aspects of Latin American policy as it affects
the Caribbean.3
<P>
<OL>
<LI>To build upon the notion of the existence of a Hispanic people,
linked by a common past, language and a shared culture, to which
the Spanish Caribbean belongs. Although democratic governments
in Spain no longer speak of <I>hispanidad because </I>it is tainted
with the paternalism and even neocolonialism of Francoism, no
other framework has yet been put forward successfully to replace
it. The nearest is 'the Ibero-American community' (del Arenal 1989).
The problem resides in the difficulty of articulating an alternative
ideological framework on which to base the idea of a common heritage. At the
same time it should be remembered that for all Franco's manipulation
of hispanidad, it was by no means a Francoist invention. The concept
of hispanidad predates Francoism and developed on both sides of
the Atlantic. Spain's interest in Latin America rests fundamentally
on the deepseated conviction, present at all levels of Spanish
society, that Latin America is an extension of the Peninsula.
Spain is the only European country where it is common to refer
to Europe as <I>el viejo continente </I>('the old continent'),
which carries with it the unconscious assumption that the 'new'
world, the recreation of Europe and its future are to be found
in Latin America. In this sense, then, we can identify some degree
of policy continuity from the period prior to 1977, although the
content of policy has changed somewhat.
<P>
The Quinto Centenario in 1992 is a celebration of the concept
of a Hispanic people. 1992 also offers Spain the opportunity to
project herself globally as the centre of the Spanish-speaking
world.</li>
<P>
<li>Perhaps the tragedy of contemporary Spanish foreign policy
is the contradiction between the central role allocated to Latin
America within the internal global vision of Spain's policy makers
and the economic and diplomatic necessities of Spain as a modernizing,
capitalist European state. The 'special relationship' was developed
as a way of overcoming this contradiction, which for the Socialists
initially meant deepening Spain's relationship with Latin America
on the basis of solidarity with the underdeveloped world and as
a way of increasing her influence internationally (Mor&aacute;n
1980). Once in government, however, this was translated primarily
into the promotion of political dialogue.</li>
<P>
<li>Limited bilateral cooperation, for example, through the <I>Plan
de Cooperaci&oacute;n Integral, </I>run by the <I>Instituto de
Cooperaci&oacute;n Iberoamericana. </I>At the moment, the Plan
is in operation in Central America and the Andean countries, and
although it would be possible theoretically to extend it to the
Caribbean, its budget is inadequate and its purpose primarily
symbolic. The <I>Plan de Cooperaci&oacute;n Iberoam&eacute;ricana
Quinto Centenario, </I>which comes into effect in 1990, will absorb
ICI's. Plan de Cooperaci&oacute;n Integral and has a budget of
14,000 million dollars for the period 199093. Although the terms
of its distribution are not yet clear, Argentina, Mexico, Chile,
Venezuela and Colombia would appear so far to be the privileged
partners of the Plan since it prioritises cooperation through
bilateral agreements (Landecho 1990).</li>
<P>
<li>Recent use of aid funding to pressurize aid recipient countries,
including Caribbean countries, to accept members of the Basque
terrorist/armed struggle group ETA. This is a controversial policy,
and one which the Spanish government denies, but there is little
doubt that it has become an important issue in SpanishDominican
Republic bilateral relations in particular.</li>
<P>
<li>Promotion within the European Community of stronger ties between
Latin America and Europe. This has taken the form of activity
in the European Parliament, promotion of grouptogroup dialogue
between the two regions, and attempts to win a greater share of
EEC concessionary aid for Latin America. With the possible exception
of the Spanish Caribbean, there may be a tradeoff between incre&aelig;d
political cooperation by Europeans and accepting that economic
ties are likely to diminish in importance.</li></ol>
<P>
If Spain's policies towards Latin America have been described
as reactive and shortterm (Grugel 1987) her policy as it relates
to the Caribbean is infinitely more so, based as it is on the
underlying presumption that the needs of the Caribbean are in
essence the same as those of Latin America. Her Caribbean policy
can be summed up as follows:
<P>
<ol>
<li>Application of the idea of a Hispanic people to the Spanishspeaking
Caribbean. Little more than lip service is paid to the indigenous
and black components of Caribbean identity. However, the most
controversial area of application is with Puerto Rico because
of its Commonwealth status with the United States.</li>
<P>
<li>Application of the concept of the special relationship to the
Spanish Caribbean. In practice this relates particularly to Cuba.</li>
<P>
<li>Attempt to introduce changes in the European Community aid
policy to lesser developed countries and support for the Dominican
Republic's application to join the ACP block of countries which
enjoy preferential relations with the EEC member states.</li>
<P>
<li>A limited projection in the English and Dutch Caribbean.</li></ol>
<P>
I now propose to examine the major aspects of contemporary Spanish
policies in turn: economic relations; Spain's mediation within
the EEC of issues relating to the Spanishspeaking Caribbean; the
'special relationship' with Cuba; 1992 and the Quinto Centenario
and its impact in the Caribbean; educational and cultural policy
in the region; and finally relations with the nonSpanish Caribbean.
<P>
<a name=econ></a><H3>Economic Ties - Spain and the Caribbean</H3>
<P>
It is traditional within the discipline of international relations
to presume that the closer the economic ties between states the
greater the political and diplomatic interaction. This framework
is thought to be particularly appropriate for relations between
centre and periphery states. However, this is only partly true
in the c&aelig; of Spanish relations in the Caribbean. Close SpanishCuban
bilateral relations have been cemented since the Francoist period
by economic exchange; yet Spain's interest in Latin American and
the Spanish Caribbean is not predicated upon particularly close
economic ties. Nonetheless, the Spanish Caribbean absorbs a significantly
higher percentage of the total volume with Latin America than
one would have expected, given the relatively low importance Spain
ascribes to the region.
<P>
<a name=trade></a><H3>Trade</H3>
<P>
As with Spanish trading relations with Latin America, the volume
of SpanishCaribbean commerce is not particularly large and on
the whole the balance favours Spain. To take the Spanishspeaking
Caribbean country by country: Puerto Rico spends around $125 million
annually in Spain; Spain is the Dominican Republic's second largest
market (sugar and fruit) after the U.S.A., although representing
only a total value of $23 million, though this should change significantly
after 1992 when the transitional period of Spanish membership
of the EEC ends and the Dominican Republic enters Lome IV; the
volume of trade with Cuba is most significant, and again favours
Spain. In 1985, Spanish exports to Cuba were worth $229 million
while Spanish imports from Cuba were worth almost half, only $124
million (Roy 1988). This is an almost inevitable consequence of
the structure of commercial exchange between Spain and Cuba, for
while Spain exports a variety of manufactured products (motorised
vehicles, lifts, generators, agricultural machinery) and machine
parts, Cuba exports to Spain principally tobacco, coffee and fish
and seafood. Cuba has diversified its exports in recent years
but remains an exporter of primary products to Europe <I>(Cuba:
Guia de Mercados, </I>Secretaria de Estado de Comercio, 1986).
Neither should the size of SpanishCuban trade be exaggerated.
It is effectively a significant percentage of a small and decreasing
total volume of SpanishLatin American/Caribbean trade (Nieto Solis
1989). The recent economic crisis in Cuba, the result of strained
relations with the USSR, internal contradictions and the incompatability
of the revolution's model of development with the present internadonal
system, could lead in the medium term to Cuba looking for a renewed
commercial relationship with Europe, but in the short term it
has reduced Cuba's capacity to import. Commercial relations with
the rest of the Caribbean are much weaker, though there exists
the possibility of some improvement after 1992.
<P>
<a name=inv></a><H3>Investment</H3>
<P>
Of all Spanish investments abroad the banking sector has proved
most dynamic in recent years. In Puerto Rico Spanish finance occupies
a particularly important place, with three Spanish banks, the
Banco Central, the Banco de Bilbao and Viscaya and the Banco de
Santander among the top eight of the island's domestically chartered
banks <I>(Caribbean Business </I>April 7, 1988). Puerto Rico takes
a total of up to 10% of all Spanish investment in Latin America
and the Caribbean <I>(Bolet&iacute;n Econ&ocirc;mico de Informaci&ocirc;n
Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola, </I>No 2046, July 28-August 3, 1986).
<P>
Elsewhere in the region, however, the picture is somewhat different.
Spanish investment in the Dominican Republic represents less than
1% of all Latin American and Caribbean investments and received
only 0.26% of all Spanish investments abroad during 1898 <I>(Bolet&iacute;n
Econ&ocirc;mico de Informaci&ocirc;n Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola,
</I>March 1218, 1990, No 2224). Spanish investments in Cuba represented
only 0.03% of total investments abroad in 1986 <I>(Bolet&iacute;n
de Informaci&ocirc;n Comercial, </I>No 2046, July 28August 3,
1986) a figure which has varied only slightly since then, constituting
a meagre 0.01% in 1989 <I>(Bolet&iacute;n Econ&ocirc;mico de Informaci&ocirc;n
Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola, </I>March 1218, 1990, No 2224). The
tounst sector accounts for almost all of this investment.
<P>
Low levels of Spanish investment in Latin America and the Caribbean
have been a source of concern for Spanish nongovernmental organisations
dedicated to the promotion of deeper Spanish commitment in the
region. Granda has pointed out Spain's failure to make use of
the Centre for Industrial Development of the European Community
which exists to channel European investment into the ACP countries
and has criticised the absence of a national programme of industrial
promotion in lesser developed countries in Spain in comparison
with other European countries (Granda 1985). Both Cuba and the Dominican Republic have expressed an open interest in attracting
some of the European investment which goes into the Caribbean
and look to Spain for assistance in this respect. Although it
is difficult to predict with certainty, a positive response in
the short term seems unlikely. The first step would be a bilateral
<I>Tratado de Amistad y Cooperaci&ocirc;n </I>along the lines
of those Spain has signed with Venezuela, Mexico, Chile and Argentina
and so far negotiations have not yet begun.
<P>
<a name=loans></a><H3>Loans and Commercial Credits</H3>
<P>
Spain, as a medium-sized European state, does not figure as one
of the principal lending countries in Latin America or the Caribbean,
though interestingly 80% of its exposure is in Latin America,
induding the Spanish Caribbean <I>(Bolet&iacute;n Econ&ocirc;mico
de Infonnaci&ocirc;n Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola </I>No 2138, June
1319, 1988). Of the Caribbean countries, only Cuba is in receipt
of Spanish credit, with a debt of $418 billion in l9S8. This represents
4.50% of Cuba's total external debt. Taking Cuba as part of Latin
America, Cuba is Spain's sixth largest debtor.
<P>
<a name=aid></a><H3>Aid</H3>
<P>
Spain's commitment to lesser developed countries overall, measured
in development assistance, is poor and the <I>Fondo de Ayuda al
Desarrollo </I>(FAD), which offers soft credits, was only established
in 1976. In 1989, Spain dedicated omy 0.15% of its GDP to development
aid, compared to an average of 0.36% within OECD countries, which
is itself well below the 0.7% which is the accepted target. The
total aid channelled through FAD for 1989 was 64,760 million pesetas
($518 million approximately). There exists the possibility, however,
that it may in fact be less than this figure, since the Spanish
government admits that there are serious administrative difficulties
in the way the figures are calculated <I>(El Pa&iacute;s July
</I>25, 1989). More seriously, Spain would appear to be using
access to aid both as a commercial tool and as a political lever.
It has been used, for example, to increase sales of Spanish mil,itary
hardware to the Third World.
<P>
The Caribbean does not appear as one of the regions in receipt
of important quantities of Spanish aid with the exception of Cuba,
which is the largest single recipient country. The amount of FAD
credits conceded to Cuba has increased from 1,700 million pesetas
($15,223,000) in 1985 to 8,828 million pesetas ($79,053,349) in
1987 to 13,255 million ($118,601,300) in 1988. Spain also donates
a significant amount of project aid to Cuba  in 1987 and 1988
combined an estimated 446 million pesetas ($3,993,875). Since
1985, the Dominican Republic has also been in receipt of Spanish
government to government aid. FAD credits totalled 1,000 million
pesetas ($8,954,876) in 1985, 949 million pesetas ($8,840,293)
in 1988. Project aid to the Dominican Republic totalled 205 million
pesetas ($1,834,271) for 1987 and 1988. Recent studies have shown
that successful applications for aid are closely linked to a willingness
to accept presumed members of the Basque nationalist group ETA
exiled from Spain. <I>(El Pa&iacute;s July </I>22, 1989). The
Dominican Republic, for example, accepted ETA exiles for the first
time in 1985, the year it first received Spanish aid. There can
be no doubt that cooperation on this issue has acted as the cement
of the Spain's relationship with the Dominican Republic since
1985. The first contingent of ETA members arrived in Cuba in 1984,
since when the size of FAD credits awarded to the island has increased
more than six times.
<P>
<a name=puente></a><H3>El Puente: Spanish Mediation in Europe</H3>
<P>
Part of the 'new realism' in Spanish foreign policy apparent since
the transition is a muchrepeated emphasis on the restrictions
on policy making imposed by Spain's status as a mediumsized country
with a limited capacity for operating independently within the
international system. The result has been a tendency to view the
European Community as the forum where Spanish diplomacy can be
most effective. The PSOE government has specifically undertaken
to promote Latin American (including Spanish Caribbean) initiatives
within the Community. The weakness of the Latin AmericanWestern
Europe subsystem is a major stumbling block to this strategy but,
in theory at least, it should be more successful with regard to
the Caribbean, an already established European interest. Successful
promotion of Spanishspeaking Caribbean interests will depend fundamentally,
however, upon the Spanish Caribbean adopting an unequivocal 'Caribbean'
identity and upon Spanish diplomacy being able to make clear distinctions
between the two regions  Latin America (composed for the sake
of convenience of mainland South and Central America) and the
islands of the Caribbean Basin. Spain cannot assume that European
initiatives in the Spanish Caribbean set a precedent for South
or even Central American states.
<P>
The first major test for the effectiveness of Spanish mediation
of Spanish Caribbean interest came in September 1987, when the
Dominican Republic applied for entry into Lom&#233; IV, which came
into effect in 1990. The reasons for the application must be sought
primarily in the economic crisis which shook the Dominican Republic
in the mid1980s, culminating in violent food riots in 1984. The
recession was exacerbated by the U.S. decision to cut drasticaUy
its sugar quota from the Caribbean <I>(The Wall Street Journal,
</I>June 22, 1987). The application, made in conjunction with
Haiti, was welcomed formally and supported in the European Parliament
from the beginning. But it quickly ran into serious problems,
both from the European Commission and from the ACP bloc. As a
result, the April 1989 Lome negotiations in Madrid ended in a
rejection of the Dominican Republic's application. This was rectified
during the negotiations in December, however, when strong support
from France, then occupying the Presidency of the European Commission
and for whom Lome is a priority in foreign policy making, and
Spain combined to overcome opposition from the rest of the Community
and both Haiti and the Dominican Republic were admitted to Lome
IV along with the newly independent African state of Namibia.
<P>
It is worth examining in more detail the causes of the delay in
bringing the negotiations to a close. To deal with the problems
from Europe first, other Community member states viewed with misgiving
Spain's apparent inability to separate the Caribbean from Latin
America and the suspicion that this would be the first of several applications handicapped the initiative.
It was late in the day when Spain categorically stated that this
would be the only application she would sponsor from Latin America
or the Caribbean. The Spanish are still new to the complicated
diplomatic procedure in the Community, which hindered the negotiation
of an effective alliance behind the application, and Spain and
the Dominican Republic had to overcome the opposition of those
member states who consistently oppose deepening European commitment
to lesser developed countries. It must be remembered that Spain
and the Dominican Republic had to overcome the idea in the Community
that Lom&eacute; exists for recently independent states  the Dominican
Republic has been independent since 1865. Finally, the Commission
dealt with the applications for membership of the Dominican Republic
and Haiti together, and the coup which ousted Leslie Maniget affected
negatively the outcome in April 1989. Without a doubt, therefore,
the Spanish initially underestimated the difficulties the application
presented.
<P>
But successful Spanish mediation in Europe depended as much on
the Dominican Republic's ability to improve relations with its
Caribbean neighbours as on the situation in Europe. In effect,
from the point of view of the Dominican Republic, the decision
to join Lom&eacute; represented a belated recognition that it
shares the determining economic characteristics of the region:
a small economy, relying almost exclusively on primary production
(sugar and fruit) for foreign exchange and very vulnerable to
fluctuations in international demand for these products. At the
same time, Lom&eacute; offers the Dominican Republic, commercially
highly dependent upon the United States, the opportunity to diversify
significantly its external markets.
<P>
Yet the application to join Lom&eacute; met initially with suspicion
from other Caribbean states, whose support was vital to gain a
majority with the ACP bloc. This was primarily for two reasons:
firstly, there existed some degree of generalised resentment towards
the Dominican Republic because of her tendency in the past to
identify with and vote with Latin American states in international
or regional fore  the United Nations or SELA meetings, for example;
and secondly, and potentially a more serious problem, was the fear
of commercial competition in sugar and bananas in particular.
The Dominican Republic was forced to reiterate on several occasions
that its goal was the exportation of manufactured or assembled
products to Europe from its expanding Free Trade Zones rather
than sugar (Grugel 1990). Nonetheless some scepticism persists
about whether the Dominican Republic can replace its traditional
exports with manufactured goods to a sufflciently significant
degree (Gonzalez 1984). It is still unclear the extent to which
membership will noticeably benefit the troubled Dominican economy,
especially since at the end of the day, the same as for Haiti,
'a kind of second-class Lom&eacute; membership', was agreed without
participation in the concessionary trade protocols for sugar,
bananas and rum.
<P>
<a name=special></a><H3>The 'Special Relationship': Spain and Cuba</H3>
<P>
It is evident from even a cursory examination of Spain's economic
and commercial relations in the Caribbean that Cuba occupies a
prominent place within Spanish foreign policy in the region. Indeed,
SpanishCuban bilateral relations are something of a substitute
in Spain for regional policy. The 'special relationship' is not
b&aelig;d solely upon Cuba's privileged commercial and economic
relationship with Spain, but also upon genuine political dialogue,
particularly on Latin American issues. This is due to a number
of factors: in part it is a result of the military and strategic
importance of Cuba in the region; it also reflects the fact that
no government with pretensions to a progressive policy in Latin
America could afford to reject the Cuban revolution, especially
in the 1970s (this is particularly important for SpanishCuban
relations in the early years of the transition in Spain); and
finally Spain's acceptance and even support for the revolution
is a legacy of the contradictions of Francoist policy. It should
be noted, however, that SpanishCuban relations in the period 1982-1990
since the Socialists came into of fice have undergone considerable
strains and transformations. In particular, the relationship no
longer commands allparty support from within Spain; and the collapse
of the Communist regimes in Eastern Europe has exposed a clear
crisis of direction within Cuba.
<P>
According to Carlos Romero, Cuba has a dual foreign policy, firstly
as a result of ties with the Soviet Union and Eastern European
states, and secondly in the Caribbean, where in the 1970s <I>'a
raiz de la creaci&oacute;n de nuevos estados en el Caribe angl&oacute;fono,
y por el mismo car&aacute;cter de la distensi&oacute;n internacional
se dieron las condiciones para el reencuentro entre ambos' </I>(Romero
1988). In spite of the fact that Cuba shares many of the economic
problems endemic in the region, a small island economy heavily
dependent upon primary production and upon one major external
market, even the temptations of drug smuggling and corruption,
it remains the key state in the Caribbean from an international
relations perspective. In addition, from the perspective of Cuba,
promoting close relations with Spain could be seen to correspond
to two of the basic goals of Cuban foreign policy according to
the framework elaborated by Jorge Dominguez in the late 1970s:
the survival of the revolutionary government; and economic development
(Dominguez 1978).4 It is evident, therefore, that SpanishCuban
bilateral relations have acquired a degree of complexity absent
from Spain's relationship elsewhere in the Caribbean.
<P>
Close Spanish-Cuban relations in the 1980s were premised on both
sides upon a strong pragmatic tendency in foreign policy making.
In the case of Spain, this can be traced back to the Francoist
regime, Pollack and Hunter identify a continuity in Spanish Cuban
policy since the revolution (Pollack and Hunter 1987). This immediately
distinguishes Cuba from the rest of the Caribbean and indeed from
the rest of Latin America, where policy making has been more reactive
and adhoc. In Cuba, the tendency in foreign policy during the
1980s was pragmatic rather than ideological with Cuba attempting
to diversify relations outside COMECON (Yopo 1985). Steps in this
direction included the establishment of diplomatic relations with
the European Community in 1988. Cuba also announced in 1989 its
intentions of attracting foreign capital to the island to create
sugar derivative industries <I>(Cinco D&iacute;as, </I>10 August
1989). So far, however, Spanish industry at least has responded
negatively towards the invitation. At present, trade with Europe
as a whole represents only 13-15% of the total volume of Cuban
exports and Japan rather than the European Community has become
her main economic partner outside COMECON.
<P>
In the early years of the Spanish transition to democracy and
during the first part of the PSOE period in of fice diplomatic
relations between the two countries deepened, symbolised in the
exchange of high level diplomatic visits. In November 1987, Felipe
Gonzalez became the first head of a NATO country to visit Cuba
(his second offficial visit as head of the Spanish government).
During this visit a longstanding dispute was solved relating to
compensation for Spanish property confiscated after the Cuban
revolution and the detention of Cuban political prisoners of Spanish
descent, the best known being Gutierrez Menoyo. On compensation,
the Cuban offer of $40 million was accepted, which must be interpreted
as a gesture of goodwill by Spain in view of the fact that $300
million was the original Spanish estimate.
<P>
If Gonzalez has been able to resolve some points of contention
with Cuba, however, others have emerged. Cuba has been outspoken
in its criticisms of some aspects of the Quinto Centenario, which
it sees as imperialist for example. There have also been open
criticism from both sides over aspects of the other's foreign
policy: Castro launched a bitter attack on PSOE's decision to
ratify membership of NATO, calling it a 'grave historical error'
(Yopo 1985); and PSOE has publicly accepted the thesis that Cuba
has acted as a bridgehead for Soviet expansionism in Latin America,
thus contributing to the destabilisation of the region (Flores
1984). And the exclusion of Cuba from the annual meeting of Spanish
and Latin American parliamentarians on the grounds that Cuba does
not have a democratically elected parliament also led to a heated
exchange between Castro and Felix Pons, the leader of the Spanish
Chamber of Deputies.
<P>
The most serious strain on Spanish-Cuban relations so far came
in July 1989, however, with a mass entrance of Cubans in both
the Spanish and Czech embassies in Havana requesting asylum. The
incident coincided with the eruption of an apparently similar
process in Albania, where dozens of Albanian citizens entered
various European diplomatic buildings requesting asylum, many
of whom succeeded in leaving the country. As the numbers inside
the Spanish embassy grew, the issue was obscured by serious doubts
over the identity of some of the Cubans inside the embassy, most
of whom had entered by force or deception, amid allegations that
some were members of the Cuban security forces incognito, there
to assess the situation from the inside. The Cuban government
rejected the idea that they were in any sense political refugees,
alleging that all were 'vagos habituales', common criminals, and
generally antisocial elements, manipulated by outside governments
<I>(Granma </I>July 15,1990).
<P>
Although a thorny problem in itself, the incident was inflated
to such a degree that it temporarily became the prime concern
of the <I>Ministerio de Asuntos Exteriores, </I>and for a time
seriously threatened bilateral relations. The impact of the incident
was due largely to the perception that the collapse of the Communist
regime in Cuba would inevitably follow on the demise of the Communist
system in Eastern Europe in 1989. Increasing isolated internationally,
the Cubans overreacted, fearing intentional destabilisation from
outside. From the Spanish side there was rather uncertainty and
ignorance of how to interpret and respond to the influx of Cubans
into the embassy without unduly undermining a friendly government,
bearing in mind that there is as yet no clear organised opposition
to Castro acceptable to Spain. The incident culminated in a vehement
attack on Francisco Fernandez Ordo&ntilde;ez, the Spanish Foreign
Minister, in <I>Granma </I>and growing pressure on the Socialist
government in Spain from the rightwing press and the Popular Party
to break relations. By mid July, the situation was stalemated
and by August the wouldbe asylum seekers began to leave the embassy,
apparently of their own accord.
<P>
Although it is still too early to be sure of the exact consequences
of this conflict, there is no doubt that it heralds a change in
Spanish-Cuban relations. Perhaps the most direct result is that
it makes it almost impossible for Castro to realize the of ficial
visit to Spain which was one of the goals of Cuban foreign policy,
in the near future at least. It also opened a breach with the
Spanish Socialists which will almost certainly have repercussions
on Cuba's relationship with the Socialist International. Deepening
relations with Social Democrats in Europe and especially in Latin
America were an important strand in Cuba's attempts to reduce
its international isolation and be readmitted into the various
regional fore of Latin America. The new rapprochement between
Cuba and Latin American Social Democrats culminated with Castro
assisting at Rodrigo Borja's inauguration as President of Ecuador
in 1988. The consequence of cooling of relations, therefore, could
be grave for Cuba. And finally the crisis has affected perhaps
irrevocably Spanish-Cuban relations in that, for the first time
since coming to power, the Spanish Socialists now conceive of
bilateral relations with Cuba as potentially independent of the
regime in power on the island.
<P>
<a name=quinto></a><H3>1992 and the Quinto Centenario</H3>
<P>
The most important event in Spanish-Latin American/Spanish-Caribbean
relations in the coming decade will almost certainly be the Ouinto
Centenario. The decision to celebrate Spain's relationship with
Latin American and the Spanish Caribbean in 1992, the 500th anniversary
of Columbus' historic voyage, is prem~sed upon arguing that hispanic
ties are no longer those between an imperial power and her excolonies,
but have evolved in the years since Independence to signify a
primarily linguistic and cultural union between national states.
This is possible, so it is argued in Spain, because Madrid/Seville
ceased to be the metropolitan axis of the Latin American/Caribbean
economies on Independence due to Spain's own economic decline.
Although this is undoubtedly the case, the decision to celebrate
what is in effect the 500th anniversary of an imperial conquest
(not an <I>encuentro, </I>which presupposes a voluntary rather
than imposed comingtogether) has caused some problems, both within
Spain and Latin America. The 'Americanist' lobby inside Spain
finds itself caught in a dilemma between welcoming the media and
goveroment attention focused in the region and the increased funds
available for research, and criticising the imperialist overtones
of the venture. The attitude of Robert Mesa, Professor of International
Relations at the Complutense University of Madrid, reflects this
confusion:
<P>
'En sus terminos justos, el 92 es un buen a&ntilde;o, tanto como
cualquier otro, para recordar la problem&aacute;tica actual, heredera de aquel
encuentro y pese a sus contradiciones, sus servidumbres y grandezas, cultural
y geopol&iacute;tico, posible emblema del 92, que a&uacute;n no se
ha materializado' (Mesa 1988).
<P>
From the point of view of Spain, 1992 serves as a way of focussing
world attention in Spain, perhaps in a way similar to the 200th
anniversary of the French Revolution, and provides a substitute
for a thoughtout policy towards Latin America. It has the advantage
of not tying Spain to any specific commitments for the future.
From within Latin America and the Caribbean, motives for participation
are various. It is interesting to contrast the reluctance with
which Cuba, Spain's most important reference in the Caribbean,
has decided to participate with the eagerness of Puerto Rico.
<P>
Relations between Spain and Puerto Rico warmed considerably in
the early years of the Spanish transition and for the first time
a Puerto Rican delegation was set up in Madrid in 1977.. For Governor
Hernandez Col&oacute;n, participation implies recognition of Puerto
Rico as part of Latin America and the Spanish Caribbean. To this
end, San Juan was the setting for the fifth conference of the
Quinto Centenario in 1987, coinciding with a visit by the Spanish
king, Juan Carlos, to the island.
<P>
<a name=educ></a><H3>Educational and Cultural Policy</H3>
<P>
Spain's educational and cultural policies in the region are coordinated
primarily by the <I>Instituto de Cooperaci&oacute;n Iberoamericana
</I>(ICI), whose origins lie in the Francoist period. One of ICI's
responsibilities is the allocation of Spanish educational grants
to Latin American and Caribbean students. In 198990, out of a
total of 838 grants, Puerto Rico obtained 13, Cuba 27, the Dominican
Republic 27 and Haiti 4. This makes a total of 71 for the Caribbean.s
Although part of the budget of the <I>Plan de Cooperaci&oacute;n
Iberoamericana Quinto Centenario is </I>intended for educational
and cultural projects, neither the actual amount nor the projects
approved are as yet certain. It is likely that the main beneficiaries
will be those countries which enjoy bilateral <I>tradatos de amistad
y cooperaci&oacute;n, </I>which does not include the Caribbean.
<P>
One interesting area of educational cooperation which has developed
in recent years, however, between Spain and Puerto Rico is the
fight to maintain Spanish as an offficial language on the island.
Interestingly, Spanish philologists have advised the Puerto Rican
<I>Comisi&oacute;n Nacional de Educaci&oacute;n </I>on the teaching
of Spanish in schools, which is done so succesfully that Puerto
Ricans are in effect monolingual not bilingual, despite the relationship
with the United States <I>(El Pa&iacute;s </I>October 26, 1990).
<P>
<a name=spain></a><H3>Spain and tbe Non-Spanish Caribbean</H3>
<P>
Beyond establishing formal diplomatic relations, Spain cannot
really be said to have a policy at all towards most of the nonSpanish
Caribbean states. The exception to some degree is Jamaica, where
the PSOE has contacts through the Socialist International with
the National People's Party (PNP) of Michael Manley. It is also
interesting to see the emergence of a lowkey cultural and educational policy, under the aegis of ICI, directed at parts
of the Englishspeaking Caribbean. In 1986, for example, the Spanish
began to finance a programme of excavations and of restoration
of the colonial city of Sevilla Nueva in Jamaica, with the aim
of creating a museum commemorating the Spanish legacy in Jamaica.
A Spanish language programme has also recently been set up. In
August 1988 a joint language programme for private and state schools
throughout the Caribbean was organised in collaboration with the
Organisation of American States (OAS). A summer school for Spanish
language teachers was also held in 1988 in Trinidad and Tobago,
organised jointly by ICI and the National Institute for Higher
Education, Research and Technology of Trinidad and Tobago. 53
teachers were admitted to the Summer School, of which 43 came
from Trinidad and Tobago, 5 from Barbados and 4 from Jamaica.
A second summer school was organised in Salamanca, Spain, in 1989.
<P>
Relations with the Dutch Caribbean are weaker, except in one area:
finance. Although apparently Spanish investment in the Dutch Antilles,
a taxfree investment zone, represents only 0.42% of all Spanish
investment abroad in reality the figure is thought to be considerably
higher. According to the <I>Bolet&iacute;n Econ&oacute;mico de
Informaci&oacute;n Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola, </I>published by
the Spanish Ministry of Economy, a significant percentage of Spanish
investment in Holland is reinvested in the Dutch Antilles. In
1989, Spanish investment in Holland totalled 36,743.71 minion
pesetas (S367.43 million), 13.01% of all investment abroad <I>(Bolet&iacute;n
Econ&oacute;mico de Informaci&oacute;n Comercial Espa&ntilde;ola
</I>March 1218, 1990 No 2224).
<P>
<a name=con></a><H3>Conclusions</H3>
<P>
Spain's relationship with her excolonies in the Caribbean differs
markedly from those which have developed since Independence between
other excolonial powers and their respective excolonies in the
area. It merits less obviously being described as a neocolonial
relationship. Not only has the Spanish Caribbean enjoyed independence
for far longer than the rest of the Caribbean but relations in
the period after Independence were established principally on
the basis of cultural interchange and immigration (Spanish citizens
emigrating to the Spanish Caribbean rather than the reverse) rather
than economic exploitation. It is nonetheless true that the Spanish
community within the Caribbean forms part of a relatively privileged
elite (Naranjo 1987). This has not led to widespread antiSpanish
feelings, however, within the excolonies, principally because
contemporary nationalism in Cuba, Puerto Rico and the Dominican
Republic has been shaped in response to the military and economic
hegemony established in the region by the United States. The United
States made its presence felt militarily from the very moment
of Puerto Rican and Cuban independence from Spain. A vindication
of the Hispanic legacy in the Caribbean therefore, became a fundamental
aspect of at least moderate nationalist disaourse.
<P>
The above could be said to be the positive side of the balance
sheet of contemporary relations. On the deficit side, we should
note firstly that the absence of a clear neocolonial framework
of relations between Spain and her excolonies in the Caribbean
in no sense denotes a relationship of equals and secondly, that
Independenae though signifying the end of Spanish dominance did
not liberate the Spanish Caribbean, especially Puerto Rico and
Cuba, in any real way. Indeed, it should be said that it left
the islands without any very useful patron among the developed
countries. The Spanish Caribbean continued to suffer neocolonial
exploitation without this being mediated in the least by any sense
of political responsibility or obligation towards the islands
on the part of either the United States or Europe. The establishment
of the Lom&eacute; Convention, with the newly independent excolonies
of France and Britain as major beneficiaries, showed to the Spanish
Caribbean how far they had been left behind.
<P>
Relations between Spain and the Caribbean weakened considerably
after the loss of Cuba and Puerto Rico in 1898, in spite of the
continuous flux of Spanish immigrants which continued well into
the 1930s. And with the exception of limited solidarity with the
Cuban revolution, the period of Francoism did little to reestablish
ties on any firm or coherent footing. It was therefore left to
the democratic period and especially to the Socialist in the 1980s
to redefine a new role for Spain in the Spanish Caribbean. The
contents, contradictions and limitations, usually of a structural
nature, have been the subject of this article. Spanish foreign
policy in the coming decade will be determined fundamentally by
Spain's international obligations and economic aommitments her
membership of NATO, the EEC and the exclusive club of advanced
capitalist countries. These aommitments will aontinue to aondition
her policy towards Latin America and the Caribbean. In this sense,
the orientation of Spanish foreign policy in the democratic period
was established with the internationalist orientation of the transition
to democracy.
<P>
We should expect no major changes in policy toward the Caribbean
in the coming decade. However, 1992-3 should prove to be especially
important, as much for the Quinto Centenario celebrations as because
it signifies full membership for Spain in the European Community.
Although the implications of this process for Latin America and
the Caribbean are not yet fully clear, we should expect both benefits
and disadvantages, though not in equal measure nor spread evenly
throughout the region. For the Spanish Caribbean overall, it should
herald some incremental improvements in relations with Europe.
On the other hand, one area where the Spanishspeaking Caribbean
will be affected negatively, along with other Latin American countries,
is in access to Spanish citizenship, as privileged access for
Latin America comes to an end.
<P>
Overall, the forthcoming decade should witness a continuing policy
of limited solidarity with Latin America and the Spanish Caribbean,
steady and regular political dialogue though within the framework
of diminished economic exchange, and the maintenanae of a 'special
relationship' with Cuba, notwithstanding bilateral tensions, a
Cuban economic crisis and possibly even the growing exhaustion
and isolation of communism on the island. And finally, the 1990s
should herald the creation of a separate policy for the Caribbean
for the first time, bringing Spain in line with other members
of the European Community.
<P>
